<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S LUNETTA IS AILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. - USC is fortunate it opens College World Series
play today instead of Friday, or the Trojans might have been
without star freshman Anthony Lunetta, who has the flu and missed
both practices here.
</P>
<P>
   Lunetta, the Pacific-10 Conference freshman of the year, came
down with the virus Thursday and has been held out of all workouts.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Mike Gillespie said there were indications Lunetta
might have strep throat but expected him to start at second base
today when the fourth-ranked Trojans play fifth-ranked Florida
State at Rosenblatt Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allowed him a day and a half to get fine, and if he's not,
he'll still be fine,'' Gillespie said. ``He's feeling better now.
He's on an upswing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunetta is one of USC's most dangerous hitters, leading the
Trojans with 22 doubles. Overall, he is hitting .350 with 11 home
runs and 49 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard weighing options: Stanford right fielder Joe Borchard
of Camarillo, the 12th pick in the baseball amateur draft, hit a
towering home run Friday night in the Cardinal's 6-4 victory over
Louisiana-Lafayette, then said after the game he had not decided if
he would return to play quarterback for the football team in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all going to be worked out in the near future,''
Borchard said. ``I have to keep my options open. I didn't know I
would get drafted so high. At this point, everything is still
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the chances were he would play football, Borchard
replied: ``Right now, it's tough to say anything. We have a big
game to play Sunday. It is nice to be able to relax right now with
everything that went on in the draft this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Still the underdog: Gillespie believes the Trojans have been
mentally sharp in the regionals and super regionals, but is
concerned how USC will react to playing in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week, it's been about taking the next step. Are we
overrated by taking this next step? Quite frankly, it's what I
worry about right now,'' he said. ``I hope they believe they can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem to be a problem with the players, who are not
lacking self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to win this thing,'' USC pitcher Mark Prior
said. ``The thing that gives me confidence is we're playing so well
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   No jitters: USC pitcher Rik Currier pitched two games in
Rosenblatt Stadium during the Trojans' last visit here in 1998,
victories over Mississippi State and then Arizona State in the
national-championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I couldn't believe I was here,'' Currier said. ``By
the fifth or sixth inning, I was on the mound and just kind of
looked at the crowd and went, `Wow.' The only way pitching here
before will help me is with nerves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
