<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE FANS BOO CLEMENS OFF FIELD AS METS BEAT YANKEES, 12-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens stepped off the mound in the sixth
inning of Friday night's game at Yankee Stadium and walked steadily
into a head wind of boos, the tempest of Yankee fans raging over
his horrible performance against the Mets. Clemens crossed the
first base line, the discontent growing louder, reaching a pitch
just before he disappeared into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Tyner of the Mets, five days into his major league career,
had been the first batter to get to Clemens and Mike Piazza all but
finished him with a grand slam in the third inning, as the Mets
destroyed the Yankees, 12-2, in the opener of their three-game
weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   Two events have occurred without fail in each of Clemens' three
starts in the series against the Mets since he joined the Yankees:
Piazza has hit a home run, and Al Leiter has been the pitcher who
beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter (7-1) allowed seven hits and two runs last night; Clemens
(4-5) has allowed 21 runs (20 earned) in 13 innings in the three
games against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Before he pitches, Clemens covers his body with a scentless balm
called Red Hot to help him get ready, even on warm and muggy
nights. He finished his warm-ups under a coating of sweat, walked
to Monument Park, pressed a palm against Babe Ruth's plaque and
took the field, at 37, the oldest starter in the season's first of
six games between the New York City rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The game's youngest player batted first: Tyner, tall and
bat-handle thin, 22 years old, and he pushed Clemens to a full
count before lining a game-opening double over the head of Bernie
Williams in center.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner did not score in the inning, but he did scamper to third
on a ground ball to Derek Jeter's right at shortstop, beating
Jeter's throw.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees understood from this play about Tyner is that
he is not afraid to take chances. Maybe this is what weighed on
Clemens' psyche in the third inning, affecting everything he did in
the game's decisive inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner opened the third by pushing a bunt in front of home plate,
toward the mound, the ball rolling perhaps 15 feet before the
catcher Jorge Posada grabbed it and threw to first _ high, taking
Tino Martinez off the base. Tyner was on and the Yankees obsessed
over him.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens came set, ready to pitch to Derek Bell, who had four
hits in his last 54 at-bats (.074), and the pitcher stepped off,
watching Tyner. Clemens threw a fastball and Bell swung through it;
in fact, all six pitches Clemens threw to Bell in the at-bat were
fastballs, the pitch most advantageous in throwing out base
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitched out on the second pitch and Tyner wasn't moving.
Clemens threw to first, pushing Tyner back, then pumped a fastball
high to Bell; two balls and one strike. Tyner broke from first on
the next pitch with a good jump, and Bell fouled off the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens rushed his delivery and threw high, and with the count
full, he rushed again, his fastball sailing out of the strike zone
for ball 4 on the slump-ridden Bell, a killer walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had first and second and nobody out in a scoreless
game.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fired high again on the first pitch to Edgardo Alfonzo,
Posada wincing as the ball bounced out of his glove for a passed
ball, and both runners advanced. Clemens walked Alfonzo, as well,
loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   A roar of anticipation followed Piazza as he walked to the plate
to face Clemens, off whom he had five hits in 10 career at-bats,
including two home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens tried to spin a slider. Piazza was ready, swinging, his
left leg stiffening and serving as anchor, and the ball rocketed
toward center field, Clemens' head jerking skyward as the ball
carried over the fence. It was only the second grand slam Clemens
has allowed in the 3,542 innings of his career, and it was the 11th
Piazza has hit in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the signature hit Friday night, for Leiter was
pitching effectively, and with the Mets now leading 4-0, the rest
of the game seemed unnecessary, other than to inflame the feelings
of Yankee fans toward Clemens. There were 55,822 in the park, most
of them cheering for the Yankees .
</P>
<P>
   Bell singled home a run in the fourth inning, his fifth hit in
55 at-bats, and after the Yankees got a run in the fourth, the Mets
got another in the fifth. Tyner pulled a single through the right
side of the infield, haunting Clemens, then taking second when
Clemens bounced a pick-off attempt into the first base stands.
</P>
<P>
   Bell doubled inside the right field line, scoring Tyner, and
before Alfonzo batted, Posada walked toward the mound to say
something to Clemens, turned and looked toward the dugout, wiping
his brow with his gloved hand.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitched to Alfonzo, there was a sharp crack, and in an
instant Alfonzo's drive had landed beyond the wall in center.
</P>
<P>
   Now Yankees Manager Joe Torre stepped onto the field to get his
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The booing began, and Clemens spoke to the infielders
surrounding him as they waited for Torre. But before Clemens
departed, Torre spoke into his right ear, knowing what Clemens
would hear on the way back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The booing was scathing, the message clear: Throughout Clemens'
tenure with the Yankees, fans have extended his probation,
occasionally embracing him, but now they were furious. He had
flopped badly in a game that means more to them than any other
regular season game he has pitched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
