<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-KILLER-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. COURT ORDERS PAROLE FOR CONVICTED KILLER; STATE APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LODI, N.J. _ In a rare judicial step, a New Jersey appeals panel
Friday ordered the parole of a 62-year-old convict who has been
imprisoned since 1964 for pistol-whipping and fatally shooting two
Lodi police officers in a highway bar.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous ruling by a three-judge panel of the Appellate
Division instructed the New Jersey Parole Board to release the
inmate, Thomas Trantino, in 30 days. He is serving a life sentence
from which the only release is parole.
</P>
<P>
   The order represents a victory for Trantino, who has been in
state prison longer than any other New Jersey inmate and has been
campaigning for freedom for 20 years, over the objections of many
in Bergen County, where the officers were killed in August 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The judges told the state Department of Corrections to transfer
Trantino immediately to a halfway house or residential center as
preparation for his release. But in response to a request by the
state attorney general, the judges ordered a temporary postponement
of the transfer, said Chuck Davis, a spokesman for Attorney General
John J. Farmer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that on Monday the panel would review Farmer's
request that it also set aside the order to release Trantino in 30
days while the New Jersey governor's administration appeals the
order to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The judges' order rankled parole board officials, who said that
Trantino was only the second state prison inmate in history to win
court-ordered parole. The other, a man serving 10 years for
molesting a 10-year-old girl, was ordered released this week by
another appeals panel, said Michael Carlin, deputy executive
director of the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin said the two orders ``raised very serious legal issues''
about the courts interfering with the workings of the executive
branch of government.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also touched off a new round of protest by Bergen
County and municipal officials, representatives of seven police
departments and survivors of the two slain officers, Sgt. Peter
Voto, 40, and Officer Gary Tedesco, a 22-year-old rookie patrolman.
For years, the county's elected representatives and law enforcement
officials have argued, in rallies and candlelight vigils, that
parole for Trantino would be disrespectful to the memories of the
two officers.
</P>
<P>
   Against this heated political backdrop, the parole board has
rejected nine parole applications from Trantino since he became
eligible in 1980. And Friday's appellate ruling suggests that the
state's judicial system has grown impatient with the board's
handling of Trantino's case and its legal reasoning for the latest
rejection, which was issued last June.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges _ Michael P. King, John E. Wallace and Robert
A. Fall _ found that the parole board's conclusions and findings
were unreasonable, based on the evidence in Trantino's file, and
conveyed a ``sense of wrongness.'' The judges said the state's
parole laws and standards required them to intervene and reverse
the board, which had failed to adequately consider the
``substantial and positive'' factors in Trantino's parole
application.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, other appellate panels and the New Jersey Supreme
Court, the state's highest tribunal, found flaws in the parole
board's rejections of Trantino's applications. But those rulings
always instructed the board to again review Trantino's case. This
time, the appeals judges did not order the board to review the
case, instead ordered Trantino's parole in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer, the state attorney general, said Friday that Gov.
Christine Todd Whitman had instructed him to appeal the case. In a
written statement, he said the parole board believed that Trantino
had no plan for life after parole, could not handle stress and was
easily agitated and prone to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lethal combination created an unacceptable risk of
recidivism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling in May 1998, the state Supreme Court refined the
legal standard for Trantino's parole, saying he should be freed
unless the parole board found a ``substantial likelihood'' that
Trantino would commit a crime after parole. The court also
suggested that Trantino did not pose such a risk and told the board
to look at his case again.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ruling said the board had not properly applied the 1998
``substantial likelihood'' standard. In part, the decision said,
the board had improperly based its rejection on the opinion of a
board psychologist, Glen Ferguson, who in the mid-1990s favored
parole for Trantino, but in 1999 and said that Trantino had the
potential for committing new violent crimes if freed.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's ruling, about 30 police officers from Lodi and
surrounding towns gathered outside Lodi's municipal building, next
to an eagle-topped memorial to Voto and Tedesco. The Bergen County
executive, William P. Schuber, vowed to fight what he called a
``wrong, wrong decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
