<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTENFIELD PITCHED IN PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- Pitcher Kent Bottenfield tried to pitch through the
tendinitis in his right shoulder for the past three weeks, but
finally came to the realization that he was only hurting himself
and the team by going to the mound every five days.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield said he had the same problem at the same time of the
season last year with the Cardinals, but got through it without a
trip to the disabled list. He wasn't so lucky this time, as the
Angels placed him on the DL Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The later I'd get into games the less I could get my arm and
shoulder into position they needed to be in,'' he said. ``I tried
to throw a fastball down and away and it would be up and in. That's
not me. If I were to keep throwing to the point of fatigue, I was
only setting myself up for injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield admitted that being the only veteran in the starting
rotation might have played a role in him trying to pitch through
the problem. But he said missing one or two starts is better than
risking missing one or two months.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield is eligible to come off the DL June 23, roughly
coinciding with the returns of Tim Belcher, Ken Hill and Jason
Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two weeks, everybody will be back in the rotation,'' he
said. ``We're going to be in this race. You have to give so much
credit to the offense. They don't sit around and moan about the
pitchers giving up leads. I've never been on a team this mentally
tough in my entire life. It's been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia admitted that past performances against
Diamondbacks pitcher Randy Johnson came into play when he made out
his lineup Friday, but it wasn't the determining factor. Otherwise,
player-turned-broadcaster Rex Hudler would have been playing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had hit Johnson well during his career, Hudler said:
``No ... only about .450!''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Garret Anderson and second baseman Adam Kennedy
-- both left-handed hitters -- did not start Friday's game.
Anderson is 0 for 9 in his career against Johnson and Kennedy has
never faced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pitchers you might look at matchups a little more,''
Scioscia said. ``But G.A. needed a day off. He's been pressing the
last week. He needed a breather and this was a good day for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad moved from left to center, and Edgard Clemente
started in left. Benji Gil started at second base in place of
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's game was Scioscia's first opportunity to manage a major
league game under National League rules. Before the game he said he
was looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different approach, with things like the double
switch,'' he said. ``In some aspects it's more of a challenge. In
other aspects, some strategy goes out the window with the DH. We
use the DH to manufacture runs at the bottom of the lineup. I enjoy
that part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as any advice for the Angels pitchers hitting, Scioscia
said: ``(Hitting coach) Mickey (Hatcher) said `Close your eyes and
swing from your (rear).' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
