<HEADER>
A0077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT     06-10 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL TOO MUCH FOR PACERS AS L.A. WINS GAME 2, 111-104 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The handmade placard at the Staples Center
illustrated well the plight of the Indiana Pacers. ``Stop Shaq?
You're joking, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Fouling him hard, swarming him each time he received the ball,
they tried desperately Friday night. But at 7 feet 1 inch and 330
pounds, with the moves of a lithe swingman, Shaquille O'Neal is
beginning to resemble the bully at recess, holding the ball above
his head while all his inferior classmates jump in futility.
</P>
<P>
   It does not look fair.
</P>
<P>
   Too big, too strong and simply too good, O'Neal again backpacked
the Los Angeles Lakers to a 2-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game
National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   He had 40 points and 24 rebounds and made 18 of 39 free throws
in the Lakers' 111-104 Game 2 victory over Indiana before a loud,
to-be-seen-and-heard crowd of almost 19,000. His total of 39 free
throws was an NBA finals record.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal may even have to climb higher on Sunday night. With the
series moving to Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis for Games 3, 4
and possibly 5, the Lakers may be without the other half of their
young All-Star tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant was injured in the first quarter and did not return.
After hitting a 17-foot jump shot over Jalen Rose, Bryant fell
awkwardly to the floor with 3 minutes 26 seconds left. He rolled
his left ankle on Rose's foot while coming down after releasing the
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Helped to the locker room, he was told he had a moderately
sprained ankle after X-rays came up negative. Listed as day to day,
his status for Game 3 was questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant injured the same ankle in Game 5 of the Western
Conference finals, but returned in time for Game 6. He had been
undergoing therapy for the injury since last week, using
range-of-motion exercises to increase flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird said he would not employ the Hack-a-Shaq
defense, in which O'Neal is repeatedly fouled to increase
possessions for Indiana and free-throw misses for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game in the balance in the fourth quarter, Bird
resorted to the same strategy used by Portland in the Western
Conference finals. Other than whether O'Neal would miss badly or
sink the shot, it made for awful theater. But it did stop the clock
and give the Pacers a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Rose led the Pacers with 30 points. Reggie Miller finished with
21 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Rik Smits again played poorly. He picked up his fifth foul
with 7:09 left in the third quarter and made only two of six shots.
Unable to stop O'Neal on defense or at least make him guard him
from the perimeter on offense, Smits is hurting Indiana like no
other player.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the Lakers were resilient, the Pacers were not up to
the challenge. With a few minutes left, they essentially were
battling a team that had missed 18 of 36 free throws and was
without the services of its second-best player.
</P>
<P>
   This was the opportunity Bird had wanted for so long, this was
the best chance Indiana had of putting fear into Phil Jackson's
often-fragile team. Who knew when Bryant would play again or if he
would have the same effectiveness?
</P>
<P>
   They were right there, trailing by only 93-89 with 3:14 left.
All they needed was a crucial stop on defense. But they could not
get it. Robert Horry outdueled Austin Croshere for a long rebound
off a miss by Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   And seconds later, O'Neal was at the line. He made only one of
two shots _ missing the first with a line-drive delivery that
nearly chipped paint off the rim. But that five-point lead would
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had an open look at a 3-pointer to cut it to within two
points with less than 3 minutes left, but he could not connect.
</P>
<P>
   Without Bryant, role players like Glen Rice and Ron Harper
shouldered the scoring load and played as if they were the key
components to the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was so strong and forceful, not even the officiating crew
could fathom his power and agility.
</P>
<P>
   With less than seven minutes left, the Lakers center appeared to
cleanly block a driving layup by Travis Best, who used his forearm
to initiate the contact.
</P>
<P>
   But the referee Eddie F. Rush somehow called a flagrant foul on
O'Neal, which had the Laker bench up in anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers withstood every Pacer run, finally putting the game
away midway through the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the fourth, O'Neal attempted his 25th free
throw _ the most by a player in finals history.
</P>
<P>
   Harper contributed 20 points to the victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal swarmed, Harper drove the lane instead of forcing
the ball inside. He scored on four driving layups and made his
medium-range jump-shot count each time.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was lethal from the perimeter, spotting up from beyond the
arc. He made four of five 3-pointers. As a team, the Lakers did not
miss a 3-pointer in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Miller found his rhythm on offense, making seven of 14 shots
through three quarters and consistently keeping the Pacers in the
game with a timely jump shot. But with 6:40 left in the game, he
had yet to attempt a shot in the fourth period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
