<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTING OF COLORADO
 STIRS WORRY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY SHAUN MCKINNON 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Colorado River water contaminated by a chemical used
to make rocket fuel may have contrib uted to higher levels of
potentially dangerous hormones in Yuma newborns, a study concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The study can't prove the chemical, ammonium perchlorate, caused
the hormone spikes or even that it is harmful to humans. But Ross
Bre chner, chief of the state Department of Health Services
epidemiology of fice, said it underscores the need for more
in-depth research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to scare the public because there's nothing to
be scared about,'' said Brechner, who will present his findings to
the American Water Works Association on Thurs day in Denver. ``But
we hope it will put more money into some sort of definitive study
of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuma officials had not seen the study Friday and were not
prepared to comment, city spokesman Mike Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Brechner studied the results of the state newborn screening
program in Yuma, which takes all of its drinking water from the
Colorado River, and Flagstaff, which uses no water from the river.
He found slightly higher levels of the thyroid stimulating hormone
in some Yuma newborns.
</P>
<P>
   The study provided a unique oppor tunity to examine how
perchlorate affects humans, said Will Humble, chief of the DHS
environmental health office, because the newborn screening program
tests for thyroid problems.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe ammonium per chlorate interferes with the
thyroid's ability to regulate hormone produc tion and can impair
metabolism and growth, especially in young children. But so little
is known for certain that federal officials can't even establish a
safe level of exposure for the chemi cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what this study means for sure, except that it
adds to the picture,'' Brechner said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects more feedback from other scientists when his work is
published later this year in the ``Journal of Occupational and Envi
ronmental Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Perchlorate seeped into the lower Colorado River, which provides
drinking water for 20 million people in Nevada, Arizona and
California, from an industrial complex outside Las Vegas. Nevada
officials have been monitoring levels since 1997 and have
discovered high concentra tions in Lake Mead.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also has measured perchlo rate levels along the Colorado
and in water delivered by the Central Ari zona Project, which draws
1.5 mil lion acre-feet a year from the river.
</P>
<P>
   That survey found levels of the chemical ranging from
undetectable in most Phoenix area locations to about 6 parts per
billion at Lake Havasu and near Yuma, well below Arizona's risk
guideline of 14 parts per billion. No perchlorate was found in
groundwater wells.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Envi ronmental Quality is working with
the federal Environmental Protection Agency and a special
perchlorate task force to establish a health standard, spokesman
Kurt Maurer said. The state agency plans to measure levels along
the Colorado, within the CAP systems and in a number of groundwater
wells again later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it occurs, and we don't anticipate it going away for a
little while yet,'' said Tony Curry, admin istrator of the CAP's
environmental compliance program. ``It is going to be an issue,
probably a greater issue than it has been in the past if this study
pans out to be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Humble said the DHS study was possible because of recent
advances in measurement technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at lower levels, new problems can surface,'' he
said, which is why more research is critical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
