<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS RATES RISING AMONG
 MINORITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY DANIEL GONZALEZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - After having unprotected sex with another man,
Willie Johns ton was surprised to discover that he had the AIDS
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (AIDS) was something that gay men had,'' said
Johnston, 40, who is Black, explaining why he didn't take
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, father of four by two women, doesn't consider himself
gay or bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   His confusion about who is at risk for AIDS may help explain why
minorities represent a growing per centage of AIDS and HIV cases in
Arizona, according to AIDS preven tion educators.
</P>
<P>
   Other cultural factors, such as resist ance to condom use, also
factor in, which is why AIDS prevention work ers have begun
reaching out to minority groups where they live and work.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts are aimed at people like Maudie Battle, who was
suicidal after learning she was HIV positive six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she attends a support group for women infected with human
immunodeficiency virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out I'm not the only one,'' said Battle, a Phoenix
resident.
</P>
<P>
   New AIDS cases have declined steadily to 255 new cases in 1999
from a high of 708 in 1992, accord ing to the state Department of
Health Services. But at the same time, minorities account for a
greater percentage of those cases: 49 percent in 1999, up from 18
percent a decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities also accounted for 45 percent of the 331 HIV cases in
1999, compared with 29 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The growing HIV and AIDS rates among minorities suggest that the
stigma about homosexuality among men of color may be standing in
the way of AIDS prevention in their communities, AIDS prevention
workers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk to communities of color they think it's a gay
White man's disease,'' said Garry Robin son, program coordinator of
TRIBE, a community-based AIDS prevention program that targets
Blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is educate communities of color that AIDS is
a human disease, and it can and will affect anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about the disease isn't reaching minorities at the
same level as Whites, and underscores the need for culturally
sensitive information, AIDS prevention workers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``(W)hat I'm seeing with Hispanics is that they may not know
they are infected, so they don't seek out treatment; or they know
they are infected, but they don't know where to get treatment,''
said Federico Saenz, program coordinator of La Zona Hispana, an
AIDS prevention program that targets Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In both the Black and Latino com munities, homosexuality is more
ta boo than the larger society, said Frank Repice, director of
prevention and outreach for AIDS Project Arizona, the largest
provider of HIV-related services in the state. That's partly
because of church influences, and partly due to fear of being
ostracized by family members and community, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to help stem the spread of AIDS in communities of
color, TRIBE and La Zona Hispana will hold an HIV and AIDS
awareness health fair Saturday at a south Phoenix park.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts have taken on a sense of urgency because health
officials pre dict an increase in the number of AIDS cases in
Arizona linked to a recent jump in syphilis cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same behavior that is going to infect someone with
syphilis could infect someone with HIV,'' said Denise Boyd, who
monitors HIV trends for the state. ``In other words, unprotected
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   HIV can lead to AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
The virus is primarily spread by having unprotected sex with an
infected partner or by sharing intravenous drug needles with
someone infected with the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The virus can weaken the immune system, making it hard to fight
off infections. Medical advances can slow the rate at which HIV
weakens the immune system, but there is no known cure.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several months, out reach workers from TRIBE and La
Zona Hispana have been passing out AIDS prevention information and
condoms at bars, street corners, grocery stores, even laundries.
They also distribute needle sterilization kits to IV drug users in
minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating efforts to pre vent the spread of AIDS in
commu nities of color is the steady influx of non-English speaking
immigrants from Mexico. Many are ignorant of the AIDS threat and
come from a culture that enables machismo be havior, Hispanic
outreach workers say.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from wives back home and confined to close living
quarters, Mexican migrant workers sometimes engage in sex with
other men, said Graciela Mera, an outreach worker at La Zona
Hispana.
</P>
<P>
   Men looking for sex also prey upon migrants desperate for cash
by prop ositioning day laborers waiting for work on street corners,
Mera said.
</P>
<P>
   To help educate Mexican workers about AIDS, Mera passes out AIDS
prevention information to day labor ers on street corners.
</P>
<P>
   Health workers say another factor fueling AIDS infection rates
among some Hispanics is the phenomenon of married men having sex on
the side with other men.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Hispanic male will consider himself macho and believe he can
have sex with either a man or a woman and still not consider
himself a homosexual as long as he is not penetrated,'' Saenz said.
</P>
<P>
   The practice puts not only them selves at risk, but their wives,
Saenz said.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS prevention workers are also finding that more
African-American and Latino men than White men resist using
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   And many women of color will not insist on their male partner
using condoms, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Johnston discovered he had AIDS three years ago, after
his male lover of four years died of the disease. At a friend's
suggestion, Johnston was tested for the virus and came up positive.
</P>
<P>
   His then-girlfriend, who bore his two youngest children, has
tested nega tive for the AIDS virus, as have his children.
</P>
<P>
   Now that his 14-year-old son is showing interest in girls,
Johnston is counseling him against having sex. He also advises him
to use condoms, should the boy not choose absti nence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out and bought him a pack of rubbers,'' Johnston said.
``I tell him rubbers are like a bicycle helmet. You've got to have
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
