<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEST-NILE-VIRUS-1STLD     06-10 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-NILE-VIRUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS CONFIRM WEST NILE VIRUS KILLED BIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change Clarkstown to New City in 2nd and 3rd grafs. In 3rd
graf, changes `several' miles to 15 miles. Deletes `NY' from
slug.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three crows found dead _ two in New York and one in New Jersey _
were confirmed Friday as this year's first known victims of the
West Nile virus, the mosquito-borne disease that killed seven
people in New York City last year, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, one male and one female crow, believed to be a
mating pair that had been in the area since March, were found near
each other in New City by passers-by on May 22, and taken to the
Rockland County Health Department. The West Nile virus was
confirmed as the cause of the two birds' death Friday, said Ward
Stone, the chief wildlife pathologist for the New York state
Department of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the state Department of Health and Senior
Services announced that a crow found in River Edge, in Bergen
County, 15 miles south of New City, was confirmed to have died from
the virus. Christine Grant, New Jersey's state health commissioner,
said the bird was believed to have been recently infected. Stone
said the Rockland County birds had also been recently infected, and
were believed to have contracted the virus from mosquito bites in
the area where they died .
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ostraff, associate director of the National Center for
Infectious Diseases at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, said the birds were the first confirmed cases of the
West Nile virus anywhere in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said new cases of the virus had been expected to surface
as mosquitoes proliferate with the arrival of warm weather.
Mosquitoes carry the disease, picking up the virus from infected
birds and transmitting it to other birds, and to humans, that they
bite. Among other symptoms, West Nile virus can cause encephalitis,
or brain swelling, and older people and people with weakened immune
systems are most susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockland County executive, C. Scott Vanderhoff, issued a
statement Friday reminding residents that people and animals cannot
contract the disease directly from birds. The county health
commissioner, Gabriel R. Guardarramus, urged residents to use
insect repellent, repair broken screens on windows and doors in
their homes, and avoid mosquito habitats _ just about anywhere
water is allowed to pool.
</P>
<P>
   The disease control center is still reviewing New York state's
test results, although federal health officials said they had no
reason to doubt the state's confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of birds from 20 species died from the virus in New
York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Maryland last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's outbreak prompted widespread fear of the virus,
and sweeping efforts by city, county and state health officials to
watch for the disease this year, plus efforts to eradicate the
mosquito population through treatment of mosquito breeding grounds
with larvicide, and campaigns to improve public education.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's cases surfaced much earlier in the year than the first
cases last year, but Ostraff cautioned against any inference that
the disease may be more widespread this summer. ``Last year,'' he
said, ``nobody was looking for the virus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
