<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS GET A WAKE-UP CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Pacers got that bus thing down, but life on
the road found a new hurdle on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A very early one.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 6 a.m. the fire alarm went off at their Santa
Monica hotel. And kept going off.
</P>
<P>
   Rise and shine, Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go out,'' said Pacers forward Jalen Rose. ``I wasn't
going to go out until I saw smoke. I would have been the last one
to leave, trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so for the Pacers' main man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got out,'' said coach Larry Bird. ``I was already up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, of course, no fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Rose said. ``The fire alarm in
the hotel went off, and kept going off. Then somebody got on the
recorder, telling us to follow the fire drill rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another 10, 15 minutes after that, they notified us it was a
false alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers know all about fire alarms on the road during the
Finals, having experienced the same thing in Philadelphia in 1983
and Boston in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion, naturally, is that some local fans thought it
would be a really clever idea to wake the invaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Detroit PSL (Public School League), I've seen all
kinds of tricks,'' Rose said. ``I went to games where they left
some kind of dust on the floor so it will be slippery, or flat
balls, or a losing team trying to tip our bus over. This is a lot
more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of being a road team. You take it as it
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Get outta my face: Bird was never afraid to challenge his
teammates while a member of the Celtics - he spared no one after a
25-point loss to the Lakers in the 1984 Finals - but he's taken
another tactic as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bird said despite the rough loss in Game 1, he did not get in
the face of any Pacer. His comments are reserved for more private
moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individually I talk to them,'' he said. ``But not on the
court. ... You know, these guys are very sensitive. Everything you
say to them, they take to heart. It's always better to do it
one-on-one with this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some coaches that would challenge you in front of the
team, and they get embarrassed by it. But these guys are good if
you bring them in and talk to them one-one-one.''
</P>
<P>
   No second guessing: Forward-center Sam Perkins is expected to
retire after the Finals, but don't look for him to utilize his
degree from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins majored in communications but can't see himself joining
the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said. ``The last thing I can talk about
are other players. The last thing I can do is analyze other guys
and tell them what they're not doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoosierville: The Lakers can expect a different atmosphere when
the series moves to basketball-mad Indiana for the next three
games.
</P>
<P>
   First off, there is the Pacers' new facility, Conseco
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a basketball feel, as opposed to Staples
Center,'' Rose said. ``Staples Center is for basketball, but it's
also for entertainment. They have two teams from the NBA that plays
here, which is a unique situation. From the outside looking in,
it's like a varsity and a JV team.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the general basketball attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Indianapolis at a game, it's a lot different,'' Rose said.
``In L.A. you have people willing to pay $10,000 for a ticket;
celebrities. And rightfully so, this is a great arena in a great
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Indiana being a small-market team, we're more of a unit.
We love our fans, and our fans love us. We come back from a huge
win or a tough loss, we may have fans waiting for us at the
airport. Entire families are Pacer fans, from the baby in the crib
to the grandmother in the rocking chair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
