<SLUG> BC-LABOR-IMMIGRANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS RALLY FOR AMNESTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ National labor union leaders expect more than
10,000 participants in a public forum with state and federal
officials at the Los Angeles Sports Arena to push for amnesty for
millions of undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Saturday is the culmination of a series of similar
town hall discussions on immigrant worker issues sponsored in
recent weeks by unions in New York, Chicago and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, which represents hundreds of thousands of workers
nationwide, made a historic policy shift in February, calling for a
general amnesty for the estimated 6 million undocumented workers
currently living in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, which have not spelled out a specific proposal,
intend to draw attention to the issue during a presidential
election year, especially with recent union contract victories in
Los Angeles, said Eliseo Medina, national vice president of the
Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amnesty would let workers and their families participate
in society and live their dreams,'' Medina said. ``That also allows
them to make a bigger contribution to our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the early 1900s, when most immigrants came from Europe to
look for work, he said, recent years have brought mostly
job-seeking Latinos and Asians, who face tougher obstacles
receiving U.S. residency status.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have in common is that they are often mistreated by
bosses and limited in their possibilities because they lack the
legal rights of residents,'' Medina said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee for
president, has not come out in favor of a general amnesty but
instead proposed expanding current amnesty programs.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the apparent Republican presidential
nominee, has so far been opposed to any amnesty expansion.
</P>
<P>
   While both candidates compete for the key support of Latino
voters nationwide, the amnesty issue could become a deciding factor
in their campaigns leading up to the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new era in friendly government toward unions and
immigrants,'' said Miguel Contreras, secretary-treasurer of the Los
Angeles County Federation of Labor. ``Working people just want the
same rights as everyone else, nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum is scheduled for noon at the Sports Arena in
Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
