u e BC-OBIT-SEGAL-ART-1STLD-     06-10 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SEGAL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE SEGAL, 75, POP SCULPTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to delete last name for Rena and Morris in 4th graf. Inserts
`to' in 3rd sentence of 6th graf.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Segal, whose rough-surfaced casts of actual people
brought a new, often eerie realism to postwar sculpture and made
him one of the most quietly influential artists of his time, died
Friday at his home in South Brunswick, N.J. He was 75 years old and
had lived in South Brunswick for 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Claes Oldenburg, Segal was often considered one of
the pre-eminent sculptors of pop art. But Oldenburg and pop art
painters like Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and James Rosenquist
found inspiration in the products of popular culture, be they
comics, magazine ads, movie-star photographs or hamburgers. In
contrast, Segal fixed his gaze on the ordinary consumers of that
culture, and through his use of the full-body plaster cast he
devised a way to incorporate them into his work virtually warts and
all. His influence can be traced through several generations of
figurative sculpture, some of it cast, some of it meticulously
handmade, by American artists like Duane Hanson, Charles Ray,
Robert Gober, John Ahearn and Kiki Smith.
</P>
<P>
   A casual, approachable man known for his sense of humor, Segal
worked for much of his career in a 300-foot-long former chicken
coop on his family's farm near South Brunswick, N.J. There he
applied Johnson &AMP; Johnson cotton bandages dipped in plaster to the
faces and forms of sundry family members, friends and neighbors.
His wife, Helen, whom he married in 1946, was one of his most
frequent subject models, having first sat for her husband in the
1940s and '50s when he was still a painter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Segal is survived by a daughter, Rena,
of Somerset, N.J., a son, Jeffrey, of Vineland, N.J., and his
brother, Morris, of North Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   To create appropriate settings for his figures, Segal developed
what he called ``assembled environments'' by incorporating, uncast,
props like chairs, tables, beds or a pinball machine; sections of
cars, school buses and even a subway car and a butcher shop window
as well as brick walls, gas pumps and windows. He paired a
full-length portrait of his dealer, Sidney Janis, with one of the
Mondrian paintings that Janis owned. (Janis commissioned the work
and on his death bequeathed it to the Museum of Modern Art.) And
for a 1965-67 portrait of the sculptor John Chamberlain, he showed
the sculptor wielding the chunks of automobile bodies from which
he, Chamberlain, made his own work.
</P>
<P>
   Segal's tableaus were emotionally confounding, at once deeply
familiar in their forms and subjects, yet ghostly and strange in
their stillness. To a great extent, these works had an emotional
resonance that was alien to pop art and that reflected Segal's
beginnings as an expressionist painter. His tableaus also connected
to several long-running artistic traditions, most notably a strain
of understated American realism that included Thomas Eakins, Walker
Evans and Edward Hopper; the 20th-century evolution of collage and
assemblage as practiced by Kurt Schwitters, Joseph Cornell and
Robert Rauschenberg, and finally the history of figurative
sculpture that reached from Rodin back to the Greeks. More than one
observer also likened them to the monochromatic figure casts
created by archaeologists to record the postures of Romans found at
Pompeii.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his career, Segal did not veer too far from
his original and rather simple formula, yet it seemed to be capable
of almost infinite variation and elaboration. He sometimes reduced
his figures to shallow paintinglike reliefs, or zeroed in on his
subjects, making busts, or isolating an arm or leg from which the
viewer extrapolated the body.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1970s, he sometimes painted the figures and
their settings in bright, flat colors, giving them a visual
vibrancy that again reflected his roots in painting. (His painting
background was also manifest in the robustly worked pastels that he
made throughout his career and that occasionally showed up in his
tableaus). The figurative nature of his work also allowed him to
revisit traditional themes, starting with ``The Legend of Lott,''
from 1966 and including a public commission, ``In Memory of May 4,
1970, Kent State: Abraham and Isaac,'' of 1980, at Princeton
University.
</P>
<P>
   Public and outdoor commissions became possible in the 1970s when
he turned to casting in bronze, which he often finished in white to
resemble plaster. Other public works include ``Gay Liberation,'' a
portrayal of two same-sex couples installed in Christopher Park in
Greenwich Village that commemorates the Stonewall riot there; and
``The Holocaust, a work incorporating both standing and fallen
figures and a barbed wire fence created for Golden Gate Park in San
Francisco in 1983. He also created the three large tableaus for the
Franklin Delano Roosevelt Memorial in Washington: ``Depression
Breadline,'' ``Appalachian Farm Couple'' and ``Fireside Chat.''
</P>
<P>
   As these works suggest, a strong sense of social conscience was
another thing that separated Segal from the pop artists.
</P>
<P>
   Segal was born in the Bronx, N.Y., in 1926, the son of Jacob
Segal, whose small Kosher butcher shop his son memorialized in one
of his sculptures. In 1940 he moved with his family to the South
Brunswick farm where he lived until the end of his life. His father
had decided to try his hand at chicken farming.
</P>
<P>
   Segal studied art at the Cooper Union Art School, Pratt
Institute, New York University, Rutgers and the State University of
New Jersey, where he earned a bachelor's degree in art education in
1950 and a master's degree in fine art in 1963. He also studied
with Hans Hofmann and several other Abstract Expressionist
painters, but was untempted. ``I couldn't divorce myself from the
sensual things of life _ things I could touch,'' he later
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Like many artists who came of age in the mid-1950s, Segal began
his career as a painter, edging toward sculpture almost
unconsciously. Pressure came from the dominance of Abstract
Expressionist painting and from a growing interest in reality, in
the potential for using objects and events that existed outside art
that was already evident in the work of Jasper Johns and
Rauschenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Segal may also have been pushed toward reality by his friendship
with Allan Kaprow, one of the inventors of the multimedia events
called Happenings, whom he met at Rutgers. Kaprow staged the first
such event at Segal's farm in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   In that year, Segal began making sculpture out of chicken wire
and plaster. He later wrote that he did so out of ``a need to
achieve my own grasp of pictorial space ... what would happen if I
ventured into real space?'' He hit upon the idea of the plaster
casts in 1960, when one of his students brought him a large supply
of medical scrim used by physicians in making casts for broken
bones. He was his own first subject, having his wife wrap him in
the plaster-soaked gauze, and ended up with a sculpture that he
later titled ``Man at a Table.'' He wasn't quite sure that he was
making sculpture. ``People call what I created sculpture,'' he
wrote. ``But my own reaction to it is as to the presence of man in
his daily life.''
</P>
<P>
   He initially thought that this new process would be direct and
easy, rather like taking a photograph. But he soon found it
necessary to work every square inch of surface of the plaster, not
unlike a painter, both as it was drying on the sitter and
afterward, to get the effect he wanted. In an interview, he once
attributed the unusual emotional reality of his figures to the
fatigue of his models. ``To hold a pose for 40 minutes, you can't
be in a social or artificial posture,'' he said. ``Then the body
reveals certain truths about itself.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, Segal had had several solo shows at the Hansa
Gallery, an artists' cooperative near 57th Street. He had met with
little success and resigned himself to a life of teaching art. But
his new sculpture caught on. In 1960 he had the first of three solo
shows at the Green Gallery, run by the perceptive dealer Richard
Bellamy, who showed younger artists interested in bringing new
physical realities to their work. They included Oldenburg and
Chamberlain, and also Dan Flavin, Donald Judd, Yayoi Kusama, Lee
Bontecou and Lucas Samaras.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 Segal was included in ``New Realists,'' an important
group show that helped anoint pop art, at the Sidney Janis Gallery.
From 1965 onward, he was represented by the Janis Gallery. He was
soon successful enough to give up teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Segal was the recipient of many awards and honors, including the
Premium Imperiale from Japan, which he received in 1998, and a
National Medal of the Arts, in 1999. The list of museums that own
his work, nearly three pages long and divided according to
continents, attests to the broad appeal of his art. As he put it,
``I count heavily on the human ability to spot metaphor. The urge
to read poetry into things is universal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
