<SLUG> BC-ROYALS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBOULET TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK KAEGEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ It was Buck Night but not the Bucs' night.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Reboulet's one-out single drove in Rey Sanchez in the 10th
inning, giving the Royals a 6-5 interleague victory Friday night
over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing like this all year,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many have we won like that? Ten, 11, 12? I don't know how
many.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the 14th time the Royals have won in their last at-bat
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good change from last year, I think,'' said Royals starter
Jeff Suppan.
</P>
<P>
   Sure is. That's two more of the derring-do wins than the club
had all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a typical Royals game,'' said Mike Sweeney, who had
four hits, including a homer.
</P>
<P>
   It provided a nice dessert for 30,963 fans after they'd wolfed
down $1 hot dogs, peanuts and soft drinks. They groaned when,
before the ninth inning, an announcement was made that the usual
fireworks display was canceled because of dry, windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pirates' Brian Giles quickly provided fireworks of his
own, smashing closer Jerry Spradlin's first pitch into the
waterfall in right-center field, an estimated 440 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Giles' second homer of the game created a 5-5 tie.
</P>
<P>
   So into the 10th they battled. Sanchez opened the inning with a
double to left field against left-hander Jason Christiansen. Johnny
Damon advanced him with a sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Christiansen,'' Royals manager Tony Muser said.
``Johnny hasn't been extremely hot, and I wanted to get the guy to
third base because there are more ways to score from third than
from second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do the little things to help us win. That's the
way we're going to do it, and we've got people who don't mind doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The count went full on Reboulet, and he suspected he'd get a
pitch to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``On 3-2, I'm always looking for anything,'' Reboulet said,
``but I felt like they were going to come after me with Mike
(Sweeney) and Jermaine (Dye) hitting behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reboulet stroked a single into short right field, and the Royals
had their ninth walk-off win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of dorked it out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first four-RBI game in Reboulet's nine-year career.
He cleared the bases with a double in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reboulet is a hero tonight,'' Muser said. ``Many people
thought that with Carlos Febles being hurt, that we were going to
miss out on something. Jeff is a veteran player who has filled in
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney had a four-hit game for the fifth time this year and
launched his 13th homer against Pirates starter Jason Schmidt. But
Sweeney bowed in Reboulet's direction after this latest thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of the unlikely hero,'' Sweeney said. ``He came
through when we needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   All four runs in the Royals' fourth were unearned after first
baseman Kevin Young couldn't handle Damon's bouncer, which would
have been the third out. Instead the bases were loaded. Reboulet
grounded a double past third base and then scored on Sweeney's
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play that Kevin usually makes,'' Pirates manager Gene
Lamont said. ``If he does, we get out of the inning. But if we get
Reboulet out, then we'd have been out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has 61 RBIs in 59 games, and no Royal in history has
gotten to the 60-mark quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Giles each homered off Suppan, who went seven innings.
He gave up seven hits but no walks. The Pirates got their fourth
run off Jose Santiago. Spradlin was charged with his third blown
save _ the team's 15th against 14 saves _ but wound up with his
second victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals are 12-6 in one-run games this season, giving them
one more victory in that category than they had last year. They
were only 11-32 in one-run games in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Muser, as usual, was thinking of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we won the game because I know they were disappointed
about the fireworks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
