<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0101 &Cx1f; kan-z
b x BC-TERE-KAN &LR;      06-10 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Plan to send Robinson to prison in 1985 backfired  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ As detectives searched in 1985 for clues to the fate
of Lisa Stasi, who disappeared with her infant daughter shortly
after meeting John Edward Robinson Sr., they found another woman
they hoped could help them send Robinson to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But because they feared that the woman _ Teresa L. Williams, 21
_ might be in danger, they hid her and wouldn't let Robinson's
lawyer talk to her out of concern that Robinson would learn her
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that maneuver backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who was on probation at the time in a white-collar
crime, now is charged in Johnson County with sexually assaulting
two women, and authorities have linked him to the disappearance of
three women besides Stasi and the discovery in the last week of
five women's bodies in barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi, 19, was last seen after Robinson put her up in an
Overland Park motel as part of what he called charity for young,
single mothers and their babies, according to investigators'
records at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Her disappearance led to an investigation by two FBI agents and
Robinson's probation officer into allegations of drugs, guns and
prostitution. Officials suspected Robinson might have sold her
5-month-old baby.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, one of the women authorities talked to in the
investigation, appeared to be in such danger that they hid her from
Robinson, thus preventing Robinson's lawyer from subpoenaing her
for a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   A Missouri appeals court later ruled that by hiding the key
witness against Robinson in the probation violation case,
prosecutors and investigators had violated his constitutional
rights to confront his accuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be the least doubt that the actions of the
probation officer and the FBI agents denied (Robinson) due process
rights,'' judges on the Missouri Court of Appeals' Western District
wrote in July 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's victory was short-lived, however. He soon was
convicted for fraud in Johnson County and was imprisoned in Kansas.
That conviction violated his Clay County probation. At the
conclusion of his Kansas sentence in 1991, he returned to prison in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 investigation into Robinson is detailed in area court
files.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Robinson was on probation from a 1981 felony
conviction in Clay County, where he had pleaded guilty to stealing
a $6,000 check from Guy's Foods in Liberty when he was a personnel
manager there.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that Williams had been living in an apartment
at 8110 Troost Ave. that Robinson rented for her. During interviews
with her in June 1985, she told probation officer Stephen Haymes
that Robinson had both guns and marijuana, a probation violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She states that approximately two weeks after she began living
at the apartment rented by Robinson, he brought to her a half bag
of marijuana and gave it to her,'' Haymes wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also told the probation officer that Robinson carried a
pistol in a shoulder holster and showed a disturbing tendency for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robinson threatened her with the handgun and sexually
assaulted her with the handgun,'' Haymes wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams told investigators about a diary she was
fabricating under Robinson's instructions that made them fear for
her safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the diary, which Williams said Robinson gave her with orders
to transcribe it in her own writing, Williams was to discredit a
man who was going to testify against Robinson in the probation
revocation hearing. It was supposed to end on June 15, 1985, with
an entry about her fear that something would happen to her, and
instructions for Robinson's attorney to receive the diary and
property she had in a safe-deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes' report notes a promise to the woman: ``Williams states
that Robinson told her he was going to take her to the Bahamas on
6-14-85 and that her belongings would be put in storage.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators quickly moved Williams to a new apartment and
ultimately bought her a plane ticket out of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It...appears that (Robinson) has continued to use people to
his own end, including Ms. Williams, with whom there is concern for
her safety...,'' Haymes wrote in a June 1985 probation report.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes declined to comment this week, but a woman identifying
herself as Teresa L. Williams called /{The Kansas City Star/}
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   She asked for information about the case and suggested that the
newspaper buy her story. She was told that /{The Star/}'s policy
does not allow payment for news information.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had started a new life since leaving Kansas City
and expressed concern for her safety, questioning the ability of
authorities to keep Robinson in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Before she ended the brief conversation, she said, ``I had
nightmares for life about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 probe intensified when investigators learned that
Robinson had contact with Stasi before she vanished earlier that
year. But FBI agents Tom Lavin and Jeff Dancer could not
conclusively link Robinson to Stasi's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Bruce Houdek, who represented Robinson, argued for the
right to interview Williams in motions to Clay County Circuit Judge
John Hutcherson, who since has retired. Her written statements,
which Houdek had been given, were vague and inconsistent, Houdek
contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Investigators) were just hiding her,'' Houdek said Friday.
``(Her written statements) were all over the place. She was a very
unreliable person, and they didn't want to pin her down. The FBI
couldn't make a case against him, and they took the easy way out by
getting his probation revoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Houdek said he never considered Robinson dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutcherson also was concerned about Williams' safety. This
week, the retired judge said that had he required Williams to give
an interview, she may have been compelled to disclose her new
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let (Robinson) have that address,''
Hutcherson said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hutcherson used Williams' testimony in court to revoke
Robinson's probation in July 1985, the appeals court reversed his
decision the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County Prosecutor Don Norris, who helped file the initial
stealing charges against Robinson in 1981, said authorities always
had a bad feeling about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that the officers said this guy is dangerous and we
need to put him away,'' Norris said this week. ``We filed the
charges and tried to accomplish that. We had a suspicion about this
guy, and now, years later, we hear there may be something to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
