<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX PREPARER'S SHARES SINK TO THREE-YEAR LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Shares in H&AMP;R Block Inc. fell to their lowest levels
in more than three years Friday before recouping some of the loss
by the end of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City-based diversified tax preparer and financial
services provider warned investors after markets closed Thursday
that profits for the fiscal year 2000 may be almost 20 cents a
share lower than analysts had been forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy selling when the markets opened Friday dropped the price
of Block shares to 26 a share, down more than 4 points from
Thursday's close and to levels last seen in November 1996. By the
end of trading Friday, shares had rebounded to close at 28, down 2
</P>
<P>
   Block said Thursday profits would be lower than expected partly
because of overstaffing at its more than 9,000 U.S. tax offices
when a surge of last-minute taxpayers failed to materialize. Block
also attributed the profit setback to a change in the way it
accounts for the cost of assets it acquired last year and a
one-time loss connected to mortgage operations it sold.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives said they expect earnings for the fiscal year
that ended April 30 to be the equivalent of somewhere between $2.52
and $2.55 a share when final numbers are tallied and released June
21.
</P>
<P>
   The expected profits are still larger than the equivalent of
$2.36 a share Block earned in fiscal 1999, but well below the
$2.72-a-share range Wall Street anticipated before the warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers were disappointing, particularly because this is
the second time Block has come to the well,'' said Michael Millman,
an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Block warned investors six weeks ago that it expected pretax
losses on its fledgling e-commerce operations would be about $18
million, or twice what analysts previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses and the additional profit-trimming costs disclosed
Thursday are widely regarded as growing pains resulting from
Block's rapid diversification into mortgage lending, investment
brokering and other financial services in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been punished more than adequately,'' Millman said.
``Their basic business continues to be strong. They've learned a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Prestopino, an analyst at Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull in
Chicago, said he thought investors overreacted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those situations where the glass is half empty
or half full,'' Prestopino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The encouraging news is that it now appears the company is
going to go back and re-evaluate how it's going to spend money in
the future,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
