<SLUG> BC-CLAMP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHER OF MISSING WOMAN RECALLS HER ATTEMPT AT NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Catherine Clampitt moved to Overland Park, Kan., from
Wichita Falls, Texas, in 1987 to start a new life with her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Months after what was to be a new beginning, she disappeared
without a note, phone call or goodbye. This week, authorities told
her family that they are actively investigating her missing person
case once again after finding two bodies in barrels on the property
of Clampitt's former employer, John Edward Robinson Sr., and three
more bodies in barrels in his Raymore storage locker.
</P>
<P>
   The news gave Clampitt's brother, Robert Bales of Lenexa, the
chills.
</P>
<P>
   ``A flush went over me. I knew that name,'' he said, referring
to Robinson. ``I never will forget it, not in my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Bales heard that authorities had found
women's bodies on a piece of property in Linn County, Kan., but he
didn't pay attention until he heard Robinson's name. Bales
remembered that his sister had worked for Robinson's company, Equi
II.
</P>
<P>
   The task force investigating the Robinson case initially
released Clampitt's name as ``Katherine Clampet'' but on Friday
confirmed the new spellings.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed in the deaths of the women found in
the barrels. Robinson has been charged with aggravated sexual
battery and felony theft relating to sadomasochistic sexual
encounters with two women he met on the Internet. He is being held
in Johnson County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Bales said he picked up Clampitt at the Kansas City bus station
on a January night in 1987. She needed a fresh start, and Bales and
his wife had agreed to take her in.
</P>
<P>
   She left Texas to escape drugs and drinking, but starting over
meant leaving her young son, Ryan, now 16, behind in her parents'
custody, her mother said Friday in a telephone interview from
Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came up here to get away from the crowd,'' Bales said.
</P>
<P>
   Clampitt was born in Korea but grew up in Texas after she was
adopted by Bales' mother. Bales described his petite sister as an
intelligent woman with a wild side.
</P>
<P>
   Once she arrived, Bales lined up interviews for his sister, and
she began looking for a job. Clampitt discovered Equi II through a
newspaper ad, Bales said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It promised a great job, a lot of traveling and a new
wardrobe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bales said it did seem a little far-fetched to him and his wife,
but Clampitt was 27 and old enough to make her own decision, they
decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a grown lady; you don't lock her in a room and say you
can't come out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once she started working, Clampitt traveled often and would
sometimes stay at local hotels for several nights at a time. When
she didn't return for weeks, Bales called police.
</P>
<P>
   Bales said he spent eight months investigating her
disappearance. He put together a file of receipts, pictures and
anything he could.
</P>
<P>
   He became consumed with finding his sister. He called Robinson's
office often and at one point took to staking out the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew I was looking for her,'' Bales said of Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   He said that police talked to Robinson but that there wasn't
enough evidence to connect him to Clampitt's disappearance in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Now the family will wait as police continue the latest
investigation. Bales turned over his file to police this week, and
Clampitt's mother also gave police more identification.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, Bales said, he didn't expect to find Clampitt alive,
but he never gave up hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritually, emotionally, I always had hoped she was flying
over Europe or Asia,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
