<SLUG> BC-JOHN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER SUSPECT LINKED TO FORMER PRISON LIBRARIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By By SCOTT CANON and TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Police are investigating the 1994 disappearance of
Beverly Bonner, a former Cameron, Mo., woman who may have met John
Edward Robinson Sr. when she worked in a prison library.
</P>
<P>
   She may also have rented a storage unit where barrels containing
three bodies were found Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cass County Prosecutor Chris Koster said one of the leads
investigators were following involved the statement Robinson
reportedly made to a worker at Stor-Mor For Less in Raymore that he
was storing furniture for ``Beverly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was renting the space for his sister,'' in
addition to at least one unit for himself, said a worker Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also remarked to storage workers that the sister was
enjoying herself traveling so much she might never come back.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who is being held in connection with bodies found on
his property in Linn County and in Stor-Mor units he rented, has
two sisters, but neither is named Beverly.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's second husband, physician William Bonner of Stockton,
Mo., was also contacted by investigators from Raymore and the task
force probing the allegations against Robinson. William Bonner said
he suspects that Beverly Bonner came to know Robinson well when the
two worked in the Western Missouri Correctional Center library in
Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner dropped out of sight after coming to the Kansas City
area. Following a pattern of missing women linked in various ways
to Robinson, she told friends that she had an excellent job
prospect, in this case a job that would take her abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonner's case, however, she would have known that Robinson
had a criminal background. Her former husband, who worked as a
physician at the facility, recalled Robinson and remembered talking
with his wife about him.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was serving time for a probation violation after being
convicted of felony theft from Guys Foods in 1981. He was released
in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very gregarious, outgoing, friendly,'' William Bonner
said. ``He came across well-spoken grammatically. He seemed like a
businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner suspects Beverly visited Robinson in the Kansas City area
after his release. When she left Cameron after their 1994 divorce,
Bonner sent monthly checks to a post office box in Olathe, but he
said he did not know why a woman ostensibly working overseas for a
Chicago company would need money sent to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   He has not seen his ex-wife since they both left Cameron.
Acquaintances told him that they thought at one time she was in a
Scandinavian country, but he hasn't heard from her since 1994.
Movers told him that her belongings were to be stored in a Raymore
storage locker, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was living in Belton at the time. Nancy Jo Robinson,
his wife, managed the Southfork Mobile Home Community and they
resided at 464 Valeen Lane from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Former neighbors said they saw little of the Robinsons. Kathy
Reed said she would occasionally see his wife because she worked in
the manager's office, but rarely saw him.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Stor-Mor said Nancy Jo Robinson rented the first unit
in November 1992. John Robinson Sr. rented others in November 1992
and May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The facility's owner said he never saw Robinson and never
suspected anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did, I would have called the police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, the Stor-Mor worker said, first inquired about
Robinson's wife about three months ago. She said Friday that
investigators had asked her not to comment further on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Elston and Mary Gann had become close friends with Beverly
Bonner during her years in Cameron. After she left, they mailed a
letter to a Kansas address she had left with them. It was returned
to sender.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Bonner has two sons from her first marriage, both of
whom lived with their father in Kansas City, North, after the end
of her second marriage. Randy, the eldest, died in December 1995.
She did not attend his funeral, said one person who did.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison, who has been
leading the investigation, declined to comment on Bonner's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing anything on that this weekend,'' Morrison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators Friday afternoon finished searching Robinson's
16-acre lot west of La Cygne, Kan., but found little to help build
a case, said Linn County Sheriff Marvin Stites.
</P>
<P>
   The sealed barrels recovered from the storage units Monday
contained three sets of human remains. Earlier they found two
similar barrels at the Robinson property in Linn County.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been held since June 2, but has not been charged
with murder in any of the set of remains. Authorities said they
have identified only one body, that of Suzette Marie Trouten.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the Johnson County judge assigned to hear the
sexual assault case pending against Robinson issued an order
outlining what police and prosecutors can say to the media.
</P>
<P>
   District Judge John Anderson III met in his chambers at the
courthouse in Olathe Friday morning with Regional Defender Byron
Cerrillo and Morrison before issuing the order.
</P>
<P>
   While some reports have referred to it as a ``gag order,''
Friday's action is a reiteration of the rules that attorneys in a
criminal case are required to follow in every case.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, the court also received Robinson's signed
affidavit to show that he qualifies for the court-appointed
attorney he requested during his initial court appearance on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, Robinson has been unemployed for at
least the last 12 months and receives $1,021 a month in Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He owns land that is valued at $28,000, according to the
affidavit. It does not state if that refers to the field in Linn
County, where two bodies were found last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 investigators will continue to work through the
weekend, although each has the option of taking one day off. They
have received countless calls, and still ask anyone with
information to call the task force at (913) 477-7633 or toll-free
from out of the area at (877) 732-6322.
 &LR; tag1:The Star's Tony Rizzo, Richard Espinoza and Matt Stearns
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 0126EDT &QL; 
