<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-MILLER-LAD     06-10 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-MILLER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING IN ACTION _ AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The work in progress that is Reggie Miller in the
NBA Finals took its next step Friday in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The results: Slight improvement, but not enough to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't New York, and Spike Lee isn't in the Staples Center
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one expected Miller, late of Riverside High and UCLA,
to duplicate his 1-for-16 performance in Game 1, and he didn't,
scoring 21 points on 7-of-16 shooting. He had his first field goal
after just 41 seconds, a far cry from Wednesday, when he went
scoreless in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the fourth period - crunch time, Miller's time, if you
will - Miller was as invisible as he was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When the fourth period began, the Lakers led 73-69 and Miller
had 19 points. With 1:14 to play, Miller made two free throws,
ending a scoring drought that began after he scored a field goal
with 4:47 left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Since Miller didn't score another field goal, that's more than
15 minutes without a point and 16:47 without a field goal. He
attempted just two shots in the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird said it wasn't anything the Lakers did
on Miller in the fourth period. Rather, others were taking care of
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalen (Rose) was doing most of the scoring, and Austin had a
good game,'' Bird said. ``We had enough firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before Game 2, Miller said he felt the need to carry his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a good job of performing in the Milwaukee, Philly
and New York series,'' he said. ``Now that we're in the bigger
stage, you know, I feel I have to play my absolute best to help
this team beat a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen Friday night, nor did it happen this season at
Staples. With Ron Harper shadowing Miller, Miller had difficulty
getting open.
</P>
<P>
   This was in contrast to Game 1, when Miller got several open
looks but couldn't sink the shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers knew Miller would come out shooting, and he did,
scoring eight points, mostly from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   But when he picked up his second foul in the first period, to
the bench he went, and he only played half of the first half. He
had two points in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie got off to a great start,'' Bird said. ``Too bad he
picked up that cheap foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller wasn't surprised Harper defended him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great defender because he plays great position
defense,'' Miller said before Game 2. ``As you know, covering
Chicago and throughout the series we had with them two years ago
.... him, Kobe and even Brian Shaw, all three play great position
defense. Every time I made a move, (Harper) was right there. You
have to give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   So back to Indianapolis they go for Sunday. Miller said he
believes the Pacers have the confidence to make the series
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe shoot as if he were in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to make adjustments, which we do,'' he said. ``And
we'll let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
