<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Even in death, togetherness marked two teens  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The parents of Katherine Kreisel and Cally Mullins
loved that the girls were together so much. The high school
sophomores often spent weekends at each others' homes or, as on
June 3, hanging out in Sedalia.
</P>
<P>
   But when Jim Kreisel learned that his daughter was killed in a
car wreck, his first hope was that Mullins wasn't with her. She
was. Both girls died in a collision with a suspected drunken driver
who was driving north in the southbound lane.
</P>
<P>
   Kreisel and Mullins, both 16, were buried Friday in a joint
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone says that we've lost a daughter, we consider it
like we've lost two. They were that close,'' Jim Kreisel said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' lifelong bond had created an extended family among
their relatives who found some peace by sharing their grief.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Cole Camp, 110 miles southeast of Kansas City,
offered support, too. In a town of about 1,000 residents, more than
500 mourners attended the funeral in the high school gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of mourning, their families also have found
surprising solace in the girls' friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives reminisce about the zest with which Kreisel and
Mullins lived. They can picture the girls driving home on U.S. 65
that final night. The music surely was blaring. They surely were
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Now their relatives are glad they were together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a comfort to know that,'' said Kreisel's sister
Jennifer. ``They were always laughing, yapping. You know that's
what they were doing just before they hit. You know that their last
few seconds were happy.''  &LR; brk:`We're all feeling this'
 &LR; tx:Friendships last in Cole Camp. The mothers of Kreisel and
Mullins went to high school together. So did their fathers. The
girls' friendship began at age 3 in the Sunday school of Trinity
Lutheran Church.
</P>
<P>
   The families still have a picture of their kindergarten
graduation. Both wore the same style dress _ one in blue, one in
pink.
</P>
<P>
   As the girls grew up, their interests diverged.
</P>
<P>
   Kreisel, the musical one, played in three school bands. She was
a cheerleader and joined the math and science clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins, the athletic one, played on the volleyball, basketball
and softball teams. She also served as sophomore class treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Their parents said they supported each other _ no matter what.
Relatives can't recall them ever fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they compacted a lifetime into 16 years,'' said
Tom Smith, Mullins' stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night so many residents attended a prayer service
that it took nearly an hour for them to file into the gym. About
150 plants and flower displays surrounded the girls' matching
caskets.
</P>
<P>
   Students wrote farewells on two paper banners stretched across
cafeteria tables. ``I know you will be watching over us all,'' one
wrote. Another lamented: ``I'll just never get to see that smile of
yours anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every student knows every other student here. It's not like
Kansas City where you have 1,200 kids, somebody dies and you might
know them,'' Principal William Smart said. ``All of my students
know who Cally and Katherine are. We're all feeling this.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding the service in the gymnasium was bittersweet. The
spacious facility, which one resident compared to an NBA arena, was
completed in mid-May after months of anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Kreisel and Mullins were looking forward to cheering and playing
in the new gym. Mullins proudly proclaimed that her volleyball team
would be the first squad to compete in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hoped and anticipated coming to this gymnasium,'' the
Rev. Randal Ehrichs told mourners. ``They couldn't have anticipated
coming here together under these circumstances.''  &LR; brk:Anger mixed
with grief  &LR; tx:Ehrichs tried to comfort the grieving by saying they
should be filled with joy that the girls are with God. The families
can accept that, but feel nothing but anger toward the man who
caused the fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   In November the license of Dale R. McCaslin, 43, was suspended
for an alcohol violation. State records show that he didn't have a
valid Missouri license.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol says McCaslin was driving north in the
southbound lane of U.S. 65. His car struck Mullins' Ford Escort as
it reached the top of a hill. She had no chance to swerve.
</P>
<P>
   McCaslin was arrested for driving while intoxicated. He died in
a Columbia hospital two days after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol has not released results of blood-alcohol
tests, even to the girls' families. But relatives say troopers told
them of finding a fifth of Jack Daniels in McCaslin's car. Most of
it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to have this Christian attitude when he has
taken something so precious,'' said Kreisel's mother, Gail.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives hope to start a Students Against Drunk Driving chapter
at the high school. Donations are filling jars in businesses all
over town.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the families turn again to the girls' friendship for
inspiration. In recent days, they've come across letters and notes
between the two. Almost every one closes with ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   And Verna Smith, Mullins' mother, can't help but think back to
the trooper's description of the accident scene.
</P>
<P>
   He told Smith that the girls' bodies were found on top of each
other, forming the shape of a cross. Smith and other relatives see
this as a sign that God was with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Just as comforting, Kreisel and Mullins had each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went through this world together. They were lost
together,'' Tom Smith said. ``We're not happy that this happened,
but if they had to be with someone, we all would have wanted it
this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
