<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMONS-IMPORTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE CITRUS TO ENTER 34 STATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID GREENBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ The U.S. Department of Agriculture announced
it has approved a controversial policy that allows the import of
Argentine citrus into 34 U.S. states that do not grow the produce.
</P>
<P>
   Local growers and industry leaders blasted the ruling, claiming
the imports will come from areas infested with crop-destroying
diseases and pests. Ventura County would be particularly vulnerable
because of its strong tourism base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we're concerned about is citrus canker,'' said
Ventura County Agricultural Commissioner Earl McPhail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that, with the lack of inspections down there,
fruits can get commingled and then get shipped out as if it came
from a pest- and disease-free area. The last I heard, the USDA had
one inspector down (in Argentina).''
</P>
<P>
   ``People bring illegal fruits and vegetables into California all
the time. If it's contaminated, we have a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 acres of lemons, Valencia and naval oranges, and a
small amount of grapefruit are grown in Ventura, Oxnard and the
Santa Clara Valley. Citrus constitutes approximately 30 percent of
the county's $955 million agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA made its ruling behind closed doors Thursday, after
more than a year of often-heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will implement a three-phase plan, with the first
allowing for the immediate importation of lemons, oranges and
grapefruit to 34 states.
</P>
<P>
   Phase two will begin in May 2002, when imports will be allowed
into ``buffer'' states of Alabama, Arkansas, Colorado, Georgia,
Mississippi, Nevada, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Oregon and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine citrus would be allowed into California and the rest
of the continental United States when phase three begins in May
2004.
</P>
<P>
   USDA spokeswoman Sue McCalley said Friday that Argentina has
implemented stringent risk mitigation measures to prevent rotten
fruit entering the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pest mitigation measures at each level to ensure the
fruit doesn't have any pests that can come into the United
States,'' she said. Industry experts acknowledged that damaged
produce arriving in the United States would be tossed out before it
is placed on supermarket shelves. But they also questioned whether
Argentina's inspection process is adequate to prevent bad citrus
from being shipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think science has taken a back seat to trade politics,''
said Joel Nelson, a board member of the U.S. Citrus Science
Council, an ad hoc group of lemon producers who oppose the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fruit disease) is a communicable disease. It can come on
brush, clothing, in the air and the bottoms of shoes. You could be
transmitting the disease. The USDA's science is inadequate. And if
they are wrong, we're the ones who suffer the consequences,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Oxnard, and U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., will monitor the effects of the policy, their aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stance is that if they are going to import fruit in the
United States, that it be disease-free,'' said Tom Pfeifer,
spokesman for Gallegly. ``He has been in constant conversations
with Dan Glickman, secretary of agriculture, to make sure the
proper steps have been taken.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
