<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-RATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY JOBLESS RATE EDGES DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Southern California's economy shook off the
effects of an actor's strike during May as unemployment drifted
down 0.2 percentage points on an annual basis, the state said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's unemployment rate dipped to 5.6 percent in Los
Angeles County from 5.8 percent in May 1999, the California
Employment Development Department said Friday. The rate was 5.5
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the jobless rate fell to 5 percent from 5.3 percent a
year ago. The statewide rate was 4.8 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment has been low for months, but the surprise in May
came from the motion picture sector, which added 7,200 jobs on a
monthly basis even though the Screen Actors Guild struck commercial
production companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the heck was the SAG strike?'' wondered Jack Kyser,
chief economist for the Los Angeles County Economic Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good, solid growth report for L.A. County.''
</P>
<P>
   The only sour note locally was the aerospace sector, which is
down 11,000 jobs on an annual basis. However, that trend could
start reversing later this year when SR Tecnics of Switzerland
opens a facility in Palmdale that could employ up to 6,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, by the end of the year, we will see some
stabilization,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Total nonfarm employment grew by 31,400 jobs from April to May.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that unemployment in the Los Angeles/Long Beach area
rose slightly on a monthly basis was not unexpected or troubling,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 12 months, the county has added 91,800
nonagricultural jobs, with 38,500 of them government-related.
</P>
<P>
   However, 14,200 of those jobs were temporary positions added
last month because of the 2000 Census, said Bill Freed, a state
labor market analyst who tracks the region.
</P>
<P>
   The state and county numbers followed the same trend as the
national numbers released a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, May's unemployment rate was 4.1 percent, slightly
lower than the 4.2 percent rate a year ago and up from 3.9 percent
in April.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
