<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 9 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-FOOD (Tumen, China) _ In the last month, North Korea's
reclusive leader has made historic overtures to the outside world,
but his new international openness springs in part from ongoing
domestic tragedy: His government has been unable or unwilling to
solve by itself Korea's desperate longstanding food crisis. Five
years into food shortages that experts say have killed up to 2
million people, death rates in Korea are dropping. But that is
largely because of Western food aid, and because North Koreans have
themselves developed survival strategies to blunt the lethal impact
of what U.N. experts have called a ``slow-motion famine.'' By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-RACE (Tsakane, South Africa) _ For years, the country
girl wished she could wiggle out of her skin and shed her color
like the molting snakes that rustled through the green fields. It
was the 1960s and she was the daughter of white Afrikaners, who
proudly supported the government's brutal system of apartheid and
racial segregation. But for Sandra Laing, it was hard to swallow
the message of hate. Her birth certificate said she was white, but
when she looked in the mirror, she saw a honey brown face framed by
a halo of kinky-curly hair. For a time, the Laings ignored the
whispers about the African blood many suspected flowed through
their veins. But by age 15, Sandra Laing had been expelled from her
all-white school and disowned by her humiliated parents, and her
story had become the country's most harrowing example of a family
destroyed by the crushing weight of apartheid. The saga should have
faded into the yellowing pages of forgotten newspapers. But about
eight months ago, Laing drove home for the first time in nearly 30
years, accompanied by a documentary filmmaker, and what she saw
became prime-time news. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-GAYS (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ After legislation on
rights for gays languished for three years, the government has
issued an executive order approving same-sex unions, the first
nation in Latin America to do so. This comes in a nation that has
one of the highest rates of anti-gay crimes, but where cities and
counties have been increasingly approving gay-rights ordinances. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-ASSESS (Washington) _ News Analysis: A
consideration of whether congressional interest in campaign finance
reform represents a fundamental change or an accident that will be
quickly undone. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (New York) _ By now, many Americans can claim at
least a passing familiarity with the 14th Dalai Lama, the exiled
spiritual and political leader of Tibet. He was well enough known,
for example, to have drawn an audience in the tens of thousands for
a public teaching he gave in Central Park last August. And, perhaps
more to the point, he has had a book, ``The Art of Happiness''
(Riverhead), on the best-seller lists for well over a year. But how
many know of the 41st Sakya Trizin, supreme head of one of Tibetan
Buddhism's four traditions, or schools? He has just embarked on a
three-month teaching visit to the United States and Canada that
began this week in New York. ``He's second only in importance to
the Dalai Lama,'' said Jeff Watt, a translator of Tibetan texts. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-II (Andover, Mass.) _ A special report: Gov. George W.
Bush's prep days were in most respects supremely undistinguished,
and anyone hoping to find reassurance about his candidacy through
signs of great intellect in those years will be disappointed. Yet
there was one important area where young George did excel: people
skills. It was in high school that he first seemed to cultivate
them, using the tactics that carved out an identity for himself, an
identity that is more subdued today but otherwise intact. By
Nicholas D. Kristof. (A shorter version, BUSH-BIO-II-ABRIDGED, has
also moved.)
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 18,19,20,21.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-WINDOWS (Seattle) _ A spectrum of events now taking
place in the computer industry suggests that whether Microsoft wins
or loses its appeal of the antitrust ruling that could break the
company in two, its world has changed. Some of the changes are
linked to a growing belief that because the software publisher is
under government scrutiny it has found it more difficult to flex
its industry might. Others are linked to the emergence of new
consumer markets ranging from handheld computing to digital
streaming media where the so-called Wintel standard is now seen as
a handicap. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ If the United States' bionic economy
has a soft underbelly, it may be trade. As Americans gorge on
imported cars, electronics, clothing and a long list of other goods
from abroad, the nation's trade deficit has swollen to record
proportions, leaving economists and policy-makers increasingly
concerned. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Two years after suffering
a calamitous economic downturn, Indonesia is springing back to
life. But the revival has been obscured by political instability in
Jakarta. Few other countries, for example, could report a 36
percent increase in exports in the first four months of 2000 and
then watch their stock markets sink to the lowest level of the
year. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE/ARTS (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FREUD-TRANSLATIONS (Undated) _ Sigmund Freud's theory of
psychoanalysis has been revised from the moment it was conceived.
Now Freud's very words (at least as they have been rendered in
English) are being revised in several new translations that will
appear in the next few years. The Freud dispute centers on
copyright law, the fine points of translation and the meaning of
Freud's work itself. By Robert S. Boynton.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT 15.)
</P>
<P>
   COLD-WAR-SPYING (Undated) _ In the years since the breakup of
the Soviet Union and the opening of its secret files, much has been
learned about the accomplishments of Soviet spies in the United
States. But lest Americans are left with the uncomfortable notion
that their country remained passively at the mercy of traitors, new
studies are drawing attention to huggermugger by the Western allies
after World War II. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   LIVESEY-NOVEL (Undated) _ In a recent interview about her new
novel, ``The Missing World,'' Margot Livesey said, ``Writing a
novel about amnesia in the age of the memoir has a certain
appeal.'' By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-LAWRENCE (Undated) _ Painter Jacob Lawrence, whose stark
images in bold colors illuminated the black experience in paintings
like the celebrated ``Migration'' series, died Friday. He was 82.
By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 23, 25.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SEGAL (Undated) _ George Segal, whose rough-surfaced casts
of actual people brought a new, often eery realism to postwar
sculpture and made him one of the most influential artists of the
second half of the century, died Friday at his home in South
Brunswick, N.J. He was 75. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
