<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-10 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERSITY AN UNWELCOME VISITOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A sickeningly familiar face from days gone by made
the Staples Center scene Friday. Pamela Anderson Lee didn't create
as much of a stir parading to her courtside seat as did this tawdry
vixen, who had clung to the Lakers like a groupie in seasons past.
</P>
<P>
   She had been conspicuously absent this year, not that anybody
missed her. So unwelcome a sight was she that heads naturally
turned and gasps punctured the silence that greeted her when she
made her grand entrance to Game 2 of the NBA Finals between the
Pacers and the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived late, of course. The game was nearly nine minutes
old when Adversity looked at the startled faces on the Lakers bench
and breathed,``I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Adversity, like so many other two-bit players in this city, is
famous for her multitude of disguises. This time she took the form
of a sprained ankle that Kobe Bryant suffered when his left foot
rolled over one of Jalen Rose's feet as Bryant was touching down
after launching a perfect strike from 17 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant crumpled to the court as though he had been shot and was
writhing in pain in full view of the Lakers' bench as the Pacers
pushed the ball upcourt and Austin Croshere put up an errant shot.
Bryant was still struggling to stand when his starting backcourt
mate, Ron Harper, drove for a layup a few feet away from him after
receiving a pass from Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, limping so noticeably the 18,997 spectators ached, made
it to the bench and was promptly shepherded to the locker room for
X-rays by trainer Gary Vitti. By the end of the night, the results
were in and they were as good as the Lakers could have hoped for:
Bryant's X-rays came back negative and the Lakers took an injurious
situation and turned it into a positive, defeating the Pacers
111-104 to take a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a village to replace Bryant, who had four assists, one
blocked shot and one defensive rebound when he went down. One by
one, the bodies stepped forward to fill the void: Harper had 21
points, 13 more than his postseason average. His aim was so true,
it looked for a while as though he was going to score his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shifted back into Cleveland mode tonight,'' said Bryant of
Harper, alluding to the latter's days as the Cavaliers' go-to guy
in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Glen Rice, who missed seven of eight shots in
Game 1 and had finished with single-digit scoring in four of the
Lakers' previous seven games dating back to Game 2 of their Western
Conference final against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Rice strung together 13 points by halftime and finished with 21
points, reminding us anew what he can do when the offense flows
like electricity through him. He got 15 shots, one more than he had
in any previous playoff game, and got into a groove outside the
arc, making five of his six 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' bench manned the crisis hotline with aplomb; Robert
Horry, Rick Fox, Derek Fisher, Brian Shaw and Travis Knight
combined for 23 points to offset Indiana super sub Croshere's 24.
</P>
<P>
   Adversity can be so overbearing, the Lakers did well to hold her
off. Goodness knows they were a sucker for her advances last year,
weakening at the knees when the season was delayed by a work
stoppage, when coach Del Harris was fired, when Dennis Rodman was
signed and scrapped and when the San Antonio Spurs snuffed them in
the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson's hiring last June seemed to scare her off. Either
that or Adversity couldn't score seats in the Lakers' new arena.
Whatever the reason, the Lakers in the first year of Jackson's
coaching reign got by with just a few rumored sightings of
Adversity Bryant missed the first 15 games of the season with a
broken right hand and Brian Shaw sat out Game 5 of the Portland
series because of a suspension. They didn't see her in the flesh
until Bryant fell down.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's status for Sunday's Game 3 at Indianapolis is
uncertain. If the Lakers thought it was a challenge winning a
playoff game he started but couldn't finish, they haven't seen any
hardships yet. If the Lakers have to face a hostile Conseco
Fieldhouse crowd with Bryant sitting in street clothes, they'll
feel Adversity's full sway. It was wonderful they were able to keep
her at arm's length Friday, but the sterner test of their character
is just ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
