<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 RECORD LABELS REACH AGREEMENT WITH MP3.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite 1st two grafs. In 2nd graf, distinguishes between
Time Warner and Warner Music Group.)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Signaling a new era of cooperation in the
volatile world of online music distribution, two major record
labels said Friday that they had settled a copyright lawsuit with
MP3.com in a deal that permits the music start-up to store
consumers' record libraries and provide access to them over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, MP3.com will pay roughly $20 million each
to BMG Entertainment, a unit of Bertelsmann AG, and Warner Music
Group, a subsidiary of Time Warner, along with licensing fees for
use of the labels' music on the service, parties close to the
negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal hardly dispels the recording industry's pressing
concerns about music piracy online, nor does it yet make the bulk
of the music from the major record labels available for purchase
and listening over the Internet. But it appears to signal a
recognition by the labels and MP3.com that the traditional and
online businesses need each other, and can profit going forward by
working together.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robertson, chairman and chief executive of MP3.com,
declined to discuss the amount of the settlements, but said that
even if the reports were accurate, the fees would not jeopardize
the company's long-term viability.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company, which is based in San Diego, has $380
million in cash reserves. ``The reality is, cash is not an issue,''
he said, adding that he believed the settlement paved the way for
growth of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sheirer, an entertainment analyst with Forrester Research,
a market research firm in Cambridge, Mass., said that by settling,
the music labels at once scored a victory but also signaled a
willingness to embrace the online marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was of symbolic importance that the record
labels settled with MP3.com, which is just one of the companies
that uses the MP3 format to distribute music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge day for the recording industry,'' he said. ``They
are embracing a business model that revolves around the MP3
format.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that the labels are embracing a
mechanism for piracy, record industry officials said. They said
that the use of the MP3 format under the settlements announced
Friday was confined to allowing consumers to listen only to music
that they had already purchased, and not to download or trade music
they did not own.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that could have more dramatic implications, the
Recording Industry Association of America remains in litigation
with Napster, an online service that provides software that
Internet users employ to share and trade music files, including
copyrighted material. The service says it is not responsible if
some people use its software to pirate music, but the recording
industry disagrees, and asserts, generally speaking, that piracy
costs the industry and the artists it represents tens of millions
of dollars in lost sales. That case is still being heard in a
federal court in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Friday, MP3.com has agreed to license,
for undisclosed fees, the use of songs from BMG and Time Warner for
use in its My.MP3.com service. The service allows consumers to
store their own record collections on MP3.com's computers in
so-called ``virtual lockers'' _ and access them via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com launched the My.MP3.com service in January. In hopes of
making the service easy to use, the company itself purchased tens
of thousands of commercial compact discs. Consumers who proved they
owned a copy of a given disc, by inserting it into their PC while
visiting the site, would then be able to access that music from the
MP3.com computers.
</P>
<P>
   But the recording industry argued in court that MP3.com was
violating copyrights by copying the music, compiling a vast
database without permission or license. Although Robertson argued
that his service simply extended to cyberspace consumers' legal
rights to make a copy of their own music, a federal judge in New
York agreed with the labels in April, finding that the practice
violated copyright law because MP3.com had not received permission
from the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   Three other major record labels, including Sony Music, EMI and
Universal Music Group, said they were continuing independent
settlement negotiations, and declined further comment. A spokesman
for Time Warner said the company declined comment on the
settlement; in a press release, Kevin Conroy, chief marketing
officer and president of new technology for BMG Entertainment, said
that ``the best enforcement is the creation of legitimate
alternatives for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought by the Recording Industry Association of
America, which represents the five major record labels, but because
of antitrust regulations, the labels must settle the licensing
agreements separately, industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming that the other labels settle for around $20 million
also, as industry analysts expect, the cost to MP3.com could be
upward of $100 million, excluding future licensing fees, people
close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the My.mp3.com service has about 500,000 accounts,
but the virtual lockers do not now include music from the major
labels. Robertson said the service would continue to be free,
despite the fact that Mp3.com will have to pay licensing fees to
the labels, and he said the revenue would be raised largely by
advertising. The site, which also sells some items online, also
offers music from independent artists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to any deal struck with the major labels, MP3.com is
seeking licensing deals with music publishing groups, and Robertson
said that the service would not be fully functional until both sets
of deals were finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is building foundation for creating a massive online
business,'' Robertson said, calling the settlement a ``win-win''
for the two parties. ``Shareholders of major record labels are
getting a bite of the online apple.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal apparently played well with investors. Shares of
MP3.com were up $1.938, or 11.23 percent, to $19.188 in late
trading Friday on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the settlement may represent a partial
victory for MP3.com and for Robertson, who has ruffled many
feathers in the recording industry by asserting that traditional
music business models have been outdated in the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   Michael B. Nathanson, a music industry analyst with Sanford
Bernstein &AMP; Co. in New York, said he was surprised the settlement
came so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have thought they would punish Robertson,'' he said.
``But what it shows me is they realize there's a lot of traffic on
his site and that, at the end of the day, it makes sense to work
with these sites rather than oppose them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
