<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ IMPRESSIVE, BUT DODGERS LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The more the plan seems laid out and ready to be
executed, the better left-hander Carlos Perez performs, throwing
said plan out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   With right-hander Orel Hershiser pitching 65 miles away in the
minor leagues and lying in wait to rejoin the Dodgers, and perhaps
their starting rotation, Perez went out and had his best outing of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed a season-low one run on three hits in seven
innings, but it was wasted thanks to reliever Antonio Osuna's third
straight brutal outing. Olmedo Saenz hit a two-run homer in the
eighth off Osuna to lift the Oakland A's to a 3-1 win over the
Dodgers at Dodger Stadium on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna (0-3) walked Jason Giambi with two outs to set up Saenz's
homer, and is in the midst of a rough time. Osuna's allowed five
runs, walked eight and hit a batter in his last three appearances,
totaling 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tam (1-2) struck out four in 1 innings of relief for the
win and right-hander Jason Isringhausen pitched the ninth for his
15th save.
</P>
<P>
   While the loss dropped the Dodgers (32-26) three games behind
West Division-leading Arizona, there is a bigger picture, and
that's Perez. His outing throws a kink, albeit possibly only
temporarily, into what the Dodgers were thinking of doing. They're
still likely to recall Hershiser for the upcoming series against
Arizona, but instead of joining the starting rotation he'll go to
the bullpen, which he should be better prepared to do this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Hershiser wound up with Single-A San Bernardino
because he was having trouble adjusting to his role in the bullpen.
When he tried it earlier this season, Hershiser had a 15.18 ERA in
five relief outings.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was supposed to start today for the Stampede, but his
start was pushed up a day, making for a nifty safety net in case
Perez was rocked by the A's. Hershiser, who allowed three runs on
six hits in four-plus innings against the Mudville Nine, could've
stepped into Perez's spot in the rotation Wednesday against Arizona
if Perez failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Perez was sensational and should face the left-handed
dominated Diamondbacks, not to mention left-hander Randy Johnson.
Of course, Perez already defeated Atlanta's Greg Maddux earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Hershiser), and where he's at right now, he could
handle (pitching in the bullpen),'' Johnson said. ``He could handle
it better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the specter of being sent to the minors is something that
will follow Perez until he's either demoted or he reaches June 25,
after which he can refuse a minor-league assignment based on
service time. That marks the date his agreement with the Dodgers,
in which he temporarily waived his rights to refuse an assignment,
expires.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who enjoys early run support in most of his starts,
didn't get quite the quantity he's used to, but got some
nonetheless when second baseman Mark Grudzielanek hit a one-out
solo homer in the bottom of the first off Oakland starter Tim
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The A's have had trouble against left-handers. They entered
batting .224 against lefties, 39 points lower than they do against
right-handers, and the A's did nothing to change that against
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   For a fleeting moment of what is maybe the most insane thought,
Perez didn't allow a hit until Miguel Tejada's two-out double in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez, after recording the first two outs in the sixth,
experienced his only trouble. He walked Giambi and gave up a bloop
single to Saenz. Ben Grieve tied it 1-1 with a double down the
right field line.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers wasted a glorious chance to break the tie in the
seventh inning. Alex Cora led off with a double and pinch-hitter
Dave Hansen walked. They moved up a base on F.P. Santangelo's
sacrifice bunt and Jeff Tam relieved and struck out Grudzielanek
and got Gary Sheffield to fly out to center field to end the
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
