r s BC-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN     06-10 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON STOPS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- Troy Glaus made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' third baseman hit a 97-mph fastball from Arizona
Diamondbacks pitcher Randy Johnson 457 feet and into the
second-deck restaurant at Bank One Ballpark Friday night for a
second-inning home run and 1-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus' homer was the third longest in the ballpark's brief
history, but they don't award extra runs for distance. It turned
out to be the Angels' only run in a 4-1 loss before 39,468 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson returned to the rotation after missing a start with a
sore shoulder, and that was the only reason he lasted just six
innings. Besides the homer to Glaus, he gave up just two other hits
-- singles by Mo Vaughn and Scott Spiezio -- and improved to 10-1.
His ERA actually went up from 1.41 to 1.42.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe he's had shoulder trouble,'' said Angels
manager Mike Scioscia. ``He didn't show any signs of it. He had
great command. No pitch got away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Brian Cooper was up to the challenge of facing
Johnson, at least for four innings. But the Diamondbacks scored all
four or their runs in the fifth inning against him.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Womack tripled and scored on a single by Jay Bell. Luis
Gonzalez followed with a two-run homer for a 3-1 Diamondbacks'
lead. They added one unearned run in the inning on a throwing error
by Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper (2-2) lasted five innings, gave up the four runs (three
earned) and six hits and got the loss. Pitching against Johnson was
a daunting task, but one Cooper wasn't afraid of.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it forces you to pick up your concentration
because you know you've got to have your best game out there,'' he
said. ``You have to keep your team in the game no matter what. It's
not like we're going to put up a five-spot in the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson started with a bang, striking out the side in the first
inning, including Vaughn on a 98-mph fastball that ended the
inning. He struck out eight in all, which gave him 2,832 in his
career, tying Mickey Lolich for 13th on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time in 28 games the Angels have been
held to fewer than two runs in a game. They had five hits in all,
and had only three baserunners get into scoring position after
Glaus' homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's Randy Johnson, you know what I mean?'' Vaughn said.
``He's one of the top two pitchers in the game. I remember facing
him in Seattle, and what's different about him now is he's become
more of a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over there he used to rear back and try to throw it by you,
and he would throw it by you. Now he's got a two-seam fastball that
goes in on lefties and away from righties. He's got two different
breaking balls and a 97-mph fastball. He's as much a technician as
he is a power pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had lost five in a row and their N.L. West lead
over the Dodgers had shrunk to two games. But Johnson put and end
to the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fairly sharp, not knowing what to expect when you
haven't pitched for about eight days,'' Johnson said. ``But it was
a great win, obviously, because of the situation we went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came up big in the sixth inning when the Angels put two
runners on with nobody out. But Johnson struck out both Kevin
Stocker and Vaughn, then got Tim Salmon on a line drive to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me who'd I pick between Randy and Pedro
(Martinez),'' Vaughn said. ``Hey, flip a coin. They're both going
to be that effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
