r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-10 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ABOUT ARISTOTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everything went the Indiana Pacers' way Friday in
the Black and Blue Division championship game, advertised as the
second game of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Everything except the two things that matter: Shaquille O'Neal.
And the score, 111-104 for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   What a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out - if we didn't know this already - that nothing
else in this series is going to matter if the Pacers can't stop
O'Neal from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   They tried a different way this time, hacking Shaq and sending
him to the free-throw line for an NBA-record 39 free throws, but
the result was another 40-points-plus night for the battered and
bruised MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played as hard as we could, but tonight I thought Shaq was
better than he was the other night,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird said.
``We're down 2-0, we've lost both games on the road and we've got
to figure out a way to win one.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there a plan C?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had scored 43 points in Wednesday's opener, the Pacers
had been blown out and they'd vowed that wouldn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. O'Neal got 40 this time to go with 24 rebounds - they
said he wouldn't score 43! - and the Pacers weren't out of it until
the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, he did it with 21-for-31 shooting from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he did it with 18-for-39 shooting from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Same difference for Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Lakers' history of letting down in Game 2s after
winning Game 1s, this looked like the Pacers' best chance to steal
a road game, something they'll have to do sometime to win the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   That chance looked better almost from the start. What went wrong
in the opener was going right this time.
</P>
<P>
   Rik Smits hit his first shot and boldly took shots that missed
on the next two possessions, forcing O'Neal to pay attention to him
as he'd failed to do Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller hit a jumper from the right side on the Pacers'
first possession, drew a foul on the second, and drove for a layup
on the sixth, to put aside any thought he'd repeat his 1-for-16
performance Wednesday _ one of the memorably bad nights in
championship-round history, you name the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad he picked up a cheap foul there that sent him to the
bench,'' Bird said. ``I thought he was in the game, was in the
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened. The break _ make that sprain _ the underdog
Pacers needed.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant nailed a 20-footer to give the Lakers a 22-20 lead
nine minutes into the game and landed on Jalen Rose's foot. Bryant
crumpled to the floor and clutched his left ankle. He hopped to the
bench, out of the game and maybe out of Sunday's game in
Indianapolis as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a golden opportunity game there, with Kobe out,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a heck of a game, the Lakers defending small
leads most of the time, until Los Angeles began to pull away and
Bird went back on his semi-promise not to use the Hack-a-Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   We should have seen it coming when the fan who came to the
Staples Center in a Pacers tuxedo for Game 1 showed up in a
Pacers-yellow construction helmet for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers fouled O'Neal _ with the ball, away from the ball,
even under the Indiana basket immediately after one change of
possession _ on six consecutive possessions beginning as they
trailed 93-87 at the 3-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's stated plan, to take a physical approach to Shaq, was
being carried out in front of him. But it couldn't do anything
about the simple equation that rules these two teams in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are 9-0 when they score 99 points or more. The Pacers
are 0-6 when they give up 98 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers got to the magical 99 in excruciating fashion, a
half-step at a time, with O'Neal sinking one of two free throws on
each of those six trips to the line. Then they kept going.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal found Robert Horry cutting left to right under the basket
for the layup - and subsequent foul shot - that made it 102-96 at
:58.8.
</P>
<P>
   That more or less clinched a 2-0 series lead for the Lakers. And
that assist - O'Neal had four to go with his huge point and rebound
totals - was a last reminder that this series really is about only
one player.
</P>
<P>
   If Indiana can't hold him under 40, nothing else matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
