<HEADLINE>
GET EXCITED ABOUT PEDRO'S CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Picked-up pieces while wondering if Al Gore can
produce Shaquille-esque energy in the Staples Center when the
Democratic National Convention comes here in August.
</P>
<P>
   --Is anybody else looking forward to Pedro Martinez back in
Yankee Stadium Tuesday night? Pedro has officially moved into the
Koufax pantheon. It's June and his ERA is 0.95. Don't expect to see
anything like it again.
</P>
<P>
   --After the New Jersey Devils win the Stanley Cup, the Bruins
should bring Devils general manager Lou Lamoriello on board to
succeed Harry Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   --Exactly what got into the men's club at Sports Illustrated
when it produced the soft-core pornographic Anna Kournikova cover
story? OK, she's a beautiful girl (must be the only attractive
19-year-old out there), a coconspirator in her own exploitation,
and an OK tennis player. That gets her 11 pages and 11 photos in
the No. 1 sports weekly in the world? Not to mention a panting
story by the estimable Frank Deford, who should know better than to
be part of such a sensational, sophomoric package? Heavy breathing
over teenage female athletes should be reserved for the middle-aged
white guys of sports talk radio. Pathetic. Wonder what SI will do
with Marion Jones, a true winner?
</P>
<P>
   --The visitor's locker room at the Staples Center looks like it
was designed by Red Auerbach. It's the smallest room built into a
new arena in decades.
</P>
<P>
   --The Red Sox should be ashamed of themselves for their shoddy
treatment of John Valentin. The veteran has given his career and
maybe his left knee to the organization, but they sent him a
contemptuous letter, and threatened to void his contract because he
didn't ask Dan Duquette for a bathroom pass before having major
knee surgery (Valentin did speak with Red Sox physician/part-owner
Arthur Pappas). Control-freak Dan needs to know when to let it go.
This would be one of those times. Boston is the organization that's
been sued by an ex-player for medical malpractice. Valentin went to
a reputable doctor. Why must Duquette conduct business like some
coldblooded IRS auditor?
</P>
<P>
   --You know you're in California when you read that the UCLA
baseball team had 12 players drafted in Monday's big league meat
market.
</P>
<P>
   --Any publication that sent an ``invited'' reporter to interview
Bob Knight should be ashamed of itself. Before the ESPN Roy
Firestone-Digger Phelps farce, Knight spoke with seven print
reporters who had been handpicked by the bullying coach. Globe
readers can be thankful that our college guy, Mark Blaudschun, was
not invited.
</P>
<P>
   --The Pacers and Lakers are the lucky ones for these games in
LA: They don't have to make any decisions about what to wear.
Players wear standard uniform garb while the likes of Salma Hayek &AMP;
Co. try out next year's Oscar outfits.
</P>
<P>
   --Everywhere you go, you hear people talking about the Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   _Winthrop's Rick DiPietro, a freshman goalie at BU, might be the
No. 1 pick in the NHL draft at Calgary. The Islanders have the
pick, but have no need for a goaltender and are expected to deal.
The young man has great local roots: His mother, Cheryl, went to
high school with Mike Eruzione, and he's represented by Bobby Orr's
Woolf Associates.
</P>
<P>
   --Pacers guard Mark Jackson is one of the NBA's good guys. When
Indiana last played in Boston, he went out of his way to fulfill
the dying wish of a young patient at the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute. Jackson still stays in touch and the family is forever
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   --Iceman George Gervin coached the guy who attempted the
million-dollar shot at halftime Friday night. We knew there was no
danger of the guy passing.
</P>
<P>
   --Perhaps Ted Kennedy can bring ``Mike McGwire and Sammy
Soo-ser'' to the Convention at Staples.
</P>
<P>
   --Count me among those who have zero interest in who's going to
be joining Al Michaels in the booth for ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   --Rick Carlisle is ready to coach the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   --Jason Varitek has two homers and 15 RBIs. Anybody worried
about that?
</P>
<P>
   --Sam Horn's playing for Butch Hobson with the Nashua Pride?
This we gotta see. Proof that not everybody can play first base,
Big Sam always looked as if he was going to go deep. Then he was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   --Why don't the Patriots just do the obvious and re-sign Bruce
Armstrong?
</P>
<P>
   --Adjusting to a new offensive coordinator isn't Drew Bledsoe's
toughest obstacle this fall. Maura Bledsoe is expecting again,
which means that when the baby is born in November, the Bledsoes
will have three kids under 3.
</P>
<P>
   --The NBA Finals are broadcast to 200 countries and there are 50
international crews on site. ``Some of the countries have no
commercials and run a continuous feed, so they are experts on the
Laker Girls,'' said commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   --Bill Walton's John Wooden interview will air during Sunday's
telecast of the NBA Finals. Walton teases us by saying that Wooden
``gives his feelings on Bobby Knight.'' Walton on Rick Reilly's
Wooden column in Sports Illustrated: ``I laminated it. I read it
three times a day and that doesn't count my morning and evening
prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached at
dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
