<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOXBRAVES-BOS &LR;      06-10 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOXBRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSTERS COULD HAVE HELPED CAUSE VS. BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves 6 Red Sox 4
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Who knows if Jose Offerman would have made a
difference in Friday night's 6-4 loss to the Atlanta Braves. Maybe
he wouldn't have even played. He hit .100 against the defending
National League champions last season, and is 0 for 9 lifetime in
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   But the point that was lost on the Red Sox Friday is that
Offerman could have played. They thought he wasn't eligible to come
off the 15-day disabled list until Saturday. It wasn't until after
the game, when Red Sox spokesman Kevin Shea forwarded a reporter's
inquiry to manager Jimy Williams, that Williams acknowledged
Offerman could have been available Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have told me in the last few minutes that he could have
come off today,'' Williams said after a game in which the Sox
spotted Greg Maddux a 5-1 lead. They knocked Maddux out in a
three-run seventh that started with Brian Daubach's 10th home run,
then went out quietly after Andres Galarraga, poster boy for
inspirational sagas, took fellow Venezuelan Rich Garces deep in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The mixup with Offerman was reminiscent of last season's roster
gaffe involving reliever Tom Gordon, who ran in from the bullpen to
a thunderous ovation from a Fenway Park throng for what he thought
would be his first appearance in three months, then was quickly
ushered out when it was discovered that he had not yet been
activated from the DL.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who received a frantic call in the dugout from general
manager Dan Duquette telling him that Gordon couldn't play, took
the blame for that bureaucratic snafu, and he tried to take the hit
Friday, too, even though roster moves are never made from the
manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, a mistake was made, it was better to have someone
on too long than have something really adverse happen,'' Williams
said. ``That's kind of the way I look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've made a lot of mistakes in my lifetime. I can own
up to them. If a mistake was made, so be it. We can't move
backward. We have to move forward. If you want to beat me up, that
we waited a day too long, that's up to you folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman hurt his left groin in a game against the Toronto Blue
Jays May 24. Three days later, the Sox were in New York and
reinstated Nomar Garciaparra, who had been out with a strained left
hamstring. A roster spot had to be created to make room for
Garciaparra. It was decided that Offerman would go on the 15-day
disabled list. The Sox made his disabling retroactive to May 25,
under provisions that allow a team to backdate putting a player on
the DL to the day after he last played.
</P>
<P>
   For Offerman, the 15-day period that included the 25th ended
Thursday night, making him eligible to play Friday night. Last
weekend, when the club was in Philadelphia, reporters had raised
the question of whether Offerman could come off Friday or Saturday;
Williams came back the next day and said it was Saturday. During
Friday night's game, Sean McAdam of the Providence Journal raised
the issue again with Shea, which led to Williams's admission
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, neither Offerman nor his agent ever raised a
question about his eligibility. He said he didn't find out about
the error until he was asked by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' Offerman said with a little shrug.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it wasn't OK, on a night that Williams used two pinch
hitters, three third basemen, two right fielders and made two
double switches.
</P>
<P>
   If Offerman had been activated, pitcher Dan Smith, who was
optioned to Pawtucket after the game, anyway, would have been gone.
Pedro Martinez had saved the bullpen with his magnificent effort
Thursday night, so a 12th pitcher probably wouldn't have been a
factor Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Another hitter might have been able to bail out Sox starter Jeff
Fassero, who came unglued in a three-run Braves uprising in the
fourth inning, which he began by walking the first two batters,
Brian Jordan and Reggie Sanders. Fassero, still fuming over what he
believed was a missed call on a 1-and-2 pitch to Sanders, gave up a
first-pitch RBI double to rookie sensation Rafael Furcal. He was
left sputtering when rookie catcher Fernando Lunar reached down for
a pitch well out of the strike zone and stroked a soft, two-run
single that just cleared the peak of Fassero's cap before drifting
into center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who took a 1-0 lead in the third on singles by Lunar
and the Jones boys, Andruw and Chipper, were now comfortably ahead,
4-1. They made it 5-1 in the sixth against reliever Hipolito
Pichardo when Furcal dropped a double in front of Troy O'Leary,
stole third, and scored on Maddux's squeeze bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (inhaled excessively),'' Fassero said of his outing, which
was curtailed with two outs in the fourth. ``How's that sound?
</P>
<P>
   ``That 1-and-2 pitch to Sanders, a call there and the inning
might have been a much different inning. I got a little frustrated
there. Then Lunar hit a pitch that was 2 inches off the plate and 2
inches off the ground _ it practically fell straight down _ and he
hit it how it was pitched. Soft pitch, soft hit. That's a pitch you
want him to hit on the ground, and somehow he hit it over my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a night for things flying over Red Sox heads. An extra
day for Offerman, who never thought his injury was serious enough
to warrant going on the DL in the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
