<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERSPACERS-BOS &LR;      06-10 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSPACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS RUN AFOUL OF SHAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Indiana Pacers played Hack-a-Shaq to the max,
but in the end, Shaquille O'Neal found a new way to win. On the
heels of his 43-point outing in Game 1, Shaq scored 40 more points,
grabbed 24 rebounds, took a playoff-record 39 foul shots, and
contributed a beautiful assist to help seal a 111-104 Game 2
victory over the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were gaining ground by fouling the LA giant (O'Neal
made only 18 foul shots) when he fired a perfect pass to a
reverse-cutting Robert Horry under the basket in the closing
seconds. Horry made the shot, got fouled, and LA had a 6-point lead
with 58.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was even better tonight than he was on
Wednesday,'' said Indiana coach Larry Bird. ``He's a handful.''
</P>
<P>
   So now the series shifts from the beach to the heartland, from
Jack Nicholson to Jim Nabors, from Hollywood to Hooterville. The
Lakers may play Sunday' Game 3 without Kobe Bryant, who sprained
his ankle in the first quarter and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers put up a better fight Friday night. They worked
harder on defense, put some skin on the floor, and threw a scare
into the Californians. Rik Smits (4 points, two rebounds in 16
minutes) was useless again, but Austin Croshere (24 points) picked
up the slack and the Pacers put O'Neal on the line and dared him to
beat them from 15 feet. Shaq struggled at the stripe, but had
enough to beat the overmatched Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chastened him mildly for putting up in that situation in the
first half,'' said Laker coach Phil Jackson. ``But he shot his free
throws much better in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   It was tied after one and the Lakers led by 3 at the half.
Bloodless Reggie Miller (21) tied the game with a pair of free
throws with 7:09 left in the third, but Derek Harper (another big
21 points), Glen Rice (21), and O'Neal carried LA to a 73-69 lead
after three.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were within 2 early in the fourth, but an 8-0 LA run
made it 86-78 with seven minutes left. Indy ran off 6 straight, but
Rice drained a three and Shaq hit a jump hook and it was 91-86.
Shaq went to the line the next six times down the floor and made 1
of 2 each time. It took 48 minutes to play the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game is that tight and you're 4 or 5 points down,
your best option is to get the ball back,'' said Bird. ``But the
more you put him at the line, the better he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller admitted, ``I'm not a fan of Hack-a-Shaq, but it almost
worked for us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird said, ``I don't worry about (television) ratings. I'm
trying to win a ballgame. Whatever it takes. If it takes a
four-hour game, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers should have been in good shape when Bryant went down
early. Making a routine jumper with 3:26 left in the first period,
LA's young guard rolled his left ankle when he came down on the
foot of Jalen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Play continued for two possessions while Bryant stayed down, got
up slowly, then limped around. When time was finally called, Kobe
went to the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays were negative, but Bryant (2 points, four assists) did
not return. He is listed as day-to-day, and the series resumes
Sunday at Indiana. Game 4 is Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Miller made his first shot, an 18-foot jumper in the first
minute. In the wake of Wednesday's 1-for-16 performance, he'd
pledged to keep shooting, and he kept his promise. He went 4 for 5
and had 10 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   There were six lead changes and six ties in the first two
periods. Indy managed to bother O'Neal under the basket and for a
while Shaq's teammates lost sight of him, much as they did in the
first three quarters of Game 7 vs. Portland.
</P>
<P>
   It was 28-28 after one. Dependable Harper once again bailed out
the home team. Harper made all of his shots, scored 11 in the first
period, then made LA's first 4 points of the second.
</P>
<P>
   Smits continued to be an impossibly invisible 7 feet 4 inches,
but Croshere (8 in the first half) came off the bench and gave Indy
a lift for the second straight game. A bucket by Rose gave the
Pacers a 38-36 lead with 6:40 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal started clanking free throws (5 for 17 in the first two
quarters), but brought fans out of their seats when he one-handed a
Brian Shaw pass and slammed it home as he was fouled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
