<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACK-A-SHAQ TACTICS SMACK OF DESPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Game 2 of the NBA Finals suits your taste in
pro basketball, you also must like meat loaf ice cream,
long-sleeved swimsuits and Chick Hearn hip-hop records.
</P>
<P>
   The pivotal tableau was large men standing around, watching the
largest man nearly fail at his weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Must ZZZ-TV.
</P>
<P>
   A sport that was at one time all about swooping and swooshing by
elegant athletes was reduced Friday night to three hours of
nail-pounding. ``Tool Time'' without Tim Allen's attempts at humor.
</P>
<P>
   The helplessness consuming the Indiana Pacers regarding
Shaquille O'Neal inevitably decayed into the Hack-a-Shaq routine.
Decayed? More like rotted.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Indiana coach Larry Bird declared his disdain
for the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation overcame taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, when a game's that tight and you get down four or five,
I think it's the opportunity to get the ball back,'' Bird said,
almost apologetically. ``The thing about the game is, we played as
hard as we could, but I just thought Shaq was better than he was
the other night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Bird was right. O'Neal induced Indiana center Rik Smits
into even quicker foul trouble than in Game 1 and savaged the
Pacers with 40 points, 24 rebounds, four assists and three blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pacers hung tight most of the way, the Lakers
prevailed 111-104 to go up 2-0. But if this style of game keeps up,
starting Sunday in Indianapolis with Game 3, all participants and
observers will be shipped to the ``Survivors'' series on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Never has such a contest _ thank you, basketball gods _ been
seen before, especially not in the Finals, where the presumption is
two relatively well-matched teams.
</P>
<P>
   Sending O'Neal to the free-throw line 39 times _ breaking by
five a record set 38 years ago by Wilt Chamberlain _ is like
enduring George W. Bush's list of known foreign leaders, or
Microsoft's explanations of why it is not a monopoly. The action is
excruciating, exasperating and embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with the rationale behind the strategy _ as
Bird put it after Game 1, ``The matchups in this series are bad for
us'' _ but that doesn't mean anyone has to be happy with the
results.
</P>
<P>
   The distortion at center produced a final quarter that lasted 48
minutes, and a game that featured 96 free throws _ 26 more than the
playoff record. The acme of freakishness came when O'Neal could
miss nine free throws in the fourth quarter _ he flubbed 21 in the
game _ while playing with foul trouble himself, and the Lakers
could still win going away.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants, Jalen Rose was at least honest enough to
voice his contempt for the maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a pretty good theory, if you're four or five
ahead and it's above two minutes,'' said Rose, who led Indiana with
30 points. ``Other than that, I really don't think it's a great
theory. Not only does it give him an opportunity to rest, even a
bad free-throw shooter makes 50 percent. He puts points on the
board, stops the clock and it gives him a rhythm and confidence to
still play the rest of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play him straight up and he earns everything, that's
how you get to him, as opposed to giving him free points.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Pacers, they tried that in Game 1, when
O'Neal attempted only six free throws. They lost that one by more
than they lost Game 2, and Friday the Lakers operated without Kobe
Bryant, the precocious star who went out with a sprained ankle
after nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kobe going down, we had a golden opportunity slip through
our fingers,'' said Reggie Miller, the Pacers' leading playoff
scorer who rebounded from his Game 1 horrors with 21 points. ``But
when a guy goes back-to-back 40s, you gotta give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is denying credit. Aesthetic considerations are of no
importance to O'Neal, who no longer even flinches when the
inevitable cavalcade of slaps comes his way. He has grown sanguine
over the tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's total respect for my game,'' he said, offering a tough
argument. But we will dispute anyway: If he could make some free
throws, there would be no Hack-a-Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that even the greatest players have
vulnerabilities, and playoff basketball strategy is all about
exploiting those weaknesses, there is something depressing about a
career-long failure to master the game's most elemental maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lakers coach Phil Jackson admitted to admonishing O'Neal at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mildly chastised him for putting us in a situation,'' he
said, ``where we should have been maybe 10 or 12 points up, to only
be ahead by three.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah _ if there were no kryptonite, Superman wouldn't be a
good story.
</P>
<P>
   But a three-hour kryptonite festival is not a good story,
either.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
