<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS HAMMER HAPLESS HALAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is just about where the Mariners left off.
</P>
<P>
   When last we saw the Good Ship Mariner in a foreign port, the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays were scoring 11 runs in the eighth inning of
what had been a tie game.
</P>
<P>
   Time and distance apparently have not tempered the Seattle
propensity for seriously dysfunctional play away from the comforts
of Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   One day after getting a reminder from manager Lou Piniella about
the importance of playing well on the road, the Mariners sang the
same mournful dirge, dropping a 9-2 decision to the San Francisco
Giants in Seattle's first-ever game in Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mariners to 10-17 on the road, and as if
that was not bad enough, Oakland beat Los Angeles, so the A's moved
1{ games up on Seattle in the tight American League West race.
</P>
<P>
   It's the furthest the Mariners have been out of first place this
season. On May 25, the M's were one game out, but two days after
that, they were back in the lead, and they've remained within half
a game of the lead since. At their peak, the Mariners had a
three-game lead twice late in April.
</P>
<P>
   That all seems a long time ago. The Mariners continue to have
trouble scoring runs. They seem to have trouble playing defense,
too, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You can play defense all you want, but you've still got to
score some runs,'' Piniella said, aware that at its current pace,
the offense just isn't bringing home the bacon in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have scored some runs. They just haven't scored
many. And they haven't scored nearly enough. In the past 11 games,
they've scored 48 times, an average of 4.36 runs per game.
Seattle's average for the season is 5.70 runs, so the dropoff is
severe and debilitating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every day we need to come up with one big hit,''
center fielder Mike Cameron said. ``Right now we've got to roll
with the punches, come back out tomorrow and score some runs. What
we need now is a couple of hits and some luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had little enough of either commodity Friday night,
although given the kind of night starter John Halama had, anything
short of double-figure offense was going to be too little.
</P>
<P>
   The hitters didn't produce, so Halama and the M's went quietly
into the cool mists of the San Francisco night losers again on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Halama lasted just three innings, gave up 10 hits, walked three
and was victimized by two of the three errors committed by a
slipshod defense. The loss was Halama's second in succession after
six consecutive wins, and this one the left-hander found hard to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up a lot of hits, only one double but a lot of hits,''
Halama said. ``Those guys (the Giants) fought off a lot of tough
pitches, then I had to come in with 2-2 and 3-2 pitches, and they
hit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought and fought and fought, then they got the hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had one brief shining moment, that coming in the first
inning when, with two outs, Alex Rodriguez hit his 17th homer, a
savage shot to center that had Giants' starter Kirk Rueter (3-4)
rocking back on his heels.
</P>
<P>
   Rueter recovered. Halama never did, although he was a little
lucky, hard though that may be to believe. He gave up one run in
the first on a Jeff Kent single, but left the bases loaded. Halama
allowed four hits in the second inning, but didn't give up a run
and again left the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The luck pendulum swung the other way in the third. Not only did
catcher Dan Wilson and third baseman David Bell make errors behind
him, but Halama ran out of ways to dodge the Giants' bullets. The
end result was a four-run, four-hit inning that left the Giants in
command 5-1 and took Halama out of the game after a labored
79-pitch effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like this for Halama the last couple of times out,''
Piniella said. ``Tonight specifically he didn't get the ball down,
and they sprayed hits all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Rueter, meanwhile, had minimal trouble with the Seattle offense.
He got a double play from his defense in the second inning, then
escaped trouble after allowing two two-out hits in the third. At
that point the game was still a game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Giants' four-run bottom of the third, the heart
seemed to go out of Seattle's offense. Over the course of the next
three innings, the M's got just one hit.
</P>
<P>
   The scouting report the Mariners had on the Giants said that San
Francisco's offense was stoked and was going to be difficult to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scout was right on on that one,'' Piniella said. ``Those
guys on the other side are hitting the ball real good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes one team.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
