<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SURVIVE INJURY TO KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An ankle turned, a Shaq got hacked, the NBA's
grand musical was drowned by a chorus of whistles and boos, and the
Lakers' control of the championship series was nearly submerged
along the way. The Lakers had their manhood tested, then their
patience, finally their composure.
</P>
<P>
   But they emerged Friday night with everything intact, save for
Kobe Bryant's left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   With Bryant on crutches, the Lakers propped themselves up on a
40-point performance from Shaquille O'Neal and survived a
debilitating attack from the Indiana Pacers for a 111-104 victory
and a 2-0 lead in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Their home-court advantage safe, the Lakers head to Indiana for
the next three games, uncertain about Bryant's status (officially,
day-to-day) but assured they can withstand just about anything now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we had a lot of things going against us in the
course of the game,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``The little things.
They got the (3-point) bank shot from (Sam) Perkins, they got a
couple bounces went their way, shots that hit the rim and went in.
Little things were happening and just by staying positive, and we
were fortunate to have Glen Rice step up and hit a 3-pointer at
that time. Players that stepped into the vacuum were real big for
us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That giant sucking sound was the Hoover effect created by
Bryant's first-quarter injury. But the loss of the Lakers'
second-leading scorer, top defender and best playmaker only
threatened their championship hopes briefly.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, an opportunity. And Rice, dormant for much of
the postseason, took advantage, scoring 21 points on 7-of-15
shooting, including 5 of 6 from the arc. Ron Harper added a
season-high 21, going 8 for 12 from the field, mostly on hard
drives to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great. It was like he had flashbacks of his younger
days,'' said teammate Brian Shaw, who picked up the majority of
Bryant's minutes. ``I think the fact (Harper) knew Kobe wasn't
going to come back and that he wasn't going to be subbed for, he
could kind of freelance a little bit more. And that's his game.''
</P>
<P>
   No lead was safe, and no strategy off-limits as the Pacers
ravenously tore at the Lakers in an attempt to steal home-court
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana got rejuvenated performances from Jalen Rose (30 points)
and Reggie Miller (21 points) and a 24-point boost from Austin
Croshere, but it finally came down to Pacers coach Larry Bird
ordering the Hack-a-Shaq. O'Neal was fouled intentionally six times
in the last 3:08, and made 6 of 12 free throws _ and history.
</P>
<P>
   For the night, O'Neal made 18 of 39 from the foul line, the most
free throws ever attempted in any NBA game, regular-season or
playoff. The previous high was 34 attempts, by Wilt Chamberlain on
Feb. 22, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with an 11-of-18 night from the field, and 24
rebounds, gave O'Neal his best back-to-back games of the playoffs.
And left Bird _ who also tried more double-teaming _ befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about the game is we played as hard as we could,''
Bird said, ``but tonight I just thought Shaq was better than he was
the other night. I thought he was dominating, he caused a lot of
problems for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he had vowed not to use it, Bird defended the choice
to Hack-a-Shaq _ the tactic made (un)popular by Portland coach Mike
Dunleavy in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, when a game's that tight and you get down 4 or
5, I think it's the best opportunity to get the ball back,'' Bird
said. ``He was struggling early. The more you put him at the line,
the better he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 17 points in the fourth quarter, going 4 for 4
from the field and 9 for 16 from the line, as the Lakers turned
back every Pacers charge.
</P>
<P>
   But it made for a testy crowd, which loudly booed Bird's
strategy, and an edgy game for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good, though,'' Derek Fisher said. ``I think in the
first game, people didn't really think that was much of a game. ...
There was more of a feeling of 'This is the NBA Finals.' And I
think tonight was a perfect example of what we thought was going to
happen. The Pacers knew that this was a game that in terms of
percentages and what's realistic, that they had to win this
basketball game to really stay in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of clutch plays from just about every
Laker role player along the way. Rice and Fisher hit big 3-pointers
in the fourth quarter. Robert Horry converted a 3-point play (on a
spiffy pass from O'Neal for a reverse) to extend a shaky lead to
102-96. Rick Fox hit a driving bank shot to make it a 105-98 with
37.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kobe went out, we felt that we had to pick it up,''
O'Neal said. ``So I took it upon myself to get in deep position and
take the high-percentage shots. My teammates were looking for me.
When they continued to double, I was looking for guys like Glen,
Robert, Rick.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they continue to play that well, the dream will be
complete for the team, for the city, for the organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
