<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-LAZIO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-340(ADDS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SAID TO PICK VETERAN OF FORBES RACE AS MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite first six grafs to reflect confirmation of the
appointment.)  
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio has appointed a veteran strategist
for conservative causes to run his campaign for the Senate,
campaign officials said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's choice is Bill Dal Col, 44, a childhood friend from Long
Island who managed Steve Forbes' two unsuccessful bids for the
Republican presidential nomination, campaign officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters following an event in Ulster County late
Friday, Lazio said that Dal Col brought ``the depth of experience,
unrivaled frankly,'' to his Senate campaign, according to The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has national perspective,'' Lazio said. ``He knows New
York. He's got the ideal combination of political skills,
communication skills, organizational skills to help pull the
operation of this campaign effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col, who is expected to join the campaign within a couple of
days, will lead a campaign staff that includes other veterans of
national campaigns, including a political strategist who worked on
Sen. John McCain's presidential campaign. Dal Col did not return
telephone calls to his Virginia office.
</P>
<P>
   Between Forbes' presidential campaigns in 1996 and 2000, Dal Col
was president of Americans for Hope, Growth and Opportunity, a
nonprofit group founded by Forbes that advocates a ban on all
abortions, school choice for parents, and the dismantling of the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes took a strong antiabortion stance in his campaign this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has won
the endorsement of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League, has said she will make abortion rights a theme of
her campaign. Lazio has said he favors abortion rights, but opposes
public financing of abortions and a late-term procedure critics
call ``partial birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Political strategists said Dal Col appealed to Lazio in several
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col has the experience of running major campaigns, but is
also political kindred from Suffolk County, which is symbolically
important in a campaign in which Lazio has sought to contrast his
New York roots with Clinton's background. The first lady moved to a
house in Chappaqua five months ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dal Col, who ran unsuccessfully for the state Assembly in 1982,
was a councilman in Babylon, N.Y., in the 1980s. Lazio grew up in
West Islip and lives in Brightwaters, both in Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is a native New Yorker who is a childhood friend of
Lazio's, and they know each other well,'' said Greg Mueller, a
senior adviser to Forbes during his 2000 campaign. ``Lazio doesn't
have time for that `getting to know you.' And Bill knows New York
politics backward, forward and sideways. He's lived in New York and
he knows all the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller described Dal Col as details-oriented, the kind of
person who ``gets under the hood and works on the engine.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio released the first television advertisement for his
campaign on Friday. Two other advertisements made by outside groups
have already been shown. The 60-second Lazio advertisement,
``Introduction,'' shows him talking about his upbringing and
political life. It will be broadcast this weekend on stations north
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also released a new campaign advertisement in which she
mentions her visits to all 62 New York counties, and promises to
promote high-tech jobs and to practice fiscal responsibility by
reducing the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of a campaign manager for Lazio has been widely
anticipated, because his backers feel a need to set a course for a
campaign that began only three weeks ago, when Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani dropped out to seek treatment for prostate cancer. Clinton
has been campaigning for nearly a year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This week, Lazio also named several other people to his staff,
campaign officials said. Eileen Long, the chief of staff to Lt.
Gov. Mary Donohue and the daughter of Michael Long, the chairman of
the Conservative Party, will be political director; Patrick
McCarthy, a communications and legislative aide to Pataki, will be
deputy communications director; and Carlyle Gregory, a longtime
consultant to Lazio, will be a political consultant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
