<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0151 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     06-10 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ IMPRESSIVE, BUT DODGERS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The more the plan seems laid out and ready to be
executed, the better left-hander Carlos Perez performs, and in the
process throwing said plan out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   With right-hander Orel Hershiser pitching 65 miles away in the
minor leagues and lying in wait to rejoin the Dodgers, and perhaps
their starting rotation, Perez went out and had his best outing of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed a season-low one run on three hits in seven
innings, only to have Antonio Osuna waste it with his third
straight bad outing. Olmedo Saenz hit a two-run homer in the eighth
off Osuna to lift the Oakland A's to a 3-1 win over the Dodgers at
Dodger Stadium on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame to waste such a great effort by Carlos,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``It was his best performance of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers wasted a glorious chance to break the tie in the
seventh inning. Alex Cora led off with a double and Dave Hansen,
pinch hitting for Perez, walked. They moved up a base on F.P.
Santangelo's sacrifice bunt, but Jeff Tam relieved and struck out
Mark Grudzielanek looking and got Gary Sheffield to fly out to
center field to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a free-swinging guy (Grudzielanek) up there and he
didn't take the bat off his shoulder,'' Santangelo said. ``Draw
your own conclusions. Grudz hacks every at-bat. He's up swinging in
that situation. He's one of the best hitters on our team, if not
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the eighth, Osuna (0-3) walked Jason Giambi with
two outs to set up Saenz's homer. It's a continuation of a horrible
stretch for Osuna. He's allowed five runs, walked eight and hit a
batter in his last three appearances, totaling 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   And Osuna's demise didn't make Perez feel any better. Perez has
left three of his starts with a lead only to have the bullpen
falter, which is why he wanted to continue pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep going,'' said Perez, who's pitched at least
six innings in seven of his last eight starts. ``When Cora got a
double, I was going to get a good pitch and bunt. But he took me
out. He's the manager. He made the decision. There's nothing I can
say about it. I don't know why he took me out. ... I wish I could
go up and pitch the eighth and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Tam (1-2) struck out four in 1 innings of relief for the win and
right-hander Jason Isringhausen pitched the ninth for his 15th
save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, Carlos was pitching such a strong game, I was
going to let him hit,'' Johnson said. ``Cora leads off with the
double, I had to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's outing throws a kink, though maybe only temporarily,
into what the Dodgers were thinking of doing. They're still likely
to recall Hershiser for the upcoming series against Arizona, but
instead of joining the starting rotation he'll go to the bullpen,
which he should be better prepared to do this time around.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Hershiser wound up with Single-A San Bernardino
because he was having trouble adjusting to his role in the bullpen.
When he tried it earlier this season, Hershiser had a 15.18 ERA in
four relief outings.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was supposed to start today for the Stampede, but his
start was pushed up a day, making for a nifty safety net in case
Perez was rocked by the A's. Hershiser, who allowed three runs on
six hits in four-plus innings against the Mudville Nine, could've
stepped into Perez's spot in the rotation Wednesday against Arizona
if Perez failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Perez was sensational and should face the left-handed
dominated Diamondbacks, not to mention left-hander Randy Johnson.
Of course, Perez already defeated Atlanta's Greg Maddux earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to do my job,'' said Perez, who didn't allow a hit
until Miguel Tejada's two-out double in the fifth. ``I still
believe in my team. I'm glad with my outing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 0309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0153 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     06-10 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHER LAKERS FILL KOBE VOID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's get one thing straight: No one here is
saying the Los Angeles Lakers welcomed the opportunity to play Game
2 of the NBA Finals Friday night at Staples Center without Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an opportunity there for the fellows who usually
toil in the shadow of the thought that the Lakers are a two-man
team, or even a one-man team when that one man is The Big Flagrant
Foul, Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   On a night the state of Indiana will rue as an opportunity lost,
it was Glen Rice, Ron Harper and other Lakers who stepped up large
after Bryant went out of the game late in the first quarter with a
sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice made five of six 3-pointers en route to 21 points. Ron
Harper had a season-high 21 points and an array of eight field
goals that came from baseline jumpers and some age-defying drives,
and all that was in addition to six assists and his usual
claustrophobiic defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry and Brian Shaw added only 11 points between them,
but Horry had six rebounds and four blocks and Shaw seven assists
while eating up 65 minutes of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   While the biggest headlines today will still deal with Bryant's
availability for the rest of the series and another prodigious
night for O'Neal, this was a win seized and insured by the other
fellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys came into the locker room at halftime, and they all
talked about stepping up,'' Bryant said. ``Harp went back to
Cleveland mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper averaged 20 points a game with the Cavs in his first four
years in the league, before becoming a defensive specialist with
the Bulls. Phil Jackson even joked with Harper before the game,
asking him not to miss any shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow I found some energy. I just came out and did the
things I had to do,'' said Harper, who seemed to unnerve the Pacers
defense with all of his unexpected touches. ``We are a team that is
trying to do something here. When a guy gets hurt, we have guys who
can step up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kobe is out, there are some special things we do,''
Jackson said. ``He likes to penetrate, and Harp picked some of that
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The sight of Rice stepping up shouldn't have surprised anyone,
although Pacers coach Larry Bird said he didn't think Rice would be
as active as he was. In the season's first 15 games, played without
Bryant, Rice averaged 18 points a game, three more than his average
for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see me as the third option,'' Rice said.
``Without Kobe, there seems to be more things happening for me out
there. When we swing the ball around like we did tonight, it's
going to create open looks for people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rice is most dangerous when he knows the ball is coming his
way. He's a rhythm shooter (aren't they all?). But Friday, he took
his game to another level by often driving to the basket once he
got the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Now that had to be surprising. ``When Glen gets going, he's very
hard to guard,'' Bryant said. ``And then when he takes it to the
paint, he's even more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people will remember this game for the 39 free throws
O'Neal shot, a NBA record, and for the Pacers lapsing into the
Hack-a-Shaq strategy that is flawed in general and of no use to the
aesthetics of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq, who finished with 40 points and 24 rebounds, started
missing nine of his first 11 free throws, but he was better than
.500 thereafter. The fourth quarter, which lasted 45 minutes, was
an abomination, with the Pacers committing 16 fouls and Shaq taking
16 free throws (and the Lakers 27).
</P>
<P>
   When the Staples Center music director ordered up Queen's ``We
will rock you,'' one was urged to change the words to ``We will
foul you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to win a game. If it takes four hours, then it
takes four hours,'' Bird said. ``When the game is that tight, and
there's four or five minutes left and it seems your only
opportunity ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is a handful. Two or three guys can't stop him. When you
have a guy that quick moving in and out, you just can't defend him
very well. We played hard, but Shaq was better. We're not getting
any post points. They're beating us up inside and we're trying to
live on jumps shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq takes the fouls as a sign of respect you can't stop me, you
can only hope to foul me. He felt that way, too, about the flagrant
foul that was called on him when Travis Best drove the lane and
Shaq knocked the 5-11 guard into Pacoima.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the rules,'' he said. ``Guys grab me and
throw me to the ground. But when a little guy in a sports car hits
the wall, it's a flagrant foul (on Shaq). I guess they figure I'm
big enough and can take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Kobe to perhaps put Shaq and the Pacer dilemma into
easy and inevitable terms: ``Shaq was Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little reason for the Pacers to look forward to Games3,
4 and (maybe) 5 at home, other than sleeping in their own beds.
They couldn't overcome the Lakers on a night when Kobe was idle,
and Hack-a-Shaq fizzled. The Lakers are supremely confident that
they can take the Pacers' best shot.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not even getting it. Outside of Jalen Rose and
Austin Croshere, the Santa Monica Crossroads High product, everyone
else is having a bad series. Reggie Miller is in a serious funk. He
scored 21 points, but didn't have a field goal in the final
quarter. It looked like Reggie didn't want the ball, which is truly
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, both Miller and Rose disagreed with the Hack-a-Shaq
strategy. If all that isn't a sign that the Lakers' stars _ all of
them, and not just Kobe and Shaq _ are aligned properly, then we're
all looking in the wrong solar system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 0323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
