<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0159 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SENATE-ARGUE-TEXT-REV     06-10 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-ARGUE-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SNIPING: WHEN SENATE LEADERS ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(Eds: Text that can be italicized is marked with (BEGIN ITALICS
HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE; replace double parentheses (( )) with
single brackets, which cannot be transmitted to some newspapers.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last few weeks have been unusually acrid in the Senate, with
rhetorical eye-gouging more typical of the fractious House of
Representatives than the stately Senate. The low point came on May
17, when Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, and Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, lobbed verbal
volleys at each other in an angry, arm-waving screaming match on
the Senate floor, largely over the right of the Democratic minority
to offer its legislative priorities as amendments to unrelated
bills. Legislative gridlock ensued.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate returned last week from a 10-day recess, both
leaders seemed a tad chastened by their outburst. Like a married
couple after a bad fight, Lott and Daschle began patching things
up, trading olive branches in the form of legislative wish lists
for the remaining days before the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Senate approved a major campaign finance
measure last week (though it rejected a bill to overhaul the
nation's managed care system). Nonetheless, both sides concede that
the truce is shaky, and that the next partisan breakdown could be
just around the corner. Let's eavesdrop on the spitting match that
launched a thousand insults.
</P>
<P>
   By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) It all started after Republicans and
Democrats passed a pair of dueling symbolic votes on gun safety.
Republicans at first tried to block their rivals' resolution, but
relented after Democrats complained that Lott was stifling debate,
the mother's milk of senatorial life. The senator begged to differ.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   There were a number of things said earlier today on which I just
bit my lip and took it because I thought, for the greater good of
the chamber, we should get an agreement and move forward. . . . I
also feel personally maligned ((dramatic pause for emphasis)) and I
do not appreciate it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) At this point, Lott's voice rises in anger.
His face is taut and he starts waving his left arm toward Daschle,
who is standing a few feet to his left. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I do not think we have any God-given rights in this institution.
We all have certain rights, and I am going to work to protect those
rights. . . . I am getting really tired of people questioning my
commitment to the Senate and to the opportunity for debates. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I tell you, what I am trying to do is find a way for the Senate
to do its work. These charges that are leveled against me are
nonsense. . . . People talk about that civility has broken down,
and there is acrimony. That is ridiculous. I think we have a very
good relationship here. . . . What it is really all about is
getting the work of the Senate done, dealing with real bills and
real issues, not playing games. . . .
</P>
<P>
   As far as order and comity, I support that. I am going to do
everything I can to continue to support that. But I think for us to
have basically one, two, three, four days tied up having debate on
gun amendments instead of having debate on Kosovo and the military
construction appropriations bill is not the way we should be
operating. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Lott holds his folded speech in his hand,
sounding mortally wounded. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I have to go on the record saying I do believe I have been
maligned unfairly. I have bent over backward to try to give notice
when we were going to call up a bill and to have cooperation with
the Democratic leadership to make sure senators had a chance to
make their case.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Lott's final salvo drips with sarcasm. (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   But to come in here and think we have to have a right to offer
non-germane amendments to every appropriations bill that comes
through, and then criticize us for not getting our work done _ Oh,
boy, that is really smart, really smart.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we demand our rights to offer our issues. By the way, why
aren't you guys getting those bills done? I do not believe the
American people are being fooled by all of this.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Having said his piece, Lott yields to
Daschle, who begins calmly, smiling. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Let me say the majority leader was able to get some things off
his chest. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I will tell you this. The way the Senate is being run is wrong.
No majority leader in history has attempted to constrain Senate
debate as aggressively as Senator Lott has chosen to do. . . . That
is his right. He has chosen the way he runs the Senate. I think he
is doing that for what many believe is a laudatory reason. He is
trying to protect his members so they don't have to vote on tough
issues. . . . But no majority leader has ever gone to the extent
that he has. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The usually placid Daschle starts chopping
the air for emphasis, and his voice rises in anger. (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Why do we want to have a debate on amendments? Because that is
the only ability for the minority to express itself. . . . The
majority leader has phrased it very interestingly. He said: I don't
want all these amendments to cause trouble. The more they cause
trouble, the more in jeopardy the bills will be. . . . Over and
over and over and over again, we are told that is the way it is
going to be.
</P>
<P>
   One of our colleagues the other day said it is like the frog
sitting in a pot of water who doesn't notice that the water keeps
getting hotter and ultimately the frog boils to death. Well, the
water continues to heat, and we are slowly boiling to death,
procedurally. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I hope, when we are in the majority, we understand the rights of
the minority. I will admonish my colleagues to do that. But this is
getting to be more and more a second House of Representatives. This
is getting to be more and more a gagged body. This has nothing to
do with the traditions of the Senate that I admired when I became a
senator. . . .
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The senator then delivers an ultimatum.
(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   We have drawn the line. We are not going to be conducting
business as we have in the last several months. That is over. That
is behind us. We can do it the Senate way, or we are not going to
do it at all.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Daschle stops. Lott, looking down at his
lectern, exasperated, lashes back. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   If that is the way it is going to be, then that is the way it is
going to be. . . . I am not going to be threatened and intimidated
by the minority in trying to get our work done. If you want to go
through this approach, if you want to shut down everything, then
everybody loses in the process.
</P>
<P>
   We can cooperate and we can get these bills done. . . . But on
both sides, we have senators who want to offer things that will
cause mischief and delay or kill a bill.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Lott quickly shifts from a stern lecturing
voice to a scold. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I have tried to avoid having an acrimonious relationship. Maybe
it is unavoidable in this election year, but I think that would be
a shame for the American people because, after all, that is about
whom we should be thinking. . . .
</P>
<P>
   But if we are going to hold our breath, turn red in the face and
threaten, then that is the way it will be. But everybody needs to
understand that in that kind of relationship nobody wins; everybody
loses.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Daschle, noticeably calmer, slips on his
glasses and wraps things up with a flourish. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Let me just say no one wants to stomp their feet and get red in
the face _ certainly not me. That is not my style. If it has
happened, it is only because the frustration level continues to
mount. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I am not trying to get excited here. But let me just say as
softly and sincerely as I can: That is not cooperation. That is a
Senate version of dictatorship that I think is unacceptable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
