<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0161 &Cx1f; var-z
u p BC-POLITICS-MONEY-REVIEW     06-10 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-MONEY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLITICS, IT'S ONLY MONEY. YOURS OR THEIRS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Name recognition was never cheap, but this year it
has become more expensive than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Spending at a clip of $300,000 a day, an unknown Wall Street
multimillionaire introduced himself this spring to the voters of
New Jersey. And last week, after investing a record $35 million
(all of it his own money), Jon Corzine won the Democratic primary
for the seat being vacated by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, another
multimillionaire who used his personal fortune as a launching pad
to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's victory over former Gov. Jim Florio is the most recent
reminder that in America these days, candidates must spend enormous
sums _ either their own, or money they have collected _ if they
hope to have even a remote chance to be elected to Congress or the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly impossible for candidates to win armed only with
ideas but little or no money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds corny, but you have to scratch your head and
wonder how would Abraham Lincoln or Harry Truman have functioned in
today's money-takes-all environment,'' asked Charles Lewis,
executive director of the Center for Public Integrity. ``Americans
have two choices _ we can either elect rich, bored
multimillionaires or plastic figures, with perpetual smiles on
their faces who are bought and paid for by special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. who is
worth an estimated $400 million, shattered all spending records for
a Senate primary. He spent $141.50 for each of his 247,351 votes,
an amount that experts say is extraordinarily high. His opponent,
Florio, spent a meager (by comparison) $2.5 million, or $13.89 a
vote. Florio repeatedly accused Corzine of trying to ``buy the
election'' by spending ``obscene'' sums. But Corzine defended his
expenditures as necessary for a political novice running against a
household name like Florio's.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional campaign's largest expense is media commercials.
Because New Jersey has no widely watched television stations of its
own, candidates are forced to advertise on stations in New York
City, the nation's most expensive media market, and Philadelphia,
the nation's fourth most expensive market.
</P>
<P>
   To put Corzine's $35 million war chest in context, he spent
nearly as much in his primary bid as the  &UR; combined total &LR;  spent in
1998 by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and the challenger who unseated him,
Charles Schumer. At the time, it was the most expensive Senate race
in New York history, though the record will most likely be broken
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Corzine's jaw-dropping spending spree should not come as
much of a surprise in a year when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
already spent a record $82 million to win the Republican
presidential nomination and experts estimate that a record $3
billion will be spent on the 2000 presidential and congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious why the regular person doesn't even bother to
run,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21 and former
president of Common Cause, who helped shape the post-Watergate laws
that govern today's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gulf between winning well-financed candidates and their
underfinanced opponents just continues to grow,'' Wertheimer said.
``And that gulf greatly narrows the pool of individuals in this
country who are prepared to become candidates. Any potential
candidate is faced with the huge costs of campaigns, the big
advantage your incumbent opponent starts out with in terms of
surplus funds and the fact that the only place you can turn to is
personal wealth or donors who want something in return.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 94 incumbents in the House of Representatives ran
unopposed, the highest number in 40 years. An additional 114
incumbents ran against challengers who had raised less than
$25,000, a study by Common Cause found. For all practical purposes,
nearly half of the House races in 1998 involved incumbents who ran
unopposed or with no threat of losing. In Florida, 18 of the 23
House incumbents seeking re-election ran unopposed, including 12
Republicans and six Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This year, political strategists say only three dozen highly
contested House races are likely, or for less than 10 percent of
the 435 seats. The experts attribute the few competitive races to
the extraordinary advantage that the current campaign finance
system gives to incumbents, who can raise money with relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves only self-financed candidates with the ability to
get in the game. Candidates who spend millions of their own money
lose more often than they win.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Michael Huffington poured nearly $30 million _ almost
all of it his own money _ into his unsuccessful bid to defeat
Dianne Feinstein for a U.S. Senate seat in California. And Al
Checchi, a California airline executive, set the record for any
statewide primary when he spent $38 million of his fortune in his
failed gubernatorial bid in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do candidates who are outspent by wide margins win. But
in a House race on New York's Long Island in 1992, Rick Lazio
unseated incumbent Rep. Thomas J. Downey, even though Lazio was
outspent by a 5-to-1 margin. Downey was hurt _ and Lazio was helped
_ by Downey's overdrafts at the House bank.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to judge if Corzine's victory was attributable
more to his $35 million investment or New Jersey voters' disgust
with Florio's $2.8 billion tax increase as governor in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, Corzine will go against Bob Franks, a
four-term Republican congressman from Union County. In his victory
speech last week, Franks borrowed a line of Florio's to begin his
campaign against Corzine: ``Good evening, New Jersey, I'm Bob
Franks, the candidate with experience that money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, for his part, will continue to add to his spending
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center
for Responsive Politics, ``when you've broken the record for the
most spending ever and there's still five months to go until
November, you've left the stratosphere and entered the
ionosphere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
