</P>
<P>
   The EPA found that chlorpyrifos, also known by the trade names
Dursban and Lorsban, caused brain damage in newborn rats and an
unacceptable rate of ailments in children. Manufacturers agreed to
stop making the chemical for uses outside farms by the end of the
year, and agreed to curtail its use on grapes, apples and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANDREW C. REVKIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Congo Death Toll
</P>
<P>
   A leading refugee agency said two years of warfare in eastern
Congo have caused the deaths of more than 1.7 million people. Many
of them died from hunger and malaria after fleeing the fighting,
according to the agency, the International Rescue Committee. The
survey, conducted in April and May, put the death toll in a
five-province area at 18 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Perot May Not Run
</P>
<P>
   In his quest for the Reform Party's presidential nomination, Pat
Buchanan got a major lift when a spokesman for Ross Perot, the
party's founder and two-time nominee, said Perot had all but
decided not to seek the nomination this year.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for Buchanan's opponents, who fear he will
impose his conservative social views on a party that has taken no
official position on such issues. John Hagelin of the Natural Law
Party, which favors across-the-board government reform, is
preparing to fight Buchanan for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL JANOFSKY
</P>
<P>
   Hurdle for Abortion Pill
</P>
<P>
   The French abortion pill's long and convoluted journey to the
United States took another turn, with the news that the Food and
Drug Administration is considering tight restrictions on the drug,
RU-486, including a requirement that only doctors who perform
surgical abortions prescribe it.
</P>
<P>
   Though preliminary, the plan outraged abortion rights advocates,
who say it would defeat the purpose of the pill: to provide easy
access to abortion in the privacy of the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Charges Dropped
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Atlanta dismissed murder charges against Ray
Lewis, the Baltimore Ravens' all-pro linebacker. Instead, Lewis
pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor count of obstruction of justice _
the result of his misleading statements to the police _ and
accepted a sentence of 12 months of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 25, had been charged, along with two friends, in the
stabbing deaths of two men during a street brawl outside a
nightclub on the night of the Super Bowl in Atlanta in January. The
trial of the co-defendants is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination on Wall Street
</P>
<P>
   Even Wall Street traders who make $1 million a year can be
victims of sex discrimination in the workplace, the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission declared after taking up a
complaint against Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Paving the way for lawsuits, the commission said the firm had
discriminated against women who worked in its institutional stocks
division and had retaliated against a trader, Allison K.
Schieffelin, for complaining publicly. The firm denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PATRICK McGEEHAN
</P>
<P>
   Support for a Cosmic Theory
</P>
<P>
   The terrain in Earth's corner of the cosmos has become a lot
clearer. At a meeting of the American Astronomical Society,
scientists described measurements of the distances to 100,000
galaxies, all lying within a few billion light years of Earth and
its galaxy, the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   The galaxies revealed colossal structures the scientists likened
to cosmic continents. Cosmologists were pleased to see that, just
as their theories of cosmic origins predicted, the survey found
these continents to have a maximum size _ a limit they call ``the
end of greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   Ending a Royal Chill
</P>
<P>
   The curtsy and the garden party chat took only a moment, but
they ended two decades of enforced silence between Queen Elizabeth
II and Camilla Parker Bowles, mistress to Prince Charles. By
agreeing to attend a formal luncheon at her 51-year-old son's
country estate with full knowledge of just which 52-year-old
divorced woman would be by his side, the monarch signaled her
acceptance of the relationship that the heir to the throne had long
sought.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Laser Shoots Down Missile
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when politics thrust laser-based missile defenses
into the spotlight, the technology was clearly not up to the job.
Now it has caught up a bit: A laser designed to protect Israel's
northern border blew up a small rocket in flight during a test at
the Army's White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico. Supporters said
the success showed that a national missile defense was no longer
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   Shorter Lives for Americans
</P>
<P>
   By most demographic estimates, an American born in the last year
or two should live, on average, to nearly 77. But the World Health
Organization, using a new calculation, has lowered the figure for
``healthy life expectancy'' to 70 because of the risks faced by
Americans, particularly men _ smoking and violence are high on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
