<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-10 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-EUROPE (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin had barely said
farewell to President Clinton this week before the Russian leader
and his top aides fanned out across Europe to campaign against the
American plan for a national missile defense. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND-SOCCER-THUGS (London) _ It was the English who first
formalized rules for the sport called ``the beautiful game,'' but
England is less known these days for the gracefulness its athletes
show on the soccer field than for the ugliness its rabid supporters
cause off it. As a reflection of what a serious national matter
soccer hooliganism has become for England, the responsibility for
combating it has been assigned to the top-level intelligence agency
that was created in 1992 to combat organized crime, international
drug dealing, money laundering, immigration fraud and
counterfeiting. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   FIJI-SCENE (Nadi, Fiji) _ On approximately 299 and two-thirds of
its 300 islands, there are no indications that Fiji is in turmoil,
with rebels occupying Parliament and holding three dozen hostages
who include the elected prime minister, much of his Cabinet and the
daughter of the country's president. As Brad Ammann, a 29-year-old
honeymooner from Hermosa Beach, Calif., put it: ``The only sign
there's a coup going on is that there's nobody around.'' By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX (Mexico City) _ To his opponents Vicente Fox, who is
mounting the most serious challenge to Mexico's governing party in
a presidential election in 70 years, is a political chameleon who
talks out of both sides of his mouth. To his supporters, he is a
clever strategist who has built strength well beyond his small
rightist party by defying ideological labels. Whatever the case, it
is clear that by pairing conservative credentials with a
center-left position on a range of issues Fox has succeeded in
attracting supporters from across the political landscape. By Sam
Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Endowed with a
constitution that has been called an international model and beset
by an AIDS crisis that is among the worst in the world, South
Africa finds itself trying to reconcile the two in the face of a
challenge here to the longstanding practice of disqualifying gay
men from giving blood. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-WOMEN (Undated) _ Five years after a watershed conference
held in Beijing articulated and affirmed what more than 180 nations
could agree were the universal rights of women, a week-long
follow-up meeting ended Saturday at the United Nations with no
significant victories for opponents who have spent the last five
years trying to reverse those gains. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-ASSAD (Undated) _ Syrian President Hafez Assad died
Saturday, a Lebanese doctor with close ties to the Assad family
says. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-TV-DRAMA (Baltimore) _ Who Gets to Tell a Black Story?:
When David Simon proposed to HBO a television series based on his
book, ``The Corner,'' about black inner-city drug addicts, he was
not thinking much about the fact that he was white. But as the
project began to take shape, the issues of race loomed ever larger.
HBO was not about to make a series about black drug addicts created
by, as one HBO executive put it later, ``a bunch of white guys.''
Charles S. Dutton, who had grown up in the city, spent his early
years on its streets and had his own tale of redemption, was chosen
to direct all six episodes. But, as he said, there would not be one
moment when he would forget that ``it's a white writer and a white
producer and it's HBO and a black director.'' By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-HEALTH-REFERENDUM (Boston) _ With one final petition drive
this weekend, a coalition of physicians, nurses, senior citizens'
groups, labor unions and others are expected to gather the last
several thousand signatures they need to put before Massachusetts
voters what experts call the most sweeping health-care referendum
on any state's ballot this fall. The referendum would require the
Legislature to find a way to provide health insurance coverage for
all by mid-2002 in a state where more than 600,000 people lack it.
It would also introduce a super-powerful ``patient's bill of
rights.'' And it would put a temporary ban on the conversion of
nonprofit hospitals to for-profit. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATHROW-LAWYER (Houston) _ On death row at the Terrell
unit of the Texas state prison in Livingston, inmates and death
penalty lawyers refer sardonically to a place they call the Mock
Wing. This metaphorical prison enclave has housed at least a dozen
death row inmates, some already executed, who shared the same
lawyer, Ronald G. Mock. One of Mock's clients, Gary Graham, 36, is
scheduled to die by lethal injection after a 19-year court battle.
In addition to the innocence claim, what makes Graham's case
particularly compelling is that his new lawyers are portraying it
as a textbook example of how bad lawyering sends poor people to
death row. By Sara Rimer and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   YESHIVAS-EXPAND (Baltimore) _ Inside Ner Israel Rabbinical
College, the study hall reverberates with the voices of hundreds of
young Orthodox men, debating one-on-one, across tables stacked high
with books of Jewish law and tradition. What is happening here is
part of a growing trend within Orthodox Judaism's most rigorously
traditional sector. The number of collegiate and graduate students
pursuing religious studies in these all-male institutions ``has
probably almost doubled'' since 1980, to about 18,000 nationwide,
writes William B. Helmreich in ``The World of the Yeshiva.'' By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-PAL (Undated) _ On Aug. 27, 1998, Brian L. Buckley, a Los
Angeles lawyer, received an e-mail message from a New York literary
agent, Lucianne Goldberg. Her one-sentence message to him said,
``Someone very important wants to know who you are.'' The important
someone turned out to be Linda Tripp. It turned out that Tripp had
been reading and finding inspiration in Buckley's observations
about the Lewinsky scandal on a conservative, anti-Clinton Internet
site, FreeRepublic.com. In the ensuing months, Buckley and Tripp
began a friendship that blossomed from e-mail messages to telephone
calls. ``She and I are pals by now,'' said Buckley. By Jill
Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-TEACHER (Newton, Mass.) _ A first-grade teacher who told his
students that he is gay has provoked a debate among parents and
educators here about how soon is too soon to talk about sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ADS (Undated) _ Responding rapidly to a 15-state
advertising campaign by the Democrats, the Republican Party
unveiled its first national commercial, a spot detailing Gov.
George W. Bush's proposals for overhauling Social Security that
will begin running Monday in 17 states, from New England to the
Pacific Northwest. The swiftness with which the Republican National
Committee is taking to the airwaves is a marked departure from four
years ago, when the Democratic Party began running issue
advertisements on behalf of President Clinton weeks before the
cash-strapped Republicans could start their commercials for their
presidential candidate, Bob Dole. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-HOUSE-FUNDS (Washington) _ Democrats have a financial
advantage in the contest for control of the House of
Representatives. That's right, Democrats. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ High-level attention for state
House seat; Nashville billboards bring smiles to GOP; Congressman
changes ways after a defeat; A spot for LaRouche? No way, party
says. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ What Women Want, part two. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Technology, the all-purpose
justification. By Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
