<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGNS-COMPARE-REV     06-10 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGNS-COMPARE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNS PAST: WHAT A YEAR THIS HAS BEEN! BUT WHICH ONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is an argument to be made that modern
politics and science fiction have a great deal in common, from
unusual life forms to freaky and largely inexplicable phenomena.
But they are perhaps most similar in this regard: Both exhibit a
peculiar fascination with time travel.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you probably think you are watching the
presidential race of 2000. Wrong. It is really 1988, or at least
that is where many political scientists and Democratic strategists
will transport you. They cite the familiar dynamic of a vice
president (the elder George Bush then, Al Gore now) who belonged to
a successful administration and whose apparent disadvantage against
a heavily promoted governor (Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts then,
George W. Bush of Texas now) turned out to be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it is 1960, as other political scientists and
Republican strategists would have you believe. The vice president
(Richard M. Nixon then, Gore now) cannot trade on his
administration's high regard in the face of an upbeat, arguably
more charismatic challenger (John F. Kennedy then, Bush now), who
ultimately prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Any takers for 1992? That was when the administration in power
was challenged and eventually defeated by an intermittently folksy
southerner (Bill Clinton then, Bush now), who was attacked as both
a foreign policy know-nothing and the chief executive of a state
(Arkansas then, Texas now) with abysmally low national ratings on
several important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick any year,'' conceded Allan J. Lichtman, chairman of the
history department at American University, ``and you're going to
find some similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what a plethora of prognosticators are doing, to the
point where the first presidential election of a new millennium is
being presented as deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as Lichtman theorized, it is because the 2000
presidential election hasn't proved terribly interesting so far.
The economy is peachy, we're not at war and the two principal
candidates have overlapping pedigrees (sons of famous politicians,
graduates of prep school and the Ivy League).
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the very difficulty of predicting the outcome makes
rummaging through the past for a vision of the future more
seductive.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the practice is rampant. At a briefing for
reporters in Austin, Texas, last week, Bush's advisers variously
mentioned 1960, 1968, 1980 and 1988 as providing omens favorable to
their candidate. One of the advisers dwelled for a bit on 1980,
when challenger Ronald Reagan defeated President Jimmy Carter. By
this example, a Republican governor tarred by opponents as risky
and extremist defeated a nationally known quantity who was regarded
as perhaps a little dull and pious.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the Bush campaign's chief strategist, has been known
to derive inspiration from as far back as 1896, when William
McKinley, the Republican governor of Ohio, united a divided party
and reached out to new groups of voters. McKinley was reaching out
to immigrants; Bush is making his appeal to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Martin P. Wattenberg, a political scientist at the University of
California at Irvine, is not buying it. ``It's definitely not
1896,'' he said, ``because that was a realignment election.
Although, if Bush does win big, then I guess it could be 1896.''
Then again, he added, ``1988 sounds pretty good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does not sound good to Henry F. Graff, a retired
professor of history at Columbia University who has written
extensively about the American presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say 1960, when you had a vice president running
against an upstart,'' said Graff, who played down 1988 for several
reasons. Dukakis' period of ascendance in polls, he noted, was
briefer than Bush's has been, and it came when he was less familiar
to voters than Bush is now.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the scholars who do not look for any one year but
rather devise a timeless recipe _ a teaspoon of economic growth, a
soupcon of the current president's approval rating, a dash of
voters' appetite for change _ that explains and predicts the
outcome of every election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more informative,'' said Alan Abramowitz, a
political scientist at Emory University whose mathematical model
augurs a victory by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would violate the example of 1960, but it would
confirm the lessons of 1988, and maybe even 1908 and 1928, when the
departing president's designated successor _ in each case,
admittedly, someone other than the vice president _ succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   Graff acknowledged that it is all just a guessing game, with no
year exactly like any other, for an exceedingly simple reason:
``History does not repeat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   His scientific proof? ``These candidates running around now, in
their dress-down clothing, don't look like anything in the history
books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
