<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-EASTEUROPE-WOMEN-REVI     06-10 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTEUROPE-WOMEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE FALL, TRAFFIC IN FLESH, NOT DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ALISON SMALE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anybody has borne the brunt of the changes in Eastern Europe
and the former Soviet Union since the fall of communism, it has
been women. While the picture varies wildly from the relatively
developed countries of central Europe to the huge, impoverished
swaths of the Balkans, Russia and central Asia, women have not
benefited from any economic gains as men have. At the same time,
they appear to have disproportionately shouldered the stresses
brought by a total change of lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Health care and child care have all but collapsed in many
places. In some, fewer girls are finishing high school than 10
years ago. Between 1985 and 1997, a recently released U.N. study
found, the transition to a market economy meant that the number of
working women fell by 40 percent in Hungary, 21 percent in Russia
and 24 to 31 percent in the Baltic states. Of course, men have lost
jobs, too, and they often sink into apathy and alcoholism, women
say. Women who might have hoped for a clerical or professional job
under communism find themselves forced into menial work _
frequently in the unprotected realm of the black economy _ to make
ends meet while caring for children and keeping their family
together. Some, indeed, are forced into prostitution, often after
being trafficked abroad on the pretense that they will work as a
maid or waitress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women take the role of savior _ they try to save themselves,
their family,'' said Olga Gerasymyuk, the host of a popular
television program on social affairs in Ukraine. Women's magazines
there promote what may seem to the West an idiosyncratic message of
empowerment: ``They teach them to save the gentle spirit of their
husbands, who are at a loss,'' Gerasymyuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Zina Mounla, who coordinates programs across the former Soviet
bloc for the U.N. Development Fund for Women, said that statistics
are hard to come by on how poorly women are doing compared with men
in this shifting environment.
</P>
<P>
   One area in which east European women have clearly regressed is
in political representation. Under communism, quotas ensured that
one-third of the seats in the often nominal parliaments went to
women. ``Even now,'' said Gulmira Asanbayeva, an activist from
Kyrgyzstan who promotes women's leadership, ``we remember the names
of famous women from the Soviet period,'' women who had the kind of
political sway now exercised almost exclusively by men.
</P>
<P>
   Asanbayeva, 22, was one of the 10,000 women estimated to have
attended a conference in New York last week titled Beijing Plus
Five, which examined the worldwide status of women five years after
a giant gathering in Beijing that was attended by, among others,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who inspired heated debate in the United
States over the wisdom of a first lady visiting China. In hundreds
of meetings, formally and informally, women discussed the gains
made toward equality and set goals for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Although Asanbayeva and several other eastern Europeans spoke
out on women's causes, there was little indication that they would
succeed at home any time soon. Lenka Simerska, a 24-year-old
working with the Gender Studies Center in Prague, said she feels
far removed from the stresses of poverty described by women from
the Balkans or the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic, she said, men were frustrated by the
deadening hand of Communism for so long that they took over
everything after its fall in 1989. As a result, educated women
seeking a good job often fall prey to chauvinist prejudices about
leaving their jobs to have children (paid maternity leave in the
Czech Republic lasts up to three years) or taking time off to rear
them; above all they lack the mechanisms for righting perceived
wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's consciousness and solidarity are not great,'' Simerska
said, predicting change only when ``young women will slowly get
angry, and something will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For some women and girls, particularly the poor and
undereducated, notions of power are unimaginable. Indeed the poorer
and more uneducated the women are, the more likely it is that they
will become involved in prostitution. Irene Freudenschuss-Reichl,
Austria's delegate to Beijing Plus Five, estimated that half a
million women from central and Eastern Europe are shipped abroad
each year as part of the worldwide trafficking in prostitutes. A
recent American study shows that an increasing share of the 45,000
to 50,000 such women traveling to the United States each year come
from the former Soviet bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Selma Gasi, 20, an activist with the Women to Women group in
Bosnia, tells a particularly chilling tale of pimps, accompanied by
older women, scouring the war-devastated villages, ostensibly for
sitters or housemaids, and taking girls as young as 14 to
strip-dancing bars where they become prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mounla said this is not unique to the Balkans; it is seen in
Ukraine and Russia, where pimps have been known to take teen-agers
from orphanages that release them at age 16. Some women know they
are going to work as prostitutes, she said, but that doesn't mean
they should forfeit all their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Yasmina Dimiskovska, of the Union of Women in Macedonia, said
Russian and Ukrainian women are trafficked through her country to
Italy, or their passports seized locally and they are sent to
strip-dancing bars. Again, statistics are hard to come by, but 40
women came from Ukraine last month alone, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk to them, go to the police,'' Dimiskovska said. But
``there is no shelter willing to help'' women who lack official
identity papers. If they are shipped home, she added, they risk
repercussions from the criminals who first sent them abroad. ``It's
a circle which can't be stopped,'' she said. ``I think they cannot
do anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0182 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-N     06-10 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS THE MOMENT IN THE MIDEAST. (BUT FOR WHAT?) 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Shultz said it. James Baker said it. So did
Warren Christopher and Madeleine Albright. When it comes to making
peace in the Middle East, four successive secretaries of state all
sounded the same theme: Americans cannot want peace more than the
parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the United States must be both available and
aloof, appearing as a willing partner but not an over-eager suitor.
In fact, in late 1993, less than a year into the Clinton
administration, Christopher set modest goals, saying that making
peace was going to take ``a lot of time and patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and patience are the two things President Clinton no longer
has. And now, with only seven and a half months left as president,
he even may want peace more than the parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in Clinton's announcement, after meeting with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel in Lisbon 10 days ago, that
peace between the Israelis and the Palestinians was ``within view
now.'' He said the two sides would restart negotiations in
Washington this week and his administration dangled the possibility
of a three-way Camp David-style summit in which Clinton himself
would take part. The sense of urgency Clinton expressed was
reminiscent of the pleading that the late King Hussein of Jordan
was famous for, using every new political wrinkle and change on the
ground to say that that was the last chance for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and Middle East experts talk now of the
need to seize the moment created by a new reality: Israel's
withdrawal from Lebanon two weeks ago, which Clinton said imposes a
much greater sense of urgency on the parties to resolve the very
substantial differences that remain between them: the size and
shape of a Palestinian state, the future of Jerusalem and the fate
of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only certain moments in history when all the parties
are available, when they see that a negotiated deal is in their
interests and they don't believe they have better options,'' said
Thomas R. Smerling, Washington director of the Israel Policy Forum,
a research institute that focuses on the peace process. ``This is
one of those times.''
</P>
<P>
   But moments and deadlines come and go, and urgency is one of the
most easily manipulated commodities in the Middle East. It has been
used to derail progress toward peace. Witness all the years wasted
because of Palestinian terrorist attacks and Israeli retaliation,
troop movements and street violence. In that atmosphere,
concessions became impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But urgency can, if invoked with skill, be used to push the
region toward peace as well. The argument is that every opportunity
is fleeting in the Middle East, where attitudes can shift with
remarkable speed, so that when a moment is ripe for conciliation,
it must be seized.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having run out of time for the more familiar formula of
patience, Clinton is left with the appeal of urgency, in effect
trying to turn his biggest liability _ his lame-duck status _ into
an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the moment is urgent for him. And certainly urgency
is felt by Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the newspaper Haaretz last month, Barak
spoke of ``a golden opportunity'' for Israel to make peace, not
only with the Palestinians, but also with the Syrians and the
Lebanese. ``Do we await the future passively with our eyes shut,''
he asked, ``or do we take an active stance vis-a-vis the reality
and try to modify it to our advantage?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Arafat, he has no good alternative. Unilaterally
declaring an independent Palestinian state, as he has threatened to
do, would deprive him of the aid and good will he has received from
the rest of the world since he set out to make peace in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Both men know that if they don't get a deal this year it may be
a long time before a similar opportunity comes. Clinton offers a
carefully built reputation as an honest broker that neither of the
presumptive presidential nominees, Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, enjoy. Over the years, Gore has taken an
uncritical pro-Israeli stance; Bush is a blank slate when it comes
to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rushed nature of the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon
has stirred up Israeli and Palestinian politics in ways that may
prove damaging to prospects for a quick deal. Barak is fighting off
a rebellion by conservative coalition allies that could produce new
elections. And the frenzied meetings of long-divided families at
the now-accessible Lebanese border could create a new dynamic for
the extremely sensitive issue of what happens to the many
Palestinian refugees who would remain outside a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's pleas for urgency notwithstanding, the
lame-duck year of any administration tends to limit its
accomplishments in diplomacy. The last president to be finishing
out a second term was Ronald Reagan; in 1988, Shultz launched a
peace initiative after the Palestinians began the uprising known as
the intifadeh, but the effort went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for any U.S. negotiator, Middle East peacemaking requires
both staying power and an unswerving belief in the impossible.
``There is a good chance to come to an agreement,'' said Henry
Kissinger, who as secretary of state spent seven straight weeks
shuttling between Damascus and Jerusalem after the 1973 war. ``Both
sides have run out of options and both sides are at the limit of
their concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would give Clinton, Kissinger said, ``I
would tell him to stay calm and be available as a facilitator. And
I would tell him not to be more interested than the parties
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; var-z
