<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-DEATHROW-LAWYER     06-10 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATHROW-LAWYER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWYER'S DEATH ROW RECORD A CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: List of Mock's clients who have been executed or are on death
row follows story.) 
 By SARA RIMER and RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On death row at the Terrell unit of the Texas state
prison in Livingston, an hour's drive north of here, inmates and
death penalty lawyers refer sardonically to a place they call the
Mock Wing. This metaphorical prison enclave has housed at least a
dozen death row inmates, some already executed, others awaiting
their final punishment, who shared the same lawyer, Ronald G. Mock.
</P>
<P>
   Mock, who was appointed by Harris County judges to represent
indigent defendants in capital cases, says he believes he has had
more clients sentenced to death than any lawyer in the country. One
of those clients, Robert Anthony Carter, was executed on May 31. On
June 22, another of Mock's clients, Gary Graham, 36, is scheduled
to die by lethal injection after a 19-year court battle.
</P>
<P>
   In large part because Graham's conviction turned on a single
eyewitness who saw him only fleetingly and at night, his new
lawyers are insisting that he is innocent and are pressing for a
postponement of his execution and for a new trial. In earlier
pleadings, they also raised questions about Mock's competency as
trial counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's is the latest high-profile death penalty case to focus
attention on Gov. George W. Bush and how the death penalty is
administered in his state. With their appeals exhausted, Graham's
lawyers are asking the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles to
recommend that Bush grant Graham some form of clemency. Last week,
Bush granted a 30-day reprieve to another condemned prisoner, Ricky
Nolen McGinn. It was only the second time during his tenure that he
has stepped in to stop an execution.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the innocence claim, what makes Graham's case
particularly compelling is that his new lawyers, and other critics
of the death penalty, are portraying it as a textbook example of
how bad lawyering sends poor people to death row here and in other
states across the country. Mock, who boasted in an interview this
week that he had flunked criminal law at Texas Southern
University's Thurgood Marshall School of Law, called no witnesses
during the guilt phase of Graham's trial, which lasted two days. He
did not challenge the testimony of the single eyewitness who sealed
Graham's guilty verdict, although other witnesses could have
provided conflicting testimony. He called only two witnesses during
the penalty phase, when his job was to persuade the jury to spare
his client's life.
</P>
<P>
   Mock, who had only three years of legal experience when he took
on Graham's defense, acknowledged in the interview that he did
almost no investigation of the case. He knew in his gut, he said,
that none of the witnesses could help his client. Mock's
investigator, Mervyn West, as well as his co-counsel, Chester L.
Thornton, both say Mock had made it clear that he assumed Graham
was guilty, an assertion Mock disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton said Graham's fate had haunted him for 19 years. It was
his first and last capital case. ``I have serious questions whether
we presented a fair and adequate defense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mock said that five of his clients on death row have petitions
pending in court that accuse him of ineffectiveness of counsel. The
Texas Bar Association has reprimanded him several times for
professional misconduct. ``I have a permanent parking spot at the
grievance committee,'' Mock said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Mock, who drives a Rolls-Royce and a
Harley-Davidson, was one of the top-earning court-appointed lawyers
on death cases here, making by his estimation $120,000 to $130,000
a year. Mock said he stopped handling capital cases 10 years ago
because there was not enough money in them.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Mock got so much work is that there was
plenty to go around. Harris County, where he practices, tries more
capital cases than any other county in the state. The county, which
includes Houston, has 148 people, including Graham, on death row.
Since executions resumed here in 1976, Harris County has put 62
people to death, making it the jurisdiction with the third-highest
number of executions in the country. Only the state of Texas itself
and the state of Virginia have had more.
</P>
<P>
   Like most counties in Texas, Harris County does not have a
public defender system. Thus judges, who are elected, appoint
lawyers for the indigent, and while standards have improved
considerably, when Graham and many other death row inmates were
being tried in the 1980s there were no guidelines for
court-appointed lawyers. Defense lawyers and former judges say that
many judges routinely appointed lawyers who moved cases quickly,
and that there was pressure on lawyers to contribute to the judges'
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cronyism was rampant,'' said Jay Burnett, who presided over
capital cases as a district judge in Houston for 14 years and
crusaded for the higher standards that are now in place in Harris
County, including certification and training procedures for
lawyers. But back when Mock was handling the Graham case in 1981,
Burnett said, ``They were appointing people who had no business
doing capital cases.''
</P>
<P>
   With his easy manner and jokes, Mock became a favorite of a
handful of Harris County judges, some of whom were impressed by the
strong rapport he established with clients. Another reason judges
appointed Mock, Thornton and other lawyers said, was that Mock is
black, and with few African-American lawyers practicing criminal
defense law in Houston in the 1980s, judges were interested in
promoting what diversity they could.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Trevathan, who was the judge in the Graham case and is
now in private practice, said, ``I always thought Ron Mock was a
good lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   But a review of Mock's legal career here shows that he was
jailed during jury selection in one capital murder trial for
failing to file court papers in another case on time for a
condemned client's appeal. A federal judge who later reviewed the
case during which Mock was jailed wrote that his confidence in the
verdict was ``completely undermined'' because of Mock's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Several clients filed complaints against Mock, with one claiming
that he smelled alcohol on Mock's breath during their discussions.
Mock at one time owned 11 bars, including Buster's Drinkery, a
popular downtown hangout for judges and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drank a lot of whiskey,'' Mock said, talking in his office
in Houston, where the walls are decorated with portraits of the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X. ``I drank whiskey
with judges. I drank whiskey in the best bars. But it never
affected my ability. It never affected my performance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The performance of appointed lawyers in capital cases has become
a subject of national concern. Texas has 468 condemned prisoners,
the second-largest death row population in the country (California
has the largest), and Bush has vigorously defended the fairness and
professionalism of his state's judicial system. He insists that not
one of the 131 people executed during his tenure was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined a request to be interviewed about the Graham case.
His spokesman, Dan Bartlett, said: ``Governor Bush takes every
death penalty case very seriously. The governor's office conducts
an exhaustive and lengthy review process of each death penalty
case. Having said that, we believe it is inappropriate for the
governor or his staff to grant an interview in the middle of this
review process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case has put a spotlight on the way Texas appoints
lawyers to handle death penalty cases and the woeful performance of
scores of local lawyers, two of whom slept through parts of several
trials and others of whom have presented few if any arguments on
behalf of their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't indict Ronnie,'' said Thornton, who rarely practices
law these days and runs a small business exporting medical
equipment. ``I indict the system that creates Ronnie, and lawyers
like him. Judges appoint lawyers who play along with the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers and judges say there are now some highly skilled
court-appointed lawyers on capital cases in Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   Roe Wilson, the Harris County assistant district attorney who is
handling the Graham case, said: ``I think Ron did a competent job.
By law you are not guaranteed a perfect or excellent counsel.
You're guaranteed competent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking from a holding cell on death row in Livingston on
Wednesday, Graham said the fact that Mock was also a black man had
been reassuring. ``I tended to trust him more,'' Graham said. ``I
felt like he would stand up and fight the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a high school dropout who grew up poor with a mother in
and out of mental hospitals, was charged in May 1981 with fatally
shooting Bobby Lambert, 53, during an attempted nighttime robbery
in the parking lot of a Safeway supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was arrested after a weeklong crime rampage that followed
the murder of Lambert, and he subsequently pleaded guilty to 10
aggravated robberies during which he terrorized his victims by
pointing guns at them and threatened to kill them. He shot two of
the victims; one of the men later lost a leg as a result. Rape
charges against Graham were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his arrest, a Harris County judge appointed Mock
as the lead lawyer in Graham's capital case. Thornton, who knew
Graham and had represented him on some juvenile offenses, was
appointed his co-counsel.
</P>
<P>
   West, a former police officer, was brought in as the
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   While defense investigators in capital cases routinely spend
months searching for any shred of evidence that might save their
client's life, West said in an interview this week that he wrapped
up his work on the Graham case in less than a week. ``I had a
couple of quick talks with eyewitnesses and went over the police
report,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mock said Graham was unable to tell him where he had been on the
night of the murder. ``His position was that he was on a drug and
alcohol binge, and didn't remember where he was,'' Mock said.
During the trial, two witnesses went to the courtroom to tell Mock
that they wanted to testify that they were with Graham the night of
the murder. Mock said this week that he was too busy to talk to
them, but that he knew they could not have helped his client. This
contradicts an earlier affidavit, used by the state to deny Graham
a new trial, in which Mock denied knowing of these witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   At least two witnesses who might have helped Graham were named
in the police report. Sherian Etuk, a child protective services
worker for the state, and Ronald Hubbard, a postal worker, had been
working at the Safeway at the time of the murder, and both said
they saw the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Etuk and Hubbard, whose affidavits are included in Graham's
clemency petition, both said in interviews this week that Graham
was not the man they saw. Graham is just under 5 foot 10. Both
Hubbard and Etuk said that the man they saw was under 5 foot 5.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the assistant district attorney, said Etuk and Hubbard
were sincere but mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   Mock said this week that he did not bother to interview the
other witnesses because if he had put them on the stand, it would
have allowed the prosecution to tell the jury about Graham's other
crimes. But Wilson said that Mock was wrong about the law, that
such testimony would not have given the prosecution that opening.
</P>
<P>
   No forensics evidence connected Graham to the murder, and the
police report contained ballistics evidence showing that the
.22-caliber revolver found on Graham when he was arrested could not
have been the weapon that killed Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   The case came down to one witness, Bernadine Skillern, a former
school secretary who has never wavered in her identification of
Graham over the years. ``She was stronger than an acre of garlic,''
Mock said this week, repeating an assertion he has made many times.
He did not attack Skillern's identification before the jury, and in
his closing arguments he said she deserved a standing ovation for
her bravery in testifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put on no defense,'' said Jack B. Zimmermann, who is
working with Richard H. Burr on Graham's case before the board of
pardons and parole. ``If he didn't attack the mistaken
identification, there was nothing for the jury to do but come back
with a finding of guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court warned in a 1967 case against ``the
vagaries of eyewitness identification,'' arguing that ``the annals
of criminal law are rife with instances of mistaken
identification.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Mock had known of the eyewitnesses and the ballistics
report, legal technicalities prevented the lawyers who followed him
from getting a hearing on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Graham's case lies on the fault line of the Texas death
penalty system,'' Burr said. ``He had abysmal trial counsel, who
failed to present stark evidence of his innocence based on
exonerating eyewitnesses and forensics evidence. Thereafter, when
this evidence was discovered, the courts all decided that this
evidence was presented too late to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   With the execution of his former client approaching, Mock said
he had no regrets about his work on the Graham case. ``There's
nothing I could have done that would have changed the result,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
