<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0185 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MIDDLECLASS-CULTURE-R     06-10 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDDLECLASS-CULTURE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONELY CROWD JOINS THE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Bobos in Paradise,'' his acute if sometimes cutesy new book
about the merger of America's bourgeoisie and its Bohemians (which
he merges into ``Bobos''), David Brooks looks back now and then to
the 1950s, the golden age of the liberal science of sociology.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, journalists like William H. Whyte Jr. (``The
Organization Man,'' 1956) and sociologists like David Riesman and
his colleagues Nathan Glazer and Reuel Denney (``The Lonely
Crowd,'' 1950), were lamenting the plunge of the middle class into
corporation-dominated conformity.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, Brooks, though mocking the tastes and
pretensions of today's upper middle class, confesses to being
generally satisfied with its success in combining acquisitiveness,
social consciousness and easygoing tolerance into a genial
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   They are anti-establishment establishmentarians. Sociological
journalism, which at its best provides snapshots of the big
picture, does not have a great reputation for prophecy, and the
writers of the 1950s could not foresee the transformation of the
economy and the creation of a far wealthier set of men and women
whose loyalty is less to their company than to the perks it can
deliver. (Whyte reported in 1956 that only ``the venturesome few
buy stocks.'') Their admonitions about America's burgeoning
consumer society are strikingly different from Brooks' amused
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Did the best-selling sociologists get everything wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Whyte was troubled by the postwar appeal of corporate power and
authority, with its assumption that the interests of the companies
where most Americans made their living coincided with morality. The
key word was ``belongingness,'' which Whyte saw as a lure and a
snare that threatened everyone's independence. He warned that the
apparent beneficence of corporate life masked a basic conflict
between the individual and society: ``The group is a tyrant; so
also is it a friend, and it is both at once.''
</P>
<P>
   On the popular subject of consumerism, with the nation awash in
cash after the scarcities of the war years, Whyte discerned that
``it is the group that determines when a luxury becomes a
necessity.'' Who could foresee the amounts of money the Bobos would
have to throw around and the ways, which Brooks describes so
humorously, that marketeers would devise to relieve them of it?
</P>
<P>
   But Whyte's basic point, that most people with spare income
don't know what they ``need'' until the commercial tastemakers tell
them, is also evident in Brooks' up-to-date analysis. And it is how
they spend that largely defines their class.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is too sharp a reporter to miss the way his Bobos go
about their socially inspired duties to consume. He even offers
rules for Bobo buying: bathrooms and kitchens, however oversized
and overequipped, are more virtuous than a wide-screen television
set; gardening tools, however overpriced and underused, are more
virtuous than jewelry. The adroit Bobo avoids vulgarly conspicuous
consumption and practices ``one-downmanship'' in the form of very
expensive simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying difference between Brooks and Whyte is
ideological. While Whyte inveighed, ``We must fight the
Organization!'' Brooks is comfortable with what he sees, at worst,
as harmless excess. It's a generational and political divide. The
1950s sociologists, mostly left-leaning, drew on America's
experience with the Depression and the New Deal; they were
suspicious of corporate power in all its forms. Brooks, a senior
editor at the conservative Weekly Standard, apparently learned his
sociology at the lap of Irving Kristol and other neoconservative
champions of the market economy.
</P>
<P>
   That would also account for the way he shrugs off the famous
assertion of ``The Lonely Crowd'' that the nation's move from the
age of production to the age of consumption was marked by the
emergence of ``other-directed'' types, mostly white-collar folks
who conform to the expectations of their peers and their betters.
``The other-directed person,'' Riesman wrote, ``is in a sense at
home everywhere and nowhere, capable of a tepid if sometimes
superficial intimacy with and response to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   When Riesman, no humorist, addressed Bohemianism, he saw it as
just another sort of other-directedness, made up of people who are
``often zealously tuned in to the signals of a group that finds the
meaning of life, quite unproblematically, in an illusion of
attacking an allegedly dominant and punishing majority of Babbitts
and Kwakiutl chiefs.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been writing about the 1960s. Brooks sees the
co-option of Bohemia into the bourgeoisie as preferable to having
rowdy demonstrators break windows and stall traffic. And the
other-directedness that Riesman described as a threat to personal
autonomy receives Brooks' embrace for the Bobos' contribution to
community and social cohesion; he likes their centrist political
inclinations and the value they put on consensus and civility. It's
a sort of 5-C club.
</P>
<P>
   So he would never thunder about the organization man, as Whyte
did: ``It is wretched, dispiriting advice to hold before him that
ideally there need be no conflict between him and society. There
always is; there always must be.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bobos find their way into Paradise, the presumed shackles of
the 1950s have become designer accessories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
