<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-AFRICA-REVIEW     06-10 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-AFRICA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN IN AFRICA: COLONIALISM'S LEGACY BECOMES A BURDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In recent weeks, Britons have been treated to two
conflicting, almost puzzling, sets of images. In Sierra Leone, an
African leader pleads with British troops to stay on, after they
arrive there to protect the capital from rebel forces who had
kidnapped hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers. Across the continent in
Zimbabwe, another African president reviles just about everything
that smacks of the British and tells them to be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Binding the two images is Britain's colonial past and, with it,
a message that has some resonance for the United States in its own
new imperial age: Once power is extended, it creates a stubborn,
messy and enduring legacy. And even when influence recedes, the
tangle of obligation, expectation and resentment survives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's left after you've gone is a very deep imprint,'' said
Dr. David Anderson, chairman of the Center for African Studies at
the School for Oriental and African Studies here. ``And it dictates
cultural links, investment flows. All these things have substantive
meaning in the way things are done.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances that motivated Presidents Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
of Sierra Leone and Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe could hardly have
been more different, and neither could Britain's responses.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, a chaotic assemblage of rebel and
pro-government forces has turned the nation into a patchwork of
armed fiefs competing, essentially, for the country's diamond
riches. A U.N. mission to achieve and preserve a peace had
collapsed, leaving a dangerous vacuum. This threatened to propel
the war-weary nation into further mayhem _ mayhem that had already
caught the world's eye through the singular cruelty of rebels who
hacked off the limbs of innocents.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain's sense of post-colonial obligation went further.
Its gunboat diplomacy in Sierra Leone also reflected a broader
readiness by Prime Minister Tony Blair's government to pursue the
same ethical _ if somewhat selective _ crusade as had led it to
promote last year's NATO bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe the fight is different: After 20 unchallenged years
in power, Mugabe is facing elections this month that he is afraid
of losing. And he has seized on the emotional issue of racial
discrimination left over from colonial days _ in this case, unfair
patterns of land distribution _ as a pretext to order a campaign of
bloody intimidation of his principal opponents. These include white
farmers and workers on the farmers' land. Hundreds of white-owned
farms have been occupied by so-called veterans of Zimbabwe's
liberation war in the 1970, and at least 25 people have died.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Mugabe is assailing the very legacy that Britons
feel links them to the land. And Britain's choices are
circumscribed, illuminating both the ambiguities of its colonial
history and the limits on its modern influence.
</P>
<P>
   While Sierra Leone was established in 1787 as a coastal
settlement for freed black slaves, white British settlers were
encouraged to migrate to Rhodesia _ as Zimbabwe was then known _ in
the late 19th and early 20th century, simply seizing vast tracts of
land from the indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
   When British officials started to protest Mugabe's behavior,
that inescapable history clouded the moral issue and gave Mugabe
the ammunition to defy the onetime colonial ruler. The collision
left Britain's standing in Zimbabwe at its lowest in decades, even
as its star rose ever higher in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   So what drives a small nation with shrunken influence to project
its influence with such Victorian zeal?
</P>
<P>
   While Britain's initial intervention in Sierra Leone was
depicted as a mission to rescue British passport-holders, it was
quickly seen here by a broad swath of the populace as something
more: an opportunity to unravel chaos that has at least some roots
in earlier British initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, by contrast, the presence of some 15,000 white
Zimbabweans entitled to British citizenship revived a far more
ambiguous legacy. Successive British governments may have voiced
support for the aspirations of Zimbabwe's black majority, but, on
the right wing of British politics, there remains an insistence
that Britain should look after its so-called kith-and-kin in Africa
_ a view that invariably leads Zimbabweans, and some Britons, to
argue that British policy is racially biased.
</P>
<P>
   The deeper reality in both Zimbabwe and Sierra Leone is that
colonialism does not have an easy cut-off point, or a simple
close-of-sale date. When the flags are furled, the colonial power
maintains a vast array of commercial and other involvements.
</P>
<P>
   Just as colonialism itself was propelled by the economics of
Europe's industrial revolution with its need for raw materials and
markets, so the post-colonial era has been driven by Lord
Palmerston's 19th-century dictum that nations do not have eternal
allies, but they do have eternal interests.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, for instance, by insisting that this month's
elections be free and fair and by offering increased financial aid
for land redistribution, Britain is signaling its broader interest
in the stability of a region that encompasses vast British
investment, particularly in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the same self-interest also creates a web of
commitment and expectation, as Americans know well from their nexus
of relationships from Latin America to the Middle East, from the
rim of Asia to the heart of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's military intervention in Sierra Leone, moreover, has
led to the same worries as dogged U.S. forces in Vietnam, Beirut
and Somalia : Once committed, troops may well have to stand their
ground at the risk of unwelcome casualties _ or contemplate
withdrawal in humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Britain has given clear notice that its 600 combat
troops in Sierra Leone will be withdrawn by mid-June. But, already,
the potential for bloody chaos has obliged Britain to station 200
military advisers there when the combat troops leave _ an eerie
echo of the beginnings of U.S. embroilment in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of mission creep is inevitable,'' Anderson
said. ``It isn't a problem as long as you draw a line in the
sand.'' But those lines in the sand, of course, are what the
players of the post-colonial era have found so elusive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
