<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-2CITIES-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HOLLYWOOD TO HOOSIERVILLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Tonight in story refers to June 11.) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ One hosts the Academy Awards, the other the
World Pork Expo. So what else do you want to know about Los Angeles
and Indianapolis?
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Game 3 of the National Basketball Association's
Championship Series sends the L.A. Lakers to the home court of the
Indiana Pacers, the Conseco Field House in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime meets Miller Time.
</P>
<P>
   The game travels from Tinseltown to the Circle City, from La-La
Land to India-no-place, from the land of face lifts to the land of
forklifts. The distinction between the two towns is as clear as the
difference between guys who want their girlfriends corn-fed or
lipo-sucked.
</P>
<P>
   The songs about each area also tell the tale. Randy Newman's ``I
Love L.A.'' speaks for itself. Then there's the 1970 top-five hit
about a fleeing felon, ``Indiana Wants Me,'' with the refrain,
``Indiana wants me. Lord I can't go back there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the people out here would laugh. We're not California
here, by golly. This is common-sense Indiana,'' said Virginia
Terpening, director of the Indiana Medical History Museum, outside
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually have restaurants and places that stay open past
nine o'clock. It's definitely not on the fast track, but you won't
be bored to tears, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Terpening's museum, a converted turn-of-the-century insane
asylum, is on the list of ``fun and funky things to do'' from the
city's Convention &AMP; Visitors Association, and features displays of
1890s surgical equipment and autopsy tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an odd and bizarre place. That's the good news. You're
not going to see this in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Hoosier City is best known for the annual
Indianapolis 500. Dozens of cars race at speeds that often top 200
miles per hour, turning left around a closed track for 500 miles,
essentially going nowhere fast. In L.A., drivers also get nowhere,
but spend hours sitting in gridlock doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about rush-hour traffic here. Midwesterners are
clueless about what rush-hour traffic is,'' Terpening said. ``You
get 10 people on the highway and that's a glut.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A., on the other hand, is best known for Hollywood, and all
the glitz and glamour that hang off it like a belly-baring Versace
gown.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hoosier state has contributed greatly to Hollywood _
after all, three of the top-grossing movies of all time are about a
man named Indiana Jones. And then there was the story of tiny Milan
High School winning the 1954 state basketball championship, which
became the 1986 movie ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The supposedly unhip state produced those icons of cool _ wry,
sly and hipper-than-thou _ David Letterman, Steve McQueen and James
Dean. Hoosiers all.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Jackson made the trip west from Gary, Ind., to
Neverland.
</P>
<P>
   What has Southern California given Indiana? Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Museum of Indianapolis is the world's largest,
both in holdings and attendance. L.A., on the other hand, is home
to the largest population of actors and models ``under 30,'' and is
the world leader in delayed adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County, if it were its own country, would have the
world's 16th-largest economy. In addition, it produces more teen
slasher films than any nation on the globe, and is the world's only
known source of Pamela Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to basketball, folks in Indianapolis say
they're the true believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoosiers love basketball. It's the Midwest's heritage. It's
much more than entertainment,'' said Linton Calvert, 52, co-owner
of the Indianapolis landmark Fountain Square.
</P>
<P>
   At Staples Center it's a toss-up who the fans are more
interested in seeing _ Shaq or Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at who goes to the games _ all the movie stars. They
show 'em on TV,'' Calvert said. ``If we went out there we couldn't
get nosebleed seats.
</P>
<P>
   Even native son David Letterman blamed the glitz factor for the
Pacers' poor Game 1 showing, in which, he said, ``they played like
little girls.'' ``Here's the problem,'' Letterman said on his show
Thursday. ``The Indiana Pacers _ they're farm boys. They're not
used to the bright lights and the big city. When you're out there
in Los Angeles _ Tinseltown _ it's hard to play `S.B.' _ Superstar
Basketball. You're nervous because the lovely Dyan Cannon is
sitting courtside. You're overwhelmed by her beauty. You're a dumb
farm kid! That's the problem.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But, Angelenos may protest, L.A. has its own basketball pedigree
_ what about John Wooden and his incredible string of 10 NCAA
championships at UCLA? Just nevermind that he was born near
Indianapolis, and was a three-time All-American guard playing for
Purdue (in West Lafayette, Ind.).
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Los Angeles has more going on simply because of its
sheer size. Los Angeles County has nearly twice as many people _ 9
million to 5 million _ as the state of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost don't want to get too big,'' Terpening said. ``We're
not opposed to being a well-kept secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvert's Fountain Square, a restored 1920s entertainment plaza,
includes the Atomic Bowl duckpin bowling alley. The game, sort of a
scale-model version of tenpin bowling, is most popular in the East,
Calvert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. does not have duckpin bowling, I assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the restaurants recommended by the Indianapolis Convention
&AMP; Visitors Association is Acapulco Joe's Mexican Foods, where at
noon every day a Kate Smith recording of ``God Bless America'' is
played. No mention of whether the specials include the Proposition
187 Palapas.
</P>
<P>
   Or there's the Slippery Noodle Inn, a blues bar that is the
state's oldest, and was a favorite hangout of public enemy John
Dillinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of downtowns, especially in the Midwest, roll up the
sidewalks at night. That doesn't happen in downtown Indianapolis.
It has a very active nightlife and it's a very clean, very safe
downtown,'' said Ted Bulthaup, president of the Indianapolis
Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   That said, he considers Los Angeles one of his favorite cities
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the climate and just the whole atmosphere out there,''
he said. ``There's a lot more excitement, a nice ocean. I rent a
convertible and just tool around.''
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis might seem like it's moving at a different pace.
Could be because they don't observe daylight-saving time.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the year Indianapolis is three hours ahead of L.A.;
right now, it's only two. Stranger still, the whole state doesn't
follow along, Terpening said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, it confuses even the natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you call Evansville, you always have to say, 'What time
is it there?' &UR;  &LR; '' Terpening said.
</P>
<P>
   But both Indianapolis and Los Angeles have their homages to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Bar &AMP; Filmworks, in downtown Indianapolis, is a
combination bar/restaurant/movie theater, and is owned by Bulthaup.
In a converted 1868 warehouse, it features a bar that replicates
Rick's Cafe from Casablanca, a yellow brick road entryway and
$500,000 in vintage movie posters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lot of good places to see movies in L.A.,'' he said.
``But you don't have a theater like this out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And L.A. has its Indiana Plumbing Supply, with stores throughout
the city. The company started on Indiana Street in Los Angeles in
1942, but is now in the process of changing its name to The
Plumbers Warehouse, said Sharon Van Valkenburg, corporate
administration manager.
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether the name change is a show of support for the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   And how many playoff games will Van Valkenburg be attending?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand the sport,'' she said, preferring instead
``fast-pitch softball or baseball. It's pretty sad. Everybody here
likes it but me.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
