<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-IMMIGRATE-TECH-2Takes     06-10 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATE-TECH-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH WORKER SHORTAGE PROMPTS DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is speeding toward approval of a law that
could open the door to thousands of foreign high-tech workers and
also deliver hundreds of thousands of resident aliens from
immigration limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Three bills have been introduced in the House and Senate that
would greatly increase the number of special H1-B visas granted to
foreigners for jobs that ostensibly cannot be filled by Americans.
The measures, which differ in content, are backed by the computer
industry, which has cited a severe shortage of domestic talent.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the number of visas also enjoys strong support in
Congress, which sees the move as crucial to sustaining the nation's
high tech-driven economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Latino leaders, including the National Council
of La Raza and the Congressional Hispanic Caucus, want to add
provisions to H1-B legislation that would grant amnesty to up to
900,000 people, including an estimated 360,000 Californians, who
were shut out of previous immigration reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of fairness,'' said Rep. Lucille
Roybal-Allard, D-Los Angeles, who chairs the Hispanic Caucus. ``If
we're going to bring in several thousand foreign workers, we also
need to assist those who've been here for years in limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   The amnesty proposal, first aired in May, is supported by
President Clinton and many Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   It is reluctantly backed by many Republicans who see no link
between the two efforts but who nonetheless do not want to be
perceived as anti-Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, including activists who favor tighter immigration
controls and crackdowns on undocumented aliens, say the H1-B visa
proposal will hurt American workers. They are also opposed to any
amnesty plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major mistake,'' said Glenn Spencer of Sherman Oaks,
president of Voice of Citizens Together and an advocate of strict
immigration controls. ``We need to invest all the billions these
companies are making into training our own people for these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service is authorized to
issue only 115,000 H1-B visas per year. They are valid for up to
six years. This year American companies, which must apply for the
visas on behalf of their foreign employees, used up the 2000 quota
by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   A bill co-sponsored by Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, would raise the limit to 297,500 over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, has offered a bill that calls for
unlimited visas, but mandates that all holders earn at least
$40,000 per year and be proficient in English.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. David Dreier, R-Covina, and Zoe Lofgren, D-San Jose, have
submitted a measure that would increase the number of visas by
362,500 over three years and double the application fee from $500
to $1,000. The fee increase would be used to train U.S. workers for
high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech employers say they have an estimated 270,000 vacancies
and no Americans to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The problem promises to get worse, according to the
International Technology Association of America, a lobbying group
for more than 11,000 companies. It recently forecast the creation
of an additional 1.6 &UR;  &LR; million jobs by next summer, half of which
would require an infusion of foreign talent.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., said Southland employers, including aerospace
giants, are also scrambling for workers. But he said the region's
pool of talent and its colleges are helping to fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's true that a lot of people can't easily transition
to a new field, we still have a lot of skilled people here in areas
like engineering,'' Kyser said. ``And, as some of these dot-coms
melt down and disappear, we'll see talent returning to the job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   An April 28 Congressional Research Office report cast some doubt
on the need for more foreign workers. Linda Levine, a domestic
policy specialist, wrote that ``available data makes it difficult
to determine whether an information technology labor shortage
exists and, if so, whether those workers are any scarcer than
workers in some other occupations.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortages in less-wired fields are giving a boost to the amnesty
effort. Legislation has been introduced by Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
to help the Nevada casino industry, which employs a large number of
immigrants from Mexico and Central America, many of whom now face
the threat of eventual deportation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The new amnesty proposal would cover people barred from the
program approved by Congress in 1986. It gave residency rights to
undocumented aliens who had been in the United States on or before
Jan. 1, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service later denied
thousands of immigrants' claims, ruling in many cases that aliens
who had left the United States for short vacations or business
trips had forfeited their amnesty rights. Thousands of resident
aliens and their advocates are still appealing those decisions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The proposal would also grant amnesty to Central Americans who
were left out of another program approved by Congress in 1997. It
gave residency rights to Nicaraguans and Cubans, who fled regimes
hostile to the United States, but excluded most Salvadorans,
Hondurans, Guatemalans and Haitians, who fled nations that were
U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take care of these long-standing problems,'' said
Joel Najar, policy analyst for the National Council of La Raza, the
nation's largest Latino civil rights organization. ``Granting legal
status to these people will also be good for the economy. They will
have a full chance to make their contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about opening the floodgates,'' said Roybal-Allard,
whose Hispanic Caucus colleagues include Reps. Xavier Becerra,
D-Los Angeles; Matthew Martinez, D-Alhambra; Joe Baca, D-Rialto;
and Loretta Sanchez, D-Garden Grove. ``We just want to give this
limited group of people the chance to legalize their status.''
</P>
<P>
   Roybal-Allard also stressed that there is no link between the
proposal she backs and a plan announced by the AFL-CIO. The
nation's largest labor organization has called for an amnesty for
all undocumented aliens and an end to sanctions for the employers
who hire them.
</P>
<P>
   The growing clout of Latino voters might also help Congress tie
the H1-B visa plan to an immigrant amnesty. Both Republicans and
Democrats are courting the electorate's fastest-growing group in
battles for Congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest Latino populations are centered in
voter-rich states, including California (9.9 million Latinos as of
1997), Texas (5.7 million), New York (2.6 million), Florida (2.1
million) and Illinois (1.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   La Raza and other groups have also been staging energetic drives
to increase registration and turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's most recent statistics on Latino voting
compare data from the 1994 and 1996 national elections. In 1994,
5.8 million Latinos, or 31 percent of the 17.5 million Latinos
nationwide age 18 and over, were registered to vote. Of that
number, 3.5 million, or 20 percent, cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Latino voter registration nationwide had risen to 6.6
million, or 36 percent, while the number who voted hit 4.9 million,
or 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 1.4 million California Latinos age 18 and up, or 24.9
percent of a total of 5.7 million, were registered and 1.2 million,
or 21 percent, voted. In 1996, the numbers increased to 1.6 million
or 29 percent registered, and 1.3 million or 22.6 percent actually
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has exhibited caution in its quest to please both
high-tech companies and Latinos while avoiding confrontation with
opponents of widened immigration.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the titles given this year's spate of bills do not
include the words ``alien'' or ``immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreier's measure is called the ``Helping to Improve Technology
Education and Achievement Act of 2000.'' Feinstein's bill goes by
the title ``American Competitiveness in the 21st Century Act.'' And
Texas Rep. Smith calls his proposal the ``Technology Worker
Temporary Relief Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the titles of the bills, critics denounce giving
more visas and amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all greed. The high-tech companies are just looking for
cheap labor, like the companies that hire illegals,'' said Evelyn
Miller of Irvine, a member of the California Coalition for
Immigration Reform. The group co-sponsored the controversial
Proposition 187 in 1994 to prohibit many public services for
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies should hire and train Americans who are coming
off welfare and can't find a job,'' added Miller. As to the amnesty
plan, she said, ``these people will never stop there. We'll have a
third amnesty and a fourth. It will never end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1201EDT &QL; 
