r a BC-PARK-POACHERS-LADN     06-10 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-POACHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TRY TO LIMIT HABITAT DAMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So you want to load up the minivan, go to the
Santa Monica Mountains and let the kids run free, collecting a few
bouquets of wildflowers and maybe even a jar of tadpoles to show to
Junior's third-grade teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture yourself in federal court, calculating the amount of
money it will cost to repair the ecosystem your progeny have
violated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. park rangers who patrol the Santa Monica Mountains National
Recreation Area aren't planning to throw the book at anyone but
professional poachers. But they are alarmed by their almost daily
encounters with visitors trotting off with flowers, frogs and
snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Park Ranger Jim Richardson recently encountered a family
collecting tadpoles from Medea Creek in Paramount Ranch. He
diplomatically reined them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to contact those folks and take a few minutes to
educate them, and help them release those tadpoles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the ranch area, bought by the National Park Service
in 1980 and still used by film companies, is a large hill whose
green foliage is punctuated by off-white stalks protruding from
star-shaped clusters of large, triangular leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Known as chalk dudleyas, the plants are prized for their looks.
But park visitors often find it hard to simply appreciate their
beauty protruding from cliff faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys actually came out with specially constructed poles with
baskets on the ends'' to take the plants, said John Tiszler, a
plant ecologist for the recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   That incident occurred in Topanga State Park, noted Suzanne
Goode, a resource biologist with the state Department of Parks and
Recreation who keeps track of wildlife in several state parks in
the Santa Monica Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountains' federal park areas, the penalty for picking up
a snake or any other animal is a maximum fine of $500 and a
mandatory appearance before a federal judge downtown. Pilfering
plants or possessing trapping equipment such as a hooked ``snake
stick'' can net a citation and a $50 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials have filed charges against several poachers,
including one who was caught last winter with a snake stick made
from a golf club. The case has not yet gone to trial.
</P>
<P>
   While poachers are clearly aware of what they are doing, like
the man who was reported sorting plastic garbage bags full of seeds
at his campsite at Leo Carrillo State Park
</P>
<P>
   for an established seed company, Goode believes the bulk of the
problem is less clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will frequently pick flowers or collect rocks or pretty
leaves or mushrooms,'' Goode said. ``These are all probably the
innocent type of collectors, and they are also probably ignorant of
the effect that they're having on resources where they're
collecting.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Goode said, ``when they pick a flower, they don't
really realize that they're preventing that plant from
reproducing.'' Picking flowers this year ``means there will be
fewer flowers next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of such prolific picking is difficult to gauge. In
some areas, such as tide pools, biologists have established that
the hand of man, or boys and girls, have harmed the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go out with buckets, even in school groups where a
teacher is in charge,'' and pluck various crustaceans and fish from
the water, Goode said, adding that even picking them up for a
better look can be harmful. ``Some organisms are attached to the
rocks, and if they're not put right back in the same location in
the same orientation, they may not get attached again, or they may
be more susceptible to being eaten by predators.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers who catch teachers in the act won't march them off in
irons before horrified kindergartners, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would happen would be that Mrs. Crabapple would be
informed that this is not a good activity, that this is not good
for the natural resources. They would appeal to her higher moral
sense,'' Goode explained.
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of the teacher's sense of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   For parents who have trouble convincing children about not
taking bits of the parkland's fragile web of life, there is always
the legal argument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
