<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-AD-CHARACTERS-REVIEW-     06-10 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AD-CHARACTERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING AD ICONS GROW UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(Eds: Replace doubles parentheses (( )) with single brackets . )  
 By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a hundred years, thirsty consumers who didn't even
know her name have recognized Psyche the nymph as the symbol of
White Rock soda. Now, however, slumping sales and a younger target
audience have prompted White Rock to give its fragile,
bare-breasted bottle girl a bolder look. The company is favoring a
Psyche depicted only in outline with a few deft brush strokes, and
who is neither crouched on a rock nor gazing into a pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been a great logo, but she really does look
old-fashioned,'' said Laurence Bodkin, White Rock's vice president
for marketing. ``We want to be thought of as a vibrant company for
the new century.''
</P>
<P>
   Psyche is not the only ad icon getting a face lift. Quaker Oats
earlier this year unveiled an all-adult version of its memorable
1972 ``Mikey'' television spot for Life cereal. ``Many of us who
once identified with little Mikey are all grown up and can now
relate to the all new adult cast,'' said Todd Magazine, vice
president for marketing of Quaker's Ready-to-Eat Cereals division.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these updatings come as other famous embodiments of consumer
products _ the Jolly Green Giant, Mr. Whipple and Charlie the Tuna
among them _ are being dusted off and presented, largely unchanged,
to a new generation of buyers. On the cable television station TV
Land, vintage commercials featuring such instantly identifiable
personae as Mr. Clean, Hawaiian Punch's Punchy, the young Mikey and
Clara ``Where's the Beef?'' Peller from Wendy's have become
programming staples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Characters in general went out of style for quite a long
time,'' said Thomas Hine, author of ``The Total Package: The
Evolution and Secret Meanings of Boxes, Bottles, Cans, and Tubes''
(Little, Brown, 1995). ``Obviously a lot of companies are now aware
that they have a kind of cultural heritage that they can cash in
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that heritage, the question arises: When should an
established ad icon be altered to breathe new life into it?
</P>
<P>
   Never, some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``These characters are more beloved than family members,'' said
Barbara Lippert, ad critic for Adweek magazine. ``I was on an Oprah
show about this subject, and Mr. Whipple ((the actor Dick Wilson))
came out with a pack of toilet paper. People went wild. He was like
Moses carrying the tablets.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. ``If icons are not kept contemporary, they
become recessive,'' said Bob Kuperman, president and CEO of the
advertising agency TBWA Chiat/Day, whose creations include the
Energizer Bunny and the Taco Bell chihuahua. ``Museums are filled
with icons that have not been kept up to date,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a company has no real choice but to go with the public
flow. Quaker's Aunt Jemima eventually lost her bandanna so that she
less closely resembled a stereotypical mammy. When the Michelin Man
was born at the turn of the century, automobile tires were thin and
narrow, but as they bulked up, so did Monsieur Michelin, lest he
become unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   But morphing can be a risky business. Take Elsie, Borden's
bovine trademark, who was once cited by Advertising Age as one of
the top 10 icons of all time. In 1993 she was transmogrified: She
spoke, walked on her hind legs, wore pants and owned a dairy store.
The campaign was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Elsie could relate more to the working woman of the
day in a human environment,'' explained Jim Montel, vice president
for marketing at American Dairy Brands, Borden's parent company.
``But it didn't move the product. Consumers did not have any
affection for her as a human.''
</P>
<P>
   If change must come to an icon, gradualism tends to work best.
Betty Crocker, for example, is so popular an image that she
routinely receives marriage proposals. But, said Pam Becker, a
spokeswoman for General Mills, ``Our whole goal is to connect Betty
Crocker with consumers out there, and for that reason we have to
change the portrait periodically.''
</P>
<P>
   Crocker has been nipped and tucked seven times since her
original 1936 appearance, most recently four years ago. Although
her features and hairdo have become less dowdy, and she has traded
in her house dress for a business suit, she has always been a
self-possessed lady in red, thus assuring continuity and
familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is to keep a character more or less intact
while putting it in an unexpected, attention-grabbing context.
``I've seen print ads for Speedy the Alka-Seltzer tablet wearing
sunglasses and a Hawaiian shirt,'' said Warren Dotz, co-author with
Jim Morton of ``What A Character! 20th Century American Advertising
Icons'' (Chronicle, 1996). ``A lot of characters are modernized by
putting them on in-line skates.''
</P>
<P>
   That path, however, can lead to madness. In 1996, McDonald's
plunked its spokesclown, Ronald McDonald, into a variety of
grown-up settings _ golf courses, discos, bars _ to promote its new
Arch Deluxe sandwich. ``They had him doing some pretty bad
things,'' a McDonald's executive told Salon magazine. ``It was a
dark moment. A complete, soup-to-nuts fiasco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
