<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUDGMENT DAY DAWNS ON AN UNREPENTANT MICROSOFT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHUTZPAH-MICROSOFT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So judgment day has come at last. Almost since it began in
October 1998, the antitrust trial against Microsoft has gone badly
for the world's biggest software company. After Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson ruled that the company was an ``abusive
monopolist'' in April, his decision to accept the proposal by the
Department of Justice to break up the company was to be expected.
This is not the end of the case, but it is, perhaps, the beginning
of the end. And given not only the ``guilty'' verdict but also the
history of the case, Microsoft's obstinate refusal to accept that
it might have done anything wrong is, at the very least, bad
tactics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA: EXECUTING LIBERTY AND JUSTICE FOR ALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEATHROW-LOTTERY-ECONOMIST-300&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year around 100 Americans will be poisoned, hanged, gassed,
shot or electrocuted. In a country where some 17,000 people a year
are murdered, this would not seem exceptional. But the killer in
these 100 cases will be the state. To those outside America, the
country's love of executions is surprising _ surprising to find
such a tolerant place in the same camp as China, Iran, Saudi Arabia
and Congo (the only four countries to execute more people);
surprising to find such a religious place addicted to a habit that
most religious leaders abhor; surprising, too, to find the crucible
of liberty decried in so many international reports on human
rights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 3 trims, totaling 300 words; 1,300 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TWO KIMS, TWO KOREAS: ONE SUMMIT DOES NOT MAKE A
RECONCILIATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIM-MEETS-KIM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After more than 50 years of hostilities, a first handshake makes
history. But whether next week's meeting between South Korea's Kim
Dae Jung and North Korea's Kim Jong II will also make Asia a safer
place is harder to fathom. These two Cold-War siblings, one
democratic and thriving, the other communist-cum-feudal and
failing, have plenty to disagree about. Hope for progress, but
don't expect miracles from the summit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for next week's summit) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGULATING CYBERSPACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `HANDS-OFF'-INTERNET-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that ``hands off the Internet'' is the rallying
cry of starry-eyed libertarians? Here is this amazingly useful
thing, built from the bottom up by idealists, largely
self-regulated and beyond the reach of governments or big business.
It is a nice idea. Sadly, the Internet is neither as different nor
as ``naturally'' free as wired Utopians claim. The sheer
pervasiveness of the Internet makes it impossible for even the
best-intentioned of regulators to keep out. The real question,
alas, is not whether to regulate the Internet, but how. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA STRIKES OUT FOUL ROCKER, BUT HAS BALLS TO FORGIVE
OTHERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OFF-HIS-ROCKER-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ OK, John Roc`KKK'er is a bigot. John Rocker is an
oaf. John Rocker is a fool. That's the almost universal public
perception of the man who, against stiff competition, has emerged
as the most widely loathed man in America. Web sites are out of
control on the subject, one even suggesting that ``if (Rocker)
played a position, it would probably be Third Reich.'' All this
seems way over the top. Sure, his remarks and behavior are
deplorable, but isn't there a hypocritical double-standard at work
here? Rocker's public disgrace as America's poster-child of
political incorrectness contrasts starkly with the kid-glove
treatment accorded his violent or even criminal colleagues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word trim at 600; 1,075 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEEP SOUTH ATONES FOR PAST SINS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTHERN-DISCOMFORT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ On the night of June 21, 1964, Michael Schwerner and
Andrew Goodman, two white New Yorkers who had travelled to
Mississippi to help register black voters, and a fellow volunteer,
James Chaney, an 18-year-old black man from Mississippi, were
executed by Ku Klux Klansmen and buried in an earthen dam. At the
time, the state of Mississippi refused to hear the case. Now, a
generation later, with many of the defendants still living, the
state of Mississippi is taking a second look at the case. Indeed,
all across the South, racially-motivated murder cases of the past
30 years are being reopened by a defiant group of young lawyers and
prosecutors, determined to discover the ugly truth before time
erodes the evidence or puts the suspects beyond the reach of
justice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Southern-State Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COUNTING MISSING HEADS _ AND DOLLARS _ IN CHICAGO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHICAGO-CENSUS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Census workers are scheduled to finish their work in
Chicago on July 7. Mayor Richard Daley is now ``pulling out all the
stops'' to make sure as many Chicagoans as possible stand up and
are counted before then. The city will spend $400,000 on TV and
radio advertisements. And one of the western world's great
political machines is humming into action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Chicago) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST OF FOES: PUTIN, CLINTON ARE DIPLOMACY'S ARTFUL DODGERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-CLINTON-DUEL-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ With no pretense to personal warmth, U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Russian President Vladimir Putin artfully finessed
their differences over strategic issues, particularly anti-missile
defenses, in a way that enabled each to claim success from their
first summit meeting while still looking good at home. But the gap
between American and Russian views remain as wide as the Volga. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE IRAQ'S LUCRATIVE SADDAM-FREE ZONE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KURDS-SANCTIONS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAL DA GHAN, IRAQ _ The shepherds of Dal da Ghan rebuilt their
village after the Gulf War. It was one of the 4,000 or so villages
in northern Iraq that in the 1980s were forcibly abandoned and
destroyed by Saddam Hussein's men. Now, however, the village is a
Saddam-free zone. And the retaliatory U.N. sanctions that have
devastated the rest of Iraq have turned out to be a boon to the
Kurds, who benefit hugely from the black market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOROCCO: FROM MEDIEVAL FEUDALISM TO MODERN DEMOCRACY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOROCCAN-KING-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RABAT _ When protestors take to the streets in other countries,
they burn effigies of their leaders. In Morocco, they brandish
pinups of the king like an amulet to ward off the baton-bashing of
the police. The amulet may not always work, but for most Moroccans,
Mohammed VI has spiritual status. It was simplier in his father's
day. Politically, the kingdom was run as a medieval state with a
feudal hierarchy. But King Mohammed has set himself the challenge
of creating a modern state while maintaining the feudal veneer. Can
he make the change? After ten months on the throne, the signals are
still mixed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for June 20 U.S. visit by Moroccan King Mohammed) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO'S HIDDEN ELECTION ISSUE: EDUCATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO-EDUCATION-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OAXACA _ They are acting like students: camping out in the
streets, shouting slogans spraying graffiti. But they are teachers.
For the past month, they have clogged up Mexico City, demonstrating
for better pay, more resources and more say in making policy. Their
strike should resonate with Mexicans; the top issue for the voters
in the July 2 general election will not be more notorious problems
with corruption or drug-trafficking, but education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word trim at 650; 925 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICAN MORTGAGE-LENDING: GIVING CREDIT WHERE NOT DUE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORTGAGE-MALAISE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Financial crises invariably have unexpected
after-effects. One such is FirstPlus Financial, a lender based in
Dallas, Texas. On June 2, as part of a bankruptcy settlement, it
announced the sale to Countryside, a Californian bank, of its
remaining portfolio of $4.3 billion-worth of mortgages. The deal
signals the demise of what was until recently one of America's
fastest-growing financial institutions. This is the latest in a
string of similar failures over recent months, all linked to a
dramatic contraction in the securitized-mortgage market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Dallas) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONLINE, OFF COURSE: SOUTH KOREA'S DAY-TRADING MANIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOREA-DAYTRADE-FRENZY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Computer clubs have been sprouting all over South Korea
recently, catering to a nation of fanatical online game-players.
And now they're discovered the stock market, as well. An exotic
hobby among the rich only a year ago, online trading has quickly
become a national passion. From their homes, their offices, and
their mobile phones, amateur share traders have turned South Korea
into the most developed market in the world for online share
trading. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGOLA'S OIL-EXPLORATION FRENZY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OIL-ANGOLA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LUANDA _ By most people's standards Angola is not a very
appealing place. But at present every right-thinking oil executive
wants to do business there. Which is why competition will be
frantic in the bidding that is about to open for shares in the
latest Angolan oil-exploration concession to come up for grabs:
Block 34. In fact, the auction of Block 34 marks the end of a
feeding frenzy that has gripped the Angolan oil industry in recent
years. Once is has been allocated, no new concessions are expected
to be offered for some time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFERTILITY AND INHERITANCE: A LEGACY OF DOOMED CHILDREN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFERTILITY-CANCER-ECONOMIST-475&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Today it is well known that in roughly half of the
20 percent or so of couples who cannot conceive, the cause is male
infertility. A study in this month's issue of ``Human
Reproduction'' offers a genetic explanation for some of these
cases. But it is an explanation that raises disturbing ethical
questions about the use of some assisted-reproduction techniques.
If the cause of a father's infertility lies in faulty DNA-repair
genes, the resulting child could also be infertile _ and might be
at increased risk of cancer. Couples who resort to modern
technology to overcome infertility could thus be passing an
unwelcome legacy on to their offspring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 450-word trim at 475; 1,275 words uncut) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
