<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6509 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     06-10 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 11, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This final budget eliminates ROCKER-STOCKBROKER-REVIEW and adds
AD-CHARACTERS-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   OLIGOPOLY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Microsoft aside, one legacy of
the Clinton administration will be that it encouraged one of the
greatest periods of industrial concentration in U.S. history,
affecting old and new sectors ranging from oil and the
pharmaceuticals to telephones, broadcasters and the Internet. The
deals, a byproduct of deregulation in the 1990s and the application
of Reagan-era antitrust guidelines, have put back together large
pieces of the old AT&AMP;T and Standard Oil trust. Moreover, Congress,
prodded by Clinton, repealed the Depression-era law that had split
the banking and securities industries, leading to predictions that
ultimately there will be broad consolidation on Wall Street. By
Stephen Labaton. (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISLAND-NATIONS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Coups have shaken Fiji and the
Solomon Islands, catapulting those small ocean nations into world
attention momentarily and exposing the ethnic tensions and economic
rivalries festering under the sun, somehow out of place in such a
perfect setting. Or are they? Small island nations, truth to tell,
often have very big problems. They are almost inevitably short of
resources on land, and even when that is not so there is usually
just one commodity to sell, putting them at the mercy of volatile
global markets. And they are vulnerable to typhoons and other
natural hazards. By Barbara Crossette. (Moved in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNS-COMPARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ You probably think you are
watching the presidential race of 2000. Wrong: it is really 1988,
or at least that is where many political scientists and strategists
will transport you. They cite the familiar dynamic of a vice
president who belonged to a successful administration and whose
apparent disadvantage against a heavily promoted governor turned
out to be temporary. Or perhaps it is 1960. The vice president
cannot trade on his administration's high regard in the face of an
upbeat, more charismatic challenger who ultimately prevails.
Analogies can also be drawn with 1992, 1980, 1968 and even 1896. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLECLASS-CULTURE-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Bobos in Paradise,''
his new book about the merger of America's bourgeoisie and its
Bohemians (which he merges into ``Bobos''), David Brooks looks back
now and then to the 1950s, the golden age of the liberal science of
sociology. In those years, writers lamented the plunge of the
middle class into corporation-dominated conformity. A half-century
later, Brooks, though mocking the tastes and pretensions of today's
upper middle class, confesses to being generally satisfied with its
success in combining acquisitiveness, social consciousness and
easygoing tolerance into a genial life style. They are
anti-establishment establishmentarians. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-APPEARANCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ What is the role of good
looks in politics? Can a candidate be too attractive? Can a
candidate be too unattractive? What constitutes good looks? Would
some unsightly American presidents of the past, like the 350-pound
William Howard Taft, be elected today? Does hair help? Some experts
on politics and the presidency offer their views. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-MONEY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Jon Corzine's victory in
New Jersey's Democratic U.S. Senate primary is just the most recent
reminder that candidates must nowadays spend enormous sums of money
_ either their own, or money they have collected _ if they hope to
have even a remote chance to be elected to the Congress or elected
president. It is nearly impossible for candidates armed only with
ideas but little or no money to win. One wonders: Could Abraham
Lincoln have defeated Corzine? By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   AD-CHARACTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although some longtime
advertising characters are being updated, other famous embodiments
of consumer products _ the Jolly Green Giant, Mr. Whipple, Mr.
Clean, Charlie the Tuna, Hawaiian Punch's Punchy and Clara
``Where's the Beef?'' Peller _ are being dusted off and presented,
largely unchanged, to a new generation of buyers. Advertising
experts debate the pros and cons of reintroducing and/or updating
ad characters from years past. By Thomas Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-ARGUE-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ On May 17, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott and Minority Leader Tom Daschle lobbed verbal
vollies at each other in an angry, arm-waving screaming match on
the Senate floor. Some excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-AFRICA-REVIEW (London) _ In Sierra Leone, a leader
pleads with British troops to stay on. In Zimbabwe, another leader
reviles just about everything that smacks of the British and tells
them to be gone. Binding the two images is Britain's colonial past
and, with it, a message that has some resonance for the United
States in its own new imperial age: Once power is extended, it
creates a stubborn, messy and enduring legacy. And even when
influence recedes, the tangle of obligation, expectation and
resentment linking erstwhile ruler to erstwhile ruled survives. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW (Washington) _ Secretaries of State George
Shultz, James Baker, Warren Christopher and Madeleine Albright have
all said it: in making peace in the Middle East, Americans cannot
want peace more than the parties themselves. In other words, the
United States must be both available and aloof, appearing as a
willing partner but not an over-eager suitor. But time and patience
are the two things President Clinton no longer has. With only seven
months left as president, he even may want peace more than the
parties themselves. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   EASTEUROPE-WOMEN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Women have borne the brunt
of the changes that have overtaken the lands of eastern Europe and
the former Soviet Union since the fall of communism. While the
picture varies vastly from the developed countries of central
Europe to huge, impoverished swaths from the Balkans to central
Asia, women have enjoyed less of the fruits of any economic
improvement than their male counterparts and simultaneously
shouldered almost all of the stresses brought by a total change of
lifestyle. By Alison Smale.
</P>
<P>
