<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ENGLAND-SOCCER-THUGS-     06-10 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-SOCCER-THUGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EUROPE BRACES, ENGLAND MOVES TO LEASH SOCCER THUGS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It was the English who first formalized rules for the
sport called ``the beautiful game,'' but the country is less known
these days for the gracefulness its athletes show on the soccer
field than for the ugliness its rabid supporters cause off it.
</P>
<P>
   When the country's national team begins its participation Monday
in a biennial Europewide competition being held this year in
Belgium and the Netherlands, a team of crack English police
officers will be taking up their positions in front of computer
screens at the National Crime Intelligence Service here to monitor
the moves of the thousands of English fans who have followed their
heroes across the Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The English soccer players enter the Euro 2000 tournament with
the worst record of any of the 16 teams that qualified. The English
police start the contest with the best reputation for handling
rampaging soccer thugs because they have had so much experience at
it.
</P>
<P>
   As a reflection of what a serious national matter soccer
hooliganism has become for England, the responsibility for
combating it has been assigned to the top-level intelligence agency
that was created in 1992 to combat organized crime, international
drug dealing, money laundering, immigration fraud and
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   While English athletic authorities are eager to shed the rioting
fan reputation to enhance the country's effort to become the host
of the 2006 World Cup, the concern goes far beyond sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of football hooliganism is to shame the nation
every time it happens,'' said Mark Steels, the intelligence
service's chief spokesman. ``It does about as much damage to
England's image as any other form of international activity. After
a while, people abroad start thinking that if English fans are like
that, that's what all the English are like.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the favored slang word for the men who shave their heads,
paint their faces in team colors, strip down to their ample waists,
drink far too much and beat up opposing fans, foreigners all the
better, Steels said, ``Our reputation has been badly sullied by
this bunch of yobs.''
</P>
<P>
   A glass case in the room where the special intelligence squad
works displays the tools of the soccer hooligan trade: retractable
blades hidden in belt buckles, lighters and pens, brass knuckles,
iron bars, spray cans of immobilizing gas and stubby carpentry
knives used for inflicting cheek-length facial slashes. On a
bulletin board are a collection of calling cards the thugs leave
with people they have bloodied. The Silver Cod Squad's reads, ``Now
is a time to convalesce, for you've been done by the SCS.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that the public shares their desire to rein in the army of
soccer toughs, the police have posted ``England needs you''
advertisements asking people to phone a number known as the
``hooligan hot line'' with information about rabble-rousers.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreaks abroad are happening at a time when at home the
soccer match violence of the 1970s and 1980s has subsided.
Principal stadiums have been rebuilt with all standing-room
terraces removed, family-friendly regulations and drinking
restrictions have been put in place, stewards are positioned at
entrances and security cameras have been installed to permit visual
checks of every seat. Opposing fans sit apart from one another
during the game and are steered away from one another as they exit
the parks by mounted police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Belgians in particular know the cost of English fans on a tear.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, violence by backers of Liverpool at the Heysel stadium
in Brussels caused a crowd stampede that killed 39 supporters of
the opposing Italian team and led to a five-year ban on English
clubs playing on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Last month English and Turkish fans rioted in the main square of
Copenhagen, just weeks after they had convulsed downtown Istanbul
where two supporters of Leeds United were stabbed to death. The
Dutch police are wary of new vengeful clashes since Turkey plays
Italy on Sunday in Arnhem, just 50 miles from Eindhoven, where
England plays Portugal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a get-tough strategy, the Dutch police say they intend to
dispel their reputation for being Europe's most laid back force,
and Belgian officials say their officers will be able to detain
people on minimum suspicion. Jeu Springers, president of the Dutch
football federation, said, ``I don't know what the English
supporters intend to do and we know their reputation, but if
they're coming with the intention of destroying our cities, we have
a zero tolerance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Alain Courtois, a director of the tournament, said at a Brussels
press conference, ``We know some people are coming here to cause
trouble, but they have to know they can be arrested based on the
feeling of the policeman and can be held for 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Eindhoven have announced that only half-strength
beer will be on sale in areas where fans will be gathering for
England's opening match. In Charleroi, the small Belgian town that
is the scene for the game next Saturday that law enforcement people
fear most _ England vs. Germany _ the garage of a 19th-century
gendarmerie near the stadium has been converted into a detention
center with steel bars and cellblocks capable of holding a total of
1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   German fans rioted in France during the World Cup two years ago
and left a policeman permanently maimed, and Berlin has responded
by passing a law that has enabled authorities to bar 2,700
identified hooligans from leaving the country. The English police
sought a similar law, but the government did not produce it.
</P>
<P>
   The English authorities are able to hold back 99 troublemakers
who have so-called international travel bans, but it cannot bar
travel by 416 others who have only national bans. Instead the
police have furnished the Dutch and Belgian police with photos and
information about them and 500 other potential rioters and have
sent men called ``football intelligence officers'' from England
over to the sites of games.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, the Dutch and the Turks all have belligerent fans
and histories of melees, but Steels, of England's intelligence
service, is impatient with people here who argue that the English
are not to blame for much of the violence that occurs when they go
abroad. ``Yes, it's always somebody else's fault,'' he said
wearily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say the police were too tough or the police were too
soft, the stadium was the wrong shape, the Turks provoked us, we
found ourselves at the wrong end of the pitch, they don't have a
proper lager, they don't speak English in `them' countries, you
can't get a cab at 4 in the morning, nobody told us this was the
red-light district, they didn't serve Theakstons bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are people supposed to react to seeing their wonderful
historic cities laid waste?'' he went on. ``People in Germany
certainly know about drinking beer, but that doesn't mean they're
used to people who start doing it at 12 noon and are still standing
up eight hours later, their guts all sunburned, singing patriotic
songs after doing nothing but laying about and drinking all day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
