<SLUG> BC-GAY-TEACHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY TEACHER'S DISCLOSURE SPURS A DEBATE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ A first-grade teacher who told his students that
he was gay has provoked a debate among parents and educators here
about how soon is too soon to talk about sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, David Gaita, who has worked at Burr Elementary
School in this suburb of Boston for five years, apparently did not
plan to ``come out'' to his students on May 17, when he was
teaching about biographies. But when students asked about his
family and whom he lived with, he is said to have told his class
that if he had a partner, ``someone you love the way your mom and
dad love each other,'' it would be a man.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-curriculum lesson led some parents to question
whether Gaita should have told his students he was gay without
first informing parents. At a Parent-Teacher Organization meeting
late last month, some parents said they thought it was their place
to teach _ or not teach _ their children about homosexuality. Brian
Camenker, director of a conservative parents' group and the father
of a Burr student, told The Boston Globe that ``a child's
psychology isn't put together for any of this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Young, the Newton public schools superintendent, said he
supported the way Gaita answered the students' questions. Gaita has
declined to comment publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the teacher at that point said, `I'm married and have two
kids,' no one would have blinked an eye,'' Young said, adding that
``there should not be a double standard for heterosexual and
homosexual teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor David Cohen of Newton said he would have been pleased to
have Gaita as the teacher of his own children. ``It's quite clear
he handled the situation with sensitivity and discretion,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the class, Gaita sent a letter to his students' parents
explaining what had happened. But as accounts of the incident began
to spread, Cynthia Bencal, the principal, sent a note to all
parents on May 22 explaining the context of Gaita's statement. It
read in part: ``One student asked him if he liked being gay and he
said that that was a hard question to answer. He said that he was
proud of who he was and that he knew he was a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Swift, whose children attend the Burr school, said she was
unperturbed when she asked her daughter how her class went that day
and heard: ``Good. Mr. Gaita told us he was gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift sympathized with parents who want to control what their
children learn, but, from what they see on television to what they
hear on the playground, ``there are many things we can't shelter
our kids from,'' she said. ``I'm grateful that my child can learn
about this in a natural, relaxed manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of educators in explaining homosexuality has been under
scrutiny here recently. On May 19, the state education commissioner
fired an HIV and AIDS education coordinator who conducted a teen
talk on ``queer sex'' as part of a gay and lesbian conference at
Tufts University. The commission called the discussion prurient and
not for the high school students who attended.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Glennon, who heads a lesbian and gay civil rights
committee for the Massachusetts Teachers Association, said Gaita
was not the first first-grade teacher to have told his class he was
gay, and in this context, it was more a lesson in relationships
than in sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a first-grade teacher and you talk about your
husband or your wife, you're not talking about sex either,''
Glennon said. ``You're talking about your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless people are willing to be out _ just be who they are _
then we send the message to students that all families are supposed
to look a certain way,'' Glennon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
