<P>
   OLY-DRUG-TESTS (Undated) _ The Summer Olympics are still three
months away, but in Australia and France a race with potentially
huge implications for the Olympics is already well under way. It is
the race to find an effective and practical method of detecting
synthetic erythropoietin, the hormone known as EPO. Unauthorized
use of the hormone, which boosts a user's red blood cell count and
hence the capacity to carry oxygen, has tainted results and
reputations in cycling and other endurance sports throughout the
1990s. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
