<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FIJI-SCENE-800(2TAKES     06-10 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIJI-SCENE-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUP TALK EMPTIES BEACHES AND FIJI'S CASH REGISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NADI, Fiji _ On approximately 299 and two-thirds of its 300
islands, there are no indications that Fiji is in turmoil, with
rebels occupying Parliament and holding three dozen hostages who
include the elected prime minister, much of his Cabinet, and the
daughter of the country's president.
</P>
<P>
   As Brad Ammann, a 29-year-old honeymooner from Hermosa Beach,
Calif., put it: ``The only sign there's a coup going on is that
there's nobody around.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is very quiet here in the main tourist city. But if
that is good news for the few visitors still enjoying these South
Sea islands, it is also an economic disaster in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's primary industry is tourism, but with hotels and resorts
at less than 10 percent of capacity, thousands of Fijians have been
laid off or put on sharply reduced hours. The second-biggest
industry is sugar cultivation, but with the European Union taking
steps to boycott Fijian sugar, and farmers refusing to harvest cane
to protest the attempted coup, Fiji Sugar Corp. also has said it
may soon lay off 3,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The third big source of jobs is garment manufacturing, which has
boomed since the mid-1990s when Australia granted preferential
tariff treatment to Fijian-made clothes. But with Australian trade
unions declining to handle any cargo to or from Fiji during the
hostage crisis, that industry has quickly sagged too.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and many small stores are also closed. Soni Kanta, the
manager of Ashiyara, a nearly deserted Indian restaurant in the
capital city, Suva, said the other evening that the armed rebels
``are not thinking of ordinary Fijians at all.'' She made an angry
gesture in the direction of the parliamentary complex. ``This is
simply hurting everybody in the country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fijians are enormously graceful people, and many seem to have a
remarkable ability to joke about their plight or say they have
faith that all will be for the best. Still, individual tales of woe
abound.
</P>
<P>
   One such story is that of Muhammad Ali Nasir, who emerged from
his home the other day to give aid to a foreign visitor who had
inadvertently lodged his rental car in a ditch while giving wide
berth to an oncoming truck full of goats on a seaside road in Nadi.
</P>
<P>
   Nasir has been a wood carver for 35 of his 49 years, and he has
a little shop in one of the resorts here. ``The hotel is
first-class, there is no doubt,'' Nasir said. ``And I am, if I may
modestly say, a world-classy wood carver. But right now there is
nobody to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   So he is in danger of not being able to afford the rent anymore,
explained Nasir, a Muslim whose grandparents, like those of many
Fijians of Indian descent, were brought to Fiji as indentured
laborers in the sugar trade in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Nasir's economic distress soon made the foreigner's
car-in-a-ditch problem pale in comparison, and the latter was soon
solved anyway with the help of a friendly neighbor of Nasir who
happened to own a tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Over a cup of tea in a neighbor's home, Nasir was philosophical:
The crisis would soon end, he hoped, and he could then resume
selling his carvings _ everything from salad bowls to replicas of
coconut palms swaying in the trade winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourists will return,'' he said _ a mantra often repeated
here.
</P>
<P>
   There are still tourists. But with the United States and other
nations having advised citizens to defer ``nonessential travel'' to
Fiji during the standoff, they are here in only a fraction of their
normal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have come include travel-hardened young backpackers,
imperturbable retirees, and a group of Americans who made Nadi a
port of call the other evening during a South Seas yachting trip
from Palos Verdes, Calif., to New Zealand and back. (``Say,
whatever happened to Microsoft?'' asked one sailor, who said he had
been on the high seas for months and lost track of the government's
antitrust battle with the software giant.)
</P>
<P>
   Many others explained, as did Ammann and his bride, that they
lacked the travel insurance needed to reschedule a Fijian vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it when I heard there was a coup going on
in Fiji,'' said Ammann, a 29-year-old contractor. ``I thought: What
in the heck do Fijians have to be so upset about?'' (The rebels who
seized Parliament are nationalistic indigenous Fijians agitated
about the rise of Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, the first
ethnic Indian ever to hold that post. Indigenous Fijians make up
about 51 percent of the population of 812,000; ethnic Indians,
about 44 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   The Ammanns, married last month, decided to go ahead with their
two-and-a-half-week honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ammann concluded that the struggle was a ``local and political
thing, something between Fijians'' that would be unlikely to visit
violence upon foreigners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Lorren, 27, an interior designer, said: ``We'd planned
this for so long. You only get one shot at a honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling around the islands, the Ammanns had Fiji virtually to
themselves. On the island of Natadola, they checked into a
dozen-room resort, only to find they were indeed the sole guests.
</P>
<P>
   It conjures up an image of Arcadia for a honeymoon couple, of
course, to be alone on a South Pacific island.
</P>
<P>
   But as they walked about the resort, the two looked at each
other and Brad Ammann recalled remarking: ``This feels a little too
weird. This is really creepy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorren Ammann said: ``I'm so glad you said that. Let's get out
of here.''
</P>
<P>
   So the couple high-tailed it to a hotel resort in Nadi, which,
while uncrowded, does at least have a few people around.
</P>
<P>
   At the Shangri-La Fijian, on the island of Yanuca, occupancy is
down to 8 percent of capacity, and 7,500 room nights have been
canceled in the last three weeks, a loss of about $1.2 million for
the 436-room resort, said Wolf-Dieter Flecker, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the resort told people who called to inquire about
conditions, Flecker said: ``We tell them Shangri-La is fully
operational, and it's up to them to choose whether to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In much of the country, there is no immediate sense of danger,
but the U.S. Department of State describes the whole situation as
``highly volatile,'' capable of turning ugly at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   David Hausmann, 19, a visitor from London, who was ``taking sort
of a gap here'' between high school and college, said such warnings
had added an undercurrent of tense excitement to his travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what might happen. There is this sense of
things sort of being on the edge,'' said Hausmann, who was
wandering around the world with a backpack. ``There could be a
civil war. I really doubt it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   So do most Fijians, though they fret constantly these days about
what the current situation will do to their nation's image. Fiji is
one of several South Pacific nations that compete to market
themselves as the ultimate tropical paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the western part of the nation, which has the biggest
resorts and best beaches, as well as most of the sugar and Fiji's
biggest gold mine, and where race relations are often described as
better than in eastern Fiji, some village chiefs and others have
even proposed breaking off to form a separate country.
</P>
<P>
   That is an idea that has spread alarm in many quarters, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unity of the Fijian people has never been more important
than at this stage of our national development,'' Radike
Qereqeretabua, a top tourism official in Fiji, told reporters. ``A
secession of the western provinces will only break up the Fijian
people even further, to the detriment of the country as a whole,
and should not be a serious option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
