<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE BEATS MARTINEZ FOR FRENCH OPEN TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Francoise Durr leaned forward and gave Mary Pierce a
kiss on each cheek, then held her tight and patted her back.
</P>
<P>
   Durr, who won the French Open title in 1967, had been waiting
with increasing impatience for 33 years for another Frenchwoman to
win the tennis tournament that matters most in France. Saturday,
her vigil came to an end as Pierce proved too strong physically and
mentally for Conchita Martinez, winning the title by 6-2, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce had often been shaky on big occasions in the past and
often at odds with the Parisians who have sat and watched her in
recent years. But she had a much smoother ride this year,
demonstrating a more complete grasp of the game than when she last
reached the final here in 1994 and earning the support, if not
quite the adoration, of the French crowd, which cheered her warmly
but not wildly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would never win this tournament,'' the 25-year-old
Pierce said in French, fighting her way through tears in her
victory speech. ``It was my dream to win it and now it has come
true, and it's great for it to happen in front of all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Pierce's second Grand Slam singles title; she also won
the 1995 Australian Open, and it restored her to a place of
prominence in the game that she had lost in recent years with the
arrival of younger rivals like Martina Hingis, Lindsay Davenport
and the Williams sisters, Venus and Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much better feeling than when I won in Australia in
1995,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She is a much better player, as well. Taught by her American
father, Jim, to swing with remarkable force from the baseline,
Pierce has long been able to slug a tennis ball with world-class
power, but in recent years, with the help of her former coach,
Michael de Jongh, and her current coach, her younger brother David,
she has improved her footwork, her volleys, her serve, her
consistency and her grasp of tactics.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of her boyfriend, Cleveland Indians second baseman
Roberto Alomar, and a deeper religious faith, she has also managed
to calm her nerves under duress. She now smiles more often than
groans when her huge shots go awry.
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals here, when she beat Hingis, the No. 1 seed,
she lost the second set after squandering a match point and then
roared back to win in three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all sure she would have been able to keep her
composure after losing that match point in previous years,'' said
Durr, who once coached Pierce as captain of the French Federation
Cup team. ``She has come a long way with her tennis, and I'm quite
delighted for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The sixth-seeded Pierce took control of the match in a hurry,
pressuring Martinez hard in her opening service game, which the
Spaniard managed to hold, and then winning five consecutive games
as her superior baseline power and Martinez's clearly tense mood
made for little suspense. The fifth-seeded Martinez, often dour on
court, credited a happier attitude with her run to this year's
final, but as she hit ball after ball ineffectively or hit them far
too short for her own benefit (Pierce makes a quick meal of short
balls), there was no trace of delight on her face.
</P>
<P>
   After just 27 minutes, she trailed by 1-5 and the crowd was
chanting ``Marie, Marie,'' but in her next service game she began
to loosen up and to begin putting her varied spins to more
effective use. She would hold to 5-2, saving three set points along
the way, and though Pierce would close out the opening set with
authority in the next game, the match would be a much more
intriguing and hotly contested encounter the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez jumped out to a 2-0 lead in the second set and then
took a 30-0 lead on her serve in the third game, but Pierce won the
next point with a very well-disguised backhand drop shot winner _
the sort of shot she was incapable of hitting in 1994 _ and then
managed to break the Spaniard after a struggle with a fine backhand
that forced an error.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce would break Martinez's serve again, this time at love, in
the fifth game as Martinez finished off with a double fault. But
just as it appeared that Pierce, up a break and with a 3-2 lead,
would begin to impose her will, she played a poor game. Martinez
broke back to make it 3-3. It would not be until Martinez served in
the 11th game that the match would turn for good. Pierce, doing her
best to stay aggressive despite the moment, pushed forward with
regularity and would end up breaking Martinez's serve with an
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   All that remained was for Pierce to stretch again on the final
changeover _ she suffered no effects of the cramps that she
experienced against Hingis in the semifinals _ and serve the most
important game of her career. It would not be easy. On her first
match point at 40-30, she dumped a forehand in the net after a long
rally. On her second, she hit a nervous backhand wide.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez returned the favor on the next point and this time
Pierce would find the solution: a powerful first serve up the
middle that Martinez scraped with her forehand into the net. Both
Pierce's arms shot in the air as she wheeled to face her brother
David and her French mother, Yannick. And appropriately for a woman
who was born in Canada, has lived most of her life in the United
States and has represented France since her teens, she gave her
victory speech in French and English.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have gone on these last few years,'' she told
the crowd, holding back tears. ``I think I will never, never forget
this day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's final Sunday, Magnus Norman, trying to emerge from
the shadow of Swedish Grand Slam champions Bjorn Borg, Mats
Wilander and Stefan Edberg, will meet Gustavo Kuerten, the gangly
Brazilian, who won the French Open in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
