<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ASSAD OF SYRIA, KEY FIGURE IN MIDEAST, DIES
</HEADLINE>
  (With OBIT-ASSAD)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Hafez al-Assad of Syria, a standard-bearer
of Arab nationalism and anti-Zionist fervor who ruled his country
with an iron hand for three decades, died Saturday. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Although Assad had long been in ill health, his sudden death,
described in early reports as a heart attack, casts a cloud of
uncertainty over the dynamics of peace and conflict in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had hoped to turn over the reins of power to his
34-year-old son, Bashar, and a crucial step toward that transition
was to have taken place next Saturday, during a rare political
convention of the Syrian Baath party. Reports from Damascus hours
after the death suggested that the transition would take place,
with the Syrian parliament amending the Constitution to allow it to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how firm a grip the younger Assad may have in
Syria, meaning potential exists for a tense and destabilizing
transition at a crucial time in the relationship between Syria and
Lebanon and between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Although Assad took a resolutely hard line toward Israel, many
Western diplomats believed that he was the linchpin to any lasting
peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian television made an official announcement only after the
news had circulated internationally first. It showed members of the
Syrian parliament standing for a moment of silence, many of them
crying and holding their heads in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had survived several assassination attempts and at least
one heart attack. Despite his gaunt appearance and his infrequent
travels abroad, many in Syria had wondered if talk of his imminent
demise was not exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Bashar Assad was believed to be overseeing an
anti-corruption drive that had led to the resignation of several
prominent officials and the suicide of a former top official
accused of embezzlement. Bashar Assad was also engaged in a power
struggle behind the scenes with his uncle, Rifaat Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak spent many months
sending messages to Assad until, finally, Israel and Syria made an
aborted attempt at peace negotiations. After Israel withdrew its
troops from Lebanon last month, tentative questions about renewing
the effort were voiced by both sides. But Barak said he wondered if
Assad's heart would ever be in it.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, he issued this statement: ``Israel understands
the sorrow of the Syrian nation. Israel has worked in the past to
reach peace with Syria, and will continue to do so in the future,
with any leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, P.J. Crowley, the national security spokesman at
the White House, said the administration learned the news from
Syrian television. ``We think that the Syrian government has
committed itself to the path of peace, and we hope that will
continue even with the passing of President Assad,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1254EDT &QL; 
