<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Summery heat and humidity will linger over much of the East.
Sinking air currents under the center of an expansive high-pressure
system from the interior Southeast to the central Atlantic Ocean
will suppress clouds and showers. Meanwhile, a corridor of moisture
along the western flank of the high will promote thundershowers
from eastern Texas to the central Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A wavering front from the Great Lakes to New England, separating
the hot air from much cooler air in Canada, will be the focus for
clouds and showers. A cool rain will fall in northern New England
while afternoon thunderstorms erupt on the warm side of the front
from the northern Ohio Valley to the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, ample sunshine will prevail in most areas, however
showers will brush the Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Born too Soon
</P>
<P>
   The first Atlantic tropical depression of 2000 formed near the
Yucatan peninsula late Wednesday. A day later it had weakened into
a cluster of tropical showers. During the past few days, a tropical
disturbance in the central Atlantic showed no signs of
strengthening as it battled vigorous high-level winds. In the next
six months, as winds aloft relax, forecasters will track over 100
clusters of thunderstorms roaming the tropical Atlantic. On
average, 10 clusters become tropical storms with winds over 39 mph
and six become hurricanes packing winds over 74 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
