<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRIPP-PAL-NYT &LR;      06-10 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-PAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP MEETS INTERNET PALS FROM CONSERVATIVE WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 27, 1998, Brian L. Buckley, a Los Angeles lawyer,
received an e-mail message from someone he did not know, a New York
literary agent, Lucianne Goldberg. Her one-sentence message to him
said, ``Someone very important wants to know who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   That someone turned out to be Linda Tripp, whose tape-recorded
conversations with Monica Lewinsky set off the investigation that
led to the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Tripp had been reading and finding
inspiration in Buckley's observations about the Lewinsky scandal on
a conservative, anti-Clinton Internet site, FreeRepublic.com.
Buckley frequently posted his legal insights on the Lewinsky case
using the screen name Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing months, Clarity and Tripp began a friendship that
blossomed from e-mail messages to telephone calls. In the
electronic age, friendships between public figures and private
citizens, who meet by chance on the Internet, are becoming more
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and I are pals by now,'' said Buckley, who said he is also
a lawyer for FreeRepublic and directs an affiliated research group.
He said he became an informal adviser to Tripp as she battled
criminal charges filed against her by the state of Maryland for
taping her conversations with Lewinsky without Lewinsky's
knowledge. The prosecutor dropped the charges in May, saying he
would not pursue them because a judge had suppressed crucial
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley did not meet Tripp in person until June 3, at a
FreeRepublic tribute dinner for Tripp in Charleston, S.C. Buckley,
45, e-mailed a photograph of himself to Tripp so that she would
recognize him. He said he was almost overcome by unexpected emotion
and had to ``catch my breath,'' as Tripp made her entrance at a
buffet dinner of fried chicken and barbecue, where about 60
supporters gave her a standing ovation and waved a homemade banner
emblazoned ``Linda Tripp. Hero. Patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Tripp said that the electronic postings of
Clarity and other FreeRepublic supporters had been a source of
comfort to her. As a way of thanking supporters, Tripp said, she
chose the conference sponsored by the Southeastern chapter of
FreeRepublic for her first public speech after the dismissal of the
state charges.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp spoke for more than an hour, appearing nervous at times.
The guests, who paid $50 to attend, were told that they could not
tape her remarks or take her photograph. Tripp said she was not
used to speaking in public and hoped she would make it through her
talk ``without fainting.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Tripp provided a glimpse of what her life
has been like since she became a starring player in the
investigation of Clinton. Tripp described how she went from being
addicted to cable news shows to depending almost solely on Internet
sites like FreeRepublic for news.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I crave fame, but I spend all my time trying to hide
from the media,'' she said. After news of the Lewinsky scandal
broke in January 1998 and journalists camped out in Tripp's
driveway, Tripp said, ``I was living in a bunker with sheets over
the windows,'' a virtual prisoner in her own home. In her speech,
she said she found herself compulsively watching the 24-hour cable
news shows about the investigation and proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so addicted to the TV coverage that I almost never
slept,'' Tripp said. Often, she said, she found herself shaking her
head in disagreement with the televised commentary. By the summer
of 1998, she said, her head was shaking so much that she worried
she might have a neurological problem. She stopped watching network
or cable news for good.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tripp said, she began getting all her news from
FreeRepublic.com, the Web site frequented by Lucianne Goldberg, who
was Tripp's confidante. It was devoid of the ``derogatory slams on
my appearance'' and ``vile things, too vile to repeat,'' which
Tripp said she found so hurtful in the mainstream news media. The
friendlier commentary from Clarity and other FreeRepublic
contributors encouraged Tripp to believe that her support ``was
more widespread'' than she had thought.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, whose legal specialty is intellectual property, said he
often posted his legal analysis of the Lewinsky matter, but was
surprised when he first heard from Goldberg. He wrote her back a
detailed e-mail message explaining his background, which included
undergraduate work at Dartmouth, and law school at William and
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the ordeal that Linda endured over time,'' Buckley said,
``if you were in that position, you would relish a place on the
Internet where you could put your feet up and relax and get some
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp told the dinner guests: ``I've rejected many other higher
profile speaking engagements. I am not a public person.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tripp is not fading away so quietly. She has filed a civil
lawsuit against the Clinton White House and the Pentagon claiming
they breached the Privacy Act in releasing information from her
employment file. ``We'll be subpoenaing every national name in the
White House,'' she promised.
</P>
<P>
   Clarity, meanwhile, is giving her some informal legal advice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
