<P>
   MLK-CONSPIRACY _ ATLANTA _ A 22-month investigation by the
Department of Justice concluded Friday that there is no evidence of
a conspiracy in the April 1968 assassination of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. (Bryce, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS-READINESS _ WACO, Texas _ A look at preparations in
Waco for the Branch Davidian civil trial, including security, the
influx of media and sympathizers and hotel room availability.
(England, Waco Tribune-Herald). 35. MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WACO-FATIGUE _ WACO, Texas _ Aaaarrgggggghhhhhhh! Can this
community really stand another siege, even if this one is contained
to the federal courthouse? How the seven long years of the fallout
from the attack on the Branch Davidian compound have impacted the
people and various institutions of Waco. (England, Waco
Tribune-Herald). 35. MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   LEOFRANK-LIST _ ATLANTA _ Mary Phagan Kean was attending a
Leadership Cobb meeting a few years ago when a man introduced
himself with a startling admission. His grandfather, he told her,
was one of the vigilantes who ``took care of Leo Frank.'' Kean, a
46-year-old special education administrator, is the great niece of
Mary Phagan, the pretty, pink-bowed factory girl whose 1913 murder
precipitated one of the most infamous chapters in Georgia history.
Her employer, Frank, a wiry, nervous young man from Brooklyn, was
convicted of the crime and then lynched near Marietta, not far from
the site of the Big Chicken. People confided in Kean. She recorded
what she heard and kept a roster of the men who believed they were
avenging her great aunt. She sealed her latest version of the list
in an envelope and printed ``To be opened at my demise'' across the
front. ``I can't show this to you,'' she says. ``Too many people
would be hurt.'' But it's too late now. One of her working lists
has been posted on the Internet against her wishes. For the first
time, one of the oldest, darkest secrets of the South _ the names
of the people who lynched Leo Frank _ is beginning to see the light
of day. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 87.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-DROUGHT _ Recent trips down two of Georgia's major rivers
show first-hand the effects of the drought. On a canoe trip down a
three-mile stretch of the Flint River, water levels are so low that
participants have to get out and drag their boats half the way.
Meanwhile, along the Chattahoochee River, boaters must put in at
Newnan because water levels are so low upstream. We report on these
and other environmental effects of the drought. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDDIE-EAGLE _ WASHINGTON _ Some call him ``Joe Camel with
feathers.'' Others call him a key to protecting children from the
dangers of guns. His name is ``Eddie Eagle,'' and the National
Rifle Association wants him in your schools. We take a look at the
recent controversy surrounding the NRA's cartoon mascot, who has
been around for a long time but has never faced this much
opposition. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). With illustration of
``Eddie Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Other
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HAZARDS _ TAMPA, Fla. _ When it comes to dangerous
occupations, most people think of firefighters or construction
workers on high beams. In fact, nursing ranks higher for injuries
and illnesses than almost any other job category. Now safety
experts are seeking ways to make hospitals and nursing homes safer
for nurses. A veterans hospital here is leading the way in safety
research. (Malone, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS
