   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ASSAD-FUTURE _ JERUSALEM _ Throughout the Middle East, Syrian
President Hafez Assad was known as a riddle, but a consistent
riddle that was strong enough to keep his commitments. Now,
following his death Saturday, the goal of reaching a Syrian-Israeli
peace _ perhaps the last major deal needed for a regional peace _
looks more elusive. A look at what his death means for the region
and American interests there. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   AIDSORPHANS _ HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Nomsa Mwale, 12, and her four
siblings have been given a chance at schooling for the first time
in their lives, thanks to Cox Newspapers readers who have embraced
their story and offered assistance. The children now have stable
housing and a tutor who try to prepare them to enter school at a
level appropriate to their ages. Both their parents died of AIDS
leaving the children to fend for themselves. Additionally,
88-year-old grandmother Lina Smoke who is raising the children of
her dead children has moved into a small wooden house ? leaving
behind her old metal shack ? thanks to contributions from readers.
There are 900,000 AIDS orphans in Zimbabwe. We update the situation
of these two families. (Roughton, Cox News Service). With photos
and information for a box/graphic on where readers can contribute.
MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story was on Saturday's budget but is still good for
papers that haven't used it.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTEBUY _ SAN PEDRO EL ALTO, Mexico _ Maria del Carmen
Peralta has little more than corn and beans to feed five children.
Her family has no bathroom and they sleep in a hut that's a virtual
ice box at night in this cold mountain region of Mexico state.
Peralta's life has been so harsh she wants to finally vote for an
opposition candidate in Mexico's July 2 presidential election. But
she's frightened that her vote might cost her the $45 a month
supplement she receives from Progresa, a federal welfare program
here. Although it is illegal, Peralta's welfare coordinator
confirms that she has been under pressure to instruct Progresa
recipients to vote for Mexico's ruling party on July 2 _ or suffer
the consequences. Other impoverished Mazahua Indians in this rugged
rural area have similar stories. All over Mexico, allegations of
vote-buying and pressure tactics are mounting as election day
approaches. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS of dissident
Mazahua Indians. EDs: MOVED Thursday
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ BRUSSELS _ Last year's disaster with contamination in
Belgium has prompted Coca-Cola to completely change the way it does
business in Europe. The company has decentralized power from
Atlanta, placing much more control in the hands of its new European
divisions, which were aligned to reflect more ``natural markets.''
(Roughton, Cox News Service). With photos and charts available from
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. EDs: MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-FRENETTE-Q&AMP;A _ Charlie Frenette, the new European chief for
Coke, talks about the changes. (Roughton, Cox News Service). EDs:
MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TENSIONS _ MITROVICA, Kosovo _ In this town, the lives of
Albanian Kosovars have returned to normal while Serb families
huddle in fear for their lives. Welcome to Kosovo, one year after
the 50,000-strong NATO-led peacekeeping force rolled into the
province and ended a campaign by Serb and Yugoslav authorities to
wipe out its Albanian majority and ethnically cleanse a whole
people. Twelve months into the peacekeeping mission, the basic
rhythms of life have returned here. But few people are naive enough
to say NATO's chief aim _ establishing a multi-ethnic society _ has
been achieved. At the same time, few officials are brave enough to
say this failure threatens the peacekeepers' mission or the
region's future stability. (Coker, Cox News Service). EDs: MOVED
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS _ DOBROSIN, Yugoslavia _ The sun glared down on
the clay-baked courtyard as a mother and father in their Sunday
best, fidgeting and nervously chatting with two armed guards,
waited for the Albanian rebel leader to appear. The parents were
searching for their 17-year-old son who had run away from home.
They heard that he and two friends had come here to Dobrosin, a
village located in the demilitarized zone between Kosovo and
Serbia, to sign up with an illegal branch of the Kosovo Liberation
Army. Indeed, they found him here. According to U.S. military
intelligence, the one-story adobe compound where they waited
anxiously for him to be returned to him is home for as many as 150
battle-ready Albanian fighters. The rebels inject great uncertainty
into the uneasy peace that exists in the Balkans a year after the
carnage in Kosovo. (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
Thursday
</P>
<P>
   EDS NOTE: This story was slugged KOSOVO-CIVIL in earlier
budgets. It was re-slugged to comport with the content of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TOURISM _ LONDON _ Finally, a surging U.S. economy is
translating into some extra dollars for overseas tourists.
Americans in Paris, London Berlin and other European locations are
finding these days that their purchasing power has increased here
along with the value of the greenback. Developing. (Roughton, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS. EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPRITE _ There's fallout from China's decision to ban
Sprite ads featuring Chang Hui-mei, a Taiwanese pop singer with a
massive mainland following, after she sang the Taiwanese national
anthem to usher in the island's new president last month (Chao, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS. EDs: MOVED Tuesday.
</P>
