<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NY-TRADES-NYT &LR;      06-10 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NY-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONES WHO GOT AWAY FROM THE METS AND YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carl Everett is not playing at Yankee Stadium this
weekend. Neither is J.T. Snow, Eric Milton, Tony Armas Jr., Preston
Wilson, Quilvio Veras, Fernando Vina or Jeromy Burnitz. Al Leiter
is, but only after taking a circuitous route to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Leiter, those players and many others are playing not
for the Yankees or the Mets this weekend but for other teams in
other interleague series. They began their professional baseball
lives in the Yankees' or Mets' minor league system, but they have
been moved elsewhere, many before getting a chance to play for the
Yankees or the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this team of players the Yankees raised but did not
keep: first basemen Fred McGriff (Devil Rays) and Snow (Giants);
second basemen Andy Fox (Marlins) and Kevin Jordan (Phillies);
shortstop Cristian Guzman (Twins); third basemen Mike Lowell
(Marlins) and Russ Davis (Giants); outfielders Everett (Red Sox),
Gerald Williams (Devil Rays) and Ruben Rivera (Padres); catchers
Brad Ausmus (Tigers) and Brian Johnson (Royals); and pitchers
Leiter, Milton (Twins), Armas (Expos), Sterling Hitchcock (Padres)
and Hideki Irabu (Expos).
</P>
<P>
   Among players the Mets have spawned and disgorged are a pair of
starting second basemen, Vina (Cardinals) and Veras (Braves); two
closers, Rick Aguilera (Cubs) and Jason Isringhausen (Athletics); a
pretty good outfield of Jeromy Burnitz (Brewers), Preston Wilson
(Marlins) and Terrence Long (Athletics); and a first baseman, Brian
Daubach, who will be at Yankee Stadium Monday with Everett when the
Red Sox arrive for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's story is well known, especially the part about his
dislike for the Yankees, who drafted him in the first round of the
1990 draft and then left him exposed for Florida to take in the
1992 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the organization who was there said the word to
leave Everett unprotected came from Joseph Molloy, then the
Yankees' managing partner and George Steinbrenner's son-in-law.
Molloy is no longer either, and Everett may be the American League
most valuable player this season.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach left the Mets' organization as a minor league free agent
in 1996 and signed with the Marlins, for whom he played in 1998
before they released him. The Marlins did not keep Everett long
either. He played 16 games for them in 1994 before they traded him
to the Mets for Veras, who had spent five years with Mets minor
league teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets signed Veras as an amateur free agent six months before
they drafted Vina in June 1990. They traded Vina to Milwaukee in
1994, a month after they traded Veras to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made trades 10 years apart that created closers for
other teams. In 1989, they included Aguilera in a package they sent
to Minnesota for Frank Viola, and last year they traded
Isringhausen to Oakland for Billy Taylor. Aguilera has earned 292
saves with the Twins and the Chicago Cubs; Isringhausen is off to
an effective start with the Athletics with 14 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets made another trade with Oakland last year, acquiring
Kenny Rogers, and one of the players in the deal, Long, has become
the A's center fielder. But the Mets have traded no young player
who has developed and produced more than Burnitz, who hit 98 home
runs in three seasons for the Brewers after they acquired him from
Cleveland, which got him from the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been productive with the Marlins, who obtained him
from the Mets in the Mike Piazza deal. Piazza's presence prompted
the Mets to trade Todd Hundley, a home-grown catcher, to Los
Angeles, where he has been joined by the former Mets shortstop
Kevin Elster.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost two catchers in drafts _ Brad Ausmus to
Colorado in the 1992 expansion draft and Brian Johnson to San Diego
in the 1991 minor league draft. Both have since moved to other
teams. Alberto Castillo was a catcher in the Mets' system for 12
years before he left as a free agent in 1998. He is now with
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Not all players become starters after leaving the Mets or
Yankees. The Yankees had three players who have become steady
part-time players _ Jordan with the Phillies, Lyle Mouton with the
Brewers and Turner Ward now with Arizona. The Mets had, among
others, Aaron Ledesma (Rockies), Butch Huskey (Twins) and Gregg
Jefferies (Tigers).
</P>
<P>
   Of more recent vintage, the Yankees traded four players to
Minnesota for Chuck Knoblauch, and three of them start for the
Twins: Milton, their No. 2 starting pitcher; Guzman, their
shortstop; and Brian Buchanan, who was recently promoted from the
minors to play right field.
</P>
<P>
   Armas, whom the Yankees traded to the Red Sox so they could have
Mike Stanley for the last six weeks of the 1997 season, recently
joined Montreal's starting rotation. After nine years in the
minors, all with the Yankees, Bubba Carpenter became a major league
rookie with Colorado last month and has hit three home runs in 27
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   According to an annual study done by Tracy Ringolsby of The
Rocky Mountain News in Denver, the Yankees and the Mets last year
were among the top five teams in the number of players from their
systems playing in the majors for other teams: Montreal 40, Los
Angeles 39, Mets 38, and Yankees and Toronto 36 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0360 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-1     06-10 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS THE MOMENT IN THE MIDEAST. (BUT FOR WHAT?) 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 7th graf (bgng `But moments and...') to note death of
Assad)  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Shultz said it. James Baker said it. So did
Warren Christopher and Madeleine Albright. When it comes to making
peace in the Middle East, four successive secretaries of state all
sounded the same theme: Americans cannot want peace more than the
parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the United States must be both available and
aloof, appearing as a willing partner but not an over-eager suitor.
In fact, in late 1993, less than a year into the Clinton
administration, Christopher set modest goals, saying that making
peace was going to take ``a lot of time and patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and patience are the two things President Clinton no longer
has. And now, with only seven and a half months left as president,
he even may want peace more than the parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in Clinton's announcement, after meeting with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel in Lisbon 10 days ago, that
peace between the Israelis and the Palestinians was ``within view
now.'' He said the two sides would restart negotiations in
Washington this week and his administration dangled the possibility
of a three-way Camp David-style summit in which Clinton himself
would take part. The sense of urgency Clinton expressed was
reminiscent of the pleading that the late King Hussein of Jordan
was famous for, using every new political wrinkle and change on the
ground to say that that was the last chance for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and Middle East experts talk now of the
need to seize the moment created by a new reality: Israel's
withdrawal from Lebanon two weeks ago, which Clinton said imposes a
much greater sense of urgency on the parties to resolve the very
substantial differences that remain between them: the size and
shape of a Palestinian state, the future of Jerusalem and the fate
of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only certain moments in history when all the parties
are available, when they see that a negotiated deal is in their
interests and they don't believe they have better options,'' said
Thomas R. Smerling, Washington director of the Israel Policy Forum,
a research institute that focuses on the peace process. ``This is
one of those times.''
</P>
<P>
   But moments and deadlines come and go, and complicating matters
now is the death Saturday of Syria's president, Hafez Assad. Still,
urgency is one of the most easily manipulated commodities in the
Middle East. It has been used to derail progress toward peace.
Witness all the years wasted because of Palestinian terrorist
attacks and Israeli retaliation, troop movements and street
violence. In that atmosphere, concessions became impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But urgency can, if invoked with skill, be used to push the
region toward peace as well. The argument is that every opportunity
is fleeting in the Middle East, where attitudes can shift with
remarkable speed, so that when a moment is ripe for conciliation,
it must be seized.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having run out of time for the more familiar formula of
patience, Clinton is left with the appeal of urgency, in effect
trying to turn his biggest liability _ his lame-duck status _ into
an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the moment is urgent for him. And certainly urgency
is felt by Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the newspaper Haaretz last month, Barak
spoke of ``a golden opportunity'' for Israel to make peace, not
only with the Palestinians, but also with the Syrians and the
Lebanese. ``Do we await the future passively with our eyes shut,''
he asked, ``or do we take an active stance vis-a-vis the reality
and try to modify it to our advantage?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Arafat, he has no good alternative. Unilaterally
declaring an independent Palestinian state, as he has threatened to
do, would deprive him of the aid and good will he has received from
the rest of the world since he set out to make peace in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Both men know that if they don't get a deal this year it may be
a long time before a similar opportunity comes. Clinton offers a
carefully built reputation as an honest broker that neither of the
presumptive presidential nominees, Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, enjoy. Over the years, Gore has taken an
uncritical pro-Israeli stance; Bush is a blank slate when it comes
to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rushed nature of the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon
has stirred up Israeli and Palestinian politics in ways that may
prove damaging to prospects for a quick deal. Barak is fighting off
a rebellion by conservative coalition allies that could produce new
elections. And the frenzied meetings of long-divided families at
the now-accessible Lebanese border could create a new dynamic for
the extremely sensitive issue of what happens to the many
Palestinian refugees who would remain outside a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's pleas for urgency notwithstanding, the
lame-duck year of any administration tends to limit its
accomplishments in diplomacy. The last president to be finishing
out a second term was Ronald Reagan; in 1988, Shultz launched a
peace initiative after the Palestinians began the uprising known as
the intifadeh, but the effort went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for any U.S. negotiator, Middle East peacemaking requires
both staying power and an unswerving belief in the impossible.
``There is a good chance to come to an agreement,'' said Henry
Kissinger, who as secretary of state spent seven straight weeks
shuttling between Damascus and Jerusalem after the 1973 war. ``Both
sides have run out of options and both sides are at the limit of
their concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would give Clinton, Kissinger said, ``I
would tell him to stay calm and be available as a facilitator. And
I would tell him not to be more interested than the parties
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-1     06-10 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-REVIEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS THE MOMENT IN THE MIDEAST. (BUT FOR WHAT?) 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 7th graf (bgng `But moments and...') to note death of
Assad)  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Shultz said it. James Baker said it. So did
