   But moments and deadlines come and go, and complicating matters
now is the death Saturday of Syria's president, Hafez Assad. Still,
urgency is one of the most easily manipulated commodities in the
Middle East. It has been used to derail progress toward peace.
Witness all the years wasted because of Palestinian terrorist
attacks and Israeli retaliation, troop movements and street
violence. In that atmosphere, concessions became impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But urgency can, if invoked with skill, be used to push the
region toward peace as well. The argument is that every opportunity
is fleeting in the Middle East, where attitudes can shift with
remarkable speed, so that when a moment is ripe for conciliation,
it must be seized.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having run out of time for the more familiar formula of
patience, Clinton is left with the appeal of urgency, in effect
trying to turn his biggest liability _ his lame-duck status _ into
an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the moment is urgent for him. And certainly urgency
is felt by Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the newspaper Haaretz last month, Barak
spoke of ``a golden opportunity'' for Israel to make peace, not
only with the Palestinians, but also with the Syrians and the
Lebanese. ``Do we await the future passively with our eyes shut,''
he asked, ``or do we take an active stance vis-a-vis the reality
and try to modify it to our advantage?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Arafat, he has no good alternative. Unilaterally
declaring an independent Palestinian state, as he has threatened to
do, would deprive him of the aid and good will he has received from
the rest of the world since he set out to make peace in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Both men know that if they don't get a deal this year it may be
a long time before a similar opportunity comes. Clinton offers a
carefully built reputation as an honest broker that neither of the
presumptive presidential nominees, Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, enjoy. Over the years, Gore has taken an
uncritical pro-Israeli stance; Bush is a blank slate when it comes
to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rushed nature of the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon
has stirred up Israeli and Palestinian politics in ways that may
prove damaging to prospects for a quick deal. Barak is fighting off
a rebellion by conservative coalition allies that could produce new
elections. And the frenzied meetings of long-divided families at
the now-accessible Lebanese border could create a new dynamic for
the extremely sensitive issue of what happens to the many
Palestinian refugees who would remain outside a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's pleas for urgency notwithstanding, the
lame-duck year of any administration tends to limit its
accomplishments in diplomacy. The last president to be finishing
out a second term was Ronald Reagan; in 1988, Shultz launched a
peace initiative after the Palestinians began the uprising known as
the intifadeh, but the effort went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for any U.S. negotiator, Middle East peacemaking requires
both staying power and an unswerving belief in the impossible.
``There is a good chance to come to an agreement,'' said Henry
Kissinger, who as secretary of state spent seven straight weeks
shuttling between Damascus and Jerusalem after the 1973 war. ``Both
sides have run out of options and both sides are at the limit of
their concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would give Clinton, Kissinger said, ``I
would tell him to stay calm and be available as a facilitator. And
I would tell him not to be more interested than the parties
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
