</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-DROUGHT0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia faces severe drought conditions
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOMASTON, Ga. _ For the umpteenth time, Beth Brown heard the
awful rasping sound. The bottom of her fiberglass kayak, which
needs only a few inches of water to float, was grounded once again
on a rock in the Flint River.
</P>
<P>
   And once more, she had to get out of her boat and laboriously
pull it until she could find enough water to refloat it. ``I'm
looking for any sign of a few inches of water running in chutes
between the rocks so that I can get downriver,'' said Brown, an
information specialist with the Department of Natural Resources who
set out on the river with two other DNR workers last week. ``I'm
not finding a lot of those places.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, there would be several feet of water rushing over and
around the rocks, far more than enough to float kayaks and canoes.
But when Brown and her colleagues ventured down a 3-mile stretch of
the Flint near Thomaston, they found water levels only a few inches
deep in many spots.
</P>
<P>
   In what is shaping up to be one of Georgia's worst droughts on
record, streams and rivers all over the state are in similar
straits. Environmental and health experts say the impact on
wildlife, agriculture, businesses and public health could be dire.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every day that it doesn't rain, new record low flows are
being set in stretches of the Flint, Altamaha, Little, Ocmulgee,
Oconee, Ohoopee, St. Marys and Chattahoochee rivers and their
tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   Some streams have no flow at all. ``Several streams in South
Georgia, which normally have a trickle of water even during a
drought, are now completely dry,'' said Mike Gennings, fisheries
chief for the DNR.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has been in a drought for more than two years, leaving
some areas with rainfall deficits of more than 40 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The record low stream flows are bringing into sharp focus major
concerns that have long worried biologists, environmental
authorities and policy-makers _ but do not get much attention when
rainfall is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists, for instance, worry that the drought could be the
final blow for some endangered species _ including several types of
freshwater mussels, salamanders and fish. These species already
have been drifting toward extinction because of pollution, dams
that impede water flow and massive water withdrawals from streams
for drinking and industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fish and wildlife populations have faced stress from
droughts for thousands of years and have survived,'' Gennings said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem now, he said, is the combination of severe drought
on top of other stresses caused by humans. ``We are going to have
to give very serious thought to the amount of water we're taking
out of these rivers,'' Gennings said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Flint, for instance, authorities say the drought has
caused striped bass to disappear from the upper part of the river,
and now the fish is struggling for survival in the lower portion
because of extreme low water.
</P>
<P>
   To survive Georgia's hot summers, the bass, which can weight up
to 60 pounds and measure more than 3 feet long, congregate around
cool springs known as ``blue holes.'' Fed by aquifers, most of the
springs flow into the Flint River bottom. However, the flow in one
spring has already dropped to a trickle and officials are concerned
that others will dry up as farmers in southwest Georgia pump more
water from the aquifers this summer to keep their crops alive.
</P>
<P>
   Other species also are suffering. Gennings pointed out that
anglers this year are catching only about half the fish they caught
last year in the Altamaha River in South Georgia because of drought
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern of environmental authorities is the
scalding water discharged from Georgia Power Co.'s coal-buring
power plants. The plants draw cooling water from the Chattahoochee
and other rivers and discharge hot water back into the streams.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power is facing a $55,000 state fine for a massive fish
kill in a 22-mile stretch of the Chattahoochee last August because
of hot water discharged from the company's Plant Yates near Newnan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish kill was due mostly to low flows in the river,'' said
Georgia Power spokesman Tal Wright. He said there was not enough
water in the river at the time to assimilate the heated water and
prevent the fish from being killed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with flows running as low or lower than last year, the
worry is that there may be more major fish kills. But Georgia Power
officials say they must dump the hot water into the river for the
plant to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation that has got us very nervous,'' says Sally
Bethea, director of the Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper, who boated
down the the river this past week to look at the low flow
conditions downstream from Plant Yates.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said Georgia Power also is concerned that water levels
could fall so low that the plants' water intake pipes will not be
able to draw in adequate amounts of cooling water. That could
seriously hamper the operations of the plants, which will be
running full tilt this summer to keep air conditioners humming in
the face of what's expected to be higher-than-normal temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental authorities and public health officials have
another big worry: plummeting flows in rivers and streams mean
there may not be enough water to adequately dilute wastes
discharged into the waterways. That could make water pollution a
much greater problem this summer, say officials with the
Environmental Protection Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking that dischargers (including sewage treatment
plants) be vigilant and do the best job they possibly can treating
wastes before discharging them into the streams,'' EPD director
Harold Reheis said last week during a specially called drought
managment meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Newell of the state's Southwest Public Health District
in Albany warned that higher levels of pollution could be a public
health threat. ``The drought is just as big a threat to us as a
tornado or hurricane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
