<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MIMES0611-COX     06-10 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIMES0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mime gives voice to language of the heart
 &HT;    by Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Silent Sam has special meaning for
Deniese Kohles.
</P>
<P>
   The mime character is modeled after a homeless man who once
saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Kohles was driving from her Orchard Mesa home to visit her
sister who lived on the Redlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the Redlands cutoff on River Road,'' explains Kohles.
``There was a homeless man standing on the railroad tracks waving
his arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I locked my doors because I was afraid of him. When I stopped
to lock my doors, a car came flying over the tracks on two wheels
almost rolling over and going underneath the viaduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The homeless man saved Kohles' life.
</P>
<P>
   When she turned around to thank him, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Overcome by emotion, she sat in her car and cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried really hard to find this man and I couldn't,'' says
Kohles. ``I thought about respect and how a silent clown could
teach someone in a very quiet and emotional way to respect all
walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Silent Sam was born.
</P>
<P>
   CLOWNING RUNS IN THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Kohles is a descendent of Emmett Kelly, the circus clown famous
for his portrayal of the lovable hobo Weary Willie born out of a
cartoon character he once drew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmett Kelly was my dad's cousin,'' says the 40-something
mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   After the near-death experience, Kohles established Mesa County
Mimes, a group of individuals interested in the performance art of
mime.
</P>
<P>
   Mime is the expression of feelings through gestures rather than
words.
</P>
<P>
   She began incorporating the Silent Sam character into skits
written by kids in her mime class.
</P>
<P>
   One such skit showed Silent Sam taking the last bed in a rescue
mission as another family is turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hoarding cookies from his meals and putting them in his
pocket,'' says Kohles. ``He tapped on the window and told the
family to come in and he snuck them into his bed and gave them what
was in his pocket and walked back out and laid on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The child in the bed knocked on the window and said, `Thank
you,' and the mom told him to lay down and Silent Sam went back to
where he was and fell asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Kohles wrote to the Emmett Kelly Foundation asking for
permission to copyright the Silent Sam character.
</P>
<P>
   She was granted permission and now holds copyrights on what she
calls ``silent clowning'' and ``classical mime,'' body language
choreographed to music, which is different than traditional mime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else in the United States has it,'' says Kohles. ``I
had to take an oath and swear to it ... if I get caught with my
face paint on and I am talking, there is a $500 fine.''
</P>
<P>
   MIME HAS 2,000-YEAR HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Mime originated in China more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The geisha used to be male ... that is who the first mimes
were. They entertained by telling stories,'' says Kohles.
</P>
<P>
   The gender and role of the geisha have changed. Geishas are
Japanese women trained in the arts and conversation to serve as
hired companions to men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their faces are painted white to draw attention to purity,''
adds Kohles.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, mime was as much a part of vaudeville as
juggling, clowning, magic, music and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Chaplin got his start on the vaudeville stage, later
going on to star in his own silent pictures.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more famous mimes of all time is Marcel Marceau, who
was inspired by Chaplin, Buster Keaton, Harry Langdon and the
popular pair Laurel and Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, Marceau created ``Bip'' the clown, who in his striped
pullover and battered, deflowered opera hat, became his alter ego.
Marceau's routines include classic works like the cage, walking
against the wind and the mask maker.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the simple colors of black and white is so the
mime can become anything, Kohles said.
</P>
<P>
   France deviated from the traditional black garb, adding striped
shirts and red suspenders to be different.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has long poked fun at the stark-faced clowns.
</P>
<P>
   Take the 1995 movie, ``Die Hard: With a Vengeance,'' starring
Bruce Willis, Jeremy Irons and Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The following dialogue was exchanged:
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you trying to hit these people?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No ... well, maybe that mime.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, mimes scare people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People put the face of the unknown with fear,'' says Kohles.
``Something has scared them, whether it be Halloween or whatever,
and they've put all that reality in the face of the mime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people who will walk all the way around to avoid you
because of the stereotyping of mimes. When the opera was in town,
my job was to remove people from the table. I sat on the lap of one
guy during rehearsal without my face paint on and he was eating it
up. I came in during my dress rehearsal and did the exact same
thing and he freaked. He was absolutely frozen because he was
afraid of mimes.''
</P>
<P>
   KOHLES TEACHES WITH EMOTION
</P>
<P>
   Kohles is working to change the stigma associated with mimes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she started Artistic Combinations which offers
classes in mime.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to learning mime is in your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard at all, but you have to really want to try it,''
says Kohles. ``We spend hours looking in the mirror trying to get
the facial expressions right. I will even tie their shoelaces
together if they are partners so they are in rhythm with the same
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Six-year old Kaleigh Nitz admits she took the mime class because
she likes art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the teachers, too,'' she says, ``and the movements.''
</P>
<P>
   For David Skaff, the hardest part about mime is not talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes its pretty hard,'' admits the 12-year old who
aspires to be a forest ranger or an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Arch and Edie Chaney attended the class with their 7-year old
granddaughter, Nikyia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for her,'' says Edie. ``It's going to be something
later on that she will remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned an appreciation of quietness,'' adds Arch.
</P>
<P>
   Students from Kohles mime class, including Arch and Edie,
presented a final performance last month. Dressed in black outfits
with white greasepaint on their faces and white gloves, they mimed
to songs including ``God Bless The U.S.A.,'' ``Son of Man,''
``Let's Talk About Love'' and ``Everything I Do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see tears in your eyes, that means we've done our job,''
Kohles told the audience before the performance. ``If we see you
laugh, that means we've done our job. I think you will learn
something from these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohles, a former art teacher for School District 51, believes
that if you teach with emotion, the kids will learn with emotion
and carry it with them.
</P>
<P>
   She focuses equal attention on art history as well as mime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make them study Red Skelton because when he first started
out his self-esteem was really low and that's why he was a cutup,''
says Kohles. ``The stronger he got the more miming he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohles recalls one performance at Two Rivers Convention Center
during Christmas when a man she didn't know came up to her after
the performance and shook her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not recognize this man,'' says Kohles. ``It was Red
Skelton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said you are very good and you have my blessing. I had
tears in my eyes. That was quite the compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   MIME A COMMON LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   Mime is a powerful form of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Kohles knows that better than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   When a relative was diagnosed with non-Hodgkins lymphoma, she
was summoned to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went there, he was in intensive care with tubes down
his throat,'' recalls Kohles, who herself was diagnosed with
non-Hodgkins lymphoma 10 years ago but is healthy now.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to speak, the man was frantically trying to tell his
family what he wanted them to do and to say good-bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through mime, I was able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
