<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     06-10 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COURAGEOUS BEOWULF STANDS AT THE GARDEN BLUE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 5th graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine that skull with its fierce angles and
sniper's eyes rising from the mists of the great Northwest and
returning to us, again giving courage to those who have lost heart,
again chilling the souls of those who would dare challenge the
Blue. Call him Captain Dad, Mark Messiah, the Frozen Chosen, but as
the grandstand Beast knows, only he can justify its cry, ``We want
cup!''
</P>
<P>
   I am breathless at my own insanity. Who cares about hockey? The
New Jersey Devils can win the Stanley Cup, and the radio nutkins
will still argue whether the New York Knicks are better or worse
with Patrick Ewing. But this isn't about hockey. This isn't about
The Big Man or The Franchise Player or even about The Team Leader
or The Role Model. This is about New York's last legendary hero
since Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Messier has never been a manufactured commodity; he is too
weird looking, too unexpected, too committed to his game. You
believe him when he says he has avoided long-term emotional
attachments to keep his edge.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be dark, secret folds in his life. One imagines
him capable of the unspeakable, and then keeping his mouth shut
about it. When he giggles _ and he does _ it is easy to believe he
is receiving a joke from a parallel universe. And he is smart,
direct, a grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   If the New York Rangers do not bring him back for next season,
follow my lead and ignore hockey forever. Send acceptances only to
thelipsite(AT)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching the Rangers, we will read books not
recommended by Phil Jackson. The first should be Seamus Heaney's
new translation of Beowulf. We know whom it is really about, a
``man whose name was known for courage resolute in his helmet,'' a
man whose world was ``honour-bound and blood-stained,'' who came
from his native land pitying ``the plight you suffer in this
legendary hall.'' You can figure out who were ``the reavers from
hell,'' the opposing hockey players disguised as Grendel and
Grendel's Mother that Messier slew in exchange for a great deal of
money and power.
</P>
<P>
   Like Beowulf, Messier had come across a border from his native
country where he had won battles but never quite achieved the fame
his vanity demanded. But he had honed his steel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton was the psychological boot camp,'' he told me a year
after the Rangers won the Stanley Cup. ``Endless seminars on how to
find your superconscious, the zone. It sounds like insanity. Except
how do you explain those nights when I'm so focused that I fly,
never feel my legs, no pain, see everything, score three goals?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 18 when I joined the team; we were all young together.
The Islanders were our role models and then we beat them. It was a
wonderful time, but it was a relationship that had run its course.
I needed to leave Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, Edmonton has come to New York and beckons to him to
return. Messier is pushing 40, like Beowulf in honored twilight,
waiting for one more monster to slay. Messier's hockey father, Glen
Sather, who led Edmonton to five Stanley Cups in the 1980s (he had
Wayne Gretzky for four of them), was named the Rangers' president
and general manager last week.
</P>
<P>
   The myth expands: The heart of that 1994 Ranger championship
team _ goalie Mike Richter, defenseman Brian Leetch and Adam
Graves, the wing who guarded Messier's back in Edmonton as well as
New York _ is still in place, pining for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   And there is more. After the cup year, when the mad coach who
had driven them, Mike Keenan, left ugly, Messier took over the team
from a weak coach. Messier took a dislike to Petr Nedved, a
brilliant young Czech center, one of the many European finesse
players then coming into the league. They were disdained by the
Canadian hard cases as soft ``snow blowers'' who would pull up in a
spray of ice rather than risk collision. Messier ran him off the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved is now back, the premier center. Can you imagine these
two finding common ice, bonding?
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't rouse your blood, it may be our fault after all.
We have confused stars and heroes, pumped up that brown Barney,
Shaquille O'Neal, and proclaimed him the future face of sport.
</P>
<P>
   We have railed at John Rocker for expressing opinions we
tolerate from the drive-time schlock jocks who invite journalists
on their air. It seemed fitting that Rocker was ``sent down'' (to
the minors or the reavers from hell) after he verbally threatened
the reporter who had originally given him his megaphone. If only
Messier also had the time to start a men's therapy group and
include Rocker and Bob Knight, clueless or hanging tough, but still
working.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, Captain Dad's Vancouver contract expires. We need our
centered center with his rage to win. Who else could say,
unselfconsciously: ``When you put on the sweater, everything should
become crystal clear. You know what you have to do for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like Beowulf, he will kill that last dragon and then expire
from his wounds. Captain Dad will also get a hero's send-off
because, as Heaney writes of Beowulf, ``He was the man most
gracious and fair-minded, kindest to his people and keenest to win
fame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
