<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-DRUG-TEST-2TAKES-     06-10 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUG-TEST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST FOR PERFORMANCE ENHANCING DRUGS MAY BE READY FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Summer Olympics are still three months away, but in
Australia and France a race with potentially huge implications for
the Olympics is already well under way.
</P>
<P>
   It is the race to find an effective and practical method of
detecting synthetic erythropoietin, the hormone known as EPO.
Unauthorized use of the hormone, which boosts a user's red blood
cell count and hence the capacity to carry oxygen, has tainted
results and reputations in cycling and other endurance sports
throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Even though research teams in other countries are also
attempting to develop a foolproof, lawsuit-proof test, the efforts
based in France at the Laboratoire de Chatenay-Malabry and at the
Australian Institute of Sport in Canberra may be by far the most
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   The French have developed a urine test, which the International
Cycling Union hopes to use during the Tour de France, which begins
on July 1. The test that has been developed at the Australian
institute with the Sydney Games in mind is a blood test.
</P>
<P>
   Both methods have been published in scientific publications this
month, an important step in the validation process and a first for
prospective EPO tests. The French test's methodology has been
published in the British magazine Nature, the Australians' in the
scientific review journal Haematologica.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the sense that some of the previous criticism has been that
there has been no publication of an EPO study, this should help
answer that,'' said Dr. Peter Davis, the EPO research project
manager at the Australian Institute of Sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Canberra-based project has adequate funding, a method it
claims has worked on a small scale, and the motivation provided by
a once-in-an-Australian-scientist's-lifetime deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Australians have been among the most vocal proponents of
improved detection and stricter penalties for performance-enhancing
drug use. Developing a method to identify synthetic EPO would be
both a blow against cheating and a coup for the country. But any
test for EPO would have to be approved by the International Olympic
Committee well before the Games begin on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the chances of having a test in place are now 50-50,''
Dr. Jacques Rogge, vice chairman of the IOC medical commission,
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC usually requires six months to validate a drug test, but
Prince Alexandre de Merode, the medical commission chairman, said
that the IOC is prepared to work on a much tighter deadline in this
instance. Though neither the Australians nor the French expect to
have the test ready to formally present to the medical commission
until late July or early August, officials are scrambling to make
the procedural hurdles easier to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on track and under the impression the test is coming,''
Davis said. ``But I also understand that it's not a simple matter
of saying: `Here's the test. Now do it.' There are a lot of other
issues that go around taking blood: legal challenges and all the
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogge says that despite concerns about legal action or cultural
sensibilities, Olympic athletes will be required to submit to blood
tests if this test is ready. But Davis said that giving the
athletes of the world the impression that an EPO test is imminent
could be almost as effective a deterrent as actually completing the
test. ``Just the threat of a test might be enough to discourage
it,'' Davis said. ``But we are committed to providing a real test
for Sydney. But it will be up to the IOC how they implement it. And
that's tricky, probably a lot trickier than coming up with the
test. The test is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block with testing for EPO has been that it is a
hormone that occurs naturally in the body. Distinguishing the
injected hormone from what is already present has proved
problematic, but Davis said that a study by the Australian
institute last year, which involved about 30 subjects, produced a
model for solving the riddle.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of that effort, the IOC has contributed $1 million
and the Australian government about $1.5 million to finance the
second phase of testing, which began on March 20 and involves about
100 recreational athletes in Canberra and Sydney. According to
Davis, most of the subjects, all volunteers who are in no position
to contend for the Australian Olympic team, have been administered
either EPO or a placebo for a period of eight weeks. Davis said the
preliminary results of the study had reinforced their confidence in
the test.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the institute's research team, which is
working in conjunction with the Australian Sports Drug Testing
Laboratory in Sydney, is continuing to analyze and profile blood
samples collected from about 1,200 athletes from 10 countries and
disparate ethnic groups to make sure that all variations in blood
type have been taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patrick Schamasch, the French orthopedic surgeon
who is the director of the IOC's medical commission office, three
other independent research teams _ in Los Angeles, Barcelona, Spain
and Oslo, Norway _ have received smaller amounts of IOC funding to
develop an EPO test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The others are good projects, too, so I'm happy for this
healthy competition,'' Schamasch said. ``But the one thing we have
to be careful about is a false announcement. We are not
pessimistic, but we don't want to implement a test just to
implement one and satisfy media and public expectations.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   EPO use became widespread in cycling in the early 1990s, but the
extent did not become clear to the general public until the 1998
Tour de France, when the French border police found a large supply
of banned performance-enhancing drugs, including more than 200
doses of EPO, in an official Tour de France car driven by a Belgian
employee of one of the leading teams. The Frenchman Jerome Chiotti,
the world mountain bike champion in 1996, recently admitted using
it when he won his title.
</P>
<P>
   Though synthetic EPO, which was initially developed to help
kidney transplant patients, remains undetectable for now, the
International Cycling Union and International Ski Federation have
attempted to combat its use by implementing limits on hematocrit,
or red blood cell counts. If a tested athlete goes over a
predetermined limit _ 50 percent in the case of cycling _ he is not
allowed to start a race. Even though both Davis and Arne Ljunqvist,
an IOC medical commission member, support the intent of such
procedures, both argue against their validity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The limits are, in my view, arbitrary; I think this is the
wrong approach,'' Ljunqvist said. Davis said: ``At Canberra
Hospital, the upper limit of normal is 54, and the normal range is
47 to 50, and that's why it's ridiculous. You take Mexican athletes
at altitude from a place like Mexico City and they will be at 52
easily, and you can manipulate the level so easily. If it's 52,
take a big dose of saline, and it's 49 tomorrow morning. The thing
about our test is that it's impossible to manipulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Hahn, the head of physiology at the Australian institute,
said its test was based on probabilities and involved ``measuring a
number of different parameters,'' including hematocrit levels and
the characteristics of young red blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is a very low probability that someone could
be abnormal on all those parameters unless they were taking EPO,''
he said, explaining that the initial phase of testing showed that
the chance of a faulty test was one in 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The urine test that has been developed in France can detect only
recent EPO use _ up to three days after the fact, according to
Jacques de Ceaurriz, the director of the Chatenay-Malabry
laboratory. The Australian blood test is designed to detect use
three to four weeks later. There has been cooperation between the
French and Australian researchers, with the Australians sending
urine samples gathered in their study.
</P>
<P>
   The French are on an even tighter timetable than the Australians
because of their goal to have the test ready for the Tour de
France. The International Cycling Union has set a deadline of June
20 for validation, and the heads of the Tour cycling teams have
agreed to cooperate if the test is ready. To increase the chances
of meeting the deadline, the cycling union is relying on a less
exhaustive validation procedure than the IOC requires.
</P>
<P>
   But IOC officials are not prepared to get ahead of the science.
They do not want a repeat of what happened during the 1996 Atlanta
Games, when five athletes tested positive for the banned substance
Bromantan only to be exonerated by the Court of Arbitration for
Sport. Rogge said the court ruled that the new test had not been
through the customary validation process, which includes
publication of the results in a scientific review journal and
independent confirmation by outside experts.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Olympic movement succeeds on EPO, that does not
necessarily mean it is winning the fight to level the playing
fields. Human growth hormone, another popular performance-enhancing
drug, will likely remain undetectable in Sydney. And if Schamasch
and other experts are correct, the IOC will soon need to invest
time and money in genetic research as well as hormone research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next challenge will be genetic,'' Schamasch, of the IOC's
medical commission office, said. ``We were laughing as kids about
the bionic man or the bionic woman, but we're going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world with genetic manipulation, EPO injections would no
longer be required, because cells could be modified to produce more
of it internally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the history of nearly all the illegal
substances in sport, they were first used for legitimate medical
purposes,'' Davis said. ``I think it's only logical to think that
if there is already genetic manipulation of cells for beneficial
purposes to fight disease or eliminate disease, someone will
manipulate cells so they can carry more oxygen or recover from
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, experts are manipulating performance in other ways,
even at the Australian institute. In the room next to the EPO
research laboratory is an ``altitude house.'' It is a
self-contained apartment with a dozen beds where top Australian
athletes can legally _ if not ethically _ spend several days and
nights in artificially thin air in order to increase their
endurance and red blood cell count. Altitude chambers are
widespread around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things that athletes can do, so many ways
they can cheat,'' Davis said. ``Certainly, if we get a test for
EPO, it would be one less, but I'm also not naive enough to think
this will clean it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there are other things, and while there are 75 people
here at the AIS working their hardest to improve performance under
any legal means possible, there will be other places with 175
people who will come up with whatever works no matter whether it's
legal or not.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
