<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: SOSA TRADE LIKELY; WHITHER ROCKER?; INTERLEAGUE
LOSERS; ORIOLES SUFFER IN CANADA; A STRANGE BASEBALL LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The likelihood is growing that the Chicago Cubs will trade Sammy
Sosa sometime this season. His feud with the Cubs' manager, Don
Baylor, will not be the reason, but Sosa's public reaction to
comments Baylor made about him has sparked internal discussion
about Sosa's future with the team and the direction the Cubs want
to take.
</P>
<P>
   Andy MacPhail, the Cubs' president, said last week that the team
had no plans to trade the home-run-hitting right fielder, but he
left open the possibility by saying, ``Clearly, it's not something
that has a lot of appeal to me at the present time.'' The nonwaiver
trading deadline, July 31, is not ``the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have begun a process of deciding where they want to go.
Will they be better off in the next five years or so with Sosa
(assuming he agrees to a contract extension) or with the four or
five players they could command from another team?
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who has one guaranteed year left on his contract after
this one, has the right to veto a trade, but if the Cubs decide
they want to make a move, he will very likely not stand in their
way. If they make that decision, the Cubs are expected to tell
interested teams what they would want for Sosa. Those talks could
be the highlight of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker Going Elsewhere
</P>
<P>
   Baseball people who have talked to Atlanta Braves officials do
not expect John Rocker to return to the Braves. The front office
and his teammates, they feel, have had enough.
</P>
<P>
   The question then is which teams would be willing to take on the
volatility and attention that Rocker would bring with him. Assuming
he can straighten out his control problems in his stay at Richmond,
Va., one or more teams should have interest.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague Sweeps
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes interleague play, and the first series of
games this season has given some teams reason to dislike it.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox had not been swept in a series in the first
two months of the season. Then they played the Philadelphia
Phillies, the team with the worst record in the National League and
no series sweeps. The Phillies won all three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox have a far better record than the
Phillies; in fact, they had the best record in the American League
when they played the Cincinnati Reds. But the Reds led their
division and had suffered only one sweep before they played the
White Sox and lost all three games.
</P>
<P>
   Other interleague sweeps: Montreal over Baltimore, Cincinnati
over Minnesota, Cleveland over Milwaukee, Oakland over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles 0 for Canada
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Baltimore Orioles will not be making any vacation
visits to Canada any time soon. In fact, the Orioles should be
excused if they ask out of their next scheduled trip there July
21-23.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more bizarre streaks of recent seasons, the
Orioles have lost 20 consecutive games in Canada, 14 to the Toronto
Blue Jays and six to the Montreal Expos, whom they have never
beaten in Canada. The last time the Orioles won north of the border
was June 12, 1998. They beat the Blue Jays that day, 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckert's Legacy
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Zuckert, who was the secretary of the Air Force under
President Kennedy, died last Monday. No mention of baseball
appeared in his obituary because he had no connection to the game.
However, his name will live in baseball lore for the association he
did not have with the game.
</P>
<P>
   When major-league baseball owners set out to seek a new
commissioner in 1965 before the retirement of Ford Frick, John
Fetzer of Detroit and John Galbreath of Pittsburgh, co-chairmen of
the search committee, identified a man connected with the military
as a potentially good candidate. The man they were said to have in
mind was Zuckert, but somehow the owners wound up interviewing _
and hiring _ William Eckert, an Air Force general known as Spike.
</P>
<P>
   Three years into his term, Eckert was forced to resign. Not only
did he lack knowledge about the game he was running, but he also
was a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some question about whether there was really a
Zuckert-Eckert mixup, but a former club owner recalled asking
Fetzer about the matter and said the Tigers owner ducked a direct
answer. He quoted Fetzer as saying, ``Well, that isn't exactly
right.'' But neither he nor Galbreath, the former owner said,
wanted to talk about it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough anecdotal evidence,'' the former owner said.
``I believe it's true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
