<SLUG> BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORE MONEY COULD RAISE THE INJURY STAKES IN RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RAC-BELMONT, being filed after the Belmont Stakes; Post
time 5:27 p.m. EDT.) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's too bad that racing fans regarded Saturday's Belmont Stakes
as strictly leftovers, and that the general population hardly
cared, and that the friendly gents with the grandstand tickets took
such a bath.
</P>
<P>
   Counting on Japanese patrons and other well-heeled types with a
few yen in their pocket to storm to Belmont for a Fusaichi Pegasus
Triple Crown, real fans and speculators had gobbled up the 34,000
Belmont seats shortly after the Japanese-owned horse won the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But investing in tickets is a form of gambling, just like
betting on the horses or owning horses, for that matter, or playing
the stock market. Go, baby, go, indeed. A recuperating Fusaichi
Pegasus was nowhere in sight Saturday as a field of pretenders took
to the Belmont course.
</P>
<P>
   The distinct sense of deprivation at yet another year without a
Triple Crown winner revives the impression that racing is a sport
of the last midcentury, like boxing, while other sports are
creating new audiences. Now the people who run racing are talking
about throwing money at the problem, rarely a good solution.
</P>
<P>
   The racing people want to raise the stakes for the Triple Crown
races, so that owners and trainers of these delicate, overbred
animals will be more tempted to enter them in the three races
within five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, everything has a price. That may be true in the
owners' boxes as well as most other corners of the world, but the
racing people should not be proud of the clamor to raise the ante
for the Kentucky Derby ($1 million) guaranteed to the winner this
year), the Preakness ($650,000) and the Belmont ($600,000 to some
afterthought winning his first Grade I stakes Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that racing has not had a Triple Crown winner in
the 15 years since marketing types came up with the gimmick of a
``challenge'' _ now worth a bonus of $5 million. In fact, the
Triple Crown has seen more horses ruined than rewarded, not
necessarily anybody's fault, but a reality, nonetheless. That big
bonus was dangling out there last year when Charismatic, a
strapping red-tinged grandson of Secretariat, barreled out of the
chute for the fifth time in 64 days. Less than a mile and a half
later, 85,818 fans, the largest crowd in Belmont history, were
emitting prayers they did not know they remembered. Charismatic
broke down and was saved only by the gallant acrobatics of Chris
Antley, the jockey, who leaped off and comforted the agonized colt
into standing still and not further damaging his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Modern medical response saved Charismatic's life, but he was the
latest casualty in major stakes races. In 1993, Union City was put
down after the Preakness, won by Prairie Bayou, who himself was
destroyed after breaking down on the backstretch in the Belmont.
The Breeders' Cup, the autumn jamboree, has had national-television
tragedies in Go for Wand in 1990 and Mr. Brooks in 1992. And the
historic track at Belmont is still haunted by the death of Ruffian,
the noble filly, during an ill-advised match race in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Racing manages to get through these tragedies, and most trainers
are respectful of their horses. This year Neil Drysdale nursed
Fusaichi Pegasus to a Derby victory, and was squeamish about
entering him in the Belmont after he did not fire in the Preakness.
A minor leg injury a week ago gave Drysdale the reason to withdraw
Fusaichi Pegasus from the Belmont, and more power to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is a blessing in disguise,'' Drysdale said. ``The
decision whether or not to run him hadn't been made. Well, he made
the decision himself.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Stronach, the owner of Red Bullet, did not enter that
Preakness winner in the Belmont, there were some cynical
suggestions that Stronach was thinking about the money he could
make in other major stakes later in the season. Maybe he was, maybe
he wasn't, but money is not necessarily the best thing for the
horses, and does not automatically guarantee glamour, either.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Tahkodha Hills, entered in Saturday's Belmont, was
eligible for a $1 million bonus for having won the Lone Star Derby
in Texas. That gimmick did not excite anybody at the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the fans knew this was the first time since 1970 that
both the Kentucky Derby and Preakness winners had missed the
Belmont. They knew there have been only 11 Triple Crown winners,
none since 1978, and that there must be a reason for the scarcity.
Nobody has hit .400 in baseball since Ted Williams batted .406 in
1941, and that's kind of a neat mystique _ like Secretariat's romp
in the 1973 Belmont, one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the absence of star quality drastically reduced the crowd
from the record of 85,818 last year and the third-largest Belmont
crowd of 80,162 that saw Real Quiet finish second in the 1998
Belmont and the fifth-largest crowd of 70,682 that saw Silver Charm
lose to Touch Gold in '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anybody, we are disappointed with the turn of events that
have cost us the Derby and Preakness winners,'' said Terry Meyocks,
president of the New York Racing Association. ``But the well-being
of the horses comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyocks had that right. The owners will have to wrestle with the
possibility that three races within five weeks are too much. In the
meantime, raising the stakes drastically could be dangerous to the
four-legged stars of this industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
