<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-STATE-SONG-NYT &LR;      06-10 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-STATE-SONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. NOTEBOOK: SONG REMAINS THE SAME. WILL NEW JERSEY LISTEN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story does not carry a byline) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   O, New Jersey! Not only are you the butt of tedious ``What
exit?'' jokes, but you lack what most other states revel in: a song
of your own. And this is certainly not due to any lack of lyricism
west of the Holland Tunnel. It is due more to, dare we count, six
decades of legislative inaction.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the state militia sang ``Jersey Blue'' in 1794 during
the Whisky Rebellion has there been a consensus about a song for
the Garden State. There was a contest for state song in 1939, but
the Legislature didn't make the winner official. In 1956 the
Department of Education reviewed many options, but found none of
sufficient merit. In 1972 the Legislature cast its votes for the
roisterous ``I'm from New Jersey,'' written in 1960 by Red Mascara
of Phillipsburg. It goes something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from New Jersey and I'm proud about it, I love the Garden
State.
</P>
<P>
   I'm from New Jersey and I want to shout it, I think it's simply
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. William T. Cahill refused to sign the bill, reportedly
saying, ``If there is one thing worse than the song `I'm From New
Jersey,' it is Red Mascara singing `I'm From New Jersey.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 1996, when a law directed the New Jersey State
Arts Council to come up with a list of favorites. Four years and
215 entries later, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a little daunting for the tireless Mascara, 78, a
retired chemical factory worker who for 40 years has lobbied the
Legislature, schmoozing, passing out gumdrops, all for a song. He
said the sponsor of one of the three current bills in favor of his
song is Christopher Kip Bateman, whose father, Raymond, was Senate
president back in 1972 when Cahill rejected the Legislature's
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a move afoot, Mascara said, to create four state
tunes: the top three choices of the 1996 contest, so the state
would have a state song, a state anthem, a state pop song, and, be
still, beating heart _ a state march. His.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
