<HEADLINE>
NBA'S RATINGS RESEMBLE AN AIR BALL  
 JORDAN'S DIFFICULT TRANSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Dashes are being used in `M-A-S-H' instead of stars, which
are non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ David Stern will issue his annual finals address
next week in Indianapolis, going over all that is right and amiss
with his league and insisting that business is not as bad as
perceived.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the commissioner's words reflect the genuine
state of the National Basketball Association, Stern knows he is not
presiding over the megapopular product whose growth once seemed to
have no end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through change, but we're convinced things will
pick up,'' he said last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stern spoke before Game 1 between the Los Angeles Lakers and the
Indiana Pacers drew a television rating of 10.5 _ the lowest rating
in 14 years and down 9 percent from Game 1 of the San Antonio
Spurs-Knicks series last June.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the icons who propelled his league in the 1980s and
1990s candidly spoke their minds about the NBA's quality of play
and its interest level.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird: ``I don't think it's totally back. We played
Milwaukee in a Game 4 there and they didn't sell out. It just seems
like a lot of people aren't talking about the NBA as much as they
used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're doing a good job promoting it. I'd like to see
them get more teams on TV than just the Lakers and New York. I
think it's coming back. But the only way it comes back is if you
have great competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson: ``We have to establish our superstars. Who's
going to be our stars now? Who's going to take this league? It's
out there. Shaq is the most dominant. But we need a guy to be the
man in terms of Michael Jordan. So who is that going to be?''
</P>
<P>
   After the Lakers' riveting Game 7 comeback against Portland last
Sunday, even Jordan was not impressed. ``In all honesty, I don't
think they won it,'' he said. ``I think Portland lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird, Johnson and Jordan are not the only ones concerned about
the health of the game. ``When you watch a player like Reggie
Miller in the clutch, it's at its best,'' said Pat Riley, the Miami
Heat coach and team president who coached the Lakers to their last
championship in 1988. ``And you realize it will never not be an
entity. But the evolution of the player and the mentality of the
player _ caused by a number of extenuating circumstances _ has
changed the game and how it is perceived by the public.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The public likes it, but they're going to like it on
their own terms now _ because they don't get the game on the
favorable terms they used to get it. There was more humility by the
players. The money factor, too, is huge. It really is a business
now, even for fans. When fans buy season tickets now, they sign
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he had read an article about several hedge-fund
billionaires from the 1980s who lost hundreds of millions during
the stock market's recent downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were brilliant men,'' he said. ``And one simply said, `I
don't understand this market anymore.' He admitted, as a
professional investment counselor, that he doesn't understand his
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you equate back to the league, I don't think a lot of
our fans really understand it right now. They will support it until
they understand it again. But we've got to make them understand it.
The players have to make them understand it. Otherwise, we're going
to lose them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing a lot of viewers to other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though ratings plummeted during the regular season _ off 21
percent from last season's lockout-shortened year _ Stern is
unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV remains the dominant entertainment vehicle, but people
forget everyone's numbers are off,'' Stern said. ```Monday Night
Football' just experienced its worst-ever ratings. We live in a
changing entertainment environment. The number of people who
watched the final episode of `Seinfeld' was lower than the number
of people who watched the final episode of `Cheers.' And that
number was lower than the final episode of `M-A-S-H.' That's where
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern blames several factors for the low ratings and the
declining interest in the league. ``First, I think it has to do
with the post-Michael era, something we expected to happen,'' he
said. ``You throw in the lockout and an extraordinary amount of
additional programming, and that's where the problems lie. Those
are not insubstantial numbers we're talking about. Adding games on
Saturdays all resulted in the fact of a cumulative effect on the
ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird thinks there is another factor contributing to the league's
interest problems: Many of today's players, he said, do not
resonate with fans as much as players from his era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the players got to do more in their communities,''
he said. ``And stay out of trouble. And when they play, they got to
play hard. You read about all the negative stuff sometimes and we
don't think about the positive. We got a lot of great players in
our league that play hard every night. It's just that you have to
have a majority do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern discounts the notion that players were more passionate
about their jobs two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's Vince Carter, Allen Iverson, the Latrell
Sprewells or the Ray Allens and Kevin Garnetts, we see an intensity
to our players equal to any intensity in the last 20 years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion was we needed New York, everyone was writing
that,'' he said. ``It was never a concern: The ratings will be
fine. We're going through a transition, but I fully expect things
to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   But a wedge is growing, and it is not relegated to the league
and fans. The kinship between coaches and players and the NBA is
not as strong as it once was. Controversies involving league
directives over access and the use of microphones led to widespread
criticism earlier this year and a threatened lawsuit by the
coaches' association.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're marketing just like high-tech stocks,'' Riley said.
``Market the business. Market the image even though there's no
profits. The NBA has marketed their sport extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe they've gotten involved into the game too much,
making these changes. And they made them the last time in a very
arbitrary manner. They said: `Well, you guys don't want to change,
so we'll change them. We're changing the rules, so you get with
it.' That was basically the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they must feel very strongly about the direction they're
going in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading the Wizards
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Jordan's coach-search odyssey comes to a close _
University of Miami coach Leonard Hamilton seems primed to take the
job _ the Wizards' head of basketball operations must now
concentrate on finding creative ways to upgrade Washington's
roster.
</P>
<P>
   According to Magic Johnson, it will not be easy. Salary-cap
problems that prevent many of the Wizards' players with locked-in,
long-term contracts from being traded for equal value are well
documented. But Johnson said Jordan faced another hurdle, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's called payback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told people it would take him three to five years,'' Johnson
said. ``He's in a tough situation. Nobody in this league wants to
help him because he beat them most of the time. No one is going to
say, `I'll take Juwan or Rod or Ike Austin,''' Johnson said,
referring to Juwan Howard and Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to help us, either. That's the way it is.
Everybody wants to see him lose. They're smiling because he has no
cap room. But he'll break through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan appeared close to working out a deal with Mike Jarvis,
the St. John's coach, before negotiations broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Jordan is frustrated making the transition from player
to part-owner and NBA executive, Johnson said: ``I would be
frustrated. From his side, it's the same thing. He went after the
guy he wanted and it didn't happen. That has to frustrate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has a small percentage of ownership in the Lakers in
addition to his outside business interests, which include a
traveling team that plays in Europe. As his playing contemporaries
like Jordan and Larry Bird attempt to make their mark in other
areas of the game, Johnson also is contemplating a more prominent
NBA position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether it would be what Rod Thorn did or what
Larry is doing,'' Johnson said, referring to the new Nets' team
president. ``I'll have to wait. But I'm having fun at what I'm
doing, and I'm committed. When I get back into basketball, I want
to get back into it all the way. I have a goal set. I'm almost
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
