<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HARASS0611-COX     06-10 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASS0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New companies, old problems
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In this go-go economy, Internet companies are in the
fast lane. The trouble is, according to some experts in human
resource management and employment law, many dot-com companies may
be rushing toward a head-on collision with workplace harassment
claims.
</P>
<P>
   Dot-com firms are proving to be especially susceptible to
workplace harassment problems, according to Chuck Samel, general
manager of legal knowledge development with Los Angeles-based law
firm LRN. Recent cases have involved companies such as Juno, Pseudo
Programs and EarthWeb.
</P>
<P>
   And while those cases may have made headlines, many more claims
go unpublicized, says Scears Lee III, managing director of the Lee
Group, a human resources executive search firm based in Newnan.
``So many of these claims, I've found, (companies) try to settle
them before they ever go to court,'' Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies especially at risk, Samel says, are the
``pre-public or very recently public companies, probably with fewer
than 1,000 employees, probably less than 2 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Samel lists several key factors that contribute to the
susceptibility of workplace harassment at these firms:
</P>
<P>
   Dot-coms generally fail to hire human resources professionals
early enough in the development of their companies, Samel says.
``The company has great pressure to develop the organization and
the management of the company at `Internet speed,' and they need to
find the chief technology officer, the marketing and sales
professionals, the chief financial officer. It appears that human
resource managers don't get to the top of that list fast enough,''
Samel says.
</P>
<P>
   Without the appropriate focus on human resource issues, dot-coms
fail to educate and train their employees about the laws they must
comply with, Samel says. ``Without that training and education, one
can see why claims for harassment could arise more frequently,'' he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Accipiter, spokeswoman for the Society of Human Resource
Management, agrees. ``It is often the human resources department
that stands as the policy police,'' she says. ``They are the ones
that put the policies and training in place.''
</P>
<P>
   In dot-com companies, the work force tends to be less
experienced than in more traditional, ``old economy'' companies,
Samel argues, so there's a greater likelihood those employees have
not received education and training on legal compliance issues
elsewhere. ``The more-established Fortune 200 companies are often
hiring people who are on their second and third jobs and may
already be familiar with and have received training on these
issues,'' Samel says.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies tend to have a very relaxed, informal
atmosphere, casual dress code, less structured environment and less
structured work space. To some, Samel says, those factors ``imply
perhaps the company is less interested in legal compliance, and
that (perception) may lead people to think the company is fast and
loose, which may not be true.''
</P>
<P>
   In many of these cases, ``These employees are working very long
hours in close quarters,'' Samel points out. ``That leaves very
little time for socializing outside the workplace without other
employees, so their social life tends to be centered around the
work environment and around their jobs and around their
co-workers.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``fast-growing'' or ``emerging'' doesn't always mean
Internet-based, several experts stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that many of them (companies at risk) are smaller
companies and that doesn't have so much to do with the fact that
they are Internet companies. It has more to do with the fact that
they are growing companies,'' contends Samuel M. Matchett, a
partner at Atlanta's King &AMP; Spalding.
</P>
<P>
   John Putzier, president of FirStep(cq), a performance
improvement company near Pittsburgh, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, I find that technology companies are more
progressive in understanding issues of diversity. . . . They are
more colorblind and sex-blind than other companies,'' Putzier
argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company starts off probably making human resources
errors. Until they get to be a certain size, they aren't feeling
any pain yet. Maybe a lawsuit wakes them up to the need for a human
resource professional,'' Putzier says. ``I don't think they are at
any higher risk. They are vulnerable in the same way that any
company starting out is vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that since the Anita Hill/Clarence Thomas
controversy during his Supreme Court appointment hearings, sexual
harassment reports have been on the rise across all industries.
</P>
<P>
   However, Samel and others say that dot-com firms are proving
uniquely susceptible to problems in this area because of their
lightning-fast growth, their often anti-establishment culture and
their tendency to heightened internal camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of guys working on a loading dock is one thing,'' says
Michael Lotito, an attorney with San Francisco office of the
Jackson Lewis law firm as well as the chairman of the Society of
Human Resource Management. ``We're talking about people of both
sexes working 80 hours (a week) toward a common goal'' of building
an Information Age business and becoming wealthy, all at Internet
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Such high-intensity aspects make dot-coms susceptible not only
to workplace harassment but also to wage and work-hour violations
and other matters of burgeoning legal liability, including
intellectual property and compete-noncompete issues, Lotito says.
</P>
<P>
   Some venture capitalists are beginning to recognize some of
these structural issues and are suggesting the dot-coms address
them before they will back them financially, Lotito says.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, some observers say the generally younger management
of these firms may also play an unfortunate role in harassment
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when people get real rich real fast, real suddenly,
they can become pretty arrogant and feel that they can do what they
want _ so they grab somebody's behind,'' asserts employment
attorney Edward D. Buckley of Atlanta-based firm Greene, Buckley,
Jones &AMP; McQueen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of these companies you find that the management tends
to be very young, and they don't have a lot of experience in
dealing with the issues we're talking about. There is not a lot of
gray hair assisting the companies,'' Lotito says. ``You have more
of a club environment instead of a more structured corporate
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Age has nothing to do with it, Putzier argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would younger people be more likely to commit lacks of
propriety? I know a lot of dirty old men who have been in the work
force for 30 years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe along the lines of political correctness, Your
high-growth, seat-of-the pants company may be a bit irreverent, but
again, it attracts people who like that,'' Putzier says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a straight-laced conservative person, I doubt you're
going to like working at a dot-com, and I don't think they'd want
you.''
</P>
<P>
   DEFINING HARASSMENT
</P>
<P>
   What does and doesn't constitute harassment is a highly complex
matter, legal experts say. There are essentially two categories of
behavior that qualify, explains Michael Lotito, an attorney with
San Francisco office of the Jackson Lewis law firm as well as the
chairman of the Society of Human Resource Management.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the direct proposition, in which some kind of
special advantage in the workplace is promised in return for an
intimate relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The second type is the hosxual advances,'' he says. ``Sexual
overatures, inappropriate jokes, comments or requests that are
unwelcome, once reported, the company can investigate and take an
appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   Title 7 provides for remedies in the event that there is a
violation of its prohibitions, says Matchett. ``It provides for a
jury trial. In the event that an individual wins, it provides for
back pay.'' In appropriate cases, it also can provide for
compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The cases are handled initially and primarily through the
federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. Employers wth
fewer than 15 employees are not subject to the rules in Georgia,
according to Matchett. Most cases are resolved before they get to
the EEOC, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The first defense against harassment is awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employee should know what the company's policy is,''
Matchett says, and the policy will generally outline the complaint
process. ``Read your handbook so that you will know what your
company's policy is.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, advises Matchett, ``If you feel you're being harassed,
utilize the policy. Nip it in the bud. The company has the
responsiblity to investigate and take action.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
