<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL:   O'NEAL OVERCOMES PACERS' HACKING, LOSS OF
BRYANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant left the Staples Center on crutches
Friday night, unable to put much weight on his swollen and sprained
left ankle. With one All-Star shelved, the Achilles' heel in
Shaquille O'Neal's game was beginning to throb, too.
</P>
<P>
   The heavenly center _ and hellish foul-shooter _ went to the
line a record 39 times, missing 21. Purist that he is, Larry Bird
had said he would not resort to intentionally fouling O'Neal just
to stay in the game. But this was too good to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's misfortune and O'Neal's misfires had given the Indiana
Pacers a new lease in Game 2 of the National Basketball Association
finals, a chance to return home to Indianapolis for Games 3, 4 and
5 of the series with hope against the Los Angeles Lakers and their
indomitable center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was working,'' Rik Smits said. ``For a while,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Until O'Neal made nine of 16 free throws in the fourth quarter,
found an open teammate underneath the basket for a game-deciding
3-point play in the final minute and delivered another 40-point
knockout performance. There went the Hack-a-Shaq, the strategy
going down as hard as the Pacers in a 111-104 loss that left Reggie
Miller and the Eastern Conference champions in an 0-2 hole. Bryant,
who is listed as day to day, does not appear healthy enough to play
in Game 3 on Sunday night at Conseco Fieldhouse, but it may not
matter the way O'Neal and his role players played in the
21-year-old guard's absence on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kobe went out, we felt that, you know, we had to pick it
up,'' said O'Neal, who had 24 rebounds and is averaging 21.5 in the
finals. ``So, I took it upon myself to try to get in deep position
and take the high-percentage shots.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bryant fell awkwardly to the floor in the first quarter
after he came down on Jalen Rose's foot, the building went dead
quiet with concern. O'Neal, Glen Rice and Ron Harper soon
alleviated it.
</P>
<P>
   With Bryant out, the other Lakers starters seemed liberated by
the opportunity. Glen Rice and Ron Harper each scored 21 points;
Rice hit the bomb with aplomb, making five of six 3-point shots;
Harper sneaked through the lane for driving layups, hitting eight
of 12 shots for a season high.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's X-rays were negative, and the injury was diagnosed as a
moderate sprain. But Bryant's availability for Game 3 seemed
doubtful, at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had sprained ankles before,'' he said. ``I thought I was
going to get up, shake it off and keep playing. It just kept
getting worse and worse. As far as Sunday goes, the good thing is
we have a cushion now, being up, 2-0. So it's not a do-or-die
situation for me to play on Sunday. If I'm ready to go, if I can
walk and put pressure on it, I'll be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 2-3-2 finals format began in 1985, no home team has
won all three middle games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like when Kobe went out of the game, if we could've
found a way to put some pressure on them and get them down around
10 points, they would have gotten nervous,'' Rose said. ``We
weren't able to put that strong thrust against what they were
bringing toward us in order for them to start doubting
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, as usual, was to blame. He set records for most free
throws attempted in a game, burying the old record of 24 set by Bob
Pettit in 1958. He also shot more free throws in each half _ 17 in
the first half and 22 in the second half _ than Bill Russell's
previous record of 15 for a half, set in the 1961 finals.
</P>
<P>
   He also became only the fourth player in league history to score
40 points in consecutive games. After his 43-point eruption in Game
1, he is averaging 41.5 points in the two games. Michael Jordan
averaged a finals record 41.0 points over six games against Phoenix
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Pacers are putting him on the line, O'Neal might
just surpass Jordan's mark. But with each intentional foul,
controversy arose over whether the strategy was good for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't worry about ratings,'' Bird said. ``I'm trying
to win a ballgame right now. Whatever it takes to win a ballgame,
we're going to do it. If it takes a four-hour game, that's what
we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The game lasted 2 hours 55 minutes and included a fourth quarter
that included 45 free throws and lasted 56 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of Hack-a-Shaq,'' said Miller, who finished with
21 points but scored only 8 points in the final three and a half
quarters. ``I like to play straight-up, old-style basketball. When
I first saw it in the Portland series, when they were down 15 or
16, I didn't understand it. But if you're in the game and you've
got 6 or 7 minutes left and you're shooting free throws like he was
shooting tonight, then I could see it. But I'm not a big fan of it,
no.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said: ``Like I said in the last series, I think it's just
a total respect for my game. My father was in the stands tonight,
so I was able to look at him. He told me to relax, take my time,
just play, and I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were not overwhelmed, holding a lead of 67-64 in the
third quarter. And for whatever Miller and Smits (a paltry 2-for-6
shooting in 16 foul-prone minutes) did not give them, Austin
Croshere (career-high 24 points) and Rose (30 points in 48 minutes)
found a way to get to the basket and draw contact.
</P>
<P>
   But the lasting image was of O'Neal, either chipping paint off
the front iron or getting the ball to nestle into the net,
concentrating as if he had $1 million riding on a quiz-show
question. And when the game was in the balance at 99-96 with 58.8
seconds left, he found Robert Horry underneath for a reverse layup
and an eventual 3-point play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Kobe going down, we had a golden opportunity tonight that
slipped through our fingers,'' Miller said. ``But what can you say?
The guy goes back-to-back 40. You got to give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Game 1, O'Neal looked so much bigger than most of the
Pacers on Friday night, like an oversized child at recess whose
classmates could not get the ball out of his hands. In the second
half, he was called for a very questionable flagrant foul on
5-foot-11-inch Travis Best.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Best had initiated contact on the layup try
with a forearm and that O'Neal's block, which sent the guard to the
floor, was clean. But perhaps the image of a 7-1, 330-pound man
colliding with the smallest player on the court makes officials see
things that are not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the rules,'' O'Neal said. ``Sometimes they
grabbed me and took me to the ground. I'm not a little guy in a
sports car that runs into a brick wall. But I guess I'm big and I
can take it.''
</P>
<P>
   His team is up, 2-0, and he is averaging 41.5 points a game.
O'Neal will take it.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
