<HEADLINE>
GODOLPHIN USES CURULE FOR EXAMPLE OF TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Gen. Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid Maktoum, the
defense minister of the United Arab Emirates, the crown prince of
Dubai and the single most powerful global force in horse racing,
was not at the Belmont Stakes on Saturday. Nor was his trainer,
Saeed bin Suroor. The pair were in England for the Epsom Derby with
the colt Best of the Bests, who finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Best of the Bests is an apt name for the runner from the
Godolphin Racing Inc. stable, which dominates the European circuit.
As is the name of Dubai Millennium, a 4-year-old who has been
hailed as the best horse in the world after whipping such American
stalwarts as Behrens and Running Stag in March at the $5 million
Dubai World Cup at the sheik's home track.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, on Saturday, the assistant trainer Tom Albertrani and
the colt Curule were to man the front lines for Godolphin's assault
on one of the few horse races that it had not previously won _ the
Belmont Stakes, the Grade I mile-and-a-half third leg of the Triple
Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Mohammed confidently changed the name of an unraced
2-year-old from Yaazer to Dubai Millennium in anticipation of
greatness, he vowed to win the Kentucky Derby, Preakness and
Belmont. He insisted, however, on mounting the assault his way,
which meant combining heavy spending with guerrilla-training
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someday you will learn something about how to win these
races from us,'' Mohammed said before sending out Curule and his
stablemate China Visit to credible seventh- and sixth-place
finishes in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed is visible at the July and September horse sales in
Kentucky. Last September he spent $3.9 million on a Kris S. colt, a
record for the Keeneland September sale. But in the past two years
competing in the Triple Crown series, his horses have been largely
unknown when they showed up at the Derby, because he has refused to
follow the traditional preparation of running his stock in American
races such as the Florida Derby or Blue Grass Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he trains them at his racing compound in Dubai _ partly
because he wants to be close to them and partly because he believes
it is the best training facility of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 100 thoroughbreds at Godolphin's Al Quoz
Racing Stable, and industry experts estimate most of them to be
worth $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   They are ridden daily on their full-scale private track by a
well-paid staff of 40 current and former jockeys from Ireland,
England and the United States. Tending the horses and their stalls
are 70 grooms recruited from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   From the United States, Mohammed imported Albertrani, a Brooklyn
native who, as an assistant trainer for Bill Mott, was an integral
part of bringing along the great Cigar. Kiaran McLaughlin, a former
D. Wayne Lukas assistant who is a successful New York trainer, also
spends winters there conditioning the Godolphin horses.
</P>
<P>
   The formula has been successful enough for the stable to capture
the Irish Derby in 1994 and the English Derby in 1995, as well as
make Suroor the champion trainer in Britain in 1996 and 1998. But
so far, his training methods have not paid off in the American
Classics. Last year, Worldly Manner shipped to the Kentucky Derby
after a trial race in Dubai and finished an encouraging seventh,
but two weeks later in the Preakness he finished 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Curule arrived in Louisville only three days before
the race. Despite having won only one race, the dark bay colt ran
well. So Godolphin decided to skip the Preakness and come straight
to New York. The son of Go for Gin has trained well here, twice
turning in the fastest workouts of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I picked up a very good mount,'' said Jerry
Bailey, who decided to ride Curule after his Preakness-winning Red
Bullet was not entered in the race. ``Believe me, this horse is
going to run very well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Curule's progress has taken some of the sting out of the fact
that the horse who Godolphin really believed would capture a leg of
the Triple Crown will miss the series completely: Chief Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The colt was bought from the owners William Betz and Philip
Needham for $4 million after finishing second in the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile last November. He has not had an official race since. He
was forced to skip the Kentucky Derby after having a fever upon his
arrival in the United States in late April. But he missed the
Belmont after working poorly here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disappointing because we bought him purposely to try and
run him in the Kentucky Derby,'' Albertrani said. ``Being that he
got out to Dubai late, we knew it was going to be difficult with
the timing. Once he got to Kentucky and got a temperature, we lost
more time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
