NYT-06-10-00 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0392 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-OPEN-STEWART0611-     06-10 2487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-STEWART0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tragedy brings life in focus
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This week's U.S. Open at the Pebble Beach Golf Links
</P>
<P>
   is much anticipated, as it visits one of the world's most famous
courses. But it also becomes a source of sadness, because of the
LearJet crash that killed defending champ Payne Stewart and five
others in a South Dakota pasture on Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   For many PGA Tour players who had played the National Car Rental
Classic in Orlando the day before, Monday, Oct. 25 was for kicking
back at the end of a long season. Paul Azinger, like many whose
families were on the trip, went to Disney World with his wife,
Toni, and his children, Sarah and Josie. After Disney and a side
trip to nearby MGM Studios, the Azingers started for their
Bradenton home, about 90 miles away. For the first time all day,
Paul turned on his cell phone. It rang immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something horrible has happened,'' came his brother's stored
message.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger pulled off the nearest exit of I-4, turned into a rest
stop and called his parents. They were hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it?'' Azinger said, frantically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne Stewart's plane has crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger remembers collapsing to the ground outside the car.
Immediately dizzy, he tried to walk, but he started to weave on
numb legs and then threw up along the side of the road. At the rest
stop, the Azingers' screams of anguish startled other families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My equilibrium was off,'' Paul said. ``My body was in such
shock. I couldn't think. I couldn't grasp what had happened. I just
lost it. I fell down flat and bawled my head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger had taken on lymphoma and won, but he was not ready
for something like this. He woke up the next morning with tears
dried on his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying in my sleep,'' he said. ``I woke up on my back
and I had tears all over my face. It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sweep of inexplicable death, Azinger had lost Stewart and
his close friends and representatives Robert Fraley and Van Ardan.
The night before, Ardan's daughters had spent the night with
Azinger's kids. The next day, Tracey Stewart asked him to speak at
the Friday service in Orlando, which would be attended by thousands
of people, including more than 100 PGA Tour players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say no,'' Azinger said, ``but I'm thinking, `How am I
going to do this? There's no way. I can't even think. I can't
talk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Four days after the most chilling day of his life, Azinger would
offer a strong, emotional eulogy. In addition to Stewart and Leader
Enterprises agents Fraley and Ardan, the crash also killed course
architect Bruce Borland, pilot Michael Kling and co-pilot Stephanie
Bellegarrigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``To grasp the magnitude of this tragedy was the hardest thing
I've ever had to do,'' Azinger said. ``Clearly, more difficult than
battling cancer. For me, it was.''
</P>
<P>
   A BONDING IN ORLANDO
</P>
<P>
   The sorrow-filled faces of the PGA Tour players assembling at
the First Baptist Church of Orlando will not be forgotten soon.
Many of them, like Fred Couples, who had lost both parents to
cancer, were overcome with grief when Tracey Stewart went past. The
service was broadcast live on The Golf Channel on Friday, Oct. 29,
when play was suspended in the Tour Championship. Azinger's
humorous stories about Payne were the service's highlight. As a
tribute to his friend, he tucked suit pants into his socks in plus
fours-type fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, at a Thursday morning service in Houston, with
Tom Lehman conducting, a lone bagpiper played through an unusual
morning mist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other athlete would have impacted the world the way Payne
Stewart's death did?'' Azinger asked. ``None. Even (Princess Diana)
death didn't impact the world like that, because hearts weren't
changed over it. . . . Payne Stewart's death impacted the world.
It's like I said in the eulogy. Those guys fought the good fight
and they finished the race _and God called them home, and it
impacted the world. Now what does that say? I don't know. When good
people start leaving at the rate I see good people leaving, I'm
starting to wonder, who's going to be left? Just the bad people?''
</P>
<P>
   Years before, Azinger's cancer experience had changed Stewart
and his appreciation of life. Now Stewart's loss had done the same
for millions of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eyes are open,'' Azinger said. ``You see things
differently. You want to live a different way. You want to be
better. You want to spend more time with your family. . . . That's
the part that changed everybody who saw that service _ never to
take anything for granted again. That's the good that came out of
it. I think hearts were changed and lives were changed and a lot of
people grew. They matured. I think the tour matured. I think the
players' perspective was changed. The reality of death and our
mortality is very real, and every time we jump on a plane, it's in
the back of our minds. . . . Heck, if I had played better last year
(and made the Tour Championship field), I might have been on that
plane with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger's loved ones, who almost lost him once, know it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say goodbye to my children, I say, `I love you,' '' he
said. ``I just want them to know that if I don't come back, I'll be
all right. I don't tell them that, but they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger felt Stewart with him during the Hawaii tournament in
January and won for the first time since the cancer was discovered
in his shoulder in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that everybody looked at and said, `Wow, that
was great. I'm glad that happened,''' Azinger said. ``Think about
that. A guy who hasn't won in seven years. After a horrible
tragedy, he busts out and did it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the storybook scenario that could unfold this week at
Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be great if I won the U.S. Open?'' Azinger said.
``I'll be the most focused guy there. I can promise you that. I
will be the most focused man in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN: PROTECT THIS PLANE
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Tom Lehman has regularly ridden airplanes for a
living, the routine has not varied. Strongly religious, he always
makes a pre-flight plea for the safety of the pilots and
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk into the plane,'' Lehman said, ``and I put my hand on
the doorway and I say, `Lord God, please protect this plane.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Lehman's hand never had the opportunity to touch
the LearJet that flew from Orlando toward Dallas, with Payne
Stewart, his Ryder Cup teammate and friend, on board Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to go charter a plane now, I'm going to make sure
I know whose plane it is, how old it is, who the pilots are _ all
those factors,'' Lehman said. ``I'm not just going to call up the
first available charter service and say, `Can I get a plane?' I'm
going to definitely make sure whose plane I'm getting on. In
Phoenix, I know there's two guys I call, and if I can't get one of
those two guys, I'll go commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   The references Lehman has made all year regarding a newly
discovered inner peace are a direct effect of Stewart's death.
Lehman lost a close friend, but gained an appreciation of
everything else. A winner twice since Stewart's death, Lehman never
considered life more precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm way more at peace than I've ever been,'' he said. ``Part
of it is, when you're dead and gone, what's your legacy going to
be? I think the legacy that he left is a pretty good one. What is
my legacy going to be? That's got me really focused on how I want
my son to grow up and perceive his father. How I want my daughters
to perceive their dad. How I want my wife to think of me, and my
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Lehman who offered such comforting words at the Thursday
service in Houston, who stated that he wasn't ``afraid to cry.'' He
helped soothe everyone's aching souls during the draining week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life's too short,'' Lehman said. ``Other things are more
important. I've learned, `Don't sweat the small stuff,' because it
usually doesn't matter. You change your priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest compliment you could give Payne Stewart and his
family is by going on with a changed heart, a changed attitude, a
changed life _ for the better. That would be the ultimate
compliment, that they've affected me that much that my life is
going a different direction. That's quite a legacy to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after Azinger's victory, Lehman won the Phoenix Open
in January to end a PGA Tour victoryless streak of more than three
years. ``A big part of playing your best golf is being free from
the chains and the bindings, so to speak,'' Lehman said. ``It's a
cliche, I know, but it's being free to be who you are. The game's
tough enough without putting that bondage on yourself. I'm sure
'Zinger came into the season with the clearest perspective he's had
since he came back from cancer. . . . You only can get that
perspective, usually, through some kind of a big event in your life
_ usually, something you have to deal with that's difficult. It's
like that movie, `League of their Own,' when Tom Hanks said, `Of
course baseball's hard. If it wasn't hard, everybody would do it.'
It's meant to be hard. The hard part about it is what makes you
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   MISSING THE BENEFIT
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Sally Hoch were angry with Payne Stewart the day he
died.
</P>
<P>
   After Payne promised to play that Monday in an Orlando charity
tournament at Bay Hill for the local Arnold Palmer Hospital for
Children &AMP; Women, Sally called to remind him the night before.
Payne said he had to go to Dallas. It could not be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he told Sally. ``I forgot to call you. I can't do
it. I've got this other thing I have to do. I'm real sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   A miffed Scott Hoch said, ``When was he going to tell us he
wasn't going to play?''
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart had changed his life's priorities, yes, but every
once in a while some old selfishness would surface. Ironically, if
he had kept the charity tournament obligation, he probably still
would be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hoch was on the 16th teebox when his cell phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has happened,'' Sally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me go ahead and hit this shot,'' Hoch said, driving a ball
down the fairway and then grabbing his phone quickly. Told the
plane had crashed, Hoch informed his amateur playing partners,
``Guys, I can't do this. I've got to go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, Hoch stood in the locker room at the
Memorial Tournament, remembering Payne Stewart. Suddenly, he cocked
his head to the side and decided, ``You know, I'm not sure Payne
even knew what the front of my house looked like. We both lived in
a lake, and he'd always come over by boat. Just pull up and show up
for a beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever he was, we always had a good time,'' Hoch said. ``We
would rib him. He would rib us back. We'd play shootouts, and I'd
get him for something because he hadn't played any good, and he's
say, `How many majors have you won?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Close in their amateur days, and when they both tried PGA Tour
qualifying school in 1979, Hoch and Stewart grew apart in the
1980s, ``when our careers started going in different paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Sally called the Stewarts one night and suggested
getting together for dinner. ``Tracey checked and said, `We've got
an opening three weeks from today on a Thursday,' or something like
that,'' Scott said. ``My wife turned to me and said, `They've got
to look at a calendar?' They had a different lifestyle than we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the last couple of years were a lot different,'' Hoch
said. ``He kind of realized that maybe the best part of his career
was gone. We became pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch's reputation is that he doesn't care what others think of
him, but Stewart's death has made him think about life. Hoch easily
could have been with Stewart that day. They shared the same
executive jet service, but that plane was arranged privately by
Leader Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed when I play poorly now, but it doesn't mean
as much in the whole scheme of things,'' Hoch says. ``It's made me
think to do more of the stuff that I enjoy _ you know, don't put
things off. It's the first time that I've gone on some vacations _
men-type trips like fishing, which I've never done before. And when
I'm home, I'm trying to spend more time with my family, really
trying to do more the things they want to do, more than what I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   LOVE: HURTING AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III's sorrow for Payne Stewart held special
significance. After the plane crash that took Davis Love Jr. in
1988, his son hoped to never again feel the type of numbness that
spread across him on Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Love doesn't know what to expect this week at Pebble Beach, when
the void in the golf world that Stewart used to fill with his style
and personality, will hit everyone again. This past week, Love
recalled what Stewart's instructor, Chuck Cook, had said during the
memorial service in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember (Chuck) saying that he was going to sit down at the
sea wall (along the 18th hole) and enjoy the sunset,'' Love said.
``Maybe I'll go down there and find Chuck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we'll be missing (Stewart) more next week, but I
said the same thing when my Dad died. We don't miss him just
because it's the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot more people talking about it, which will
be nice. It will be out in the forefront and that will keep his
memory going.''
</P>
<P>
   Love's father died the same year Alexia was born and five years
before Davis IV came into the world. They know about their
grandfather from their dad's stories and reflections. But with
Stewart's death and another family emotionally ravaged, they got a
present-day reminder of the horror.
</P>
<P>
   When Love heard the news Oct. 25, he was in Nashville on a
golf-course project. His mother, Penta, called from St. Simons
Island to make sure he was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was to turn around and come home,'' Love
said. ``I felt like the right place to be was at home with my
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A man Love met at the course handed him a devotional book and
added a touching inscription. The man also told Love, ``You know
what you need to do. You need to go home and tell your kids that
this doesn't happy every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of the tragedy, Love found his life changing
already. And he's ready for another life-altering moment at the
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to play a little more like he was trying to
teach me to play at the Ryder Cup, with a little bit more passion,
with a little bit more confidence and aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I can win (the Open). That would be the best
tribute I could give. To thank him and to thank Tracey and the kids
on (the 18th) green Sunday would be the best thing that could
happen. Somebody will get to do it, but I hope it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
