<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WAITER WORE A BOW TIE AND CARRIED THE CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ In 1989, Skip Kendall was a 24-year-old budding
professional golfer with big dreams, but with little money.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a steady income, Kendall took a job waiting on tables at
an Olive Garden restaurant in Orlando, Fla. Between shifts, he went
to a nearby field and hit golf balls, sometimes still dressed in
his waiter's outfit, bow tie and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the tie on because it was so hard to put on,'' Kendall
said. ``People passing by probably thought that I was crazy, seeing
this guy in a bow tie hitting golf balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks Kendall is crazy now. He woke up Saturday morning
in second place at the Buick Classic at 7 under par (135), two
strokes behind the leader, Dennis Paulson (9 under par), with a
chance to win his first PGA Tour event and $540,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those days of waiting tables and struggling to make ends meet
are long behind Kendall, who finished 38th on last year's money
list, with earnings of $962,642. Kendall has made the big time,
playing against the world's best, as he dreamed of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kendall remembers the long road he took to get to this
point, whenever he sees an Olive Garden restaurant or has a
conversation with a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where I've come from,'' said Kendall, now 35. ``If I
had the chance, I don't think I would've done it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had done it differently, with a lot of money backing me,
would I have made it? I don't know. Some people have done it that
way, but maybe I wouldn't have been as hungry with the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall already has one top-10 finish this year, third place at
the Bay Hill Invitational, but he has yet to taste victory on tour,
now in his fifth full season. His closest call came at the 1998
Buick Invitational, when he lost in a playoff to Scott Simpson.
Kendall made a 9-foot birdie putt on the 72nd hole to force the
playoff, but on the next hole, he 3-putted from 25 feet, while
Simpson got up and down from the rough for a birdie to win.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Kendall will have another chance. But with a
player like David Duval (5 under par) lurking in contention,
Kendall was not overconfident, not with 36 holes left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out here long enough to realize it's only halfway
done,'' Kendall said. ``I've learned that unless I'm coming down
the stretch the last nine holes on Sunday, it's not even worth
talking about. It's like halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the tenacity Kendall used to reach the tour will serve him
well this weekend. He spent years playing on minitours in Florida,
unable to play consistently enough to reach the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Even when times were difficult, Kendall said he never considered
quitting. He grew up in Wisconsin, playing golf with three other
players from that state who have made the tour _ Steve Stricker,
J.P. Hayes and Jerry Kelly. If they could make it, Kendall figured
he could, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a backup plan,'' Kendall said. ``Once you start
thinking about a backup plan, I think you're better off doing
something else.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Kendall waited tables, golf was still his priority. He used
the money not only to support himself but to pay for entry fees to
qualify for tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   But Kendall's career blossomed in 1997, after he made the tour
by finishing in the top 10 on the 1996 Nike Tour list. At 5 foot 8
and not one of the tour's long hitters, Kendall battled to 74th on
the money list in 1997, keeping his tour card and building his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   With each successful season, Kendall feels more as if he
belongs, and he has learned to deal better with setbacks. He will
not be playing in next week's U.S. Open, because he failed to
qualify, but a victory this weekend would help ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be watching my peers on television,'' Kendall said.
``Have some fun, play with my son, have a big old cocktail in front
of the television.''
</P>
<P>
   How satisfying would it be this weekend for Kendall to beat many
players who are headed to Pebble Beach? He liked that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe guys want to peak next week, but I don't think David
Duval or Phil Mickelson or any of those guys are coming here not to
win,'' Kendall said. ``Those guys all want to win just as much as I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what happens this weekend, at least Kendall will
be doing what he loves, no longer waiting on tables to make ends
meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to continue to play well,'' Kendall said.
``Hopefully on the last day, I'll be there down the stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
