<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-MISSING-WRITER-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKER'S DISAPPEARANCE IN JAMAICA BAFFLES POLICE AND FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Claudia Kirschhoch set foot in Jamaica, she had
lived a year in France and taken a handful of language courses. She
worked as an editor for the Frommer's travel guide series and pored
over maps with an intense curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister called her ``a very savvy traveler,'' and a fellow
travel writer said she was ``bright and intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the reasons that the disappearance of
Kirschhoch, 29, more than a week ago from a beachside hotel in
Jamaica has confounded her parents, friends and local police
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1, the day Kirschhoch, a resident of the Astoria
section of Queens, failed to fly back to New York as scheduled,
Jamaican police officers have plastered their country with her
photograph. Island newspapers have carried the story of her
disappearance on their front pages. And her parents have flown to
Jamaica and offered the equivalent of about $6,200 for information
leading to her whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the search has dragged on, from beaches to nightclubs,
from posh hotel lobbies to street markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a terrible feeling, because you're helpless even
though you know every effort is being made,'' said Deborah Martin,
34, Kirschhoch's sister. ``But we're very hopeful and confident
we'll find her.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch disappeared from the small resort town of Negril, on
the lush western tip of Jamaica, while on a working trip sponsored
by the Sandals resort chain, which has 10 luxury hotels throughout
the Caribbean. Kirschhoch accompanied a freelance travel writer to
Negril on May 25 after a Sandals-sponsored trip to Cuba was
canceled during a stopover in Jamaica because of visa
complications.
</P>
<P>
   The other writer, Tania Grossinger, said she returned to New
York on May 27 after having a final buffet breakfast with
Kirschhoch in the Beaches Negril hotel, where the two were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch was last seen by a lobby receptionist on either May
29 or May 30, police officials said. The two exchanged greetings.
Nothing seemed amiss. But by June 1, Kirschhoch still had not
checked out, prompting hotel staff to enter her room.
</P>
<P>
   There, they found her clothes, her passport, even her wallet,
with cash and credit cards still inside. But there was no sign of
her.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica has long been popular with tourists, but recent years
have seen a surge in street violence due to turf wars between rival
drug gangs. Last year the number of visitors declined.
</P>
<P>
   Baffled police officials said they were keeping all
possibilities open in their investigation into Kirschhoch's
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She tended to be interested in seeking out local color as
opposed to doing organized hotel-type activities,'' Martin said.
``She's a very open and trusting person, completely without
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But by all accounts, Kirschhoch was not one to travel
irresponsibly. She grew up in a modest two-story stucco home in the
quiet suburb of Morristown, N.J., and her family often took summer
vacations, driving up the coast to Cape Cod or Maine. Her parents,
Frederick and Maryann Kirschhoch, encouraged their children to
travel, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Kirschhoch became an avid bird-watcher and grew close to
nature, the kind of person who often combed a beach for seashells,
her sister said. In high school, she studied French. And after
graduating from Washington &AMP; Lee University with a degree in
journalism, she lived for a year in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch also dabbled in other languages, Martin said, and
took frequent trips to places like Italy and the Canary Islands.
She had played the violin since she was a toddler, and she loved
reading poetry, newspapers and novels. In particular, she admired
the writing of Paul Bowles. In Bowles' most famous novel, ``The
Sheltering Sky,'' a woman vanishes into the Sahara desert while her
lover desperately searches for her.
</P>
<P>
   After returning from France, Kirschhoch lived for several years
in Morristown with her parents while working as an editor at small
book publishers. Then last year, she landed an editing job with
Frommer's, a position her sister called ``a perfect fit'' for her.
She also moved into a one-bedroom apartment in Queens to be closer
to Manhattan's cultural events.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Frommer's job took Kirschhoch on a trip to
Seattle and on a junket sponsored by Walt Disney Co., Martin said.
Then along came Sandals and the offer of a trip to Cuba. Martin
said she last saw her sister at a family cookout on Mother's Day,
May 14. The two chatted by telephone a couple of weeks before the
Cuba trip, just catching up on each other's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch was offered the Sandals trip only after two of the
four travel writers originally assigned to the journey canceled at
the last minute, Grossinger said. On May 24, Sandals flew
Kirschhoch, Grossinger and a couple from Chicago into Montego Bay,
a tourist resort on the northwestern coast of Jamaica. There, the
group was told that they would not be able to continue to Cuba
because of visa problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Sandals offered the writers the option of staying at its
Jamaican resorts, Grossinger said. The Chicago couple stayed in
Montego Bay, while Kirschhoch and Grossinger caught a hotel van the
next morning for the two-hour drive to Negril, a town with a 7-mile
stretch of white-sand beach and a population of about 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Grossinger and Kirschhoch checked into separate rooms in
low-slung wooden buildings surrounded by lush tropical plants. They
had balconies overlooking the ocean, Grossinger said, and king-size
beds and terry-cloth bathrobes in their rooms. Rainstorms kept them
off the beach most of the time, and Kirschhoch spent hours reading
a book on Asian metaphysics. But the two writers shared meals
together, eating jerk chicken during the day and having dinners at
the hotel's Japanese and Italian restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   On May 27, they ate their last breakfast together, right before
Grossinger flew back to New York. She said Kirschhoch mentioned
that she wanted to see more of the island, like the Bob Marley
Museum in Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that when we get into the city, we'll call each other
and get together for lunch,'' Grossinger said. ``She was a bright
and intelligent young lady with whom I would have been happy to
continue contact.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, police officers have been asking people
all over Jamaica whether they have seen a slim white woman, 5 foot
2, with long brown hair. Last week, Michael Spring, the publisher
of Frommer's, flew to Jamaica with Kirschhoch's parents to help in
the search. The U.S. Consulate there has supported them by issuing
press releases and holding news conferences, as well as by helping
the police..
</P>
<P>
   But so far, all the efforts have yielded only frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing whatsoever,'' said Superintendent Linette
Williams of the Negril Police. ``She likes to explore, she likes to
go places on her own. As much as you want to be adventurous, how
long would you go without checking in? But we still have hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0402 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ASSAD-DEATH-1STLD-WRI     06-10 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-DEATH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-890&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAFEZ ASSAD, WHO TURNED SYRIA INTO A MIDDLE EAST POWER, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Rewrites throughout.)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Hafez Assad of Syria, a standard-bearer of
Arab nationalism and anti-Zionist fervor who ruled his country with
an iron hand for three decades, died of a heart attack Saturday. He
was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Although Assad had long been in ill health, his death casts a
cloud of uncertainty over the dynamics of peace and conflict in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But Syria itself moved swiftly to give at least the appearance
of stability. After the announcement of the death, the Syrian
Parliament began to pave the way for Assad's son Bashar, a
34-year-old ophthalmologist, to take over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had long hoped to turn over the reins of power to Bashar
Assad. Indeed, a crucial formal step toward that transition was to
have taken place next Saturday during a rare political convention
of the Syrian Baath party.
</P>
<P>
   An autocrat who brooked no dissent, Assad wielded such authority
that Syria, a nation of 17 million people, remained largely
unconnected to the Internet because of his fears of its influence.
Still, he is credited with transforming Syria from a backwater
nation into a semideveloped one and, more importantly, into a
regional powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he earned begrudging acceptance from world
leaders who criticized his outmoded Soviet-style leadership but
came to respect his courtly tenacity and deep-seated convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our differences, but I always respected him,''
President Clinton said Saturday as he issued condolences from
Northfield, Minn., where he gave the commencement address at
Carleton College.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad, according to his father's authorized biographer,
the English journalist Patrick Seale, ``would not deviate from his
father's legacy.'' But even if he formally assumes power in the
near future, it will take him considerable time to emerge from the
shadow of his father and assert himself as leader.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he could face a family feud with his uncle, Rifaat
Assad, who had sought to succeed his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Also unclear is whether the ruling Alawite minority led by the
Assads will be able to retain its tight grip on Syrian politics.
</P>
<P>
   This opens up the possibility of tense and destabilizing
transition in Syria at a crucial time in the relationship between
Syria and Lebanon and between Syria and Israel. Israel's recent
troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon after 22 years scrambled the
power lines in the Israeli-Lebanese-Syrian triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Although Assad took a resolutely hard line toward Israel, many
Western diplomats believed that he was the linchpin to any peace
breakthrough between Israel and its northern neighbors. Many also
believed that only Assad was strong enough to deliver a change in
five decades of hostile habits. He had survived several
assassination attempts and at least one heart attack and he had
suffered from a variety of debilitating illnesses for years. But,
despite his gaunt appearance and his infrequent travels abroad,
many in Syria had wondered if talk of his imminent demise was not
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian television made an official announcement only after the
news had circulated internationally first. It showed members of the
Syrian Parliament standing for a moment of silence, many of them
crying and holding their heads in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a day of sadness and sorrow in every home, school,
farm, factory and quarry,'' the announcer on state-run television
said. ``Sadness is in the heart of every man, woman and child
because the legacy of his accomplishments is a sun that will shine
not just on this generation but on the many to come.''
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, state television interrupted programming to run live
broadcasts from the Syrian Parliament _ a highly unusual sight here
_ that included recitations from the Koran in memory of Assad.
</P>
<P>
   When he first took office last summer, Israel's Prime Minister
Ehud Barak assiduously courted Assad, issuing flattering public
messages about his strength as a leader. Barak and many Western
experts believed that Assad wanted to return to peace talks with
Israel in order to regain the Golan Heights, which he had lost as
Syria's defense minister in 1967, within his lifetime and to ease
the burden on his presumed successor, his son.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter the two countries communicated briefly, but the
peace effort, with the United States as intermediary, screeched to
a halt.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva in March, President Clinton made a final, failed
attempt to revive the talks at a meeting with Assad. The meeting
ended with American pronouncements that its diplomatic focus would
shift to the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
   But after Israel withdrew its troops last month from Lebanon,
where Syria is the power broker, officials here and in Syria
proffered tentative hope about renewing the peace effort. Barak,
however, said publicly this week that he was wondering if Assad's
heart would ever be in it.
</P>
<P>
   Israel expressed condolences Saturday night to the Syrian
nation, but it also voiced concern over how a transition period
would affect the calm that has reigned on its northern border since
the troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel views with importance the keeping of quiet on its
borders with Syria and Lebanon and expects that Syria will continue
to do so, too,'' said a statement issued by Barak's office.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel's deputy defense minister, Ephraim Sneh, also sent a
message regarding relations between the nations. ``The true test of
any new leader is how fast he renews the peace process with
Israel,'' Sneh said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Syria possesses a largely Russian-equipped military machine that
is believed to be far less potent today than when Assad, a career
military man, assumed power in 1970. But with mid-range and
long-range missiles, and with 30,000 troops stationed in Lebanon,
it remains a force in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Syria installed the current civilian leadership of that country.
But after the recent Israeli troop withdrawal, eager to reconcile
their nation and enter a new era of calm, the Lebanese leaders _
and the Hezbollah guerrilla movement, which is backed by Syria and
Iran _ started to test just how much autonomy Damascus would
permit. This transition period could strengthen their move in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Lion of Damascus'' because his family name means
lion in Arabic, Assad was the last surviving member of a generation
of Arab rulers after the deaths of King Hassan of Morocco and King
Hussein of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had surprised Middle East observers by attending King
Hussein's funeral, a visit that marked a warming in what had been
an icy relationship with Jordan. Since then, the late King
Hussein's son, King Abdullah, has been a frequent visitor to
Damascus and has cultivated a personal relationship with his fellow
Western-educated scion, Bashar Assad.
</P>
<P>
   From Gaza City, Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader who was an
archrival of the Syrian president, declared a three-day mourning
period. In a statement, he said that the Palestinian people ``would
stand with their Syrian brothers and believe in their ability to
survive this critical moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Arafat said they hoped the moment would serve to
reunite the Palestinian and Syrian people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
