<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ASSAD-REACTION-NYT &LR;      06-10 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-REACTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPREHENSION, HOPE FOLLOW IN WAKE OF ASSAD'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The death Saturday of Hafez Assad, the Syrian strongman
who skillfully managed to keep his nation a pivot of political
power in the Middle East, brought expressions of both apprehension
and cautious hope for stability from regional and world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, where Assad exercised complete power, government
leaders praised him effusively as the guardian of Arab pride and
the man who helped Lebanon emerge from its long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faced with the terrible catastrophe that strikes Lebanon at
its heart, because of what the late leader gave through his
efforts, his thinking, his reason and his heart, we decree a week
of official mourning starting today,'' said Lebanon's prime
minister, Selim al-Hoss.
</P>
<P>
   Syria maintains about 30,000 soldiers in neighboring Lebanon,
which it treats as a satellite state.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's son, Bashar, who appears poised to take over his
father's post, has been in charge of Syrian activities in Lebanon
for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the office of Prime Minister Ehud Barak issued a
statement that underlined Israeli hopes that Assad's heir will
exercise authority to make decisions and, if possible, sign a
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a statement issued in Northfield, Minn.,
where he was speaking, also offered condolences to the Assad family
and to Syrians while adding his hope for a renewed peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past seven years, I have met him many times and
gotten to know him very well,'' Clinton said. ``We had our
differences, but I always respected him.''
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents last met in Geneva this spring, but their
meeting ended in disappointment. Despite high hopes for an
agreement on restarting peace talks between Israel and Syria, Assad
returned to Damascus without committing his country to a date for
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had calculating, and often rancorous, relations with his
fellow Arab leaders. But after his death, the decades of bitterness
were not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat, who was alternately embraced and undercut by
Assad, declared three days of mourning in the
Palestinian-controlled territories.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, Esmat Abdel-Maguid, the secretary-general of the Arab
League, predicted that Syrian policy for the moment would continue
along the same lines as under Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Syria will proceed along the same path chosen
by the departed president with strength and might,'' he told the
Al-Jazeera pan-Arab television station. ``I am certain the Syrian
leadership will complete this process.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, Assad was remembered as a crafty leader by Yevgeny
Primakov, a former prime minister and intelligence chief who knew
the Syrian president well. Syria, under Assad, was a major client
and recipient of military aid from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known Hafez al-Assad since 1966,'' Primakov said. ``I
had great respect for him. He was a wise statesman who ran his
country under the difficult conditions of confrontation with Israel
and the West.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Russian analysts, looking ahead, said Assad's death
could open a window to a more confident search for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``An entire epoch in the Middle East is coming to an end,''
Andrei Kozyrev, the first foreign minister of Russia after the
collapse of the Soviet Union, told the Echo of Moscow radio
station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
