<SLUG> BC-NY-PUERTO-RICO-PARADE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN TO THE PARADE, WITH PRIDE AND PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Each spring for the last 20 years, Nestor Rantas has
traveled to the Bronx from Juana Diaz, Puerto Rico, to sell hats,
T-shirts, key chains and anything else bearing the colors or name
of his native land. So it was no surprise that early Saturday, the
day before the annual Puerto Rican Day Parade in Manhattan, Rantas,
44, was standing near Southern Boulevard in the Bronx with a bundle
of flags in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   He was a small dot in a sea of red, white and blue flags on East
Tremont Avenue. Men carrying their own collections of flags and
hats came by and asked what he still had in stock. Some were
looking for flags to place on their cars or to drape around
themselves during the parade; others were sellers trying to stock
up.
</P>
<P>
   Each year in the weeks before the parade, hundreds, perhaps
thousands of vendors and hawkers take to the streets of the Bronx
to sell the symbols that unite proud Puerto Ricans, many of whom
travel across the country for the event. And this neighborhood,
where Rantas also owns the Borinquen Records store, is at the
center of that industry.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Rantas said that he sold the apparel ``for the people
of Puerto Rico.'' But his next comment, which came after the driver
of a flatbed truck stopped to pick up a flag, suggested a motive
somewhat less altruistic. Rantas said he made tens of thousands of
dollars each spring selling the items on the street and in his
nearby store. But he does think that the economic returns show
another type of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Puerto Rico, everything,'' he said. ``It is also good for
the community because so many people are buying flags and selling
them on the streets, and that helps the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Among New York City's many annual parades, the Puerto Rican Day
Parade is particularly merchandise-rich. In the weeks before the
event, flags begin popping up in windows all over heavily Puerto
Rican sections of East Tremont and Mott Haven in the Bronx, East
Williamsburg in Brooklyn and the Lower East Side and East Village
in Manhattan. People also drape flags on the hoods of their cars or
use them as shawls, hang trinkets in their cars and wear T-shirts
emblazoned with slogans like ``I love you Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   The vendors are the economic engine of the annual rite.
</P>
<P>
   There are no official city estimates on the revenue generated by
the hundreds of thousands of people drawn into New York City by the
parade, or ``el desfile,'' as it is more commonly known in the East
Bronx. But business people in the neighborhood said that the
economic windfall was essential.
</P>
<P>
   Ramy Khalif, 28, the owner of Mak 99 Cents store at East Tremont
and Marmion Avenue, said he had purchased 40,000 Puerto Rican flags
about three weeks ago to sell _ at $1 to $8 _ before the parade.
Only 2,000 flags were left Saturday morning. He had already run out
of towels and caps.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandise cost Khalif about $70,000, and he expects to
make more than $100,000. He said Saturday that he expected to sell
out in several hours. ``I don't think there will be anything
left,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Rantas' music store, the rows of CDs and tapes that usually
fill the store have been replaced by flags, T-shirts, clocks, coat
racks, towels and key chains. There were even belts, plates and
umbrellas. Rantas would not say how much he expected to make from
the parade, except that it would be in the tens of thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But to many, he said, the merchandise sales are simply a symptom
of pride. For Juan Nass, who is not Puerto Rican, it is less about
pride and more about money. ``Tomorrow is going to be slow and back
to normal, but in the week before the parade we make lots of
money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
