<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UNIONS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY UNIONS CALL FOR PROGRESS IN TALKS ON NEW CONTRACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Union leaders representing 300,000 New York City
municipal workers say their members are growing increasingly angry
about the lack of progress in labor negotiations that could be one
of the last big tests of Rudolph Giuliani's mayoralty.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts of half the city's work force have already
expired, and the leaders say their unions may hold large
demonstrations outside City Hall if the negotiations do not show
significant progress soon.
</P>
<P>
   The municipal unions have taken the position that Giuliani
should be especially generous in this round of negotiations because
the city has projected a $3.2 billion budget surplus and because
city workers accepted a two-year wage freeze in their previous
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is economic prosperity in the city,'' said Lee
Saunders, the trustee running District Council 37, the umbrella
union representing 125,000 municipal workers. ``Our members
sacrificed in the past when the city was experiencing financial
difficulties. Our members made sacrifices in their wages and
pension funds, and now that the city is in strong financial shape,
we should be rewarded with increased wages and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the leaders of the city's largest municipal
unions said they saw one major obstacle to progress in the talks:
Giuliani's demand that there be no across-the-board wage increase,
but instead individualized merit increases in which some workers
would receive no raise while others might receive up to 6 percent a
year. Several union leaders said the mayor's proposal would leave
many workers without raises and would create tensions between union
members who receive merit raises and those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not realistic to ask our members to accept a system of
individualized merit pay,'' said Patrick Lynch, president of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association. ``Every police officer should
get a merit pay increase, because every police officer did work
that helped bring about a substantial reduction in crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers, also criticized the mayor's proposal, saying: ``There's
not one union in the City of New York that will accept a contract
without a pay increase for all of its members. Ultimately, if the
mayor stays on this course of individualized merit pay or nothing,
then nobody's going to do a contract with him, and then it's clear
to me that he's just not serious about bargaining.''
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Mayor Robert M. Harding insisted that Giuliani was
indeed serious about bargaining. ``He's already shown his ability
to negotiate with the unions,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Harding said that in the last round of citywide bargaining,
Giuliani and the city's unions successfully negotiated a five-year
contract containing a no-layoff clause, a two-year wage freeze and
a 12 percent increase over the last three years. He also noted that
the city reached a pension agreement with the unions just two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement, which would require state legislation to take
effect, would reduce the amount that city workers contribute to
their pensions each year by about 3 percent of their annual salary.
In return, the unions approved a plan to let the city use $808
million from unexpectedly high investment profits from union
pension funds. The one-time windfall would be used in the city's
operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor experts say some of that money may be used to finance
a labor contract (each 1 percent wage increase in the city's
payroll costs about $160 million). Several experts said they
expected that Giuliani would eventually propose a fallback position
that included a modest wage increase for all employees and
individual merit increases on top of that.
</P>
<P>
   James F. Hanley, the city's labor commissioner, said the
recently negotiated pension agreement created a spirit of
cooperation that could give some momentum to the collective
bargaining. He added that the unions would feel some pressure to
reach an agreement soon because their members would see the
reductions in their pension contributions until an overall labor
agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he would not predict when an agreement would be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the early stages,'' Hanley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
