A0409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAR DOWN IN PURSUIT OF THE CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The New Jersey Devils had primed themselves to drink
champagne out of the Stanley Cup on Thursday night in New Jersey.
Instead, they were drinking water out of small plastic bottles, and
some looked devastated when they saw five men dressed like armed
guards wheel hockey's Holy Grail out of their house.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars had denied the Devils the party they had
prepared to stage in front of their festive fans at Continental
Arena. After taking a 3-1 lead in the series by winning two games
here, a number of the Devils thought the Stars took away something
that had already belonged to them.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the triple-overtime loss early Friday morning that
some of the Devils deeply digested the fact that they need four
victories in the finals to win the Stanley Cup. And the fourth one
is the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody knows what it takes to get the final
win,'' said Devils Coach Larry Robinson, the man responsible for
taking over a team in disarray with eight games left in the regular
season and bringing it to this stage. Robinson won six Stanley Cup
rings as a player. ``I told the guys: `If you're nervous, you
should be. If you're scared, you should be.' I think that if you
have not experienced these two things in your hockey career you
have never been in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a fear of dying or a fear like falling off a
bridge. It's a different kind of feeling that you get, knowing that
the Stanley Cup is within your reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur knows very well what Robinson is talking about.
Brodeur also knows the sacrifices that have to be made to get the
reward of raising hockey's ultimate prize. That is why Brodeur cut
short an interview just minutes after the loss in Game 5 by saying:
``This is the last question. My preparation is starting now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur gave his teammates every opportunity to finish the job
two nights ago, but they failed him and they failed themselves by
not scoring a single goal in 106 minutes of hockey. Brodeur has
been one of the best goaltenders in the league the last seven
years, but overtime playoff games are not his strong suit.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday night's loss, Brodeur has three victories in 14
overtime playoff games, including triple and quadruple overtime
losses. His performance in the loss to Dallas and its goalie, Ed
Belfour, in Game 5 was as memorable as the loss to Dominik Hasek in
the 1994 playoffs. Hasek made 70 saves to give the Buffalo Sabres a
1-0 victory in that game, the sixth of the Eastern Conference
quarterfinals series, which the Devils eventually won in the
seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   The Belfour-Brodeur duel Thursday night and Friday morning
involved so many spectacular saves _ 48 by Belfour and 40 by
Brodeur _ that a number of hockey observers are calling it the
greatest display of goaltending in the history of the Stanley Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever seen anything better,'' Dallas coach
Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been more games with more shots and more acrobatic
saves, but to come up with two such brilliant goaltending
performances in the same game in the Stanley Cup finals, when one
team is looking to clinch and the other to avoid losing its title,
was something remarkable indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said his team had the advantage of ``fresher legs''
going into Game 6 Saturday night. He based his claim on the fact
that his players are younger and his belief that the ice time two
nights ago was more widely dispersed among his players. But the
official statistics proved Robinson wrong, as each team had seven
players with more than 30 minutes of ice time.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's remark that Mike Modano, who played 43 minutes and 37
seconds and scored the only goal, after 106 minutes 21 seconds of
play, had played ``75 minutes'' angered Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry should mind his own business,'' Hitchcock said, adding
that Robinson should ``worry about his own team.''
</P>
<P>
   That burst of hostility is what the Stanley Cup playoffs do to
people who have gone through agony every day for two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
