<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-ASSAD-FUTURE-0611     06-10 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-ASSAD-FUTURE-0611 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASSAD'S DEATH LEAVES MIDEAST PEACE IN DOUBT
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Syrian President Hafez Assad was the last critical
hold out in the long search for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   While Assad took a hard line, he might have also been the sole
figure in Syria capable of making a deal and staying in power to
ensure it was kept. With his death Saturday, prospects of a wider
deal between Israel and its Arab neighbors were shaken up. But they
were not lost.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Assad was the last major Arab leader to take the
so-called rejectionist line in his dealings with the Jewish State.
He held that line throughout 30 years in office. And he watched
bitterly as contemporaries such as Egypt's Anwar Sadat, Jordan's
King Hussein and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat all signed
treaties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He scorned them as sell-outs to Arab honor that he had vowed to
protect. In taking that hard line, Assad sought to keep the door
shut between Israel and the rest of the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Middle East has lost the ``Lion of Damascus,'' the
question remains whether it will get a lamb to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate wake of Assad's death, estimations over what
happens next -- and, specifically, whether peace will be easier or
harder to achieve remained divided.
</P>
<P>
   One view is that the peace process, already stalled since
January, will be on hold for months or more while the likely
successor, Assad's 35-year-old son, Bashar, consolidates power.
</P>
<P>
   A contrary view is that, while the process might be on hold in
the short run, chances have improved for deal down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The major issue of contention is the Golan Heights. Israel
captured the strategic plateau in 1967. Assad, who headed the
Syrian Air Force at the time, took responsibility for the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Several times since 1990, he had sent envoys to engage in peace
talks in Madrid and Washington, only to later arrange for them out.
to walk out. A succession of high-level U.S. diplomats came to his
palace, which overlooks the capital, vainly seeking to nudge the
process along.
</P>
<P>
   The last round Israel broke off in January, with Syrian
officials saying that they needed more guarantees that Israel would
ultimately relinquish the entire plateau.
</P>
<P>
   A peace treaty with Syria could open up the Arab world at large
to normal diplomatic and economic ties with Israel. It also could
end any real threat to Middle East stability since the
Palestinians, whatever their stance, lack anywhere near the
military might of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made peace a keystone of his foreign
policy, a goal he hopes to achieve before leaving office next
January. But Clinton, as his predecessor, had to cope with Assad's
unbending determination to recover every inch of the land lost --
in return at best for a only ``cold'' peace with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Assad knew that any peace with Israel would be tough pill for
Syrians to swallow, many of whom still remain bitter over their
nation's military defeats at Israel's hand in 1967 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   No newcomer, one argument goes, can take the risk of forcing
upon his people a controversial peace with the historic archenemy.
</P>
<P>
   As the virtual certain newcomer, Basher, had focused his
attention on becoming an ophthalmologist until his older brother's
death in a 1994 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Potential rivals for power include his uncle, Rifaat(cq) Assad,
a free-wheeling businessman who lives in Europe. Opposition could
also coalesce around the Sunni Moslems majority, who has rebelled
unsuccessfully against the regime in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he does survive politically, Bashar remains largely an
unknown. He was to receive his first official position in the
government next week.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from touting the Internet and a campaign against
corruption, his positions on external issues have closely tracked
his father's views.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar may face rivals, if not immediately, then after he's in
the job long enough to get some of the blame for Syria's economic
stagnation. Some Syrians see him as too inexperienced. Others are
tired of rule by the Alawites, who comprise only about 12 percent
of the country's 15 million people.
</P>
<P>
   he Assad family is from the minority of Alawites, a branch of
Islam within Sunni Muslim majority. Their power rests delicately
and could be upset by a controversial bargain with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Bashar be strong enough to make a dramatic step,
especially and external one? I doubt it,'' said Glenn Robinson,
associate professor of Middle Eastern studies at the Naval
Postgraduate School in Monterey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Some more optimistic views, however, were being voiced here.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's main television channels broke into their regular
coverage Saturday night with video footage from the Damascus of the
Syrian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that Bashar might be easier to deal with than
his father, who had to carry the bruises from military defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad wasn't ready all these years to make peace with us. He
tried to prove that he would get more than Sadat,'' said Israeli
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin. ``The new leadership comes into
power without that historical burden.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near future, the chances of our renewing peace talks
with Syria are slim,'' said Israel cabinet minister Haim Ramon.
``When, the peace talks do resume the chances of success are
greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow's e-mail address is larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
