<HEADLINE>
DEATH OF SYRIA'S ASSAD PROFOUNDLY CONFUSES PEACE HOPES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY 450-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIRUT _ The sudden death of President Hafez Assad of Syria last
night threw the Middle East into shock and profound uncertainty as
one of the Arab world's most powerful military nations found itself
leaderless.
</P>
<P>
   As a Syrian television announcer burst into tears while
broadcasting news of the 69-year-old president's death, Arab and
Israeli leaders desperately tried to find out if Assad's son Bashar
_ who was due to be made Dauphin at next Saturday's Ba'ath party
congress _ would be taking over the country.
</P>
<P>
   President Assad belonged to Syria's minority Alawite community
and for years Syria's enemies have been predicting a bloody
denouement if Assad were to die suddenly. But Assad himself and his
foreign minister, Farouq el-Sharaa, have always predicted an
orderly transition of power.
</P>
<P>
   This might have been easier if the Syrian government had not
just embarked on a purge of senior government officials _ including
the prime minister _ for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Alawi officers command the best trained units in the Syrian
army, but a number of former special forces officers may now wish
to stake their own claim to the leadership of the nation that, at
one point earlier this year, seemed on the verge of signing a peace
agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since 1982, when he suffered his first heart problems,
Assad's health has been a subject for constant speculation. But
there had been no prior hint of his imminent death, which has left
Syrians unprepared for the great changes which must now lie ahead
in their country.
</P>
<P>
   Will there now be a peace agreement with Israel?
</P>
<P>
   Will Syria's new ruler persuade the Israelis to return the
occupied Golan Heights?
</P>
<P>
   Will Syria's 21,000-strong army in Lebanon remain in the
neighboring country or return to their barracks in Syria?
</P>
<P>
   And what will happen in southern Lebanon where _ until Israel's
withdrawal earlier this month _ the Hezbollah were fighting a
ferocious guerrilla war against the Israelis with full Syrian
support?
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Saturday night: ``Hafez
Assad was a figure of stability in the Middle East and much
respected in the Arab world and beyond... The best testimony to
(his) memory would be for all involved to redouble their efforts to
bring a just and lasting peace to the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The past 14 months have already taken the lives of three major
Middle East leaders: King Hussein of Jordan, King Hassan of Morocco
and the Emir of Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   Few could have imagined that Assad _ the president with more
physical energy than any other who could talk foreign ambassadors
to exhaustion as he explained Syria's policies _ would now die. &QL; 
