<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LIBERTY-MONARCHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENICHEIRO STEPS ON ACCELERATOR, AND MONARCHS RACE PAST LIBERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the New York Liberty players missed their shots,
and that was with stunning frequency Friday night at Madison Square
Garden, the Sacramento Monarchs sent the rebounds directly to point
guard Ticha Penicheiro. From there, Penicheiro only accelerated,
starting the fast break every time down court with such urgency, it
was as if she were entering the autobahn.
</P>
<P>
   Her Monarch teammates filled the lanes seamlessly and she
flipped them no-look passes, leaving the Liberty looking dazed and
breathing hard through their open mouths as the ball landed neatly
in the net.
</P>
<P>
   When Penicheiro was not igniting the fastest break in the
Women's National Basketball Association in Sacramento's 77-56
victory, Yolanda Griffith was showing why she was the league's most
valuable player last season.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Tari Phillips succeeded in matching her, even getting
a game-high 25 points and nine rebounds to Griffith's 24 points and
eight rebounds, but no one else on the Liberty could keep up with
the rest of the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   With a small bench, whittled down by injuries, and ice in its
fingertips, New York (2-4) lost its fourth and worst game of the
season. The Monarchs, considered one of the top teams in the
preseason, overwhelmed the Liberty early, using a 46-27 halftime
lead to win for the first time in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Including Phillips, who converted nine of 16 shots from the
field, the Liberty shot 28.6 percent. ``It was almost like there
was a lid on the basket,'' Liberty coach Richie Adubato said.
``When you shoot 28 percent, you're not going to win. We just
played the worst game that we've ever played since I've been here,
in regard to giving them a head start and not being able to shoot
the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Penicheiro and her teammates orchestrated the head start. With
13 minutes 46 seconds remaining in the first half, forward Vickie
Johnson's 3-pointer put the Liberty ahead, 10-7, but Griffith
scored five straight points, and suddenly, the Monarchs were in the
middle of their minirun, a warm-up for their 14-0 run two minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they were done, the Monarchs held a 31-15 lead.
Griffith went into halftime having scored 14 points. ``Tonight,''
Griffith said, ``we ran the floor like the old Sacramento Monarchs
used to do last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips noticed. ``One way to kill the morale of a team is on
fast-break points because sometimes you look up and you don't know
the ball is going the other way,'' Phillips said. ``It kills you
offensively, defensively. It kills your legs and your stamina.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
