<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-965&AMP;ADD-     06-10 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 REAL ESTATE: JOINING THE ON-DECK CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For many homeowners, the benefits of adding a new
room are often outweighed by cost: Even a small addition usually
runs into tens of thousands of dollars. Price, however, becomes
less of a factor if an addition has no roof, no walls and no
interior finishing touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deck is becoming an increasingly important part of many
families' summer activities,'' said Robert Marshal, the owner of
Craftsman Custom Decks and Porches in Beacon.
</P>
<P>
   Marshal said that while there may be limitations on the size of
a new deck _ building codes often have minimum side- and rear-yard
setback requirements _ most properties have room enough to allow
for at least some extension of the house into the outdoors. But, he
said, just extending isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can build a simple rectangle and stick it on the back
of your house,'' he said. ``But a deck's shape and layout are very
important. That's why it's usually best to hire an architect to
draw up plans that take all the various factors into account.''
</P>
<P>
   Inexperienced contractors and homeowners who design their own
decks, Marshal said, often do not consider circulation paths and
privacy. ``You don't want to end up with a deck that makes people
squeeze between a picnic table and a hot grill to get to the
stairs,'' he said, adding that a professional deck designer will
typically consider such things and may include a bumpout _ a small
extension that juts beyond the main area of the deck _ for the
grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``And privacy panels are not just useful for privacy,'' Marshal
said. The panels, sometimes made of lattice, extend above the
railing and ``also provide a surface that can be used to attach
shelves for storage and hooks for hanging utensils,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The panels, when combined with a well-designed railing and
spindle system, can enhance the look of a deck from the perspective
that counts most: the homeowner's. ``A deck should be beautiful to
look at from inside the house,'' he said, adding that one mistake
many homeowners make is to build the railing too high _ and that
anything over 42 inches starts to look too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives the deck the appearance of a playpen,'' he said.
Most building codes require the railing to be a minimum of 30 to 36
inches high, he said. Spindles, he said, should be spaced about 4
inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost always necessary, Marshal said, for a homeowner,
architect or contractor to file plans and get a permit from the
local building department before construction can start.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hyman, the owner of BMI Decks in Pomona, said that an
economical way to transform an ordinary deck into a special one is
to, well, cut corners. ``The cheapest way to jazz up a deck is to
literally cut the corners off,'' Hyman said. ``It's a good
tradeoff. You lose only a little space but it looks a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to enhance a deck, he said, is to run deck boards
diagonally or in a herringbone pattern. ``I usually don't charge
more for an angled pattern or herringbone,'' he said, explaining
that some contractors might charge more because of the increased
material and labor costs necessary for the angled cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman, like many deck contractors, charges on a per-square-foot
basis, based on the material used.
</P>
<P>
   For premium grade, pressure-treated yellow pine decking, Hyman
said, he charges $14 a square foot. For standard cedar, which
generally contains some knots, and for clear cedar _ which is
knot-free _ the charges are $16 and $18 a square foot,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   And for synthetic lumber _ a composite material made of plastic
and wood _ the charge per square foot is $19. The prices include
labor and installation. A 12-by-12-foot deck, 144 square feet,
would cost from $2,000 to $2,700, depending on the materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Composites are becoming more and more popular,'' Hyman said.
``They install just like wood and they're virtually
maintenance-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Renter, president of Deck and Patio Co., a contractor in
Huntington Station, agreed. ``The nice thing about using a
composite is that it doesn't split, doesn't crack and doesn't
splinter,'' Renter said. ``And once it's installed, all it needs is
an occasional washing to keep it looking like new.''
</P>
<P>
   While composite materials cannot be used for structural framing
_ most contractors use pressure-treated yellow pine for the posts,
beams and joists that support the deck _ composite decking
materials are attractive for homeowners who want to restore or
replace an existing deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the framing is in good shape, we can tear off the old wood
surface and replace it with Trex,'' Renter said, referring to the
brand name of one composite decking product. ``Even if your deck is
15 years old, this is a very economical way of getting a new deck
that you'll never have to maintain again.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge for installing new Trex decking on an existing deck
frame, he said, runs about $12 per square foot. ``And if the
customer wants to rip off the old deck surface, we take $2 a foot
off the price,'' Renter said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are more ambitious have even more options.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Taylor, the owner of Just Decks in Toms River, N.J., said
that his company can provide custom-sized, precut deck kits that
customers can assemble themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times, homeowners who buy kits ask us to come out to dig
and pour the footings,'' he said, referring to the concrete support
posts that must be poured _ usually to a depth of about 3 feet _ to
ensure that freezing and thawing will not affect the stability of
the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that a standard 12-by-12-foot pressure-treated
yellow pine deck cut into a kit would cost about $1,800. That
amount does not include extra charges for digging and pouring the
footings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For decks he builds on site, Taylor said, he charges a flat
price of $6 a square foot for labor. ``Then we ask the customer
what kind of material they want, and we give them an itemized bill
for every piece of lumber we buy,'' he said. ``We also give the
customer the option of going out and purchasing the lumber
themselves if they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that customers should insist on itemized pricing
when getting quotes. ``Most contractors will give a square-foot
price for the whole job, labor and materials included,'' Taylor
said. ``If you're dealing with a reputable contractor, that's not a
problem. But some contractors figure that since the less they spend
on the materials, the more they can put in their pocket, why not
buy the cheapest material?''
</P>
<P>
   Marshal said that another reason decks are becoming more popular
is concern about ticks that carry Lyme disease. ``People still want
to be outside,'' he said. ``They just want to stay off the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the reason, Taylor said, more and more decks are
being built. ``Everybody has different tastes and different
needs,'' he said. ``But you can always fit a deck into your
budget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
