<HEADER>
A0417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT &LR;      06-10 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY STILL FACES HURDLES IN PREPARING FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ This city of 4 million is in the blocks for
the Olympics, which start in three months, and is becoming as
nervous as any finalist facing a chance for gold and glory.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian organizers of the 2000 Summer Games, the biggest
in Olympic history, have prepared well, but they are finding the
last warm-ups for the event harder than anything that has come
before.
</P>
<P>
   Event sites, budgets, logistics, technology and accommodations
are on schedule, the organizers say, but ticketing, transport links
and hiring enough hands to do everything remain difficult hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, a metropolis anchored on bays and beaches, is bracing
itself for the Games, which begin Sept. 15 with the opening
ceremony at the 110,000-seat Stadium Australia, the largest site
built for any Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic torch arrived from Greece last Thursday, with the
relay starting at Uluru, a dome-shaped desert monolith about 1,400
miles northwest of Sydney. Uluru was chosen for its sacred status
among Aborigines, who were here for 40,000 years before white rule
began in 1788.
</P>
<P>
   In the longest torch parade in Olympic history, about 10,000
runners, chosen from 40,000 volunteers, from grade-schoolers to
veterans, will relay it 20,000 miles. The route passes remote
ranches, gold-mining townships and the Great Barrier Reef and takes
in hundreds of crossroad communities before reaching Sydney on the
eve of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   For the Games' organizers _ the government-appointed Sydney
Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games, which includes
political and business leaders _ the televised relay is primarily a
marathon marketing exercise to boost ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Last year billing errors and delays and the controversial
reservation of prime seats for wealthy clubs and individuals slowed
ticket sales to 2 million; 3 million more, with a price tag of $140
million U.S., remain to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   A live telephone-sales campaign started last week, timed to turn
televised images of the torch into ticket orders.
</P>
<P>
   John Moore, the organizing committee's former marketing
director, said, ``The torch run is crucial to igniting more
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month sales were spurred when Australian swimmers set world
records in the country's Olympic trials, creating headlines that
helped bring 450,000 mail orders worth $30 million U.S..
</P>
<P>
   David Richmond, the Olympics Coordination Authority's director,
said he was pleased with the pace of recent sales but conceded,
``It will be a challenge to sell all the remaining tickets.''
Richmond pointed out that Australia has a population of 19 million
in an area almost as large as the United States, whereas for the
Atlanta Games in 1996 there were 19 million potential ticket-buyers
living within a five-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   Getting about 5 million ticket-holders to and from the 635
sessions of 292 events involving 10,000 athletes in 28 sports over
two weeks at 10 principal sites is a transportation task for which
Sydney has the public structure, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   But the city will need better management than was revealed
recently by a series of rail accidents and highway control errors.
Two of the dozen rail mishaps were on new tracks built to the main
stadium and the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Knight, the minister for Olympics, alarmed by such
transportation risks for the Games, engineered a switch of control
of the public rail system from bureaucrats to a senior Olympic
official, who was given priority powers to ensure reliability of
services.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a senior member of the government of New South Wales,
which is underwriting the Games, said he would be ``remorseless in
confronting problems before and during the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people and systems could be stretched to the breaking
point,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
