<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-RENT-CONTROL-REAL-     06-10 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RENT-CONTROL-REAL-855(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: RAISING THE RENT, AND RAISING THE ROOF 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is surely one of the most thankless tasks in
public service. And on Thursday morning, when the gavel pounds for
the start of this year's all-day hearing on proposed rent increases
for New York City's 1 million rent-stabilized apartments, members
of the city's Rent Guidelines Board may well have shudders from
hearings past lurking in the recesses of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   They may think of marbles arching at them from the back of the
auditorium. Of rainstorms of epithets. Of circling like covered
wagons on stage to conduct business while a phalanx of police
officers holds the placard-shaking crowd at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine board members, those most wondering why they are
doing this may well be the five public representatives seated
center stage, with landlord members on their right, tenants on
their left.
</P>
<P>
   This year the board has issued a preliminary recommendation that
rents on apartments covered by the rent-stabilization regulations
be raised by 4 percent for one-year leases and 6 percent for
two-year leases _ a significant jump from the 2 and 4 percent
increases ordered in most recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling unruly meetings of years past, Vincent Castellano, one
of the two landlord members _ who readily affirms that he serves on
the board to protect his own interests and those of the city's
25,000 other landlords _ said: ``Can you think of any agency of
government where the meetings are as bizarre? It's a zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the public members' motivation, he said, ``They're
masochists.''
</P>
<P>
   David Pagan, one of the two tenant representatives, is the
administrator of Los Sures, a housing and community development
organization in Brooklyn. ``I come in from the neighborhoods where
I deal with a lot of tenants, that's why I'm here,'' Pagan said.
``The public members, I don't know. I can't figure what's there for
a public member.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much recognition; it's not a power position,''
Pagan said. ``They really must love to be helpful. At the same
time, how long can you be helpful if you are being hit over the
head?''
</P>
<P>
   There is also not much pay; the members receive the same
$100-a-day fee that was set in 1969 when the Rent Guidelines Board
was created _ a point of particular annoyance to them. ``We get
$100 per session, about 10 times a year,'' Pagan said. ``So it's an
extra thousand dollars, for which we have to reveal our financial
history'' _ in a 35-page form.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, meetings of the board have been somewhat calmer in
recent years. ``Far more decorous than prior years,'' said
Castellano, the landlord representative, ``almost bordering on the
civil _ almost, not quite.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the relative decorum ``has to do with the economy,''
Castellano said. ``It's hard to get worked up about a 2 or 4
percent increase when you've got a job. If you're unemployed, it's
a different story. It's not the hot-button issue it was in the
early '90s.'' Yet when the board convenes in the Great Hall of
Cooper Union at 10 a.m. Thursday, the button may be pushed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   For five of the last six years _ not counting tumultuous 1996
when they were 5 and 7 percent _ the rent increases have been 2
percent and 4 percent. And in the view of tenant advocates, since
inflation is largely in check, the current proposal for 4 percent
and 6 percent increases seems unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   The landlords argue, however, that they have been hit with
significant increases in fuel costs and real estate taxes, and
deserve compensation even greater than the preliminary
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   The board's final vote will not be taken during the public
hearing, but is scheduled for 5 p.m. on June 22, also in the Great
Hall at Cooper Union. The final guidelines will affect those leases
with starting dates between Oct. 1, 2000 and Sept. 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Piqued last month by media accounts that a proposed change in
the way the board's staff provides economic reports could lead to
whopping increases of 8.5 percent and 12 percent (in fact, the
change was not adopted by the board), public interest in the
current proposal has been stirred.
</P>
<P>
   And with it, renewed railing on opposing sides of the
landlord-tenant divide that (a) the rent board is in the pocket of
a city administration beholden to the real estate lobby or (b)
tenant advocates are simply flexing their numbers to politicize the
process, invoking protection of the poor on behalf of lots of
people who can afford to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the board's deliberations is a debate over whether
one year's rent guidelines should be based solely on economic
factors from the immediately preceding year or should compensate
for previous inflationary fluctuations. Also at issue is what role
a potentially one-time spike in a particular element of the
calculations _ fuel costs, in this instance _ should play.
</P>
<P>
   All of which sets the stage for 12 hours of vigorous contention
on Thursday, with landlord and tenant advocates from the audience
taking turns in last-word attempts to test the limits of their
allotted three-minute speaking times _ punctuated by vociferous
support or derision from opposing factions in the crowd.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Weinstein, for one, will brook little of the disorder
of the not-too-distant past. Weinstein, one of the five public
members of the board, is a retired senior partner at the accounting
firm of Deloitte &AMP; Touche and sits on the boards of six
not-for-profit organizations, including the Cooper-Hewitt Museum.
At the request of a friend in the city administration (whom he
would not name), Weinstein agreed to serve on the rent board three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given my background, I'm not quite used to what I've had to
endure from the people who attend the meetings,'' Weinstein said.
``It's a question of unruliness, and the feeling that they have the
absolute right to just yell out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if they applaud or boo or hiss, although it's
childish,'' Weinstein said, ``but they disrupt people who are
speaking and scream out their unhappy remarks. It just offends
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivid in his recollection is a woman who confronted him at the
intermission of a meeting during his first year on the board. ``She
started screaming at me that I had never heard of Patrick Henry or
the Boston Tea Party,'' Weinstein said, ``meaning I had no right to
stifle their right to dissent. I just walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   The low moment for Edward S. Hochman came in 1994, the year
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appointed him to serve as chairman and a
public member of the board. That year, the board voted increases of
2 percent and 4 percent and, after a four-year hiatus, reinstituted
what it calls the low-rent supplement _ an extra charge for
apartments with rents below a certain level. Tenants call it the
``poor tax.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the supplement was $5 for stabilized apartments renting
for $325 or less. For the next four years, no supplement was
charged. But in 1994 it was restored at $15 for apartments renting
for $400 or less (This year the board has proposed a supplement of
$15 for rents up to $500).
</P>
<P>
   ``After the final meeting in '94, when it died down,'' Hochman
said, ``I walked to the subway _ the good old City Hall stop for
the 4, 5 and 6 trains _ and a couple of people in the crowd
followed me and threatened to throw me on the tracks. I remember
thinking that's not such a bad idea, an alternative to suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   During the final meeting in 1996, the one year in the last six
in which the increases exceeded 2 and 4 percent, rising to 5 and 7
percent, ``I got hit with marbles, gum and tacks,'' Hochman, who is
a corporate lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   That '96 meeting was probably the stormiest in the board's
31-year history. Kenneth Rosenfeld, director of legal services for
Northern Manhattan Improvement Corp., a tenant rights group, was
then one of the two tenant representatives on the rent board. He
left the board last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fully the tenant advocate, Rosenfeld recalled: ``In that year,
there was a temporary increase in fuel costs. And, despite the
staff statistics in what is called the Core Price Index, the board
ignored its own data and passed what, under those circumstances,
were startling and onerous guidelines'' _ the 5 and 7 percent
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was full of people screaming,'' Rosenfeld said.
``Landlords were yelling, too. We voted on the apartments and the
crowd went nuts. In order to continue the meeting, because there
were other votes to be taken, we ended up sitting in a circle on
the stage at 1 Police Plaza, trying to conduct the rest of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 5 and 7 percent increases of 1996 were outrageous, in
Rosenfeld's tenant-protective eyes, the 2 and 4 percent guidelines
of 1994, '95, '97, '98 and '99 were less egregious only to a
degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two and 4 percent may sound reasonable,'' he said, ``but if
you recall, in almost all those years inflation was significantly
lower than in the past and, in the most recent years, almost
nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagan, one of the two current tenant representatives, agreed.
``We're talking about zero and maybe 1 percent inflation, and the
fact is that they went to 2 and 4,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' Pagan continued, ``oil is the factor that has
skewed landlord costs more than anything else, and everybody
understands that oil is one of those commodities for which the
price will come down at some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the issue of whether the board should allow a
one-time spike in a particular economic factor to govern the
guidelines, Pagan said: ``What happens is that we are building in a
higher percentage rent increase, and when the oil price comes down
and inflation comes down to a normal level, because the oil was
pushing it, we will not get a reduction on rent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're just putting costs on top of costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to an annual study produced by the board's staff
called the Price Index of Operating Costs _ or ``the PIOC,'' in
board terminology _ Weinstein said Pagan was contending ``that if
we take a look at the PIOC in relation to the increases voted upon
by the board, in general the board lags behind in those years when
the PIOC shows abnormal inflation, and the board leads the PIOC in
years of moderate or low inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So he's saying that the board tends to act as a moderating
force when it comes to prices,'' Weinstein continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I look at a year within itself, as well as within a
framework of history, and try to achieve a balance,'' Weinstein
said. ``So his interpretation is that of the tenant
representatives, and I don't agree with it. I think what we did was
appropriate, based upon the statistics that we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do, this board is not going to be popular,'' he
said. ``Either the tenants or the landlords are not going to be
happy, and probably both.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
