<P>
   &UR; `SPHINX'-ASSAD-800&AMP;ADD-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Hafez al-Assad's on-again, off-again approach to the
Middle East peace process frequently drove U.S. and Israeli
policymakers to distraction. Was the Syrian leader, who died
suddenly Saturday at 69, temperamental and unpredictable? Were his
enemies gulled by the mistaken view that Assad, a maddeningly
clever negotiator, was entirely trustworthy once he had given his
word? Many pundits in Israel and the United States think so. But
this view is a serious and unfair misreading of Assad. In fact, his
behavior was anything but erratic; it was consistent and
predictable. To understand that consistency, one must understand
the enigmatic man known as the ``sphinx of Damascus'' and the world
in which he lived. To the end, Assad remained the uncompromisingly
tough, unyielding defender of Arab honor....By Henry Siegman,
Foreign Affairs magazine.
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
