<HEADER>
A0422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-RENT-CONTROL-REAL-     06-10 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RENT-CONTROL-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: probably both.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The statistics, compiled by the board's full-time staff of six,
provide only guidance to the members in their deliberations, rather
than setting a hard-and-fast conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rent stabilization was instituted in 1969 to counter the effects
of Rockefeller-era vacancy decontrol laws that allowed a landlord
to go to free-market rents when a rent-controlled apartment became
vacant. There were widespread instances of landlords forcing out
long-time tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Under stabilization, the owner of a vacated rent-controlled
apartment could set an initial free-market rent, after which the
rent would be subject to the increases allowed by the board. There
are currently about 70,000 rent-controlled apartments in the city,
down from more than 1 million at the time stabilization was
enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The rent board's staff prepares at least five reports each year
assessing the affordability and profitability of stabilized
housing. Probably the most significant are the Price Index of
Operating Costs and the Income and Affordability Study.
</P>
<P>
   Like the federal Consumer Price Index, the PIOC surveys a basket
of goods _ among them taxes, labor, fuel and contractor costs _
that estimate the cost of running a rent-stabilized apartment. It
then offers a projection of the coming year's expenses for the
landlord.
</P>
<P>
   The Income and Affordability Study focuses on tenants, surveying
such factors as their salaries, Social Security, public benefits,
rent-to-income ratios, eviction rates and homelessness. It provides
a balance to the data on landlord costs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld, who in his years on the board frequently clashed with
Hochman, the chairman, believes the board's political balance has
changed in recent years. ``Having been appointed by Mayor Dinkins
in '93, the last year of his term, I spent most of my time on the
board under the Giuliani administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an extreme shift in the attitudes of both the city
administration and the Giuliani appointees _ from balancing out the
inequities in the rent-regulated universe toward satisfying the
landlord and real estate lobbies.'' Of the nine current members,
seven _ including the chairman and three other public
representatives _ were appointed by Giuliani. Members serve two-,
three- or four-year terms, except for the chairman, who serves at
the pleasure of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Bart D. Carmody, one of the new public members, sees no shift in
the board's attitude. ``Simply put, when the vote was 2 and 4
percent, the tenants were making statements about the public
members being pro-landlord,'' said Carmody, who is a certified
public accountant. ``This year, when the rates, in my view, could
have been higher, the landlord advocates are crying that we are
pro-tenant. So, my point is: one year yes, one year no.''
</P>
<P>
   Castellano, the landlord representative appointed by Giuliani,
thinks ``it's funny how some of the tenant advocates portray the
behind-the-scenes politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear from them that the mayor has such control over the
board,'' he continued, ``the fact is that virtually everybody on
the board is doing the mayor a favor by being there, and if he had
to replace them it would be difficult, at best. There is not a long
line of people who want to take this kind of abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no cohesive bloc of public members, Castellano said.
``My role and the role of any of the advocate members is to
persuade at least two public members to agree with us and,
hopefully, get the chair's vote,'' he said. ``That makes a bare
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Hochman, the chairman, asked rhetorically: ``Does the
administration have an interest in what the Rent Guidelines Board
does? I not only presume so, I would hope so. Do I, as the only
member of the board who, by law, can be fired at any time, the one
designated as the administration's representative, talk to the
administration?
</P>
<P>
   ``When all the reports come in, I tell the administration that
this was the board's factual findings and this is the general range
where I anticipate that the preliminary guidelines may be,''
Hochman continued. ``I have never talked to the mayor on this.
Usually I send my report to a deputy mayor. I'll say, `This is a
general range; do you guys have a problem with that?' The answer
has always been no.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmody said, ``I would think the mayor has to look more to the
voters than any industry'' _ a point not entirely lost on
Rosenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``In appointing the board and approving, to the extent that a
mayor does, the final result,'' Rosenfeld said, ``a mayor is
balancing out how much influence the real estate lobby has and the
dollars it provides to political campaigns with the potential votes
of 1 million regulated apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   Hochman pointed out that those 1 million apartments house
perhaps 2 million voters. ``I've always said that if either side
ever thanks us, we've probably done a poor job,'' he said.
</P>
