<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-HOBOKEN-JOURNAL-NY     06-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HOBOKEN-JOURNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOBOKEN JOURNAL: CANCER AND POLITICS IN CITY OF GRUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOBOKEN, N.J. _ Most people here will tell you that not much is
different since the mayor got cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Anthony Russo, a feisty 53-year-old former
schoolteacher who has ruled this bustling city of 35,000 across the
river from New York City since 1993, may be bald. (In typically
aggressive style, he shaved his head before his hair could fall
out.) But he has not slowed down appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   He signs orders, yells at his opponents on the city council and
continues negotiations to fix up the once-crumbling waterfront,
which has sprouted two lovely parks and an apartment complex during
his tenure. He accused some officials who sent him get-well cards
of doing so out of guilt rather than concern.
</P>
<P>
   But to the extent that the civic climate has changed at all
since late March, when Russo announced that he had just had surgery
to remove a brain tumor the size of a golf ball, there is
considerable disagreement about what, exactly, has happened. This
is not surprising. Beneath Hoboken's ceaseless waves of
gentrification lurks an old world where political grudges are
nursed like kittens and shifting allegiances are monitored more
closely than the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Russo's most devoted adversary on the City Council, Tony Soares,
said the mayor had mellowed a little. ``I think he's a little more
approachable now,'' Soares said recently. ``As much of a tyrant as
he's been all these years, you can't help but be sympathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, though, he reversed himself. ``As much as you
want to be respectful to him,'' Soares said, ``he forces you into
confrontations.''
</P>
<P>
   Margie O'Brien, a crossing guard in the city for more than 30
years and the author of several books on Hoboken history, said that
Russo's enemies had grown more vicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the animal world,'' O'Brien, 56, said last week as
she waved a flock of children across 11th Street. ``If one goldfish
is weak, the other goldfish go after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other events in Hoboken's fractious public life, the
mayor's handling of his health problem is viewed in some quarters
as part of a vast conspiracy. The mayor, some say, fabricated his
entire illness to help his wife, Michele, win a seat on the school
board in April. Similarly, cynics contend, the mayor, a
two-pack-a-day smoker for 40 years, started giving tearful
antitobacco lectures in the public schools shortly before the
election to garner votes for Mrs. Russo. The mayor scoffs at such
notions.
</P>
<P>
   Many have pointed out that while Russo has held a series of news
conferences to update Hobokenites on his cancer, Ruben Ramos, 26,
an opponent of Russo's on the council who has Hodgkin's disease,
has sought little publicity for his plight.
</P>
<P>
   For Russo, of course, life has changed utterly. Like his
counterpart across the Hudson, another get-things-done
Italian-American mayor who brooks little dissent and has a weakness
for mob movies ( Russo played a Mafioso's bodyguard in ``Analyze
This''), Russo says that cancer has rearranged his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become more pensive, more God-fearing, more God-loving,''
Russo said in his office on the second floor of City Hall the other
day. ``Maybe before I was looking for the glitz and the glitter. I
would go out after government events and I would have a few drinks
and flirt. And maybe this made me realize how important family is
to me. My personal future and my family's future, not my political
future, are what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the mayor was tired. He had gone in for some tests
the day before and he had not received the results as he had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit and think,'' he said. ``It's constantly on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't come in to work until 4 in the afternoon, and he made
his entrance at the 7 p.m. council meeting 15 minutes late. His
dark blue blazer made the folds of his naked head look pale. He
took his usual spot, leaning on the railing that separates the
audience from the council, and scowled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just after it was announced that Russo had appointed a
commissioner, Jean Rodriguez, to the city's public housing
authority, chaos erupted. Ramos said that the mayor had said in
April that his administration would consult with tenants of public
housing before making any new appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not say that,'' Russo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said you would meet with the residents,'' Ramos repeated.
``That's what you said, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it is not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Several others joined the fray. Russo accused Ramos, whose ward
contains most of the city's public housing, of being lax in his
duties. Ramos, who took several months off to fight Hodgkin's, took
offense. The council president, Nellie Moyeno, banged her gavel
until the room echoed like a construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually things calmed down. Rodriguez, beaming, was sworn in
and accepted hugs or kisses from all nine council members,
including Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, though, Russo got into a shouting match
with the head of the public housing tenants' association, Linda
Walker, who was also upset at not being consulted on Rodriguez's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ab-so-lute-ly pos-i-tive-ly wrong!'' Walker boomed.
For the mayor to hold a meeting on the eve of the school board
election and make promises to the residents of public housing just
to get their votes to put his wife in office, she said, then to
just disregard that promise __
</P>
<P>
   ``Every promise I ever made in the seven years that I've been
mayor has been kept, Linda!'' Russo yelled, nearly drowning her out
even though she had the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he accused Walker of being on the payroll of
one of his archrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Walker said that cancer had indeed changed Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone straight to the devil,'' she said. ``As far as
making amends and trying to make sure he doesn't land on a
pitchfork when he goes, forget it. He's worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in his office, Russo basked in the afterglow of his
outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a reprieve for me,'' he said. ``There was a little
action. It got my mind off things.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the test results came in. There was no active
cancer anywhere. Even the nodules in his lungs, where doctors
believed the cancer started, were benign, though Russo has been
directed to have one-third of his right lung removed just to be
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Russo was ecstatic and grateful.
</P>
<P>
   The news was greeted in the true Hoboken spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen the tests?'' asked a skeptical member of the
opposing camp. ``Some people believe that he's just announcing this
to keep his troops from starting to rally against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And another thing. If these things in his lungs are dormant,
why are they being removed?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
