<HEADLINE>
ONE KILLED AND 17 HURT IN NEW YORK SPATE OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 12-year-old boy who was shot in the face on a South
Bronx basketball court was one of 18 people shot or stabbed in
apparently unrelated attacks in an unusually fierce seven-hour
eruption of street violence that ended early Saturday morning, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The night of shootings and stabbings, which left one person dead
and two critically wounded, comes at a time when overall reported
crime _ which includes homicide, rape, robbery, assault and theft _
is at a record low and continuing to drop, according to police
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But police officials have been vexed by a stubborn but small
increase in the murder rate and the number of shootings, despite an
intense and controversial narcotics crackdown that officials have
said was intended to reduce street violence.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents began at about 9 p.m. Friday with the shooting of
the 12-year-old and a 22-year-old man in the Melrose Houses, a
low-income development at E. 155th Street and Courtlandt Avenue,
and continued steadily throughout the night in the Bronx, Brooklyn
and Queens until just after 4 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
