<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIRL-CANCER-ART-NY     06-10 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIRL-CANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-GRADER WITH LEUKEMIA TEACHES TOWN LESSON ON COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARRYTOWN, N.Y. _ Aria Lams was matter of fact about her
illness: ``I've been sick since I was a little girl,'' she told her
first-grade classmates last fall. ``I had lost my hair. But now I'm
better.''
</P>
<P>
   She had had leukemia since she was 3{, and after more than two
years of treatment was in remission. Her teacher, Lori Blueglass,
gave a party in class with about 40 students and teachers. Aria and
her brother, Jordan, a fifth-grader, danced for everyone. Aria was
6 and happy.
</P>
<P>
   By January, a persistent flu turned into a fresh diagnosis of
leukemia. The news settled like fog over the all-first-grade John
Paulding School, which is usually a carnival of little people, or,
as the principal says, ``a place for toothless wonders.''
</P>
<P>
   Every school has children with adult-size problems, but a
6-year-old flirting with death gave everyone new perspective on
life. As another school year winds down, the courage of the
blue-eyed girl in pink pajamas lying in isolation at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center has reminded teachers here why they
teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always hoping we have an impact on the child,''
Blueglass said, ``but for a child to have such an impact on me _
that's the kind of thing you don't imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Aria has barely been to school since January. Blueglass has
tutored her at home, helping her with reading and projects. One
day, Blueglass arranged for Aria to come to school after dismissal,
so she could make wind chimes, like the other students had.
Janitors scrubbed the classroom to protect Aria from germs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so happy,'' remembered Blueglass, the mother of three,
including first-grade twins. ``She looked around. She said: `Look,
my name's still on my hook. My pictures are still up.' I said, `Of
course, you're still part of the class.'''
</P>
<P>
   Aria endured another round of chemotherapy and again lost her
brown hair. Doctors said her only hope was a bone marrow
transplant. Her brother turned out to be a perfect match and
willing donor. ``Whatever it takes,'' he told his father, Jeff
Lams, a musician.
</P>
<P>
   Aria returned to class for three days in May before the
transplant. She wore a straw hat with a flower. A piece of tissue
inside kept the straw from scratching her head. She took off the
hat and hung it on the hook under her name. Some children didn't
recognize her at first, but then they realized it was just Aria.
``She didn't have any hair,'' her classmate, Jonathan, said the
other day, wrestling with a difficult idea, ``but it counts on the
inside more.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the moment Blueglass learned the lesson of Aria. Here
was a little girl, bald and vulnerable, yet buoyant. ``I don't know
that I could have done what she did,'' Blueglass said, ``come in
here and take off her hat and hang it on her hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Aria floated down the hall, greeting people. Her classmates
protectively whispered to Blueglass that some children had giggled
at Aria's baldness. But Aria was oblivious. In a picture she drew
of herself in class, she is wearing bold purple and orange clothes
and a distinctive purple hat. ``It's a sign of happiness,''
Blueglass said.
</P>
<P>
   After the third day at school, Aria went to the hospital for the
transplant. ``I picked her up that afternoon,'' said Lams, ``and
there was hugging and tears. Kids, the principal, teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Aria's hospital room is adorned with signs of a community
caring. There are cards from family friends at the First Baptist
Church of Tarrytown, letters from children, stuffed animals, an
enlarged $5,000 check representing money raised by raffling a quilt
made by a Paulding teacher, Mary Kate McCabe. Classmates call and
Aria's kindergarten teacher, Karen Garibaldi, telephones daily and
works on spelling with her.
</P>
<P>
   Aria is scheduled to come home soon, but she won't be able to
return to class this school year. Even so, said the principal,
Marilyn Mercado-Belvin, the year will be remembered as the one Aria
``taught us all about strength and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Blueglass is making sure Aria doesn't miss all the year-end
activities _ like publishing her first book.
</P>
<P>
   Aria's book, ``Big Bear,'' is about a family skiing trip. In the
book, there is no fear, only fun. ``We went down a hill with nets
at the bottom to catch us if we went too far,'' Aria wrote.
</P>
<P>
   With Aria in the hospital, Blueglass wrote the book's ``About
the Author'' page. ``I am in first grade at John Paulding School,''
it reads. ``I like to sing, dance and act. My best friend is
Laura.'' Then, drawing on the hope Aria taught her, Blueglass
wrote, ``I can't wait to start second grade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
