<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARRIER-HOTEL-REAL-NY     06-10 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARRIER-HOTEL-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN CHICAGO, FROM PRINTING PLANT TO TECHNOLOGY HUB 
</HEADLINE>
   By JILL SCHACHNER CHANEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A landmark building that once housed the country's
largest commercial printing facility is now being converted into a
mammoth ``carrier hotel'' housing multiple telecommunications and
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   When renovation of the onetime R.R. Donnelly &AMP; Sons Calumet
Plant into the Lakeside Technology Center is completed this fall,
it will hold what the developers say is the country's largest
planned carrier hotel. It will offer more than 1.1 million square
feet of space devoted to the technical needs of telecommunications
providers and Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-story, English Gothic-style Calumet Plant has been a
fixture on Chicago's lakefront since it was built in the early 20th
century as part of the historic Lakeside Press printing complex
that was once owned by R.R. Donnelly. Publications including Life
magazine, Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.'s Big Book catalog and the Yellow
Pages were printed in the complex before operations there ceased in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly relocated its corporate headquarters from the complex
to downtown Chicago in 1992 following the city's condemnation of
part of the complex to expand the McCormick Place convention
center. The company also moved most of its remaining printing work
to its other printing facilities throughout Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of the Lakeside Technology Center say that the market
for these kinds of facilities is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that this was a relatively underserved market in
general and in Chicago specifically,'' said Robert Stuckey,
managing director of the Carlyle Group in Washington, which is
developing the property in a joint venture with Core Location of
Bethesda, Md. ``We felt that Chicago is a tier-one
telecommunications hub, along with New York, San Francisco and Los
Angeles, and that there was pent-up demand here that was not being
served.''
</P>
<P>
   The onetime Lakeside Press complex, he said, ``had certain
physical and technological features that set it apart from
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrier hotels have unusual operational requirements, including
multiple power sources, numerous ventilation outlets and floors
capable of bearing heavy loads. Tenants of these facilities need to
have self-contained heating, cooling and ventilation systems as
well as extraordinary amounts of electric power and individualized
security systems, said David B. Larson, a senior project architect
for McClier Construction in Chicago, which is reconstructing the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Calumet Plant was built as an industrial facility,
the building was ripe for transformation. It offered 14-foot
ceiling heights, floors capable of bearing 250 pounds per square
foot and approximately 30 existing shafts to allow McClier to adapt
them as vertical risers for chilled water, electric wiring and
exhaust, Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the plant is just blocks away from the North
American fiber-optic long-haul route, a major transcontinental
fiber-optic cable route. The proximity will allow the building's
tenants easy access to the fiber- optic infrastructure that they
need to run their businesses, said Michael Jacoby, president of
Core Location, a developer of carrier hotels, data centers and
other high-tech buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The developers say that the renovation of this fabled building
into the largest carrier hotel in the country is somewhat ironic,
given that it was built as the largest producer of a different kind
of communications. Built in four stages between 1912 and 1929, the
Calumet Plant _ named for its location at the intersection of
Calumet Avenue and 22nd Street on the South Side of Chicago along
the Illinois Central Railroad tracks that follow the Lake Michigan
shoreline _ doubled Donnelly's printing capacity. It also contained
Donnelly's executive offices, an art gallery and a library.
</P>
<P>
   The developers plan to restore the building's Gothic-style
executive offices and library and will allow tenants to use them
for meetings. Some 600 printers' marks, decorative stone shields
depicting printers' tools that once decorated the facade of the
building over the main entrance, will also be restored, Jacoby
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Calumet Plant remained an active printing press plant for
Donnelly until 1993, when Sears discontinued production of its Big
Book catalog and company executives decided that operating the
plant, which was spread over eight floors, was no longer
economically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Donnelly sold the rest of the Lakeside Press complex,
which included the Calumet Plant, to Landmark America, a Portland,
Maine, development company. The company originally planned to
develop the property into a mixed-use development, though
construction has not begun on any of the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Landmark America sold the Calumet Plant to Core Location and the
Carlyle Group last year for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago officials, who once worried about the vacant Lakeside
Press buildings, are applauding the transformation of the Calumet
Plant because it has helped propel an ambitious plan by Mayor
Richard M. Daley to position the city as a leader in technology. To
spur that growth, the city provided the building's developers with
a $3 million energy grant to help subsidize the costs of
construction. An additional $1 million in tax abatements was given
to the building's anchor tenant, Global Center of San Jose, Calif.,
a Web-hosting Internet services company, as an incentive to cement
the deal, said Jimm Dispensa, assistant commissioner of the
technology development unit of the city's Department of Planning
and Development.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Johnson, vice president of design and construction for
Global Center, a unit of Global Crossing, a fiber-optic network,
said that the tax-increment funds had little to do with the
company's decision to lease space in the carrier hotel, however.
The company, which leased the center's 135,000-square-foot third
floor, had been looking for a carrier hotel to house its operations
in Chicago for some time. ``We have studies that tell us what
particular arenas in the world we should be in,'' Johnson said.
``Chicago rated high in terms of what we could get for a customer
base and for its proximity to fiber.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Global Center would like to double the amount of
space it leased in the carrier hotel but would be unable to because
the 1.1 million-square-foot building was already 75 percent leased.
Rentals in the building range from $26 to $40 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Other tenants include 360networks, a fiber-optic network, and
Qwest Communications and Level 3 Communications, both
telecommunications companies, according to Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   David Love, senior vice president of network operations for the
Vancouver-based 360networks, said that his company decided to lease
space in the building because of its proximity to its own cable
network. The company said that it would use its space to drop off
its voice and data traffic and pick up other traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a number of other carriers like us are in the
building'' was a plus, Love said. ``It makes it so easy to share
traffic with them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the developers' research had shown a need for this
kind of space in Chicago, they say they were being taken by
surprise by the demand for the space. ``We thought it would take
three years to lease this much space,'' Stuckey said. ``It looks
like it will lease up in one year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
