<HEADER>
A0429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SCHOOL-TESTING-NYT     06-10 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-TESTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUGING THE MEANING OF GYRATING SCHOOL TEST SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In this era of standardized student testing, it has
become an all-too-familiar ritual in New York City and across the
country: the leader of the school system calls a news conference
and holds a wedding or a funeral, crowing if scores are up,
grieving and accepting blame if they are down.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, most New York City chancellors have been able to
do a bit of both. Test results can be relied on to rise some years
and fall others. For parents and many teachers, the constant
ratcheting up and down of scores _ testing experts call it the
sawtooth effect _ is confusing and exhausting, if not dispiriting.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a reality test last week when Harold Levy, New York's
newly appointed chancellor, greeted two successive waves of good
news on testing _ a nine-point rise on a statewide test and a
five-point rise on a citywide test _ by urging caution. Levy
half-joked that he would post bar charts in the lobby of 110
Livingston Street in Brooklyn, headquarters of the Board of
Education, where, like a corporation reporting to stockholders, the
school system would be forced to expose its long-term gains and
losses.
</P>
<P>
   In the war of perception against reality, almost nothing can be
harder to gauge than the meaning of test scores. It seems only
common sense that a system of 78,000 teachers and 1.1 million
school children _ or, as Levy likes to point out, one out of 43
schoolchildren in America _ is too big an oceanliner to turn around
in just a year. Is the curriculum new and wonderful? Did the
quality of teachers improve? There is no systemic evidence of
either. Yet, parents and teachers are encouraged to judge their
children and schools the way investors watch the Dow industrials go
up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a quantifiable aspect to testing that is so
seductive,'' said Gary Lincoff, the father of a fifth-grader in
Manhattan. ``If a kid does well and scores high, you can dismiss
the tests as meaningless, because you're happy. But if your kid
gets a low score, you suspect he isn't getting it and blame
yourself, your child, or go the other way and blame the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success in America is like a quiz show. It's how to be a
millionaire, and there's usually a number in there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more sophisticated view, experts say, is that it is
almost impossible to attribute real meaning to a one-year gain in
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City reading test seems a particularly clear case
in point. Both New York City and New York state are now in their
second year of a new reading test, and experts say it is almost
axiomatic that scores go up in the second year of a test.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, in the first year of the new state test, 32.8
percent of New York City's fourth-graders and 56.8 percent of the
fourth-graders in the rest of the state met state standards for
reading and writing. A week ago, the state released this year's
results, showing that 41.7 percent of fourth-graders in New York
City met the standards, a gain of 9 percentage points, as did 68.2
percent in the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, the results of New York City's separate reading
test for grades 3, 5, 6 and 7 came out, offering some corroboration
of the rise in performance. On the city test, 40.8 percent of
students met the standards, up from 35.7 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Every district and almost every school in New York City
improved. But despite the overall improvement, schools at the
bottom stayed at the bottom and schools at the top remained at the
top.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimists point out that the scores still mean that 6 out of 10
students in New York City, mostly impoverished black and Hispanic
students, are not meeting city and state standards for reading and
writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools, what I call the dead zone schools, just seem
stuck at the bottom,'' said Raymond Domanico, education consultant
to the Metro Industrial Areas Foundation, a coalition of New York
civic and church groups. ``They were dysfunctional, they continue
to be dysfunctional, and they won't reap the benefits of any of
these systemic efforts until we get more highly qualified teachers
and principals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education, in its press release, ascribed the rise
in scores to a variety of causes: from more diagnostic reading
tests and expanded prekindergarten to reduced class size and
after-school reading classes. But as David Liben, principal of the
Family Academy in Harlem, pointed out, ``You have to look at this
like Sherlock Holmes.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy defended testing as a crude if necessary check on the
system, yet sided with the skeptics in suggesting that a one-year
gain revealed very little about the condition of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to identify causality with any certainty,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of standardized testing use widespread fluctuations to
argue that tests are meaningless and should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   But others, echoing Levy, warn that test results matter most in
the long term. From the 1960s to the '90s, performance on
standardized tests declined in New York City as schoolchildren
became poorer and dropout rates went up. Though both the dropout
rates and test scores have shown a slight improvement in recent
years, as the economy has improved, it is too early, experts say,
to conclude that the change reflects real progress in the school
system.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said that rather than focusing on test results, he wanted
to focus on hiring, encouraging and retaining good teachers,
principals and superintendents. ``In business,'' he said, ``you
call it management.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
