<HEADER>
A0430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOAT-FARR-40-NYT &LR;      06-10 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-FARR-40-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A POOL OF AMERICA'S CUP TALENT, AN AUSSIE TEAM RIDES HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Skirting the racecourse in these famed sailing
waters, the Sayonara, the maxi-yacht owned by the billionaire Larry
Ellison of San Francisco, was easily the most conspicuous vessel in
the spectator fleet taking in last week's Farr 40 world
championships, which finished on Friday with an impressive victory
by the Australian John Calvert-Jones' Southern Star.
</P>
<P>
   The Farr 40 series _ named for the designer Bruce Farr and his
simple, fast and identical 40-footers _ may be the premier pro-am
circuit in yacht racing.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-kept secret in sailing, according to the dockside
chatter in Newport, is that Ellison, the founder of Oracle, the
computer software company, is on the cusp of announcing his
challenge for the 2003 America's Cup. If Ellison is indeed in the
market for cup talent, he came to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   The professional tacticians in the 27-boat Farr fleet included
the cup-winning Kiwi star Brad Butterworth, the America One skipper
Paul Cayard and seasoned cup competitors like Tom Whidden, John
Kostecki, Peter Holmberg and Terry Hutchinson of the United States,
and the Australians Rob Brown and Grant Simmer, who played major
roles when Australia won the cup off Newport in 1983. It was
Simmer, one of the world's most underrated sailors, calling the
shots on the victorious Southern Star.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Farr 40 class rules, the onboard pros (in the
10-person crew, just four are allowed) can call tactics and trim
sails, but only the boat's owner is permitted to steer. So it is
not unusual in a frenzied mark rounding to see the likes of a
Butterworth or a Whidden hunched behind a helmsman barking a stream
of instructions. Driving a Farr 40 can be sailing's equivalent of
having Tiger Woods caddie for you in the club championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner-driver rule has really raised the skill level of all
the owners in the class,'' said John Thompson, whose Solution took
fifth in the regatta. ``You can be 15th or 20th in a given race and
when you look around you see an awful lot of good guys around
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Thompson, John Kilroy _ his defending class champion, Samba
Pa Ti, finished second this year _ traded down from a string of
larger grand prix racers to join the Farr 40 contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 35 years sailboat racing all over the world in maxis
and other classes and it got to the point where I was exhausted by
changing keels and rigs all the time to remain competitive,'' he
said. ``But this boat has brought back the fun of sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a Farr 40 is not inexpensive, Geoff Stagg of Farr
International said a race-ready boat with sails and electronics
costs about $315,000. The class is growing rapidly. The builder
Barry Carroll makes three a month, and by next year the worldwide
fleet will number over 110 vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a lot of money, but a custom 40-foot racer will
run over 700 grand,'' Stagg said. ``So there's a lot of value
there. And all the boats are dead-nuts even. So at the end of the
day, there are no excuses. The owners in this class are wealthy,
driven, successful people. If they have a bad regatta, they know
there's no one else to point at. They have to get better. And
because of who they are, that's what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   If the owner-driver rule is one of the class cornerstones, so
too is the simplicity of the design. ``It's got a swept-back
carbon-fiber rig with small jibs and no running backstays,'' said
the pro racer Robbie Haines, who called tactics on George
Andreadis' third-place Atalanti.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of last week's event, the sailors were tested in
conditions ranging from Tuesday's bleak, unseasonable, 30-knot
northeaster to Friday's classic 15-knot smoky southwesterly. The
top spot on the leader board changed continually until the crew
aboard Southern Star sealed the championship with third- and
fourth-place finishes on the final day of racing. ``Our team was
fantastic, and Grant did a superb job of getting us around the
course,'' said the winning skipper, Calvert-Jones, referring to
Simmer.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the week's synergy, rumor had it that Bruce Farr
would design Ellison's America's Cup racers if he decides to
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   If Ellison's goal is to win the cup, it was apparent last week
that there are plenty of skilled hired guns out there. But if
Ellison's aim is to become a better sailor, he should consider
buying a Farr 40.
</P>
<P>
   Making Waves
</P>
<P>
   Next Friday, up to 190 boats are expected to cross the starting
line to begin the 42nd sailing of the biennial 635-mile
Newport-Bermuda race, organized by the Cruising Club of America and
the Royal Bermuda Yacht Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
