<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HABITAT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: 3 DOT-COM PARTNERS FIND 4-STORY HOUSE IN THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All those baby boomers who envy the wealth of the
young Internet moguls can take solace, at least, in this: the
dot-commers may live in fabulous places, but they often work so
hard they have little time to exploit the opportunities for fun
their good fortune presents.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, John Galbraith and Chi-Lin Chang decided to start
an Internet company that would allow people to browse and shop
privately, without revealing name, e-mail address or credit card
information to individual vendors. They quickly raised money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a financial background,'' said Galbraith, 24, who had
worked at a brokerage company and a financial Internet site. And,
he said, ``some of my family's friends are in the venture-capital
world.'' Chang, 21 and like Galbraith a New Yorker, decided to take
a leave from his junior year at Columbia, where he is majoring in
economics. He had met Galbraith when they were both working on
Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   In January, money in hand, they brought in Bill Holmberg, 25,
who had gone to Georgetown University with Galbraith (no relation
to the economist John Kenneth Galbraith). They began looking for a
place for their new company, Incogniti Inc., that could be both
office and home.
</P>
<P>
   The three young men, who swivel seamlessly in midconversation to
answer telephones, started in the usual way, checking
advertisements and meeting with brokers. In a story that is
becoming eerily familiar, they told of going with one broker who
took them to a large sweatshop and promised that if they rented the
space, all the people would be gone in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they hooked up with Lake Shaw, a broker for
CitiHabitats, who took them to a 34-story building in the financial
district that is handled by her company. The former office
building, at 100 John St., was renovated and turned into
apartments. But what she showed the three men was hardly a regular
place.
</P>
<P>
   It is a house in the sky, a meandering four-story penthouse with
four bedrooms, six bathrooms, huge windows giving views in three
directions, and a rooftop terrace shared with the rest of the
building but contiguous with their space.
</P>
<P>
   They immediately took the penthouse, which rents for $9,500 a
month, and because their business had no financial history, paid a
year's rent in advance. The original rent being asked was $15,000 a
month, they said, and someone had taken it at that price but backed
out when it became clear that the roof deck was shared.
</P>
<P>
   They use their first floor, the former living room, as an
office, with space for a half-dozen desks and a conference room.
</P>
<P>
   They are working on readying their site, www.ivanish.com, which
is scheduled to launch in September. Internet users will be able to
log on to ivanish.com and type in their destinations from there,
and they will be able to shop by revealing their personal data and
credit card information only to this company, and not to the actual
vendors who sell them merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch tends to be things like Tortino's pizza rolls, cooked in
the microwave. Upstairs on the middle two floors each of them has a
large bedroom and private bath; the top floor is an entertainment
center, leading to the deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for single guys,'' said Chang. ``But a family is
not going to want to live here.'' The neighborhood has few
children, he says, and lacks stores and services, although a large
grocery store called Jubilee, with good vegetables and fruit, and a
range of upscale products and organic foods, just opened up the
street. ``Jubilee is like a haven,'' Chang said.
</P>
<P>
   They liked the penthouse because it was ready to go, not a raw
space. And if they ever have time, they'll take advantage of its
spectacular views of Manhattan, looking north. ``We haven't had any
dinner parties yet,'' Galbraith said. ``But every time we achieve a
big milestone we want to have a big party.''
</P>
<P>
   The three start working every morning at about 9 and continue
until about 10 at night. ``Since we're here, we can work all the
time,'' Galbraith said. And there's no wasted time. ``What I love
is that the commute is quick and easy,'' Chang said.''And there's a
gym downstairs. That keeps me sane.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood, he said, ``gets very barren at night and on
weekends.'' Not that it matters, really. ``When I go out ...,''
Chang said, ``well, I'm usually too lazy to get out of my room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
