<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HORSES-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21 HORSES DIE IN BROOKLYN STABLE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fire officials Saturday were investigating the cause
of a fire that gutted the Bergen Beach Stables, a century-old horse
barn in the Mill Basin section of Brooklyn, killing 21 horses.
</P>
<P>
   The two-alarm fire broke out shortly before midnight Friday,
engulfing the wooden 46-stall barn at 1364 East 66th St. in 30-foot
flames. Responding, 121 firefighters were called to the scene and
brought the fire under control by 1 a.m., fire officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   First Deputy Fire Commissioner William Feehan, speaking at a
news conference at the stable, said that investigators had no
evidence of foul play, but officials still had not determined how
the fire had started. Barns are not required to have a sprinkler
system, he said, and the barn was filled with hay, so flames moved
furiously through the stables.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not determined whether it's accidental or
suspicious,'' Feehan said. ``And there's nothing at this point that
leads us to believe it's anything other than accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters rescued two of the 24 horses in the barn, including
a badly burned pony belonging to the owner of the stables, Karen
Facciolo. She got a call from a neighbor and arrived at the scene
before the Fire Department, watching in horror as her stables went
up in flames with the horses trapped in their stalls. A couple who
live next to the barn saw smoke rising from the stables and managed
to rescue another horse by ripping apart the door to its stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole top of the barn was up in flames,'' said Facciolo,
who has owned the stables for 16 years. ``It was gone, gone. The
middle of the barn looked like a volcano.''
</P>
<P>
   Horse owners who were in the barn hours before the fire said
that all the electricity had been shut off when the horses were put
in their stalls for the night and that no flammable liquids were
kept inside the stables.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergen Beach Stables was the last of three sets of stables
in the neighborhood near Jamaica Bay, where many residents grew up
riding along Bergen Beach or brought their children and
grandchildren to watch the horses munching on hay and trotting
around the paddocks. One stable, a few blocks away, burned down in
1968, killing 54 horses and setting 50 others loose. Another stable
in the area closed shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   Several horse owners joined Facciolo early Saturday morning and
watched as horse carcasses, some of them weighing up to 2,000
pounds, were hauled out of the smoky wreckage with forklifts. By
late morning, a dozen emotionally devastated horse owners and young
riders stood on the street at the edge of the 3-acre property, now
filled with the barely recognizable remains of the stable built in
1901, as the smell of manure and burned wood wafted through the
air. Some of the owners clutched pictures of their horses,
consoling each other and talking about the possibility of raising
money to rebuild the barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a horror, it's just a horror,'' said Irene O'Brien,
who said she lost a bay quarter horse named Added Incentive.
O'Brien said she had kept that horse in the stables for the past
five years, along with two others that she was leasing for her
daughters to ride.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said she had left the stable with Facciolo at 9 p.m.
Friday _ just hours before the blaze broke out _ after completing
what had become a nightly ritual: taking her horse out to graze,
locking him in his stall for the night and feeding him a few
carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Rizzo said he had kept two quarter horses, a mare and her
offspring, at the stable for 15 years, and spent hours each day in
the barn. He said he had renovated their stalls to include
skylights, fans and varnished walls. Rizzo said that when he
learned early Saturday that the horses, Babe and Dancer, had died
in the fire, he felt like he had lost ``my daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the dead horses, Belgian Draft Horses named Jake and
Betty, belonged to the City of New York Parks and Recreation
department, which was boarding them at the Bergen Beach Stables
while they trained for the department's mounted park patrol. The
death of the horses leaves the department with eight for the
mounted park patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just very sorry that we lost two fine horses,'' said
parks Commissioners Henry J. Stern
</P>
<P>
   Two of the surviving horses were taken to the Brooklyn Mounted
Police Troop E Headquarters in Brighton Beach, where they were
being treated by a private veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Facciolo said she was keeping her pony, Dino, who was badly
burned in the fire, in her backyard, a few blocks from the stable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
