<P>
   SOUTH-DROUGHT _ Recent trips down two of Georgia's major rivers
show first-hand the effects of the drought. On a canoe trip down a
three-mile stretch of the Flint River, water levels are so low that
participants have to get out and drag their boats half the way.
Meanwhile, along the Chattahoochee River, boaters must put in at
Newnan because water levels are so low upstream. We report on these
and other environmental effects of the drought. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDDIE-EAGLE _ WASHINGTON _ Some call him ``Joe Camel with
feathers.'' Others call him a key to protecting children from the
dangers of guns. His name is ``Eddie Eagle,'' and the National
Rifle Association wants him in your schools. We take a look at the
recent controversy surrounding the NRA's cartoon mascot, who has
been around for a long time but has never faced this much
opposition. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). With illustration of
``Eddie Eagle.''
