<HEADER>
A0436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-1STLD-WR     06-10 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AIDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA IN QUANDARY: SHOULD GAYS DONATE BLOOD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite lede.)  
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Endowed with a bill of rights that
is one of the world's most expansive and beset by an AIDS crisis
that is one of world's worst, South Africa finds itself trying to
reconcile the two in the face of a challenge to its practice of
disqualifying gay men from giving blood.
</P>
<P>
   The South African Human Rights Commission has concluded that
under the country's liberal, 4-year-old Constitution, men who have
sex with other men cannot for that reason alone be disqualified as
blood donors, as they are here and in most countries, including the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's blood banks have so far refused to abide by the
commission's opinion, and the two sides are searching for a
compromise. But if they cannot find some common ground, the matter
could end up in court, pitting the constitutional freedoms that
many here died struggling for against the epidemic that so many
here are now dying from.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, which has a population estimated at about 44
million, the rate of new infections is among the highest on the
continent, and the spread of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, is
perhaps the most serious threat to the country's future.
</P>
<P>
   A safe blood supply is essential to containing the crisis, and
for the people who run the blood banks that responsibility can mean
hard decisions and hurt feelings. Understanding as they say they
are of the pain their policies can cause, they make no apologies
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to maintain the safety of the blood supply, and
worldwide there are certain risk factors that would compromise that
safety,'' said Anthon Heyns, medical director of the South African
Blood Transfusion Service, which is based here and is the largest
of the country's six blood banks, supplying about 60 percent of the
nation's blood.
</P>
<P>
   One of those risk factors is male-to-male sex, according to the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration, which regulates the blood supply
in the United States and helps set the standards used in much of
the world. Others include using intravenous drugs, having sex with
prostitutes and traveling in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the risk factors, however, have drawn the kind of
impassioned criticism that has periodically surfaced toward the ban
on men who have had sex with other men.
</P>
<P>
   For activists, the case will be an important test of the
Constitution, which is unequivocal in its protection of the civil
rights of gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an infringement on gay men's rights, and what's the worth
of the Constitution if people's rights are not being protected,''
said Carrie Shelver, director of the National Coalition for Gay and
Lesbian Equality, an umbrella organization of about 50 groups
around the country. ``It's really based on stereotypes, and the
stereotype is that gay men are promiscuous.''
</P>
<P>
   The case here began almost a year ago after a gay man filed a
complaint with the Human Rights Commission alleging discrimination
on the part of the Cape Town blood bank that rejected him because
he said he had sex with another man at least once in the previous
five years.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the matter for several months, the commission
handed down its opinion earlier this year, saying blood banks could
not exclude men who have sex with other men from giving blood. Such
men, the commission said, are no more of a risk to a safe blood
supply than any number of other groups for whom there are no such
restrictions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think the Human Rights Commission is spot on,'' said Udo
Schuklenk, the director of the bioethics program at the University
of the Witwatersrand here and the co-editor of the magazine
Bioethics. ``The problem is, you're discriminating against people.
Equal risk is being treated unequally.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuklenk says the questions asked of prospective donors need to
be more specific about their sexual practices _ for instance,
whether the sex was unprotected by a condom _ in order to discern
the risk to the blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the current restrictions say that even that is not
enough. ``We cast a wide safety net, and inevitably with a safety
net you are going to unfortunately pull in people who would
otherwise be safe donors,'' said Dr. Arthur Bird, medical director
of the Western Province Blood Transfusion Service in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has said that it would like to see a study done
on the prevalence of HIV among gay men here to see if South Africa
is indeed justified in following the guidelines laid down by public
health authorities in the United States and other countries where
the infection patterns have shown marked difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
