<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-YESHIVAS-EXPAND-1STLD     06-10 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YESHIVAS-EXPAND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTHODOX JEWISH EDUCATION FLOURISHING IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change `hundreds' to `scores of' in 2nd graf. Minor
rewrite of same sentence.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) (Eds. `chavrusa' in 15th graf is foreign
expression) By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Down a narrow lane near the western outskirts of
this city, wood-framed country houses and arching trees impart a
rural feel, giving no hint that nearby is a place where a special
kind of intellectual intensity rules the day.
</P>
<P>
   But past a park can be seen the functional beige buildings of
Ner Israel Rabbinical College, where the study hall reverberates
with the voices of scores of young Orthodox Jewish men, debating
one-on-one, across tables stacked high with books of Jewish law and
tradition. It is an activity that occupies students here morning,
afternoon and evening, Sundays through Fridays, before the start of
the Jewish sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not how much ground you cover,'' explained Isaac
Greenberg, 21, a pile of well-thumbed texts at his elbow, ``but how
you understand it and how you incorporate it in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a scene was a staple of Eastern European Jewish life a
century ago, when yeshivas _ traditional academies for the study of
Judaism's authoritative texts _ flourished. But rather than merely
reflecting the past, what is happening here is part of a growing
trend within Orthodox Judaism's most rigorously traditional sector.
</P>
<P>
   The number of collegiate and graduate students pursuing
religious studies in these all-male institutions ``has probably
almost doubled'' since 1980, to about 18,000 nationwide, writes
William Helmreich in a new edition of his book ``The World of the
Yeshiva,'' from Ktav Publishing House, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Helmreich, who teaches sociology at City College of New York and
the City University Graduate Center, said in an interview that the
growth is primarily because of a high birthrate among the adherents
of Orthodox Judaism, and greater economic prosperity that allows
them to provide more financial support to these institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews account for about 7 percent of the nation's 5.5
million Jews, but within that area of Judaism, a shift has been
occurring. As yeshiva enrollments have grown, so too has the
religious influence of the right wing _ at the expense of
Orthodoxy's once-dominant modern wing, which holds that Jews can be
fully observant and highly involved in wider American society.
</P>
<P>
   While modern Orthodox young people have become doctors, lawyers
and other white-collar professionals, sociologists like Helmreich
say, the right wing has been turning out a high number of rabbis
and religious school teachers, who in turn help shape the religious
lives of many in Orthodoxy's next generation.
</P>
<P>
   At Ner Israel, many people see growth around them.
</P>
<P>
   Yaakov Feinstein, 26, of New York City, a student of Talmudic
law, said he has seen the college add a dormitory and faculty
housing during the past dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more than Ner Israel, I think the total community
is growing,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the college, he said, ``We're really here to be
God-fearing Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Ner Israel was founded in Baltimore in 1933 by Rabbi Jacob
Ruderman, a Lithuanian immigrant, who began with 15 students. Now,
800 boys and young men attend the high school, collegiate and
graduate programs. The college's enrollment has grown by 50 percent
since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Among yeshivas, Ner Israel is unusual in that it has always
allowed students access to secular, professional education. The
college is accredited by the state of Maryland and has agreements
with public and private universities at which its students can
major in law, business and other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The roster of recent alumni includes bankers, accountants and
psychologists _ as well as rabbis and religious school teachers,
who college officials say make up 50 percent of graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Ner Israel's mission statement makes clear that its priority is
religious studies. Students pursuing secular degrees are asked to
limit their work to nights or summer. The college's purpose, the
statement says, is to preserve ``a rarified environment'' for
dedication to ``intense Torah study.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of that study is chavrusa, students working in
pairs, each young man selecting a partner based on intellectual and
social compatibility. In the daily debate over religious texts lies
educational growth, college officials say.
</P>
<P>
   How long do they spend in this kind of study? ``I'd say you've
got to figure eight hours a day, at least on average,'' said Rabbi
Ezra Neuberger, dean of the graduate school. ``The more diligent
would be a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hill from the academic buildings is a residential area
called Yeshiva Lane, where modestly dressed women with head
coverings supervise flocks of children outside the six-bedroom town
houses and three-bedroom apartments, built for faculty and graduate
students.
</P>
<P>
   The sight suggests a self-contained community, but the college
has built ties to Orthodox Jews worldwide. Since the revolution in
Iran two decades ago, it has taken in Iranian Jewish refugees.
Nearly 50 study here now, said one of their rabbis, who asked not
to be named out of concern for relatives in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others from overseas, too. ``There are a lot of
South Americans here, a lot of Europeans, a lot of Australians,''
said Rafael Mael, 20, of Baltimore. ``I've roomed with people from
Chile and Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   A person who has helped foster ties to Latin American
communities is Moshe Filler, 34, who came from Mexico City and
enrolled in Ner Israel to study as a teacher some years ago. Now he
runs programs that bring young Latin American Jews to study for the
summer on campus, while maintaining the college's links with Jewish
communities in Bolivia, Costa Rica, Peru and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become like a center for all these communities,''
Filler said.
</P>
<P>
   His job involves considerable travel. ``Last week I was in
Chile,'' he said. ``Today, I go to Guatemala.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuition at Ner Israel is $9,000 a year, but only a minority of
students pay full cost. The college considers its applicants first,
then finds out if those it accepts can pay, said Rabbi Herman N.
Neuberger, the president. ``We feel we do make a contribution to
the spiritual life of America through training of our young men,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many students have come here from Orthodox day schools. But some
have taken a different route.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latter is Gil Neuman, 31, who arrived last October
after two years' study in Israel. Before that, he worked in
Hollywood, producing and writing films.
</P>
<P>
   But his life changed one Friday evening when he attended a
Sabbath dinner at the home of a Ner Israel graduate, where, he
said, he was deeply impressed with the religious lives of those he
met.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had a sense of purpose and a sense of meaning that
nobody has in today's world,'' Neuman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
