<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 10, 2000 -- RAC-CURULE -- Godolphin
Racing Inc. stable dominates the European circuit. There are more
than 100 thoroughbreds at Godolphin's Al Quoz Racing Stable, and
industry experts estimate most of them to be worth $1 million or
more. Curule, out of the Godolphin Racing Inc. stable, being washed
down after a morning workout at Belmont Park. (Barton Silverman/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 10, 2000 -- NY-SCHOOL-TESTING -- Harold
O. Levy, New York's newly appointed chancellor, greeted two
successive waves of good news on testing _ a 9-point rise on a
statewide test and a 5-point rise on a citywide test _ by urging
caution. In the war of perception against reality, almost nothing
can be harder to gauge than the meaning of test scores. In fact,
experts say that it is almost impossible to attribute real meaning
to a one-year gain in scores. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- June 10, 2000 -- OBIT-GRABER -- Ted Graber,
an interior decorator popular with affluent West Coast social
figures who was chosen by Nancy Reagan to redecorate the family
quarters of the White House, died June 3 in Sonoma, Calif. at 80.
Ted Graber and Ronald Reagan in the Oval Office in 1981. (The New
York Times/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TARRYTOWN, NY -- June 10, 2000 -- NY-GIRL-CANCER -- Aria
Lams, 6, right, who has been fighting leukemia for three years,
with a classmate, Christina Rivera, at the John Paulding School in
Tarrytown, NY. (The New York Times/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BALTIMORE -- June 10, 2000 -- YESHIVA-EXPAND-2 -- Ner
Israel Rabbinical College in Baltimore, also known as a yeshiva,
the study halls reverberate with the voices of hundreds of young
Orthodox Jewish men, debating one-on-one, across tables stacked
high with books of Jewish law and tradition. This is part of a
growing trend within Orthodox Judaism's most rigorously traditional
sector. As yeshiva enrollments have grown, so too has the religious
influence of the right wing - at the expense of Orthodoxy's
once-dominant modern wing, which holds that Jews can be fully
observant and highly involved in wider American society. (Marty
Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BALTIMORE -- June 10, 2000 -- YESHIVA-EXPAND-1 -- Ner
Israel Rabbinical College in Baltimore, also known as a yeshiva,
the study halls reverberate with the voices of hundreds of young
Orthodox Jewish men, debating one-on-one, across tables stacked
high with books of Jewish law and tradition. This is part of a
