<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES COME BACK TO HAMMER THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball managers warn their players constantly that they must
be consistent in their approach, that they cannot turn on and turn
off their effort and expect to succeed. But Yankees Manager Joe
Torre cannot say this. His players have responded in almost every
pressure game the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of losing the first two games of
their interleague series with the Mets, the Yankees fell behind
Saturday before obliterating the Mets' starting pitcher, Bobby J.
Jones, and the relievers who followed, 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill and Derek Jeter each had three hits, each slugging
a home run, and Jorge Posada broke a fifth-inning tie with a
three-run homer. Andy Pettitte (6-2) was ordinary, struggling
early, but was good enough to beat Jones (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   The third and final game of this series will be placed Sunday
night, with the Yankees' David Cone _ who has not won a decision
since April _ pitching against the Mets' Mike Hampton (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner _ who did not
attend Saturday's game, after leaving Yankee Stadium in the middle
of Friday's wipeout _ is not a patient man, and if the Yankees had
lost Saturday, it might have only served to heighten his team's
interest in a superstar outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Mets have had cursory trade talks with the
Chicago Cubs about outfielder Sammy Sosa. Cubs scouts are combing
the Yankees' farm system, preparing for the possibility they may
decide to deal Sosa and ask the Yankees for a ransom in talent,
such as the top prospect Alfonso Soriano, the Class AA outfielder
Jackson Melian and others.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa would not be a perfect fit for the Yankees, being a
right-handed free swinger who strikes out a lot, and he is
expensive. His salary would make him their fourth player earning
$10 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   But he is hugely popular and a productive slugger, and the Mets
and the Yankees will pursue him, if he becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get in on everything to find out what the price
is,'' said Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's favorite player in baseball is Roger Clemens.
Pettitte lives in Texas, near Clemens. In the off-season, he drives
20 minutes daily to work out at Clemens' house. He follows Clemens
in the rotation. He follows Clemens in performance, it would seem.
</P>
<P>
   They pitched back-to-back for the first time May 12-13, and both
allowed 10 hits and six runs in four and two-thirds innings. They
both pitched complete games May 28-29. Clemens allowed six runs in
five innings on June 3, Pettitte six runs in six innings the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Their improbable parallel lives continued this weekend. Clemens
threw 30 pitches in the first inning on Friday; Pettitte labored
and threw 33 pitches in the first inning Saturday. Clemens allowed
a grand slam to Mike Piazza in the third inning on Friday night,
the Mets taking a lead, and in the third inning Saturday, Robin
Ventura bashed a two-run homer to push the Mets in front, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clemens-Pettitte symbiosis was broken in the bottom of
the third inning, for one very simple reason: whereas Al Leiter
stifled the Yankees as the Mets trounced Clemens on Friday, the
Yankees overcame Pettitte's mistakes by bashing Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was an All-Star in 1997 because he had extraordinary
control of his fastball and changeup. But he has had shoulder
surgery since then and his command is ordinary, leaving him
vulnerable. The Yankees' batters were taking monstrous hacks at him
right away, as if they were in a home run-hitting contest. O'Neill
swung hard in the first inning, and when he realized he had lifted
a harmless fly to right, he pirouetted to his left, angry with
himself, feeling as if he should have hammered the ball.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets leading, 3-2, in the bottom of the third, Jones
fell behind O'Neill, three balls and no strikes, tried flipping a
fastball over the plate and O'Neill destroyed it. Center fielder
Jay Payton retreated to the fence and created some drama, but
O'Neill was jogging, knowing he had just tied the game with his
seventh homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored twice in the fifth, Todd Zeile ripping an R.B.I.
double in the middle of the inning and then scoring on Payton's
run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte seemed to be barely hanging on, his pitch count
mounting on the hot and muggy afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But there were always more runs to get against Jones, though he
nearly got through the fifth inning that would have qualified him
for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had a runner at first and one out and Jeter took a
called third strike. But O'Neill laced a double into the gap in
right-center field, with Ricky Ledee circling the bases. Bernie
Williams ripped a single to left, O'Neill challenging the poor
throwing arm of Jason Tyner and scoring the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Mahomes was warming up in the bullpen; Jones remained in the
game, wounded, at the mercy of the hitters.
</P>
<P>
   With the count no balls and two strikes on Tino Martinez,
Williams broke from first and shortstop Kurt Abbott rushed over to
cover second _ and Martinez lined the ball just to Abbott's right,
and with his momentum carrying him toward second, Abbott could only
get the tip of his glove on Martinez's hit. First and second, two
out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' pitching coach, Dave Wallace, emerged from the dugout,
and when Jones saw him, the pitcher's body rippled with a curse.
Jones walked off, looking over his right shoulder to see who would
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mahomes, a right-hander who ran the count to 3-2 on
Posada, until he relented and threw a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Posada murders most fastballs. He murdered this fastball,
driving it about six rows into the upper deck, a homer worth three
runs. To Yankees fans among the 55,839 at Yankee Stadium, the
natural order of the world had been restored.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was just overkill: Jeter homered in the sixth inning.
The Yankees added four more runs in the seventh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
