</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COMMENTARY: SAMMY SOSA? METS YES, YANKEES NO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the middle of the Yankees-Mets interborough
weekend, Sammy Sosa's name blew in from Chicago to intrude on
conversations for at least a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old right fielder, who hit 66 and 63 homers the last
two seasons and has hit 19 so far this season, would prefer to
finish his career in Chicago, but if he and the Cubs cannot get
together on a multiyear contract for more than his current $10
million salary, he may be auctioned sooner or later to the highest
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   That highest bidder could be the Mets; it probably would not be
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Neither New York club would comment officially Saturday on
Sosa's possible availability, to avert any tampering complaints,
but Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said the idea of a
big deal before the July 31 trade deadline did not scare his team's
front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get in on everything and find out what the price
is,'' Phillips said, sitting in the Mets' dugout before their 13-5
loss Saturday at Yankee Stadium. ``If we want to make a big deal,
I'm confident we could make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips acknowledged the ``uncertainty'' in the Mets' outfield,
which Sosa's presence would surely ease. Sosa would also give the
Mets another power hitter in the middle of their batting order,
either in front of or behind their cleanup hitter, Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   During their desperate quest in recent years for a National
League pennant and a real subway series with the Yankees, the Mets'
owners have been willing to pay top dollar for a top performer, as
they have for Piazza, Robin Ventura, Al Leiter and Mike Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, again in second place in the National League East
behind the Atlanta Braves, need Sosa much more than the Yankees do
in their duel with the Boston Red Sox for first place in the
American League East.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of Sosa's recent headlines in Chicago over his next
contract and his edgy relationship with Don Baylor, the Cubs' new
manager, George Steinbrenner has asked some of his advisers whether
Sosa would be worth the Cubs' stiff price and another $10 million
to the Yankees' payroll.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Steinbrenner's confidants has suggested that
Sosa is not what the Yankees need because he strikes out too often.
With both David Cone and Roger Clemens struggling, the Yankees'
primary need is a premier pitcher, not a slugger who swings and
misses unless he hits a homer.
</P>
<P>
   As the most popular Cub since Ernie Banks, Sosa has often said
that he wants to be a ``Cub for life, like Ernie was,'' even if
that Hall of Fame slugger never played in a World Series. The Cubs
have not been in a World Series since 1945; they have not won a
World Series since 1908.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also wants to know why the Cubs, who are always rebuilding,
don't seem to want to rebuild around him and his big bat.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago cynics contend that executives of The Tribune Co., which
owns the Cubs, have fostered the Sosa controversies over his next
contract and his relationship with Baylor to grease the skids to
his eventual departure. His contract expires after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor apparently annoyed Sosa with a spring training comment
that the right fielder had deficiencies defensively. That
assessment is true, as any major league scout would tell you, but
that line did not endear the new manager to the slugger who is
cherished as this era's Cub.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has also mentioned that if the Cubs are smart, they will
sign him to a contract extension before Alex Rodriguez, the Seattle
Mariners' shortstop, goes on the free-agent market after the World
Series. Rodriguez is expected to lift baseball's top market price
to at least $20 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   But since the free-agent era began, teams that have waited to
sign their premier players have almost always paid many more
millions than they would have if they had signed that player before
he went on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that could be the very reason the Cubs are
apparently not willing to sign Sosa now. The longer the Cubs wait,
the more they can argue that they just can't afford Sosa's price,
whatever it might be.
</P>
<P>
   After all, even with Sosa, the Cubs, with a 25-37 record after
yesterday's 4-3 loss to the White Sox, are on another treadmill to
oblivion, in fourth place in the NL Central. They wouldn't be much
worse without him.
</P>
<P>
   So for all his home runs, for all his kisses to the Wrigley
Field fans, Sammy Sosa might be changing uniforms. If that happens
before the July 31 deadline, look for the Mets to explore whatever
it would take to put him in right field at Shea Stadium. And maybe
even get him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
