<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADVISES GRADUATES A FINAL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHFIELD, Minn. _ Ask not what you can do for your country.
Listen to what your country's leader has done for you.
</P>
<P>
   In his 23d and final commencement address as president, Bill
Clinton made his own accomplishments the theme of his speech to the
423 graduates and about 7,000 other spectators who endured long
lines, metal detectors, and a brief but drenching rainstorm to hear
Clinton speak Saturday at Carleton College.
</P>
<P>
   The president included inspirational remarks to the assembled
degree recipients, urging them to help end child poverty, to ``put
a human face on the global economy,'' and to encourage racial
harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the dais in the muggy weather, the president stood
and shook the hand of every graduate of what he called ``this
remarkably diverse'' class.
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of Clinton's remarks focused on his
administration's record, particularly in education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated, as he has often done in the last year of his
presidency, that the nation is in an era of unprecedented
prosperity, with the welfare rolls and the crime rate lower than
they have been in decades.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded listeners that Saturday was the one-year anniversary
of the day the Yugoslav government agreed to NATO's demands, ending
the war in Kosovo, which Clinton said ``reversed the tide of ethnic
cleansing in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of that,'' Clinton said. ``But it showed that
it's a very different world,'' one characterized by globalization
and exploding technological development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked very hard to prepare this country for the 21st
century, and now it belongs to you. It's up to you to decide what
to do with it,'' he told the graduates.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was sitting on the dais waiting to deliver his
speech, he was handed a note confirming the death of Syrian
President Hafez Assad. But Clinton did not mention Assad during the
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The president spent much of his address recounting the specifics
of education programs, especially higher education aid and loan
initiatives, forged by his administration.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Hope scholarships'' to tax-free education investment
accounts, Clinton said the administration has done much to help
students and their parents deal with the escalating cost of the
ever-more critical higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American needs more than a high school education. It
means a college education is no longer a luxury,'' Clinton told the
group. ``Unless we can more generally spread the benfits of
education, your generation will not be able to build the future of
your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country cannot afford to leave any students behind simply
because they cannot afford to pay for college,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Representative Bill Goodling, a Pennsylvania
Republican who heads the House education committee, said he was
disappointed that Clinton would use a commencement speech to
advance a ``misguided political agenda.'' Goodling said the Direct
Student Loan program, for example, had many administrative problems
the president did not mention.
</P>
<P>
   The White House took the occasion of the graduation to release a
self-generated report card on its educational accomplishments, in
the form of a US Department of Education report called ``Expanding
College Opportunity: More Access, Greater Achievement, Higher
Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   College enrollment is up, the report said, with 66 percent of
1998 high school graduates enrolling in college, compared with 60
percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Further, while college costs have quadrupled in the last two
years, the financial rewards are clear, Clinton said. College
graduates today can expect to earn $600,000 more over a lifetime
than high school graduates; women will earn about twice as much
with a college degree than without one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reminded the graduating class that he ``came from a
family where nobody had ever gone to college before, but from the
time I was a little boy, I never had any doubt I was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am well aware, if it hadn't been for that chance I had a
long time ago to go to school, I wouldn't be here today,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   As the students and their families filed off to celebrate the
graduations, Clinton was flown by helicopter 45 miles back to
Minneapolis, where he spent an afternoon raising an estimated
$500,000 for his party.
</P>
<P>
   The president's appearance at a Democratic National Committee
lunch was expected to raise a minimum of $200,000. A later address
to the New Leadership Network and Minnesota Democratic Farmer Labor
Party at a popular music club _ where the Minnesota ban Soul Asylum
played _ was expected to raise at least $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the president used his weekly radio address
to announce regulations that allow states to provide paid leave
after the birth or adoption of a child. He also announced a
regulation, effective June 20, that allows federal employees to use
up to 12 weeks of sick leave to care for a seriously ill family
member.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks recorded Friday, Clinton said he sought the changes
because many workers cannot afford to take time off without pay, as
stipulated under the 1993 Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen states, including Massachusetts, are considering
legislation to provide paid leave through means such as
unemployment insurance, and the president said he hopes more states
will join them.
</P>
<P>
   Such assistance is strongly supported by labor and women's
groups in Massachusetts, though state officials are wary of dipping
into the $1.9 billion unemployment insurance fund, and businesses
fear an increase in labor costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
