<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE061     06-10 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardt on a roll again
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ His seven Winston Cup championships aside,
racing possibly has never have been more fun for Dale Earnhardt
than it is right now.
</P>
<P>
   The good times have been rolling this weekend. Saturday, he
finished third in the IROC race at Michigan Speedway and now needs
just a fifth-place finish in the fourth IROC race at Indy to repeat
as the series champ.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got on top of a hauler and helped oldest son Kerry to a
third place finish in the Flagstar 200 ARCA race. ``Dad was more
like a coach; he tells me how to get in the corner and what line to
take,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Earnhardt starts ninth in the Kmart 400 while son, Dale
Jr., who had the fastest car (181.287 mph) in Saturday's final
practice, starts sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest development, however, may be the sudden appearance
of The Intimidator in the rear-view mirrors of the usual Cup points
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, after 13 races of the 34-race schedule, Earnhardt has
climbed to third in the point standings, 16 points behind
second-place Ward Burton and 98 points behind today's pole-sitter,
Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has only one victory this year, at Atlanta on March
12, but he has more top 10 finishes (10) than any other driver. And
he has momentum: six of his top 10s have come in the past seven
races.
</P>
<P>
   This is familiar territory. From 1993 until the end of the 1996
schedule, Earnhardt fell out of the top 5 in points only one time
in 124 events.
</P>
<P>
   He's been here before, so he prefers to ignore the points
standings at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't really looking at the points that much,'' Earnhardt
said. ``You look at it race by race and win by win. If you're
competitive week in and week out, then the points will come. As we
start to approach the halfway mark of the season the points will
become more of an issue. Right now we just want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But crew chief Kevin Hamlin is pretty pumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty neat being right there and having it within your
grasp,'' Hamlin said. ``Last year, we always thought we had it in
our grasp but realistically you knew that it never was. We had to
rely on a lot of other people having trouble. This year, you've
still got to have an awful lot of luck. Everything's got to go just
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin would like to be within 100 points of the lead going into
the last month of the season. Being 100 points ahead in the fall
would be better yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are going right now, it looks like it will come
down to the last lap of the last race,'' Hamlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
