<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Polls show Bush and Gore even
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new national polls have George W. Bush and Vice President Al
Gore still locked in a presidential race that is too close to call.
One new survey gives Republican Bush a slight edge, 41 percent to
38 percent. The poll, conducted by Princeton Survey Research for
Bloomberg News, surveyed 1,208 adults between May 25 and June 4 and
has a margin of sampling error of 3 percentage points. A CNN-USA
Today Gallup poll taken last week gives Bush 44 percent and
Democrat Gore 44 percent. The poll has a margin of error of 5
</P>
<P>
   PARTIES UNVEIL INTERNET SITES HEAVY ON PROMOS
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats and Republicans have unveiled party-sponsored Web
sites that resemble news pages. The new sites, which went online
last week, contain news articles along with a heavy dose of
promotional political materials. The Republican site, www.GOP.gov,
is sponsored by the House Republican Conference. The Democratic
site, www.FreeDem.com, also is heavy on politics, but lists movie
reviews, news stories and offers free Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   GOP DELEGATES UNHAPPY WITH DIGS
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the delegates for the upcoming Republican National
Convention are pleased with their Philadelphia hotel assignments.
Some, like those from Virginia, will stay in the same downtown
hotel as Bush, while Michigan delegates will be stuck in a Holiday
Inn at the edge of town. The Vermont delegation will stay 25 miles
away in Wilmington, Del., during the convention that runs from July
31 to Aug. 3. Convention planners on Friday announced the
assignments, which they say was guided by logistics not politics.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION COMMITTEE COURTING CASH
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Gore campaign are coming to the rescue of
the Los Angeles organizers of the Democratic National Convention,
who are $3 million short with two months left until the opening
gavel. President Clinton will hold a fundraising breakfast on June
24 at the home of Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, a Republican
who has been working hard to raise money for the host committee.
Organizers hope Clinton's appearance will raise up to $6 million.
The host committee, L.A. Convention 2000, had agreed to raise $35
million before the convention opens Aug. 14, and has collected
about $31.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Terry McAuliffe, the Democratic Party's most prodigious
fund-raiser, has agreed to serve as chairman of the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN FIRES SPOKESMAN
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bernstein, campaign spokesman for Pat Buchanan, was fired
Friday by Bay Buchanan, the Reform Party candidate's sister and his
chief strategist. Brian Dougherty, a former producer at Fox
Television News, has replaced Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTARIAN DOESN'T WANT FEDERAL FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Libertarian Party presidential candidate Harry Browne says he
doesn't want taxpayer money and is refusing to accept matching
campaign funds from the federal government. Browne said he is
eligible to receive up to $750,000 for the primary season. He
explained that taking the cash would betray his party's drive for a
minimal government with no national tax, no gun control laws, and
no anti-drug law enforcement programs.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
