<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULER'S DEATH FREEZES ISRAEL-SYRIA PEACE TALKS, ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like many an iron-fisted ruler, Hafez Assad could
lead his people.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian president's death Saturday left an absence of the
strong leadership in Damascus that many analysts believe was a
necessary ingredient to complete an Israel-Syria peace deal in
President Clinton's last months in office.
</P>
<P>
   With Assad gone, most see the peace talks as frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Assad's son, Bashar, 34, appeared to be in line as his
successor, Syria faced the prospect of infighting and turmoil that
could easily push aside peace talks for another year or more,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israel-Syria peace process, which resumed earlier this year
only to become stalemated over the new border between the two
countries, faces new political uncertainties in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   There, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's attention is focused on
settling the troubles in his own volatile coalition. If he puts
together a new coalition and avoids early elections, Barak's first
order of business is not likely to be the Syrians, but a summit
sought by the Palestinians that would include Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, Clinton, and Barak himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Assad's death, the Israel-Syria situation was already
on ice anyway,'' said a US official, asking not to be identified.
``If Israel goes to early elections, that's another problem.''
</P>
<P>
   William Quandt, a Middle East scholar at the University of
Virginia who helped negotiate the 1978 Camp David accords between
Israel and Egypt, said Saturday he expected foreign affairs to take
a less prominent role in Damascus for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks now like things are on hold for a while,'' he said.
``Assad's death throws a lot of new questions in the air. A lot
depends on the succession, and I don't think it's going to be clear
for quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Quandt said that Clinton must wish, now that Assad is gone, that
he had tried a little harder at the last summit to ``pin things
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months ago, Clinton met with Assad in Geneva in
hopes of surmounting the last major obstacle to a deal: control of
the Sea of Galilee's eastern shore. But Clinton brought no new
proposal and Assad stuck to his position of gaining back all land
lost to Israel in the 1967 war. Clinton then put the blame on
Assad, saying the next move was his.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts say they believe that Clinton still could try
to revive the talks, or Israel could turn toward Syria with a new
plan _ especially if the Israeli-Palestinian talks deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   But those scenarios depend on a receptive new leader in
Damascus, and one strong enough to forge a peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Syria's Parliament Saturday opened the way for
Bashar, 34, to be leader by amending the constitution to lower the
required age of a head of state, there is no guarantee of an easy
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people with grudges and fears about
Bashar's succession at this point, and they are powerful people who
command real forces _ armed forces and political forces _ in the
country,'' said Helena Cobban, who recently wrote a book on the
history of Israel-Syria talks.
</P>
<P>
   An anticorruption campaign in Syria, which was linked to Bashar
Assad, reportedly played a role in the suicide of former prime
minister Mohammed Zu'bi earlier this year and the exit of Hikmet
Shihabi, a former chief of staff who met with Barak when he served
as chief of staff to the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin. Shihabi
is believed to be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shakeout in Damascus has already begun,'' said Geoffrey
Aronson, head of the Foundation for Middle East Peace, a Washington
think tank. ``The domestic situation in Syria is going to be
unsettled for many months, if not longer.''
</P>
<P>
   While Assad brought stability to Syria, largely by instilling
fear in the citizenry who witnessed his ruthless handling of
dissenters, Aronson and others said that a new group of young
leaders may usher in another benefit: opening up the country to the
influence of a larger world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an assumption they will bring a new energy or
commitment to issues . . . that will help Syria find a place in the
global economic order,'' Aronson said.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment could set the conditions for a durable peace
deal with Israel, but Middle East specialists cautioned the
transition may take a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Assad dying, people must be scratching their heads now in
a lot of different places,'' Quandt said. ``As long as Assad was
there, in the back of my mind, I always thought there was a
possibility of Israel and Syria working something out. Now that is
not very tempting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
