<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-LOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' ANDERSON ALWAYS BELONGED IN THE BIG LEAGUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Garret Anderson patrols the outfield grass at
Edison Field with aplomb, displaying a certain swagger as he lopes
toward the ball to make a play.
</P>
<P>
   Whether playing in the Angels' home stadium or any other
major-league ballpark, Anderson has looked like he belongs ever
since he led Kennedy High of Granada Hills, Calif., to a City
Section championship at Dodger Stadium in 1989. It was the first
time his spikes had ever graced major-league turf.
</P>
<P>
   While signing some baseballs before the last game of the Angels'
three-game series with the Dodgers on June 4, Anderson, a five-year
veteran of the majors, was told the Cougars had made it back to the
finals and would play El Camino Real in two days. Kennedy would
defeat ECR 4-2 to win the City title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea (about the impending title game); I go back and
play in the alumni game at Kennedy every year,'' Anderson said.
``It was a great program long before I got there and it's nice to
know it's still doing well. ... It was real nice to do something of
that magnitude and that was a great bunch of guys on that (1989)
team too.''
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson found out about the possibility of another City
title for Kennedy on short notice, he didn't waste any time before
calling to wish coach Manny Alvarado good luck before the game.
Alvarado, in his 12th year at Kennedy, coached Anderson when he
played varsity his junior and senior seasons in 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was an All-City selection in baseball both years and in
basketball his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very smooth. His nickname was `Cadillac' _ he made
everything look so easy,'' Alvarado said. ``When he started at
center field in 1989 at Dodger Stadium, he looked like he belonged
there.''
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson pursued a career in baseball. He wouldn't have
minded a basketball career, but he didn't receive any scholarship
offers. Fresno State offered Anderson a baseball scholarship but he
turned it down when the Angels made him a fourth-round draft choice
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his name turning up in trade rumors consistently
throughout his tenure with the Angels, Anderson's career average
entering this season was .300. Last year his .303 average matched a
career high and his 21 homers were a career best.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's power numbers are well ahead of his pace from last
year, when he drove in 80 runs. He's hit 14 homers and driven in 40
runs this year with four weeks to go before the All-Star break.
Despite his power surge, Anderson's average has rested around the
mid-.200s throughout the year (he was batting .251 as of Saturday's
game).
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a .300 hitter and he'll be a .300 hitter,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We need Garret to drive in the runs,
which he's been doing. We need Garret to get those clutch hits,
which he's been doing. This guy contributes what we need him to
contribute and that's RBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, on the Angels _ the only team in the majors with
five players who have at least 10 homers _ power numbers have
become almost expendable. Anderson said the trade rumors used to
get to him, but he's come to understand that baseball is a business
and it's nothing personal.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, the Santa Clarita resident would like to stay
where he is with his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson was growing up in the North San Fernando Valley,
he idolized players like Eric Davis and Darryl Strawberry and would
often imitate them on the field. He demonstrates his maturation
after 10 years of pro baseball by saying young players should play
for themselves and establish their own niche.
</P>
<P>
   Youths, regardless of how much they may have been influenced by
him, should fight the inclination to do their best Garret Anderson
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, you always try to imitate people,''
Anderson said. ``I just always tried to have fun and tried not to
be like anybody too much. I know what kind of player I am and I
just try to stay within that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope a kid just tries to be himself and goes out and has
fun.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
