<SLUG> BC-BBO-FURCAL0611-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves shortstop nabbed on DUI charge
 &HT;    By John McCosh
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves shortstop Rafael Furcal was charged with DUI
and underage consumption of alcohol after damaging his car shortly
after 5 a.m Saturday near Mableton.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal, 19, was held at Cobb's Adult Detention Center after a
breath test set his blood alcohol level at 0.11. Georgia's laws
provide for a DUI conviction if the driver's blood alcohol level is
0.08, or 0.02 for drivers under the legal drinking age of 21. He
was released on bail posted by a friend of his agent a few hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 3-year-old zero tolerance law mandates a six-month
license suspension for underage drinkers convicted of DUI.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after going 3-for-4 in the Braves' 6-4 victory over the
Red Sox, Furcal was driving when he ran into a raised median,
damaging the cover of his car's oil pan, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing the car was losing oil, Furcal drove to a nearby
grocery store, where he purchased oil and some razor blades,
according to Cobb police spokesman Dana Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigating a report of a suspicious person in the
grocery store parking lot about 5:15 a.m. found Furcal attempting
to start his car.
</P>
<P>
   The damaged car left a trail of oil from the raised median of
the road to the grocery store parking lot, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal's agent, Paul Kinzer, said that after the Braves game
against the Boston Red Sox ended about 10:30 p.m. Friday, Furcal
headed to his Buckhead apartment with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his friends was over at his house and had a couple of
beers,'' Kinzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday Furcal drove home the friend. After dropping him
off, Furcal was apparently headed back to his apartment when he
struck the median. Kinzel said he was notified of Furcal's arrest
about 7 a.m. Saturday. Kinzer said Furcal didn't realize he was too
impaired to drive and that the arrest had left him shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he called me, he was a nervous wreck,'' Kinzer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his Furcal grew up in a different country and is
learning a hard lesson about different attitudes toward drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from a different culture, from the Dominican Republic,
where they don't have a drinking age,'' Kinzer said. ``There, a
15-year-old might drink a beer or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Furcal, who declined to comment, was out of the lineup on
Saturday night but manager Bobby Cox said he would be back in
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just spoken with Rafael,'' general manager John
Schuerholz said. ``Andres Galarraga was in the room with me to be
certain that Raffy understood what I was saying and to reiterate
what I was saying. The most important thing is Raffy has apologized
for the incident and is very sorry that it happened and is very
sincere when he says that it will not happen again. We're satisfied
with that response. He realizes that he made a mistake, admits to
it and he's sorry for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people make mistakes,'' Galarraga said. ``I think
it's (not as big) a deal as a lot of people think. He's a beautiful
person, a great kid. He feels bad about it. I want to help him not
feel bad about it. Forget about what everybody says and play the
game, concentrate on what you're doing. He doesn't need any
negative comments right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are deferring any disciplinary action ``until after
whatever legal matters involved are concluded,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
