<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WALKER HAS BEEN NO PROBLEM FOR ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies lost right fielder Larry Walker to an
injured elbow at a time when things weren't going well, and it
immediately turned things around.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of falling into oblivion in the National League West,
the Rockies won 15 of their first 20 with Walker on the disabled
list and entered Saturday in second place. They're 32-25, and 2{
games behind division-leading Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe (Walker's) injury is probably the worst thing
and best thing that has happened to us,'' Rockies manager Buddy
Bell said. ``The worst thing about it is obvious. The best thing is
we've had to come together as a team. A lot of guys don't have
numbers that are Walker-like, but over the course of this time he's
been out, they've all had huge hits, or made huge plays.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walker was injured, the Rockies were three games below
.500. Now, thanks to a 20-6 mark at home (Colorado is 12-19 away
from Coors Field), they're in the wild-card chase and general
manager Dan O'Dowd is thinking about how to better the club rather
than retool it.
</P>
<P>
   STOTTLEMYRE CONSIDERS SURGERY: Arizona right-hander Todd
Stottlemyre didn't want to have rotator cuff surgery that would end
his season, but he is thinking about having an operation after the
season to reposition a nerve in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre is on the disabled list with tendinitis in his
elbow, but he's hopeful to be activated to start Thursday against
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was diagnosed with a torn rotator cuff in May 1999,
but he opted to rehab the muscles around the shoulder rather than
have surgery that would have kept him out for a year. But with the
nerve operation, Stottlemyre could start throwing in eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is much more simple,'' he said. ``It's not near as
dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   LIFE WITHOUT ROCKER: Though the Atlanta Braves are thankful they
don't have to deal with the John Rocker circus anymore, his erratic
pitching and demotion to the minors does create a hole in the
pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the Braves will go with a
closer-by-committee, using Kerry Ligtenberg as the primary closer
and Mike Remlinger and Rudy Seanez in set-up roles. But manager
Bobby Cox said he would change things around depending on matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, we've put an awful lot of emphasis on the closer,'' Cox
said. ``Sometimes you can get carried away with it. The same guy
might help inthe seventh inning if the matchup's just right.''
</P>
<P>
   SAMMY'S STATS: Sammy Sosa's criticism of Chicago Cubs manager
Don Baylor, and subsequent apology, was the talk of baseball this
week, but a closer look at the stats suggest Sosa wasn't exactly
smacking the ball all over the place during the down times this
season. He is hitting .312 with 19 homers and 56 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs began the season 6-11, and Sosa hit .219 with four
homers and eight RBI in those 17 games. When Mark Grace landed on
the disabled list May 11 with a pulled hamstring, Sosa had a streak
of 11 games without a home run. The Cubs were 3-8 in that span and
Sosa batted .248.
</P>
<P>
   FOR PETE'S SAKE: When the Cincinnati Reds honored their 1975
World Series champions last weekend, Pete Rose wasn't allowed to
attend. But he wasn't forgotten, especially by the players.
Shortstop Barry Larkin placed a rose on third base before taking
his position in the first inning, and Aaron Boone left his glove at
third base during the National Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right thing to do and I was happy to be a part of
it,'' Larkin said. ``It wasn't a protest. It was respect for a man
I grew up adoring. ... We just felt it was right to represent him
in some capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed respect for what Pete Rose has done. He's the
ultimate teamplayer. It's a shame he couldn't be here. But he was
here in spirit.I think everybody felt he should have been here. I
kept waiting for the helicopter to come and lower Pete into the
stadium.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
