<HEADLINE>
SYRIAN LEADER ASSAD IS DEAD AT 69 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Syria's enigmatic and autocratic leader, Hafez Assad,
died Saturday, leaving behind broken dreams of Arab unity and a
nation that is economically troubled and diplomatically isolated.
He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had grown increasingly frail as a result of diabetes and
heart problems that began with a heart attack in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Through nearly three decades of war and frustrating failures to
reach regional peace, President Assad's exacting and &UR;  &LR; ruthless
style of leadership made him a force in the region and earned him
the nickname, ``The Lion of Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   But his death _ without seeing the return of the Golan Heights
he lost to Israel 33 years ago _ may lead to a leadership vacuum
and create new strategies among rivals and allies in the Arab
world. An interruption in Syrian force could disrupt neighboring
Lebanon, where Syria has been the de facto power for a decade, and
affect the standoff between Israel and Muslim guerrillas in
southern Lebanon, where Assad had restrained the ambitions of the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, Assad carefully prepared a path for his
untested son, Bashar, to assume power.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after Assad's death Saturday, Syria's Parliament
cleared the way for Bashar's ascendancy with a nearly unanimous
vote to lower the minimum age of a head of state from 40 to 34,
Bashar's age.
</P>
<P>
   Then Parliament ajourned until June 25, when it is expected to
begin the process of naming Assad's successor.
</P>
<P>
   After Syria's state television announced Assad's death, hundreds
of people gathered outside the presidential palace in Damascus,
chanting: ``With our souls, with our blood, we will protect you, O
Bashar!''
</P>
<P>
   For most Syrians, Assad was the only leader they had ever known.
Members of parliament wept. Stores closed, and the red-and-black
national flag was lowered to half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   He will be buried on Tuesday, with Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright representing the United States at the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A new Syrian leader faces grave challenges as the nation comes
to a crossroads in the peace process with neighboring Israel.
Damascus also faces an economic and social stagnation if it does
not open its insular society to technology and globalization.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said it would be premature to speculate on
Syrian changes, adding: ``There will be a period of sorting out,
and the Syrian people will make the decisions and then we'll see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Assad, he noted: ``We had our differences, but I always
respected him. . . . He made a strategic choice for peace and we
worked together to achieve that goal. Throughout my contacts with
him, including our last meeting, he made clear Syria's continued
commitment to the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to working with Syria to achieve the goal of a
comprehensive peace,'' Clinton added during a visit to Northfield,
Minn., where he delivered the commencement address at Carleton
College.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian President Yasser Arafat declared three days of
mourning in Palestinian-run areas.
</P>
<P>
   Through more than three decades, Assad has insisted that Israel
must return the Golan Heights. Since 1991, Assad conducted
intermittent talks with Israel, remaining adamant about a complete
withdrawal. The talks broke down in January when Syria insisted
that Israel was trying to establish a framework for an agreement
that would not guarantee a complete withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, rumors of his death would periodically
circulate, but there had been no recent indication that his health
had declined sharply. Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said he had
spoken with Assad earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``His last words were: `Our destiny is to build a better future
for our countries' and then there was a silence and I knew
something happened,'' Lahoud said in a letter sent to Bashar and
read on Lebanon's state television.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar, a British-educated ophthalmologist, had this political
destiny thrust upon after his older brother, Bassil, who had long
been groomed for the succession, died in a 1994 car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar has never held office, but had taken on an
anti-corruption campaign in government that is widely popular in
the streets. The campaign deeply shook the aging circle of advisers
and ministers who surrounded his father.
</P>
<P>
   Considered awkward and shy compared to his icy, controlling
father, Bashar has made several official visits to Arab countries
and to France in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end, however, Assad kept control of the difficult
negotiations with Israel. Many analysts felt Assad had
miscalculated again and again in failing to cut a deal for regional
peace with Israel, first in the early 1990s and again this year
when Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak aggressively sought to
strike a peace agreement with Syria and unilaterally ended Israel's
occupation of southern Lebanon. Just last week, Assad's foreign
minister said Syria was again open to peace discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's rule had been dominated by the Arab-Israeli conflict
through the humiliating defeat Arab nations suffered in 1967 and
the less humiliating defeat of 1973. Assad also mired Syria in
Lebanon's vicious 15-year civil war, which ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's grasp on power seemed to depend in part on his ability
to keep enemies and allies guessing, and not being afraid to
reverse a diplomatic course when he saw an advantage in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   He also endured because he was willing to kill. In 1982, Assad
crushed an internal rebellion by ordering the massacre by the
Syrian Army of betwween 10,000 to 20,000 residents of the ancient
city of Hama.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's unpredictably and pragmatism was in display in his
decision to join the US-led coalition in the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
Although bitterly resistent to American intervention in the region
and long critical of Washington's strong support of Israel, Assad
sided with the US forces in ousting Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's
troops from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   For Assad, the decision paid off. He developed close ties to the
West just as Syria's longtime backer, the Soviet Union, was
collapsing. He also reaped financial benefits that included $2
billion from Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement in the Gulf War also led to Assad's surprising
steps toward making peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad did not want the political order in the Middle East
dominated by Israel,'' Assad's official biographer, Patrick Seale,
told CNN. ``He wanted a balance of power in order to keep the
peace. He felt an imbalance causes war because the stronger partner
always tries to impose his will on the weaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad, part of a military clique that gained power in the 1960s,
became leader in a bloodless coup in 1970. His tight grip on power
has been an extraordinary feat for a man who hails not only from a
peasant background but a minority Alawite Muslim sect in a
predominantly Sunni Muslim state.
</P>
<P>
   Assad often dreamed of a Saladin-like role as the unchallenged
leader of a united Arab front. It was a dream that died hard for
Assad.
</P>
<P>
   His regional ambitions were largely a faiure and often took
precedence over profound domestic concerns which had dragged Syria
into poverty and left his countrymen far behind in the age of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Assad ruled through fear that emanated from a vast network of
spies, secret police and informers. According to human rights
groups, his government jailed thousands of political prisoners
without trial, and the US State Department regards Syria as
supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Syria still has some 30,000 troops stationed in Lebanon to
maintain its authority. The rationale given for Syrian presence has
long been the need to back up Lebanon while Israel occupied its
``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But Assad's intervention faced new scrutiny after Israel's
withdrawal of forces last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
