<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-BASHAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIANS SEE IN ASSAD'S HEIR THE POSSIBILITY OF PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bashar Assad, the presumptive new president of Syria,
has waited in the wings of power for six years, nurturing a
reputation as an accessible and progressive man who wants to
satisfy the yearning of many Syrians to be part of the modern
world.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, 34, is poised to take on the autocratic powers of his
father, Hafez Assad, who died Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The machinery of the Syrian state _ a quiescent Parliament, the
ruling Baath Party and the state-controlled press _ has all but
anointed him as his father's successor to rule a country that has
spent most of the last 30 years as a heavily militarized socialist
state living in political and economic isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, who never spent more than a few days outside
of Syria in his life, the younger Assad knows something of the
outside world, and was educated in part in the West. So, for many
Syrians, the younger Assad is the antithesis of their
inward-looking past and the passing of power from father to son is
not only seen as an outgrowth of an authoritarian state, but also
as a welcome demonstration of much-cherished stability.
</P>
<P>
   Before the elder Assad seized power, Syria had undergone a
succession of military coups and social upheavals. Although he
represented a tiny religious minority group, the Alawites, and
brutally suppressed any political opposition, President Assad also
won grudging public acceptance as the ruler who could bring a
measure of calm to the fractious Syrian political scene.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1994, the heir apparent to the Assad dynasty was the
eldest son, Basil, a dashing sportsman and military officer. But in
January of that year, he died in a spectacular car crash. His
funeral was conducted as a state event, with his grieving father
shown on Arab television stations throughout the Middle East
receiving the condolences of heads of state from around the region.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after his elder brother's death, Bashar Assad, the
next oldest son, was summoned home from London, where he had lived
for two years while taking a course in ophthalmology, and set on a
track to accumulate the military and political honors seen as
necessary for the next leader of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Said by friends to be rather shy and apolitical at first, Assad
has slowly built a reputation for being all that his father was not
_ accessible, open and sophisticated in the ways of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Until very recently, however, he had not taken an active role in
foreign policy except as his father's representative in Lebanon. He
has traveled extensively in the Arab world in the past two years,
meeting with several of its key leaders. His debut on the
international stage outside the Middle East came in November on a
visit to France, where he had been invited by President Jacques
Chirac for his first official talks with a Western head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has been associated, in press reports and in the minds of
many Syrians, with a popular anticorruption drive that has already
forced a number of his father's longtime supporters out of office.
He is credited with hand-selecting many ministers in the new
cabinet, appointed in March and including a number of men
considered open to the idea of a free market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need a change today more than any time before,'' Assad
told the pan-Arab newspaper Al Hayat, based in London, just before
the new government was announced. He said the new government needed
``efficiency, honesty and administrative skills,'' adding, ``If
these three elements are available, we will have the government we
seek.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-anticipated changes in Syria's currency and investment
laws, finally put in place by presidential decree two months ago,
were also widely attributed to the influence of the younger Assad.
In the last year, Syrians have become more aware of Assad's kitchen
cabinet of advisers, which includes Western-educated economists,
young entrepreneurs from some of the traditional Damascus elite
families and newly rich scions of military figures.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, many businessmen and ordinary Syrians have told
visitors that they know _ although they have not necessarily
experienced it _ that Bashar Assad can be reached by phone or by
fax with any problem anyone has with Syrian bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   He is perhaps best known, however, as Syria's only public
advocate of computer literacy and the Internet. A group called the
Computer Society, which he heads, offers free computer courses in a
country where satellite television dishes are still outlawed and
mobile telephones have just been permitted on a limited basis this
year. With such restrictions, only the president's son could have
promoted information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Assad's success in developing an image as a modernizer,
he has had also to cultivate a reputation as a tough political
actor.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, he comes from the Alawite sect, a small
religious group that is regarded as heretical by many Sunni and
Shiite Muslim clerics, and will rule a country that is
predominantly Sunni Muslim. If he is to maintain his minority-led
government, Assad will need the skills of his father to play one
group of Syrians against another and instill fear in them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
