<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO'S BEEN NEAR PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Pedro Martinez is having a season like no other
pitcher in the history of the game, at least when his numbers are
compared to those of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's ERA is 0.95, when the next lowest in the American
League is James Baldwin's 3.07. No pitcher in baseball history has
finished with an ERA below 1.00. Bob Gibson (1.12 ERA in 1968)
holds the major-league record, and Walter Johnson (1.14 in 1913)
holds the American League record.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez allows an average of just 4.75 hits per nine innings,
when only 10 teams have an ERA below 4.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we'll not see in our lifetime again, so
enjoy it,'' Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   With eight shutout innings against the Indians in his last start
Thursday, Martinez extended his scoreless-innings streak to 22. Yet
he said he still hasn't recovered from the strained muscle in his
side that forced him to miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable is that Martinez actually seems to turn it
up a notch when runners are in scoring position. Opposing hitters
are batting .044 (2 for 45) with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of times I'm amazed,'' Red Sox catcher Jason
Varitek said. ``Especially crunch time. When teams have a good
opportunity to score a run, he doesn't make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also seems to get up for road games _ his ERA in
visiting ballparks is 0.51. With 114 strikeouts, he's is on a pace
for 324.
</P>
<P>
   Said Martinez: ``I'm only a human being. I'm not anything
special. I don't have the greatest numbers ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   FLYING BIRDS: The Orioles had to fly home to Baltimore after
last Wednesday's game in New York against the Mets, only to fly
back to New York on Thursday morning to play a rainout make-up
game.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? There wasn't a hotel within 90 minutes of Shea
Stadium able to supply the 53 rooms needed. New York was in the
middle of one of its heaviest tourist and convention periods of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken, Brady Anderson and Charles Johnson found rooms in
New York and stayed, but the rest of the team had to fly home and
return within a 12-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stinks,'' pitcher Mike Mussina said.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKER BYE BABY? The Indians considered trading for Braves
pitcher John Rocker during the spring, and with closer Paul Shuey
out with an injury and the pitching staff as a whole riddled with
injuries, speculation that the Indians will trade for Rocker has
surfaced again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would mean the Indians would have put up with
the circus that surrounds him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the guy,'' left fielder David Justice said. ``He
might just need a change of scenery. But we don't want anyone to
come in here and ruin the chemistry on this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS: Rickey Henderson has stolen a base in 40 different
ballparks in his career. With the Mariners at San Francisco's Pac
Bell Park this weekend, he has the opportunity for No. 41. ... No
Angels player has ever hit 40 home runs in a season, but it seems
the streak will be broken this year. It's just a matter of who gets
there first, Mo Vaughn or Troy Glaus. Both have 18 homers, a pace
for 48. ... The Chicago White Sox have the best record in the
American League, but have a big week in front of them. Starting
Monday, they play their next seven games against the Indians and
Yankees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
