<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-HAAKENSON-COLUMN-     06-10 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HAAKENSON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY IN THE LIFE: BIG MO VS. BIG UNIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's 3:45 p.m. Friday afternoon, and Mo Vaughn arrives
at Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and his bodyguard/pal Kyle enter through the
administrative offices and are pointed back outside and in the
direction of Gate G, the players' entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle notes how hot it is, when in fact it's only 90 degrees,
about 15 degrees cooler than the day before. Vaughn changes the
subject: ``Hey, who's throwing for them?''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? Who's throwing for the Diamondbacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know?'' a reporter asks.
</P>
<P>
   With a big smile revealing a gold tooth that reflects the bright
sunlight, Kyle jumps in: ``It's Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Unit, otherwise known as Randy Johnson, is taking his
9-1 record, his 1.41 ERA and his 131 strikeouts in 95 innings to
the mound against the Angels. The same Randy Johnson that strikes
such fear into opposing hitters, particularly lefties, that even
All-Stars like Larry Walker opt to ride the bench when Johnson
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And Vaughn, also a left-handed hitter, didn't know?
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant tomorrow,'' Vaughn says. ``Who's throwing for them
tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn gets quiet, apparently deep in thought, as he approaches
Gate G. Is he thinking about Daal? Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn isn't afraid of facing Johnson. In fact, he went into
Friday's game with a career average of .333 (8 for 24) with two
homers against him. Any secrets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky,'' Vaughn said. ``No. ... What's so crazy about it is
early in my career in Boston, I played against him a lot. I was a
young guy trying to break in and they're giving other guys a day
off. So I always seemed to be playing against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comfortable facing him, but I've been in the box
against him. It's not easy. He can make you look real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m. ... Vaughn settles into a couch in the Angels
clubhouse and watches the College World Series on TV. He is
approached with the question: ``If you're a general manager, and
you have the choice of starting your team with Randy Johnson or
Pedro Martinez, who do you take?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it matter?'' Vaughn says. ``Flip a coin, you're
getting the same thing. Either way, you're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   7:09 p.m. ... Vaughn steps into the box in the bottom of the
first inning. Johnson has already struck out Darin Erstad and Kevin
Stocker. Johnson throws an 85-mph slider. Vaughn swings and misses.
Johnson throws another 85-mph slider. Vaughn swings and misses.
Johnson throws a 98-mph fastball. Vaughn takes strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is what I like about it,'' Vaughn says of his
on-going rivalry with Johnson. ``There's always a certain amount of
respect because everybody sits down against him. We've always had
tremendous respect for each other. That's what it's all about.
Playing in the big leagues you can't play only against who you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   7:57 p.m. ... Vaughn leads off the fourth inning. He fouls off a
change-up, then takes two sliders out of the strike zone. On a 2-1
count, Johnson throws an 82-mph change-up that Vaughn hits into
right field for a single.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-10, Johnson appears to a batter to be close enough to
touch. Add that menacing glare and the intimidation factor is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of his makeup, part of his game,'' Vaughn says.
``Anything you can do to get an edge. He definitely uses
(intimidation). And he should use that.''
</P>
<P>
   8:50 p.m. ... The Angels are down 4-1 but have two on with one
out in the sixth inning and Vaughn represents the tying run at the
plate. With the count 2-2, Vaughn takes a 95-mph fastball for
strike three. The Angels don't score in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Vaughn signed with the Angels on Nov. 25, 1998, he called
Johnson and tried to convince him to sign with the Angels, too.
Johnson nearly did, but preferred to stay closer to his Paradise
Valley, Ariz., home.
</P>
<P>
   9:04 p.m. ... Johnson is lifted for a pinch hitter in the bottom
of the sixth inning. Even with Johnson out of the game, the Angels
don't score again and lose 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   10:52 p.m. ... Vaughn leaves the Angels clubhouse after going 1
for 3 against Johnson, his career average against him still at .333
(9 for 27). Despite the loss, another good night's work in the
books.
</P>
<P>
   (ital)Now(endital) he can start thinking about Daal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff Writer Joe Haakenson covers the Angels. His column appears
every other Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
