<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MERCURY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS FLY TO FOURTH CONSECUTIVE WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Using their defense again to set the tone, the
Sparks remained the only undefeated team in the WNBA with a 76-57
rout Saturday afternoon of the Phoenix Mercury in front of 6,349 at
the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika and Tamecka Dixon combined to hold the Mercury's
top two scorers _ Brandy Reed and Tonya Edwards _ to nine points.
</P>
<P>
   Mabika held Reed to six points, 16 under her average, and Dixon
limited Edwards to three points, seven under average. The Sparks,
who held the Mercury (3-2) to 27 percent shooting, a franchise low,
hit 52 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just concentrating on defense, just play aggressive,
don't let her get the ball,'' said Mabika, who fouled out with four
points, five assists, three steals and a blocked shot. ``As long as
we're scoring and we're winning I don't really care. I wanted to
contribute to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said: ``My shots were just not falling, and you're going to
have games where that is going to happen. It was frustrating. In
the second half, the ball didn't bounce our way.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between these teams got personal with about four
minutes left when Sparks center Lisa Leslie and Mercury guard
Bridgett Pettis had to be separated and were each assessed
technicals. Pettis, taking offense to an elbow Leslie stopped short
of giving Mercury center Maria Stepanova under the basket, backed
Leslie off the court, bumping the 6-foot-5 center, who retaliated
with a push.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any reason to fight her,'' said Leslie, who had
16 points to go with 10 rebounds. ``I just tried to back away from
her. I don't know why she was upset with me. She didn't have any
reason to be. I just backed away as far as I could and said, `Don't
hit me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, inbounding the ball by the Mercury bench, Leslie and
Phoenix coach Cheryl Miller, who coached Leslie at USC in 1993 and
1994, exchanged words. Leslie said Miller called her one of the
dirtiest players in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Cheryl, you didn't have a problem when I was playing
for you and now all of a sudden you do,''' Leslie said.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the game was clearly under the Sparks' command.
</P>
<P>
   They set the tone early when DeLisha Milton scored the Sparks'
first eight points to build a 22-11 advantage. But Phoenix went
into a zone and came back to lead 31-30 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed defense to change the tempo,'' Sparks coach
Michael Cooper said. ``That's a credit to Cheryl. It was a diamond
and one, with a one-one-one on Lisa. That zone caused us a lot of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sparks responded with a 13-2 run to start the second
half to build a 43-33 margin, and the Mercury came no closer the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good defensive team, and once we broke out of our
offensive slump we were able to open up a lead. As long as we
continue to play solid defense we're gonna be just fine,'' Cooper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Between Mabika, Dixon (five assists), and Ukari Figgs (four
assists), the Sparks distributed the ball well, getting 22 assists
to the Mercury's nine.
</P>
<P>
   Figgs had her best offensive game, contributing a career-high 15
points on 3-of-5 shooting from the 3-point line. Milton had a
game-high 17 points and Clarisse Machanguana had 10 off the bench. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
