<SLUG> BC-ASSAD-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FOR U.S., UNCERTAINTY IN SYRIA MAKES PALESTINIAN TALKS
MORE URGENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., this story has been added to NYT Page 1, replacing
PUTIN-EUROPE which is now inside) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the Clinton administration, the death of
President Hafez Assad of Syria makes the possibility of brokering a
peace between the Israelis and Syrians even more remote and the
desire to help forge a peace agreement between Israelis and
Palestinians even more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Syrian leader and President Clinton failed to come to
terms at a meeting in Geneva last March, the administration has
underscored the urgency of making peace between Israelis and
Palestinians. In Cairo on Wednesday, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told Syrian and Egyptian officials that while the
administration was willing to make a final push for an
Israeli-Syrian peace, there was ``no higher foreign policy
priority'' for it than the peace talks between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks were about to resume in the Washington area on
Tuesday and the Palestine Liberation Organization leader, Yasser
Arafat, had been scheduled to meet with Clinton at the White House
on Wednesday. But it was not clear whether those meetings might be
delayed because of Assad's funeral, which is also scheduled for
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will not go to Syria for the funeral, his spokesman, Joe
Lockhart, said. Although attending the funeral would present the
president with a chance to greet Assad's son as he assumes power,
the United States will instead be represented by Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that they have compiled a thick
dossier on Bashar Assad but maintained only limited contacts with
him through the embassy in Damascus. A senior White House official
said that nothing Bashar Assad has said or done in recent months
has caused the United States to believe that he would radically
alter Syria's course internally or in regional relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton learned of Assad's death before he took the stage for a
commencement address at Carleton College in Northfield, Minn.
During the ceremony, an aide slipped the president a note saying
that Syrian television had reported the death. Clinton visibly
sighed and shook his head as he read the note.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards he told reporters that this was a time for
condolences to the Assad family and the people of Syria, not for
make predictions about the future of a Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we had our disagreements,'' Clinton said, ``I always
respected him because I felt that he was open and straightforward
with me, and because I felt he meant it when he said he had made a
strategic choice for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that that peace was not achieved in his lifetime,''
the president added, ``and I hope that it can still be achieved, in
no small measure because of the commitment he made.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions, Clinton said it was ``premature to
say'' whether Assad's death would delay progress toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a period of mourning in Syria,'' Clinton said,
``there will be a period of sorting out, and the Syrian people will
make some decisions, and then we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's view reflected the one that is prevalent among Middle
East experts in his administration: that Assad's death changes the
political landscape not only in Syria but also in the region in
ways that will become apparent only over time.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Assad's death, the momentum for the Clinton
administration to help close the gaps between Israel and Syria had
been lost. That message came through loud and clear during
Clinton's failed meeting with Assad in Geneva in March, when the
ailing Syrian leader lectured Clinton on the history of the border
between Israel and Syria and demanded that Israel surrender not
only the Golan Heights but also the northeastern shore and the
northeastern portion of the Sea of Galilee that had been Syria's
before the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Clinton washed his hands of the matter,
stating bluntly: ``The ball's in his court now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Syria's domestic politics and decision-making process is a
blind spot for the United States. In addition, Syria has long been
a frustrating negotiating partner and despite the official
pronouncements is still considered a significant obstacle to a
comprehensive Middle East peace arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The succession will require time, the one thing Clinton doesn't
have left. And there are other uncertainties, officials said:
whether radical factions may use the transition to incite violence
inside Syria or whether the combination of a change in the
leadership in Syria combined with the Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon last month could spark new violence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, administration officials said they believe that Assad's
death gives the Syrian government an even greater incentive to
preserve calm and stability on the Israeli-Lebanese border and to
discourage attacks on Israel through proxies as a pressure tactic
designed to extract concessions from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Albright issued a statement Saturday that Assad ``made a
strategic choice for peace at Madrid in 1991,'' when Syria first
agreed to talk directly with Israel. ``In all of our talks, he
remained committed to that choice,'' she said. ``We strongly
believe that was the right choice and expect that Syria will
continue on the path to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Clinton administration officials noted Assad
autocratically ruled Syria for nearly thirty years and was
unwilling or unable to take the steps necessary for peace; his son
might take years to gain such strength. Even if Bashar Assad wanted
to sit at the peace table with the Israelis, it is unclear they
would trust a new and untried leader from the minority Alawite
sect.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat from the region in Washington said that the
apparently seamless transition from Assad to his son suggests that
the death was not unexpected or violent, but answers few other
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad was not loved, but he was a known quantity and very much
in charge,'' he said. ``We all will be waiting to see if his son
has full control. Assad was very much a one-man regime. Will all
the forces who supported the father support the son? The current
reality in the Middle East is based on assumptions that are no
longer necessarily true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
