<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENDABLE WINS AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ While the spirits of the missing superstars
Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet were hanging over the homestretch,
the 132nd Belmont Stakes was run Saturday with a cast of 11 horses
of far less magnitude. And the one who got there first was one of
the least likely: Commendable, 17th in the Kentucky Derby, without
a victory in six races since his debut last August at Del Mar and
an 18-1 long shot in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   If any touch of greatness rubbed off on Commendable, it probably
came through his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, who won the Belmont for
the fourth time after losing it last year when Charismatic
fractured a leg in the homestretch and missed sweeping the Triple
Crown. It also was his 13th victory in a Triple Crown race, tying
him for the record with the late Sunny Jim Fitzsimmons.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a moment of success for his jockey, Pat Day, who won
the race for the third time, and for his owners, Beverly and Bob
Lewis of Los Angeles, who have won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness
with Silver Charm and Charismatic in the last four years before
those horses were thwarted in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it was a case of the downtrodden rising up and
causing a mighty upset. Commendable, a son of Gone West, won his
first start 10 months ago but had not run better than fourth since
then. In the Derby, which Lukas faced without his customary stable
of stars, Commendable ran 26 lengths behind Fusaichi Pegasus. Then
he sat out the Preakness, which was won by Red Bullet with Pegasus
second. But Saturday, he found the winner's circle, outrunning the
favorite, Aptitude, by a length and a half with Unshaded another
length farther back in third place and Wheelaway six lengths back
in fourth.
</P>
<P>
   When Commendable and his 10 rivals appeared for the Belmont
Stakes before a crowd of 67,810 Saturday at Belmont Park, there was
no suspense about sweeping the Triple Crown. After three years of
racing drama, this was a year when three horses would win the three
classics. And the Belmont horses were suspected of being
second-tier types searching for a way to overtake Fusaichi Pegasus
and Red Bullet for honors in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Commendable was a long shot in a field of long shots,
paying $39.60 for a $2 bet to win after taking second place behind
Hugh Hefner at the start of the race and taking over the lead with
a quarter of a mile to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the head of the stretch, I hadn't asked him for anything,''
Day remembered, sounding as surprised as anyone. ``I wasn't even
sure how much he had left.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, declining to play down what his horse had achieved, said:
``My wife asked me this morning if we could win this thing. I
replied, `Absolutely.' You have to look at what you're up against
and the field you are faced with. We had a horse to fit this very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a horse who had earned $88,470 in seven races before
the Belmont, and then went home with first prize of $600,000. Also,
no horse had ever won the Belmont without racing at least once
after the Kentucky Derby, and Commendable outran just two horses in
the Derby field of 19. As it was, when Commendable turned his trick
in the Belmont on a hot and sultry afternoon with the temperature
in the 90's, he ran the mile and a half in 2:31, a full seven
seconds slower than Secretariat did in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Commendable lost his left front shoe in the
paddock on Saturday while being saddled. Lukas explained that the
hardened rubber brick matting tended to stick to horse shoes. When
Commendable turned in his stall, his shoe simply came off. But a
blacksmith was summoned, who restored shoe to hoof.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked to Mr. Lukas before the race,'' Day said, ``he
thought the important thing was to have an energy-saving ride. We
knew Hugh Hefner would be going out to the lead, so my job was to
get Commendable into a comfortable spot tracking him.''
</P>
<P>
   Day did just that. Hugh Hefner, as expected, shot into the lead
coming out of the gate and held it with Commendable right on his
heels. They stayed in tandem through some very slow fractions: half
a mile in 49 1/5 seconds, one mile in 1:39. Then when they turned
for home, Hugh Hefner was done, fading to eighth. Commendable,
though, withstood late challenges from three well-regarded closers:
Aptitude, who ran second in the Derby; Unshaded, who skipped both
the Derby and Preakness; and Wheelaway, who ran fifth in the Derby
but skipped the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the eighth pole, I still thought I had a chance,'' said
Alex Solis, the rider on Aptitude. ``But Commendable had too easy a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   After they crossed the line, Shane Sellers leaped off Unshaded,
who was wobbling with heat exhaustion. Celeste Kunz, the track
veterinarian, said: ``He had a mild case of heat exhaustion, and we
mechanically lowered his body temperature by applying hoses and ice
water. He recovered quickly and walked back to his barn.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day when several jockeys envisioned a trip to the
winner's circle that didn't materialize. Richard Migliore,
Wheelaway's rider, said: ``I was very calm because I thought I was
sitting on the winner. When I asked for more, he flattened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, the only horse who ran in all three Triple Crown
races, finished third in the Derby and Preakness and fifth in the
Belmont. His trainer, Todd Pletcher, said: ``Our worst fears come
true. We didn't get the pace we needed. He made a nice run, but
couldn't close into those splits.''
</P>
<P>
   But the highest praise for Lukas came from his West Coast rival,
Bobby Frankel, the trainer of Aptitude, who said: ``Give Lukas
credit. I don't know how he did it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
