<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SHOT AT GAME IN KAUFFMAN STADIUM; ANOTHER SPECTATOR AVOIDS
BEING HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD RRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 64-year-old
Haysville, Kan., woman was shot in the stomach and a second bullet
passed through another woman's seat as they watched the Royals play
the Pittsburgh Pirates on Friday night at Kauffman Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women, part of a crowd of more than 30,000 people, were
sitting in different sections. Kansas City police said Saturday
that they were unsure whether the bullets had been fired from
inside or outside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses reported hearing popping sounds, said Sgt.
Floyd Mitchell, a Police Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Haysville woman was hit about 10 p.m. as she sat in Section
138 in the plaza reserved level near the right field foul pole. The
bullet entered the right side of her abdomen, passed through her
left side and lodged in her left elbow, Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing what had happened but feeling severe pain in her
stomach area, she walked to the stadium's first-aid station.
Medical workers discovered she had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses near the woman later told police that they had heard
pops at the time of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   An official for Metropolitan Ambulance Services Trust, which
took the woman to Truman Medical Center, said a medic watching the
game had heard what sounded like two or three gunshots coming from
the right field general admission section.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was treated at Truman and released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after the Haysville woman was shot, another woman
sitting in the upper deck on the first base side of the infield
leaned forward in her seat in Section 416 just before a bullet
blasted through the seat and landed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Police were investigating the trajectory of the bullets. They
would not comment on the type of weapon used or whether the slugs
had come from the same gun.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lachimia, a Royals spokesman, said he was told by police
late Friday that the bullets probably had come from outside the
stadium, from the direction of Interstate 70.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not been informed that police Saturday were
saying the shots could have come from inside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the seriousness of this incident, we do believe this
was a random act. ...This woman (from Haysville) was not an
intended target,'' Lachimia said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting was the first of its kind at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals would not comment on security at any given game, but
Lachimia said the team would take steps for each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, an event of this nature is difficult to protect
against.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
