<HEADER>
A0487 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-YOUNG-BO     06-10 2438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS 49ER REALLY PANNED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All signs point to Steve Young announcing his retirement at the
49ers' Santa Clara, Calif., training site Monday, so the career of
the most proficient passer in the history of the game will come to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   Young's greatest accomplishment has to be that he took over for
Joe Montana, arguably the greatest quarterback of all time, and
somehow managed to not only continue the excellence but also become
a probable first-ballot Hall of Famer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Montana had led the 49ers to four Super Bowl
titles. Imagine him excelling when the fans were constantly
comparing him with Montana. Imagine being able to carry the team to
another Super Bowl title in 1995, when fans were still angry that
Montana was allowed to leave for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the 49er system. Maybe it was Bill Walsh. Maybe it
was the great coaching Mike Shanahan provided during the three
years he and Young were together in San Francisco or those early
days when Mike Holmgren was in charge of the offense. Or maybe it
was just an incredible athlete who had an equally incredible knack
for knowing what it took to win football games. Maybe Jerry Rice
and the other 49ers receivers played a significant role in making
Young great, but Young's ability to create with a smooth, fast, and
strong 6-foot-2-inch, 200-pound frame was unparalleled in
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Young, one of the fastest quarterbacks to play the game,
seemingly could have played football wearing a suit and carrying a
briefcase like the lawyer he had become off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Smart. Instinctive. Fluid.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for such athletes to leave the games they love,
especially when they're still performing at a high level, which
Young was, between concussions. It appeared Young was less
concerned than those around him about his head injuries, but in the
end, at age 38, he wanted to be known as a 49er, not a 49er who
ended his career with the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   He had the opportunity in Denver _ Shanahan had left a salary
cap spot open _ but Young's heart told him he should quit.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because he had persevered too long with the 49ers not to
have it end that way. Some Bay Area folks were skeptical when the
49ers pulled off an Auerbachian deal with the Buccaneers in April
1987, tossing a second- and fourth-round pick Tampa's way for
Young, who had not played well the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   In time, after Young was out of Montana's shadow, fans realized
it was one of the greatest deals in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the job was his for good in 1991, after Montana's
elbow problems had taken their toll, Young was already 28.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe thinks Young is making a good
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has nothing left to prove,'' said Bledsoe. ``He has
championship rings, he's one of the greatest quarterbacks of all
time and a first-ballot Hall of Famer. He'd be risking his health
to prove what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is a smart guy who has a lot to look forward to after
football. He's not going to be lost in life when the game is over
for him. He has business and broadcast opportunities and he can
really have a full and enjoyable life.''
</P>
<P>
   Young got married in March and his wife, Barbara, is expecting
their first child in December.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe by visiting with Shanahan last week Young wanted an
endorsement that he should continue his career in Denver. Shanahan
did not give one. Though Shanahan was willing to hand the reins to
Young and tell Brian Griese and Gus Frerotte to step aside, it was
obvious that both Shanahan and Young weren't sure.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no reason to believe Young couldn't have pulled it
off. If he could replace Montana, why not John Elway? Somewhere in
his mind, he had to be thinking that.
</P>
<P>
   But Shanahan knew Young had reservations about putting on
another uniform, and that was all he needed to advise Young to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   Though reports indicate Young will move into the ``Monday Night
Football'' booth with Al Michaels, there's also the possibility
that he will eventually supplant Walsh and run the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Walsh had a heated argument last week when Walsh
thought Young was going to Denver, but Young surprised Walsh by
deciding to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Young certainly has the intelligence to deal with salary caps,
evaluate players, and run an organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the brightest people not only in football, but in
life,'' said Bledsoe. ``He could do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that Young is retiring on his terms, that he wasn't
pressured into quitting because Walsh needs salary cap space or
because there's a feeling that it's time to begin the Jeff Garcia
era. Players like Young transcend that. Young's retirement will
save the 49ers about $3 million in salary cap space this year. For
a team that's had to trim its payroll by almost $30 million, that's
significant.
</P>
<P>
   As a parting gift, Walsh is giving Young a $1 million roster
bonus that was due on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   That's ironic. For a few years, there were stories of how Young
never cashed his paychecks because he didn't feel he earned his
money as a backup to Montana. One gets the feeling that after 13
years in San Francisco, after becoming the all-time completion
percentage leader (64.3), the career passer rating leader (96.8),
the second leading all-time rusher among quarterbacks (4,329
yards), a two-time league MVP, and the 1995 Super Bowl MVP, this is
one he'll cash, and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bishop in check
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Michael Bishop fans. Patriots offensive coordinator
Charlie Weis said last week he has no plans to use Bishop in a
``Slash'' role. Therefore, his only chance to get on the field
would be if Bledsoe suffered a major injury. Of course, as Weis's
old boss, Bill Parcells once said, he reserves the right to change
his mind . . . Chad Eaton is trying to convince former
Browns/Ravens teammate Mike Frederick to join the Patriots'
defensive line. Frederick is hoping he can still return to
Tennessee. The Patriots made Frederick a minimum offer about a
month ago, but agent Brad Blank said he doesn't know whether the
offer is still on the table . . . Hindsight is a wonderful thing,
and an oft-used tool in sportswriting. So here we go. In having to
replace Curtis Martin, who left for the Jets with a six-year, $36
million deal (that's the simplest version of a complex contract),
the Patriots have since paid four running backs and on this day are
still searching for an adequate replacement. Robert Edwards, a No.
1 pick in 1998, was given a four-year, $4.2 million deal with a
$3.1 million signing bonus. After he went down, the Patriots signed
Terry Allen, whose one season cost them about $700,000, and drafted
Kevin Faulk, who got a five-year, $3.1 million deal with a $1
million signing bonus. The Patriots dumped Allen and drafted J.R.
Redmond, who hasn't signed yet but will likely receive a three-year
deal in the $1.2 million range. Redmond just had groin surgery and
will likely not set foot on the field until the midway point of the
exhibition season. The Patriots are now inquiring about Karim
Abdul-Jabbar . . . Please scream here. Are the Patriots still too
embarrassed to make Bruce Armstrong an offer, knowing it will be
low? As soon as Bill Belichick laid eyes on Armstrong and Ben
Coates last Tuesday, why didn't he head for Andy Wasynczuk's office
for contracts to re-sign both of them? Armstrong weighs about 290
and is in great shape while Coates is 245 and has never looked
better in his nine-year career. Teams have to make tough decisions
on veterans with high salaries, but such decisions haven't always
worked out for the Patriots. Martin is the key example, but there
are others such as Sam Gash, who went to two Pro Bowls after the
Patriots cut him, and Willie Clay, who was never adequately
replaced at free safety. Now we'll see whether the Patriots made
the right choice in letting Shawn Jefferson go and replacing him
with Tony Simmons . . . More hindsight: Clearly the worst thing
Armstrong did was play on one leg after he had torn his ACL halfway
through last season. The stat guys point to Armstrong allowing 12
1/2 sacks last year, third most in the league. All of them came
after he was injured. That's the part that doesn't appear in the
stats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It starts with stopping him
</P>
<P>
   The single most important player in the AFC East might be Colts
quarterback Peyton Manning. How well other AFC East teams contain
him will go far in determining how the standings stack up. This is
where Belichick could be a huge factor. If he can find a way to
stop Manning, the Patriots could be a very good team. Last year,
teams couldn't find a way to disrupt Manning and get him off his
game. The Patriots' coaching staff is already working on some
offseason projects, and you can bet one of them involves Manning .
. . After Bledsoe takes his $6.446 million salary this season,
he'll have earned $34.4 million of the $42 million contract he
signed in October 1995. You'd find very few examples of a player
earning that much on one NFL contract. Long before that much has
been paid, deals usually are renegotiated. For those who believe
the Patriots are withholding a contract extension to ``motivate''
Bledsoe, I don't think that strategy would be effective. Not $34.4
million later. The Patriots haven't redone his deal because they
don't want to hand out a $15 million-$18 million signing bonus
while they're on the verge of breaking ground on a new stadium . .
. Weis didn't agree with some of the media experts who thought
rookie quarterback Tom Brady was throwing the ball poorly at
minicamp. Weis, in fact, was very impressed with Brady, who has
shown the poise of a kid who played under pressure at Michigan . .
. Bledsoe on his upcoming visit to a maximum security prison in
Orafino, Idaho, as part of his foundation's ``Parenting With
Dignity'' program: ``I'm a little nervous about it. I've heard it's
very intimidating and a tough place to visit. I hope I have fans in
there. I don't want them to not like me. It's going to be
interesting. We've got a great program, something we believe
strongly in. The goal is to put it to as many people as we can. We
need the exposure. The more people who know about it, the better.''
Drew's father, Mac, a former teacher who authored the program along
with his wife Barbara, said the nine-week parenting course has been
taught in the prison for two years with strong results. ``You get
to talking to those guys, and they know they've made a mistake, but
they want things to be different for their children,'' said Mac.
``When you give them a couple of tools to teach their children,
they eat it up. They want to be mentors to their own kids.'' The
last time Mac went to the prison, he spoke to more than 200
prisoners sitting in folding chairs on the baseball field,
surrounded by 20 guards armed with stun guns. Outside the grounds
are two 14-foot chain-link fences, with 10 yards of razor wire in
between. And on a hill beyond the fences are guards with scoped
rifles. ``It was one of the most intimidating things I'd ever
experienced,'' said Mac . . . The Patriots will give a bonus to the
player who does the most in the offseason program. The front-runner
is defensive end Greg Spires, who has had 100 percent attendance
and also volunteered for the rookie orientation camp back in April
even though he is a veteran . . . In addition to Frederick and
Abdul-Jabbar, the Patriots are waiting to hear back from center
Steve Everitt and lineman Anthony Pleasant on contract offers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tough turf
</P>
<P>
   The Lions are very concerned about Pro Bowl tight end David
Sloan's turf toe _ to the point where they will take a look at
Coates Monday in Detroit. Coates isn't fond of artificial turf and
would prefer to play on a grass field, but he also learned late
last week that the money has finally dried up in Washington and he
won't be going there . . . Agent Angelo Wright couldn't get the
Seahawks to bite on a deal that would pay wide receiver Sean
Dawkins $3.2 million up front and a minimum salary this year. So
the Seahawks cut Dawkins after their offer of a $1.5 million bonus
and $1.5 million average salary was refused. Dawkins has been a
pretty productive guy over the years. The Jets and Colts may have
some interest in him . . . Matt Beck, who had great credentials as
a Cal linebacker but didn't get drafted because of injuries, was
cut swiftly by the Patriots and Seahawks in his free agent tryouts
. . . The No. 1 Patriots fan of the South, Braves pitcher and
Billerica native Tom Glavine, said, ``It's a tough division but you
always have a chance to win when you have a Drew Bledsoe.'' Those
tossers of the ball stick together, don't they? . . . No offense to
capable UMass defensive coordinator Don Brown, whom Northeastern
hired to succeed Barry Gallup as football coach, but former Patriot
Steve Nelson has done a great job as head coach and athletic
director at Curry, and would have given the Huskies the visibility
and name recognition they sorely need in this area . . . Bobby Orr,
who runs Woolf Associates in Boston, said the firm has no plans to
revive the football end of its business. The Ricky Williams fiasco
_ it had Williams and then lost him _ left a bad taste, so Orr said
he will stick to baseball and hockey and keep away from what has
become a seedy business . . . Word is there wasn't complete
blessing given in Dallas for the team's signing of Randall
Cunningham. It was obviously a move by Jerry Jones to bring in a
high-profile player, but Cunningham has no experience with the Jack
Reilly-Ernie Zampese offense, which is why the team had signed Paul
Justin earlier in the offseason . . . Bobby Grier said he'll never
talk about it, but he's told friends that he felt blindsided when
Belichick fired him. He had felt completely involved in the
organization even after Belichick came aboard. And don't think that
Grier and Pete Carroll can't live in harmony again someday. Carroll
will likely be a candidate for the expansion Houston job,
especially if Jeff Fisher signs an extension in Tennessee . . . The
NFL is just kidding, right? No suspension for Ray Lewis because he
cut a deal on a double-murder rap and plea-bargained down to
obstruction of justice? So now he gets to play linebacker for the
Ravens again? Just like that? . . . Happy anniversary, Don Botieri.
For 50 years, he has cut hair and talked sports at Don's Barber
Shop in Hanson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
