</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DUVAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINO DUVA BACK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dino Duva is back where he wants to be, but he's not back where
he was.
</P>
<P>
   The former president of Main Events, the promotional company
started up by his brother, Dan, that fell apart in a sad family
squabble after Dan's death, is back in boxing. Dino is back with
his father, legendary trainer Lou Duva, and back with his sister,
Donna. He's back promoting events around the country. All in all,
he's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting over, but we're not in a new business,'' Dino
Duva said of his new promotional company, Duva Boxing. ``It's a lot
different from starting a new company from scratch because of all
the contacts we have in the business and the reputation we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not easy. It takes an investment to make an impact.
When you have a lot of stars, like we had at Main Events, it's a
lot easier to maintain yourself. It's harder to start from scratch
because you can't get things done the way you used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have fighters like Pernell Whitaker, Evander
Holyfield, and Lennox Lewis, it gives you power in the industry
that you can use to help your other fighters. We don't have that
now. That's been the hardest thing to deal with mentally. We can't
get things done the way we used to at Main Events. Leverage and
power are important in this business. When you don't have that, you
need breaks for your fighters and they're harder to come by.''
</P>
<P>
   The one break Duva never thought he'd see was the breakup of
Main Events, which also included fight manager Shelly Finkel. After
Dan Duva died of cancer at age 44 in 1996, Dino replaced him as
company president and for a time the business flourished.
</P>
<P>
   But squabbles developed over his way of doing business and that
of his sister-in-law, Kathy, and attorney Pat English, a friend of
his brother's who was on the board representing Dan Duva's family
trust.
</P>
<P>
   Bitterness arose and finally Dino, Lou, and Donna were forced
out in a power struggle that remains to be settled. Main Events has
moved but continues to be a major player in the industry with
Duva's sister-in-law in charge and former friend Gary Shaw running
the day-to-day operation.
</P>
<P>
   They retain promotional rights to some of the biggest names in
the sport, including Lewis, but their business has suffered from
the infighting, and neither side is what it was.
</P>
<P>
   The court battle may drag on for some time with the Duva family
arguing it was their business in the first place, and Dan's family
countering that they were employees who merely held a
profit-sharing interest. How it will be resolved is unclear, but
for the moment Duva Boxing fights on as it did years ago, when Lou
Duva was running tiny shows at a place called Ice World and his
kids ran the ticket booth and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   They were small-time fights for small-time money, but there was
no squabbling. That didn't come until the money and the big-time
fights, and Dan's death. Everything has changed since those days
for the Duvas, especially Dino, who is trying to make a comeback
like so many of the fighters he has handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very stressful several years as president of Main
Events,'' he said. ``There were a lot of people undermining me and
some were stabbing me in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family went through a major tragedy with my brother dying
and I became the point man for a lot of pain. I took a lot of heat,
but I thought I did a pretty good job. We made a lot of money in
those years, but it became a lousy situation for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I resent is the way some people in our own organization
acted and treated me. All I heard was, `Dan wouldn't have done it
that way.' It became personal, that's what I regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``A boxer promoter has to gamble. What's important is that you
win more than you lose. I did win more than I lost. Look at
Fernando Vargas, Zab Judah, and Vernon Forrest. They're some of the
best fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry about a lot of things that happened, but I was angry
for a long time and I let it affect me. I'll never forget what some
people in my own organization did to me, but I sat home every day
for a long time doing nothing. There's still some bitterness inside
me, but you've got to move on in life. My family is back together
and we're back in boxing. That's enough for now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Connecticut's Angel Vasquez is probably the best
fighter Duva has under contract and the problem he's had trying to
match him with Prince Naseem Hamed is an example of the leverage
problem his new organization faces.
</P>
<P>
   Duva had Vasquez on a list of three possible opponents for
Hamed's Aug. 19 HBO fight at Foxwoods, but the featherweight
champion ended up choosing Augie Sanchez, a Las Vegas-based boxer
of lesser note. In the old days, when Duva promoted some of the
sport's biggest names, he would have gotten his lesser-known
fighter that shot at a big fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't deny it's more exciting to work on big events, but
young fighters like we have are more humble,'' Duva said. ``They
appreciate things more. The hardest thing now is putting things in
financial perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Main Events, we could lose some money on small shows to try
and build a guy up. Now we have to try and make a profit on all our
shows because the losses build up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough adjustment, but we have a great prospect in
Jermaine Fields (who is 19-0) and several other kids my father is
very high on. We've got a kid named Eric Kirkland who's 6-0 and is
a hell of a puncher from Ohio. He just knocked out a kid Cedric
(Kushner, a former Duva friend and rival promoter) was high on. You
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   The odds on Oscar De La Hoya keep rising in Las Vegas, but don't
ask Shane Mosley why. ``I see myself, with a lot of speed, just
overwhelming him,'' the undefeated former lightweight champion said
of his fight Saturday night with De La Hoya. ``I have footage of a
sparring session we had just before Oscar went to the 1992
Olympics. He came to our gym because he needed some help sparring.
We threw a lot of jabs at each other. Looking at it now, it looks
like I could hit him whenever I wanted.'' Oh, really? . . . HBO
moved one step closer to making a De La Hoya-Trinidad rematch when
it announced last week a multifight deal with Trinidad, who had
previously fought for promoter Don King on Showtime. Trinidad will
make his HBO debut July 22 when he defends the World Boxing
Association super welterweight title he won March 3 from David Reid
against Mamadou Thiam (33-1, 30 KOs). In the last 18 months,
Trinidad has defeated three American gold medalists _ Whitaker, De
La Hoya, and Reid. With HBO now likely paying the lion's share of
the purse for De La Hoya-Trinidad and with both house fighters, the
likelihood of a rematch at a catch weight between 147 and 154
increases markedly if for no other reason than HBO now has nobody
to argue with but itself (and King) over the bout. And King knows
the only way he can get Trinidad the kind of money he wants is to
go back on pay-per-view with De La Hoya . . . David Tua's last
three fights have lasted less than eight minutes. He has gone
beyond the third round only once in his last seven fights, and 14
of his 35 victories (35-1, 31 KOs) have come in the first round.
Tua is ranked No. 1 by both the International Boxing Federation and
World Boxing Council and will get his mandatory with Lewis in
November. When he does, the bout will be on HBO, but Showtime will
retain its rights to his future fights. That's why it put on last
weekend's debacle with Obed Sullivan and will show him again next
month against Jorge Luis Gonzalez. ``You can draw your own
conclusions where he fights after he beats Lewis,'' Showtime
executive Jay Larkin said. ``It's not for any great humanitarian
reasons we're putting him on in two quick fights.'' . . . Mike
Tyson's trainers, Tommy Brooks and Jay Bright, insisted last week
their man will appear as scheduled June 24 in Glasgow, against Lou
Savarese. The fight has twice been postponed by Tyson, but his
people claim he is working hard in Phoenix and Las Vegas and
peeling off some of the reported 274 pounds he ballooned to since
his quick blowout of Julius Francis in February. The fight is
expected to attract nearly 60,000 to Hamden Park. ``Mike is very
excited about the crowd,'' Bright said. ``His experience in
Manchester (England) was rejuvenating for him. It took him back to
a time when the crowds in the US were so excited to see him. Mike
is ready to go. He's ready to vaporize anyone in front of him.'' .
. . Tyson remains on the antidepressant Zoloft, but although it
helps him control his mood swings, the British Board of Boxing
Control's chief medical officer has expressed concern that Tyson
might be taking ``tranquilizers.'' Bright said Tyson does not take
the medication in the weeks leading up to a fight, and it should
not be a problem. ``It's a serotonin uptake,'' Bright said. ``It
helps balance the chemicals in the brain. When something happens,
he reacts properly and doesn't lose his temper.'' That's good to
know . . . Savarese's trainer, Jesse Reid, said last week he
advised his fighter to be wary after the bell sounds to end a round
because Tyson likes to hit late. When told of this, Brooks had
another suggestion: ``Don't worry about after the bell. Worry about
the three minutes until the bell.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Although George Foreman has insisted he never paid anyone to
help get Axel Schulz rated so he could fight him for the IBF title,
promoter Bob Arum claims he was told by Foreman and his attorney,
Henry Holmes, that $250,000 had been paid to an IBF official
through another promoter, Butch Lewis. Arum says that is why he
delivered only $100,000 of a proposed $200,000 kickback to IBF
president Bob Lee for that purpose. One of Foreman's attorneys said
last week the money paid to Lewis was a consulting fee. ``George
never believed that money was a payoff and does not know if it went
to the IBF,'' said Lawrence Wechsler, another of Foreman's
attorneys. Foreman is on the prosecution witness list in the
federal trial of the IBF on bribery charges, but Lewis is not. Arum
testified Tuesday that he does not have an immunity deal, despite
reports to the contrary. He claims he came forward to testify
because ``it's time to do what I could to end the corruption in
boxing.'' What? Did he just notice it? . . . Play a sad song for
the passing of one of boxing's greatest publicists, Irving Rudd,
who died recently at 82. He showed his versatility by working for
both King and Arum, and handling King's public relations in 1977 in
the midst of the scandal-ridden ABC boxing tournament . . . The
only man who can save Julio Cesar Chavez from a birthday beating
against Kostya Tszyu July 29 is Holyfield. If Holyfield is ready to
go on that date, he would meet Chelsea heavyweight John Ruiz, but
it's more likely, according to Showtime sources, that the fight
will be Aug. 12. ``That's the logical date,'' a Showtime official
said. King is still looking for a site, with Caesars Palace in the
bidding but no longer a lock . . . Lowell's Micky Ward, the World
Boxing Union junior welterweight champion, fights on the
Hamed-Sanchez undercard Aug. 12 at Foxwoods against California's
Antonio Diaz. Diaz is the International Boxing Association
140-pound champion, but neither title will be at stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
