<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-STEWART-USOPEN-BO     06-10 2046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-STEWART-USOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S PRESENCE WILL BE FELT AT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime in the next few days _ perhaps when the sun is bidding
farewell for another day or after the moon has assumed position to
sprinkle a soft glow over Carmel Bay _ he will walk quietly toward
the 18th hole at Pebble Beach Golf Links, the roar of the Pacific
Ocean continuous, breathtaking beauty stretching to the horizon. He
will carry a bottle of expensive champagne, priceless memories, and
an indescribable pain to the wall that protects one of golf's most
precious pieces of real estate from the fury of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Though the pomp and glitz of the 100th US Open will be all
around him, the moment on that wall will have nothing to do with
golf, but everything to do with the human spirit that we all too
often forget is part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a day goes by that I don't remember him. He always treated
me great. He was a great friend and I loved him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   So, on that wall, Chuck Cook will raise a toast to Payne
Stewart, just as he promised he would in a tearful eulogy last
October in front of thousands of people jammed into First Baptist
Church in Orlando. ``How do you celebrate the life of the greatest
celebrator of life that you know?'' Cook had asked that warm fall
day, less than a week removed from the LearJet tragedy that killed
Stewart, 42, and five others.
</P>
<P>
   For Cook, the answer is: Quietly, in his own, personal
</P>
<P>
   way. Many people heard him talk about the wall at Pebble Beach,
but this will be a private moment for Cook, who lost ``a big part
of my life,'' that fateful October afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just go out there alone and sit on that wall. I'm not
telling anyone when,'' said Cook, the longtime swing coach, soul
mate, and traveling companion of the two-time US Open champion.
``I've had a hard time with it. It's been tough, tougher than I
thought it would be. But this (week) will be good for me. It will
be closure for me. After that, you know, life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, the US Open. And not just any US Open. A US Open at
Pebble Beach, arguably the most spectacular golf course in the
country, one that even veteran players get goose bumps thinking
about. That this week is all about the US Open, Pebble Beach, and
the memory of William Payne Stewart is an ironic mixture that is
not lost on colleagues who are usually focused on matters more
self-centered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he had won the AT&AMP;T, you know, at Pebble
Beach,'' said Hal Sutton, ``and the fact that he had won the US
Open in such dramatic fashion last year and that he's not going to
be there to defend his title is . . . well, it will be pretty hard
not to think about Payne Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's left to say?
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger wasn't thinking about Payne Stewart as he stood
over a 5-foot putt on the 72d hole of last summer's US Open at
Pinehurst No. 2. ``All I was thinking about was getting to Pebble
Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew he needed that putt to secure a top 15 finish, which
would bring an exemption into the next year's championship. Azinger
made the putt, but his vision of the stunning holes along the
Pacific aren't what they were following last summer's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what has happened since, Payne's death and everything,
the feeling is not quite as special,'' said Azinger. ``It's going
to be very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger was perhaps Stewart's closest friend on Tour, and the
tragedy has scarred him emotionally more so than other PGA Tour
players because also killed were Robert Fraley and Van Ardan,
agents for both players. (Bruce Borland, a design associate with
Jack Nicklaus's course architecture company, and pilots Michael
King and Stephanie Bellegarrigue were also killed.)
</P>
<P>
   Azinger has been quiet most of the year when asked about
Stewart, but as Pebble Beach approaches, reporters have besieged
him. ``I'll do one press conference Tuesday and talk about it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Mike Hicks, don't know what more to say. He was
Stewart's caddie in 1991 when they defeated Scott Simpson in a
playoff at Hazeltine, then again in 1993, at Baltusrol, and 1998,
at The Olympic Club, when fourth-round US Open leads were
squandered to Lee Janzen. And, most definitely, he was there last
summer at Pinehurst No. 2 when Stewart rolled in the longest
72d-hole putt to clinch a US Open title.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is the fellow in the memorable picture, the one leaping
into Stewart's arms, teammates in victory, friends in life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hicks works for Bob Estes. He has suffered, talked about
it, and suffered some more. He has said everything he wants to say,
so quietly he will spend this week at Pebble Beach by the side of
Estes, whose swing coach is Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has indicated that he's a little tired of talking about it
because it gets so emotional and he's tired of being put through
that all the time,'' said Estes of Hicks. ``It will be a difficult
week for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because Hicks, like Cook, knew Stewart as so much more
than the inside-the-ropes showbiz performer, the guy with the
knickers and cap who felt it was important to stand out from the
crowd. After he had won his second US Open _ and third major
championship _ on Father's Day last June, Stewart celebrated not
with Hollywood types, but with regular people at Hicks's home a few
hours from Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   They drove through the night in Hicks's truck, drank beers until
4:30 a.m., got a few hours sleep, then took part in a charity golf
tournament that the caddie had organized months earlier. Little did
they know that it would follow a US Open triumph, but with very
little fanfare, Stewart kept his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   He was, after all, a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Changing speeds
</P>
<P>
   The Payne Stewart who will be remembered so warmly during this
week's US Open was far different from the Payne Stewart who rubbed
colleagues the wrong way when he arrived on the PGA Tour scene in
1981. Fiercely competitive, Stewart was so cocky as to be
borderline arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1989 Nabisco Championship (now the Tour Championship),
Stewart let the event slip away and lost on the second hole of a
playoff to Tom Kite, one of the game's most admired players. Cook
was stunned to the point of embarrassment when he watched Stewart
storm off without shaking hands, the ultimate act of disrespect in
a game that prides itself on sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, when he won the US Open, Payne wasn't an outgoing
guy, at least not warm to the USGA,'' said Tom Meeks, director of
rules and competitions for the ruling body of golf in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say that I only knew Payne Stewart through a
casual relationship before (the 1998 US Open). I'm sure he knew of
me through the USGA, but we were never friends.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time fate brought Meeks into close contact with Stewart
at The Olympic Club in 1998, an amazing transformation had come
over the sweet-swinging gallery darling who remained popular
despite just one win in the previous six years. Though his game had
slipped, Stewart had strengthened his ties to his wife and two
children, mostly through a spiritual rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the things I admired about him _ he became a
very special person, such a well-rounded, devoted family man,''
said Meeks. ``I looked forward to establishing a stronger
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Meeks were an interlocked story at each of the last
two US Opens, the player in contention and the head rules guy whose
job it is to move along players. ``I keep telling Tom,'' said
Stewart during his celebratory soiree with the media last year at
Pinehurst, ``this is a golf tournament, not a track meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks laughed when reminded of that statement, knowing full well
that it was vintage Stewart, always prodding, always trying to get
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   At both The Olympic Club in 1998 and Pinehurst No. 2 in 1999,
Stewart was the third-round leader and thus situated in the final
group. He was trying to hold together a shaky game two years ago
when he came upon a most unpleasant sight: His tee shot at the
short, par-4 12th had landed in a sand-filled divot.
</P>
<P>
   The old Payne Stewart most likely would have kicked dirt and
tossed a tantrum, but this Payne Stewart chomped on his gum and
almost snickered. He pondered the situation, changed clubs three or
four times, slapped his second shot into the bunker, made bogey,
and got put on the clock one hole later by Meeks for being out of
place.
</P>
<P>
   Six holes later, Stewart had lost a second US Open in six years
to Lee Janzen, but unlike 1993 at Baltusrol when he pouted, this
time he stood tall and told the media that he had blown the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't happy,'' said Meeks, ``but contrary to what people
may think, he did not have an ax to grind. He handled it very well.
He didn't blame me, didn't blame the USGA. He informed me that he
was in a sand-filled divot and explained that he took his time to
decide how to hit the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Meeks was in Orlando for a rules seminar
when he sneaked away for golf at Isleworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my friends said, `Hey, Tom, there's Payne Stewart on
the practice tee,' and I immediately walked toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to say that when he saw me, he walked toward me,
too. You never would have recognized him without the cap and
knickers. He had on Bermuda shorts. He said, `We have to talk,' and
I said, `That's exactly what I was hoping to hear you say.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, his seminar wrapped up, Meeks returned to
Isleworth to play a casual nine holes with Stewart, who brought
along his son, Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart kept on Meeks about sand-filled divots, how they should
be considered ``ground under repair,'' but the USGA official held
firm. Stewart may have felt he was leading the debate when Meeks
asked him if he had ever practiced shots out of a sand-filled
divot. Stewart was speechless, a rarity for him, though he offered
a sly smile, as if to concede that Meeks had scored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drama at Pinehurst
</P>
<P>
   Their paths crossed in 1999, almost a carbon copy of The Olympic
Club. Only this time Stewart was not on the clock, though slow play
was at issue.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the deja vu, the same man who had stumbled badly
down the stretch at The Olympic Club was near-spectacular in the
closing pressure-cooker of Pinehurst. He drained a 25-footer to
save par at the 16th, then a 3-footer for birdie at the par-3 17th
put him in the lead. The 18th? It's forever etched in golf folklore
_ a drive into the right rough, 9-iron layup, lob wedge to about 15
feet, one scintillating, dead-in-the-hole, major-winning putt, and
a knockout punch into the misty North Carolina air.
</P>
<P>
   It is the most vivid memory many people will carry of a golfer
who had ridden his talents to the top of his profession while
growing into a person of great character. Not Chuck Cook, though.
</P>
<P>
   He will sit on that wall at some point this week and remember a
guy with whom he saw the world, one golf course at a time, and all
the songs they sung in all the pubs they had visited after the
day's competition had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of him as a US Open champ,'' said Cook. ``I
think of him as a friend. I think of all the people this had
affected _ his wife (Tracey) and children (Chelsea, 14, and Aaron,
11). Aaron is so much like Payne; he needs a father figure to take
him fishing and golfing. That's what hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears will flow when Cook sits on that wall, the same wall on
which he sat with Stewart in the spring of 1992. As reigning
champion, Stewart had been brought in for a media day to promote
that summer's US Open at Pebble Beach, returning the trophy, of
course, and taking along Cook. Well into the night, Stewart and
Cook drank champagne _ the really expensive stuff, Cristal _ and
toasted their friendship and good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   How fitting then, Stewart and Cook thought last June, that they
would again be returning to a US Open at Pebble Beach as reigning
champions. Indeed, they agreed to again sit on that wall, sip
champagne, listen to one crashing wave after another, and give
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   And so they shall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
