<SLUG> BC-NYJOHN11-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETECTIVES ASK FOR LETTERS ALLEGEDLY WRITTEN BY MISSING WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Detectives
investigating the deaths or disappearances of as many as eight
women and a baby have asked the mother of one woman for letters her
daughter purportedly mailed from Europe after she told relatives
she was going to work for John Edward Robinson Sr.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Bonner, who once lived in Cameron, Mo., has not been
seen since 1994, when she told relatives Robinson had found her a
job. The occasional typewritten letters with Bonner's signature
stopped arriving in January 1997. The last letter was dated in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they wanted her letters so they might do the DNA on
the stamps and so forth,'' said the mother, who spoke to a reporter
Saturday on the condition that her name and location not be
published. She said she mailed the letters about the middle of last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's mother asked a detective who called last week from
Lenexa whether her daughter was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their answer was that they needed proof, dental work or some
proof to confirm their thinking,'' the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning police told Bonner's brother that the
confirmation had come through dental records, the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Several investigators Saturday refused to say whether they
believed Bonner was dead, or whether they were looking into her
disappearance. They said only that they were continuing to try to
identify the bodies that were discovered in barrels on Robinson's
land outside La Cygne, Kan., and in a storage unit he rented in
Raymore.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to identify those bodies were ongoing this weekend, said
Johnson County, Kan., District Attorney Paul Morrison, whose office
is part of the investigations. ``Progress is being made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who has not been charged in connection with any of the
disappearances or deaths, has been held in the Johnson County Adult
Detention Center since June 2. A judge set a $5 million bond after
Robinson was charged with sexually assaulting two women who met him
for sadomasochistic sex and with stealing more than $700 worth of
sex toys from one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner first may have met Robinson when she worked in the
library of the Western Missouri Correctional Center in Cameron,
Mo., according to her second husband, William Bonner of Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was released in 1993. The next year, Bonner divorced
her husband, left Cameron and met up with Robinson, her family
said.
</P>
<P>
   At first Bonner told her mother that Robinson had found her work
with the overseas branch of a U.S. company that made perfume and
other products, but she could not say exactly what the job was or
where she would be stationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mail was always sent to a letter drop in Olathe, Kansas,
and then it was forwarded on to her. Her letters (home) never had a
return address,'' Bonner's mother said. ``She always said it was
information she couldn't divulge, and she said to trust her.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's relatives were worried, but the letters they received
with postmarks from foreign countries where her family thought she
was living were sprinkled with details that made them believe she
was safe and happy with her mysterious job.
</P>
<P>
   The typed messages over the signature ``Love, Bev'' described
current events in Moscow when she was purportedly living there, and
a letter from Amsterdam, Netherlands, accurately described a street
her mother had seen before. And although they were typewritten,
Bonner's mother said, the words sounded like her daughter's.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives investigating Robinson have said they are looking
into his connection to Lisa Stasi, a 19-year-old woman who
disappeared from Overland Park, Kan., in 1985 after telling her
family that she had signed four blank sheets of paper for Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi's family later received typewritten letters over her
signature that said she was leaving Overland Park, Kan., with her
5-month-old daughter and no longer wanted to be in touch with them.
</P>
<P>
   One of Stasi's relatives told a detective at the time that she
was suspicious because Stasi could not type and the words did not
sound like hers.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner wrote to her family that she was traveling to Australia
and different parts of Europe, and that she stopped in Amsterdam
many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (employees) seemed to come through Amsterdam, and that
seemed to be their headquarters where they went after each
assignment, if this is fact and not fiction,'' her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, Bonner's family received the last letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said that she'd be leaving Russia after the 5th of
December 1996, and they would be going to Amsterdam and they would
be going on to their next assignment, which was in China,''
Bonner's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter ended, ``Remember that I love you, and I'll be in
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's mother worried after three months passed without word
from her daughter. Then six months went by, and then nine, and the
family knew they had to begin searching for their relative.
</P>
<P>
   The company Bonner claimed to be working for said she was not an
employee, the mother said. The family then turned to U.S. Rep.
Cliff Stearns, who represents Florida's 6th District, for help.
</P>
<P>
   They received a State Department letter from Stearns saying that
the U.S. government would keep an eye out for Bonner overseas, but
that they could not put her family in touch with her without her
permission, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives also tried contacting banks but heard nothing about
Bonner's fate until police called from Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's mother said the news from police only confirmed what
she had come to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fact is a fact,'' she said. ``I had closure because she's
been missing for 3 years _ at least 3 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
