<SLUG> BC-RAC-ONRACING-LUKAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS WINS WITH SLOW HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Each year on Belmont Stakes Day, the New York Racing
Association does a favor for ABC and provides a dress rehearsal for
the big race.
</P>
<P>
   For the unknowing fan, it seems odd that the fourth race is
always run at 1 1/2 miles, a distance that usually attracts an
average collection of claiming and allowance horses. For that
unknowing fan, it is always a mystery just who in the motley
collection can run the distance seldom run on dirt in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But that race is not run for the fans, but for a television
network. The distance is the same as the Belmont distance and the
network gets to practice its camera angles at the starting gate,
its shots on the clubhouse turn, and its pans down the backstretch
to iron out any last glitches two hours before the big race.
</P>
<P>
   And once again Saturday, that fourth race was run at the Belmont
distance. It is not important who won, but what stands out _ in
light of what happened in the Belmont Stakes itself _ is the time
of the race run by the motley collection.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the motley crew ran 1 1/2 miles in 2 minutes 31.40
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Commendable won the Belmont Stakes in 2:31.19,
a mere fifth of a second faster. Only once in the last 30 Belmonts
has a winner won in a time slower than 2:30, and that was Thunder
Gulch's 2:32 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called up Coach a couple of weeks ago,'' said Bob Lewis, who
owns Commendable with his wife Beverly, ``and I said, `Coach, you
sure we're doing the right thing' '' in running the horse in the
Belmont?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach,'' of course is D. Wayne Lukas, the former basketball
coach and the trainer of Commendable. Lukas had spent hours
studying the field for Saturday's Belmont. Lukas's analysis was
confirmed: Commendable would be facing a most motley crew in this
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   And as Commendable's jockey Pat Day later would say, ``I've
learned over the years that you can't leave Mr. Lukas out in the
big races.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas surprised all when his reformed claiming horse,
Charismatic, won the 1999 Kentucky Derby and nearly pulled off a
Triple Crown, just as he surprised all when Cat Thief stole the
Breeders' Cup Classic last November. Over the years, Lukas has
pulled off this trick time and again; winning big races with horses
who either seem as if they don't belong, or seem off form.
</P>
<P>
   And the horses often pay big prices, much as Commendable's
$39.60 did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people say, `You can't do something,' I feed off that and
my help feeds off that,'' said Lukas, whose win Saturday was his
fourth in the Belmont Stakes. ``I told Bob and Beverly Lewis an
hour before the race, `We do our best when it's least expected.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas seemed to take as much pride after Saturday's shocker that
his analysis of the race's talent (or lack thereof) was right on
the bull's-eye. With Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness
winner Red Bullet out of the Belmont, all knew this would be a
Belmont Lite.
</P>
<P>
   But Lukas went further. ``I spent hours analyzing the other
horses in the race _ I mean, I did it personally, _ as far as the
opposition was concerned,'' said Lukas. ``And you have to go with
the cards you're dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   The slowness of the race proved that Lukas was on target. This
was the weakest Belmont in memory, and a comparison of the internal
splits of the times run by the motley crew in the fourth race and
the almost-as-motley crew in the Belmont confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   The horses who'll never be remembered ran a half-mile in 48 1/5
seconds, compared with the slower 49 seconds in the Belmont. The
fourth race's time for 6 furlongs was 1:12 1/5, nearly two seconds
faster than the 1:14 of the Belmont. And the motley crew in the
fourth race ran their first mile in 1:38, compared with the slower
1:39.11 in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to look at what you're up against,'' said
Lukas. ``We didn't come into the race with any grandiose thoughts
that we could win the race, but maybe we were the only ones who
believed in the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Or knew how motley were the rest of the Belmont entries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 67,810 fans flocked to Belmont on a 95-degree day even if
they sensed what Lukas knew in his head _ this was a most ordinary
field.
</P>
<P>
   And if any lessons are to be learned _ finally _ about D. Wayne
Lukas, it is these: the worse his horse looks on paper, the more
the horse should be feared. And Lukas always _ always _ has his
horses ready for the biggest races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
