<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-TRADE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS PICK UP GOALIE GIGUERE FROM CALGARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mighty Ducks general manager Pierre Gauthier usually
doesn't part with high draft choices. The player he gets in return,
he said, has to be ``pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier and the Anaheim scouting staff believed 23-year-old
goalie Jean-Sebastien Giguere is good enough that the Ducks sent
their second-round choice in the 2000 NHL Entry draft to Calgary in
a deal completed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giguere, a No.1 pick (13th overall) of Hartford in 1995, played
seven games with the Flames last season. He went 1-3-1 with a 2.73
goals-against average and a .914 save percentage.
</P>
<P>
   His only win came Dec. 29, 1999 against the Ducks. Giguere is
8-14-2 in 30 NHL appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know him well ... our goaltending is a lot better today
than it was yesterday,'' said Gauthier, who added top prospects
like Giguere are more readily available this year because teams
don't want to lose a goalie and get nothing in return in the
upcoming expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert and backup Dominic Roussel had subpar 1999-2000
seasons, but Gauthier stressed the acquisition of Giguere shouldn't
be over-analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big-picture thing,'' said Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Hebert's age (33), Gauthier said, ``It's not just
about next season. Now we have two good young goalies in the system
(Giguere and Greg Naumenko, in addition to veteran Corey Hirsch).
It's certainly an improvement in our depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier refused to say where Giguere would fit into Anaheim's
plans next season, but he believes Hebert is capable of returning
to form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know Guy is a better goalie,'' Gauthier said. ``He has
been a good goalie in the past and he will be again. But you need
more than one or two goalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you need three.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
