<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ROWING-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS RIVER LEADS TO SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ The Cooper River runs straight from here to
Sydney _ for some people. For others, it's a diversion to
Switzerland. These are the US Olympic rowing trials. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Some boats, like the unchallenged men's and women's eights, get
a free pass to this summer's Games. Others, like the men's pair and
women's single and double, still have to earn a berth at a special
qualifying regatta in Lucerne next month.
</P>
<P>
   But a few, like Aquil Abdullah, Worcester, Mass., attorney
Christine Collins and Boston-based Steve Tucker and Conal Groom,
can get their tickets here Sunday. And if Abdullah can nail down a
second victory Sunday morning in the best-of-three finals, he'll
become rowing's Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was Jackie Robinson's intention to become the
first black ballplayer in the major leagues,'' said the 26-year-old
sculler from Washington, D.C., who would be the first
African-American male rower to make an Olympic team. ``He just
wanted to play baseball. All I want to do is row. My goal is to go
to the Olympics. Everything else is gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   Once former world champion Jamie Koven switched back to sweep
rowing, the door was open for Abdullah, who put his first foot
through Saturday by outpulling Don Smith, last autumn's Head of the
Charles champion, by half a length. Now, he has two races to win
one.
</P>
<P>
   So do Henry Nuzum, last year's Harvard captain and partner Mike
Ferry, who handled David Gleeson and Chris Duffy by a length in the
men's double.
</P>
<P>
   History and form say that nearly all of Saturday's victors
should prevail Sunday. Collins and Sarah Garner, who breezed past
Angie Cummins and Whitney Post by open water in the women's
lightweight double, should win a medal in Sydney in September. So,
too, could Karen Kraft and Missy (Schwen) Ryan, who took silver in
the women's pair in Atlanta and dunked Lianne Nelson and Katie
Maloney by nearly 2 lengths Saturday. And Tucker and Groom, who
handled Bill Belden and Greg Ruckman by just under a length, figure
to make the Olympic final in the men's lightweight double.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else gets a US jersey and a promissory note. Because
the men's pair, four, and quad and the women's single and double
didn't qualify for the Games at last year's world regatta in
Ontario, they'll have to do it overseas. ``I feel somewhat
responsible for that,'' said Carol Skricki of Norwood, Mass., who
missed the cut in the double with former partner Cindy Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   This year Skricki is teamed with Ruth Davidon, who made the
single final in Atlanta, retired to go to med school, then came
back for another shot at Olympus. If they hold off Elizabeth Smith
and Julia Chilicki again Sunday, they're off to Lucerne. Or, they
can turn down the spot and go in the quad, which has already
qualified and has a better medal chance Down Under. ``It's nice to
have a choice like that,'' said the 37-year-old Skricki, a former
rock musician who didn't begin rowing until she was 30.
</P>
<P>
   If Skricki and Davidon opt for Lucerne, they can get a group
rate. Monica Tranel-Michini will be going over if she beats world
lightweight medalist Lisa Schlenker in the women's single. So will
the Augusta, Ga., quad of Sean Hall, Jake Wetzel, Ian McGowan, and
Nick Peterson, if they can best the Princeton entry of Phil Henry,
Tom Murray, Ben Holbrook, and Cy Beasley (of Newburyport, Mass.).
As will the pair of West Newton's Ted Murphy and Sebastian Bea, who
squelched Adam Holland and Tom Bohrer by a length in a showdown of
old partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only thinking about one race,'' said Murphy, who rowed
in the eight in Atlanta and won a world bronze with Holland in
1997. ``We're going to try to finish this tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
