<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-CLAMPETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAMPETT, THE PLAYER, BACK AT PEBBLE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a field of 150 players, there will be many wonderful tales
this week as the United States Golf Association conducts its 100th
Open championship. Unlike the weekly Tour events, the US Open is
special because it adds slices of life that are desperately lacking
week in and week out.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to tee it up at Pebble Beach are some amateurs who caught
lightning in their golf bags for a few days at sectional qualifying
and a splattering of club pros and mini-tour players who somehow
put it together after years of missing out. Great stories, all of
them, amid the glitz that surrounds golfers such as Tiger Woods and
David Duval. But no story is as personal as that of Bobby Clampett,
whose return to Pebble Beach as a competitor will be one of the
sidelights to this week's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Clampett grew up in Monterey, Calif., and you can do a lot worse
in life than call Pebble Beach your ``home course.'' It is where he
won the Junior Tournament of Champions and went undefeated during
two marches to the California State Amateur. His first professional
win came there, and if not for a mental error, his first PGA Tour
win may have come in the Crosby Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1981, back when Clampett joined young guys named
Payne Stewart and Mark O'Meara, John Cook and Fred Couples, Hal
Sutton and Scott Hoch in chasing the professional golf life. It is
hard to believe that Clampett is now 40 and nearly seven years
retired from the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Familywise, it was stressful,'' said Clampett of his decision
to get off the PGA Tour in the early 1990s. His third child was
born just after Christmas 1991 and Clampett saw a picture that
needed better focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I wanted to be a dad to my kids and a husband to my
wife. My commitment to the game wasn't what it had to be to be
successful. I had cut back to 15 or 16 tournaments a year, but my
game wasn't good enough to stay exempt playing so little.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his spot on the money list slipped from the security
of inside 100 to the anxiety of outside 125 to the nowhere world of
outside 150. Everywhere he looked, ``I saw young kids who were
hungry the way I used to be hungry,'' and that convinced him it was
time to get out. He traded in PGA for CBS, and has been part of the
network's golf coverage for six years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible opportunity,'' said Clampett, ``something
I enjoy so much. Priorities in my life is what I wanted and this
has given me the chance for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pebble Beach being Pebble Beach, the lure of the 2000 US
Open was too strong to resist, so Clampett honed his game and
cashed in as one of the longest of long shots by making it into the
field. He is one of the few who can say he made it through local,
then sectional challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Clampett shot 68-67 at Woodmont CC's North and South courses
Monday to earn a berth in his seventh US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been remarkable, a lot of well-wishers, just an
unbelievable feeling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His CBS friends have been his biggest boosters. Jim Nantz has
promised to walk every hole with him at Pebble Beach, and Ken
Venturi has gone a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over dinner, I kiddingly asked him what I had to do to make
the Presidents Cup team,'' said Clampett. ``He said, `Win the
Open.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If I win the Open, will I be on the Presidents Cup
team?' and he said, `That's a promise. You'll be on the Presidents
Cup team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wild, wonderful dream, one that probably will not come
true. Which is OK, because Clampett is quite proud of the one that
already has.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not one for the books
</P>
<P>
   In the months, weeks, and days leading up to the 1999 Ryder Cup,
Mark James often lent comic relief and a lighthearted perspective
to a mixture that was all too serious. But like all good things,
James's act had to end; now would someone kindly tell him to go
away? He has contributed something that the world does not need _
another golf book _ which, of course, is not a crime. What is a
sin, however, is that he felt compelled to drag private locker room
talk into the public domain and take cheap shots at a list of
people from US captain Ben Crenshaw to Tom Lehman to Nick Faldo.
The part of the book that stirred emotions overseas was James's
admission that he gleefully discarded a good-luck note sent by
Faldo, refusing to share it with the team. How utterly childish.
Like him or not, Faldo is the most accomplished Ryder Cup player in
history, one who poured his heart and soul into the event, and if
not for arguably the greatest wedge shot in the event's history _
Faldo's third shot to the 18th at Oak Hill in 1995 that set up a
crucial winning par against Curtis Strange _ the 1997 and 1999
matches may not have been what they were. Sure, Faldo offered
criticism of Colin Montgomerie for not challenging himself by
playing more in the US. So what? There was more than a grain of
truth to that comment, and, besides, Faldo had already squared
things with Montgomerie. James's act with Faldo's note was silly,
but nothing compared with his huge blunders as captain. First, he
should have had Bernhard Langer or Faldo on the team ahead of
Andrew Coltart. Second, he never should have burned out his top
nine players. It's hard to believe that James will survive as an
assistant to captain Sam Torrance for the 2001 event at The Belfry
. . . Brad Faxon did not get into the Masters field this year, but
he played Augusta National with some members before the club closed
in mid-May. ``I played the members' tees and felt like Tiger,''
said Faxon . . . Sutton is the latest to commit to the Greater
Hartford Open (June 29-July 2). He joins an already-rich field that
includes Davis Love, Justin Leonard, John Daly, Casey Martin, Mike
Weir, Paul Azinger, and Zoeller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Check that list
</P>
<P>
   You thought we were done with all those lists when 1999 ended?
Not a chance. Golf Digest, as part of its 50th anniversary
celebration, has listed _ appropriately _ the top 50 golfers in
history. No surprise that Jack Nicklaus is No. 1, or, for that
matter, that Ben Hogan, Sam Snead, Bobby Jones, and Byron Nelson
fall in behind him. (Woods comes in at No. 12, behind No. 10 Mickey
Wright but ahead of No. 17 Babe Zaharias.) There are, however, some
very glaring entries and omissions. Ray Floyd (No. 21) and Greg
Norman (22d) seem awfully high, while Ben Crenshaw (44) would not
be on my ballot, despite his two green jackets. (Jose Maria
Olazabal has two green jackets, too. Where is he?) Two-time US Open
champs Strange (33) and Ernie Els (40) get the nod, but the
always-forgotten Henry Picard (Masters and PGA winner) doesn't. The
prejudice in favor of US Open champs is obvious when Tom Kite (42)
somehow finds his way onto the list, yet Denny Shute (two PGAs, one
British Open; twice a US Open runner-up), Jack Burke Jr. (Masters,
PGA), and Love (PGA) do not. Go figure. Then again, why bother?
After all, without a Tom Morris _ old or young, doesn't matter _
and my personal favorite, Tony Lema, the list is lacking . . .
Perhaps you noticed a familiar name in the British Amateur: Raul
Ballesteros, nephew of the once-magical Seve. He shot 72-74 to
easily qualify but was ousted in the third round. The son of
Baldomero Ballesteros attended school in England and, at 19, is
tall and slender, and though he very much resembles his famous
uncle, Raul said it was his father who inspired him to play. He
has, of course, played many times with his uncle . . . As for Seve,
a painful hip forced him to withdraw after eight holes of the Wales
Open Thursday. A triple-bogey on the first hole added to the pain,
no doubt . . . While Australian Open champion Aaron Baddeley takes
his struggling game into the US Open on a special exemption, his
colleague from the Victoria Institute of Sport, Brad Lamb, made
news in the British Amateur. During a match against medalist Tim
Rice of Ireland, Lamb was in his backswing in the fairway when he
noticed his ball move ever so slightly. Lamb called a one-shot
penalty on himself, halved the hole, then went 1-down at the 17th
on a Rice chip-in. Perhaps rewarded for his integrity, Lamb squared
the match at the 18th with a 25-foot putt and won at the 19th hole
when Rice made bogey. Lamb also lost in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming swing
</P>
<P>
   James Driscoll, fresh off his ninth-place finish in the NCAA
Championship, is back home after graduating from the University of
Virginia. Indeed, it seems so few days ago that Driscoll was
leaving Brookline High School for college. He came up short in US
Open sectional qualifying Monday at Woodmont CC in Rockville, Md.,
though his 70-71 effort in a field dominated by PGA Tour veterans
was admirable. There is the Sunnehanna Amateur this weekend, then
the Northeast Amateur June 22-25, before Driscoll treats himself to
some time off before pursuing a third State Amateur (July 10-14 at
Worcester CC). He is exempt into the US Amateur (Aug. 21-27 at
Baltusrol) via his quarterfinal effort a year ago when he lost to
eventual champ David Gossett . . . The Norfolk County Women's
Classic is on tap July 7, a four-ball competition open to any woman
with a handicap. The entry fee is $90 per team, with entries due
June 30. Defending champs are Jane Welch and Jane Heggie . . .
Finally, do be careful if a Lee Chi-ming arrives some day for a
round of golf at your club. It seems the gentleman from Hong Kong
has been labeled a menace, ``so incompetent that every time he
strikes the ball, there's an obvious risk for anyone in front of
him,'' according to a judge who heard a case in which Lee was being
sued by a female caddie. Chau Fung-yee was seeking damages after
being hit in the mouth by an errant shot struck by Lee. The
defendant ``should not have played golf at all because he exposed
people to danger,'' said the caddie's lawyer. Good gracious, it
sounds like a charge many of us are guilty of.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
