</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-FRENCHOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE BRINGS HOME FRENCH OPEN CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They would forgive her anything, these citizens of
France. Mary Caroline Pierce couldn't get arrested in Paris if she
swiped Mona Lisa from the Louvre, spray-painted graffiti on the Arc
de Triomphe, or trampled flower beds in the Tuilleries Garden.
</P>
<P>
   She can do no wrong around here because she did so much right in
restoring to France the tennis championship of France, her adopted
post office box.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it took the French a while to overlook her abundant supply
of American blood, her high school French, and the fact that she
has always lived elsewhere. She made them uncomfortable, drove them
to tears and boos while failing, often miserably, during 10
previous shots at the French Open title.
</P>
<P>
   But that was all forgotten just before 5 p.m. Saturday when
Mighty Mary pounded a 93 mile-per-hour serve that handcuffed a
Spaniard who had beaten her here a year ago in the second round.
Conchita Martinez fought a pesky delaying action, and held chances
to go ahead, 3-0, in the second set, but it was Pierce and France's
day at Stade Roland Garros, 6-2, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez's feckless last swing sent the yellow ball trickling
along the muddy-looking soil toward the net, the mob filling Court
Central exploded with the kind of roar that must have accompanied
the storming of the Bastille. One of the 15,166 stood up and
shrugged her shoulders joyfully. She was Francoise Durr, the most
recently crowned queen of France _ and that was 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my shoulders feel lighter,'' she said with a laugh.
``I'm not carrying that around anymore. Now we have Mary and it's
wonderful. There is more attention now, more good players. I beat
an Australian, Lesley Turner. The stadium was smaller then, and it
wasn't full. We were amateurs in 1967, the year before prize money
began, and I received a voucher that I could exchange for $200 in
merchandise at a store. What did Mary get _ $575,000?''
</P>
<P>
   It's been 33 long, frustrating years (17 since Yannick Noah won
the men's title). This was a hungry crowd, starving for a champion
of their own _ so hungry they would have even eaten American food
if that were required to get it done. Instead, they were presented
with a magnum of half-and-half, and it went down splendidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is French, my father American. The reason this
tournament means so much to me, more special than my Australian
title in 1995, is my Frenchness,'' said Pierce. ``When my father
made the decision to play for France, I was 13. Twelve years ago. I
didn't like it because I had to leave my friends at school in
Treasure Island (Fla.). Other than that, you're 13 and your parents
make the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted funding from the US Tennis Association, and I think
they were willing but didn't want my father involved. So my mother
contacted the French Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought me here to practice. I lived in a dorm room here
at Roland Garros for a while. I couldn't speak French. I was alone,
13. I cried myself to sleep every night. It was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever had come up short so many times before becoming the
French champ. But 11 was Pierce's winning roll. She made the final
six years ago but was so tight and useless she could have
impersonated Venus de Milo. Arantxa Sanchez Vicario thought she was
up against a creation of Rodin.
</P>
<P>
   But lately Pierce has trained her emotions and nerves like a pet
dog: sit; be still; down. All the while, her strokes growl and
bite. Never had she attacked so forcefully and with such
self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the sluggish clay underfoot, she was looking to
charge at every opportunity, banging daring swinging volleys,
scoring sometimes from her shoe tops. She set up shop inside the
baseline and hammered her groundies ferociously, particularly the
double-barreled backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was trying, countering with more spins than a White
House spokesman. Martinez, a wizard of swirl and angles, threw
every imaginable slice, topspin, chop, moonball, drop shot and
trajectory at Pierce. That kept proceedings moving, almost two
hours' worth, but couldn't short-circuit the firepowering Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   With one set in her purse, Pierce paused and faltered enough to
let Martinez breathe, grab the first two games of the second, and
twice have points with serve for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the important game,'' Pierce said. It stretched nine
minutes and four deuces, during which the sun momentarily pierced a
cold, oily sky, and concluded with Pierce goading Martinez to a
backhand error.
</P>
<P>
   Rugged backhands sank Martinez's serve to 6-5, and ``my dream,
this championship'' began to fill out. It was Pierce's turn to
serve. One game for the bundle, and it wasn't easy. The nerves
wouldn't entirely roll over and play dead.
</P>
<P>
   In Durr's year, 1967, a band called Procul Harum had a hit
called ``A Whiter Shade of Pale.'' The blond and fair Pierce fit
the title as she went to the line to serve. Another nine-minute
ordeal. She butchered two match points, was beached at deuce three
times, and Martinez even had a break point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was always my dream . . . and I never thought I'd do
it,'' said Pierce. ``I went through so many emotions here, so many
disappointments. Now I was so close. The third match point I got
fired up, and I was like, `OK, you've lost two. This is the third.
Usually the third is the good one. Let's try and win this one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's valedictory serve was too much for Martinez, and the
color returned to her cheeks, the sparkle to eyes that soon dripped
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was the girl who had been pushed, and pushed around, by
her father, hired out to a foreign land where she wasn't really
wanted. She became the woman who won Australia _ and then was
dropped by famous coach Nick Bollettieri (as her ranking dropped to
No. 20) because ``she's out of shape and won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   She could identify with the Perils of Pauline. But Saturday it
was the Marvels of Mary. Maybe she hadn't always seemed sweet
French toast, but at last she was the toast of France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
