</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-COMMENDABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENDABLE EFFORT BY LUCKAS, DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those who ignore trainer D. Wayne Lukas and jockey
Pat Day do so at their own peril. That was the lesson learned from
Saturday's 132d running of the Belmont Stakes, as racing's dynamic
duo combined to win with Commendable, an 18-1 ($39.60 to win) shot,
who, frankly, would have been sent away at much higher odds were it
not for the reputations of his conditioner and rider.
</P>
<P>
   Commendable, a son of Gone West, broke his maiden at Del Mar
last August, but had not finished better than fourth in his
following six starts before the Belmont, a streak which included a
dreadful 17th in the Kentucky Derby. Saturday, however, he stalked
hopeless front-runner Hugh Hefner, took over with ease on the turn,
and boldly held off late-charging 8-5 favorite Aptitude by 1 1/2
lengths in front of 67,810.
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded and Shane Sellers also rallied to gain the show, a
length back. The time for the 1 1/2 miles was a slow 2:31 on a fast
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evaluation to run in this race concerned not so much how
Commendable was doing because, obviously, he was doing very well,''
said Lukas, who had said before Wednesday's draw that he was only
50-50 to enter Commendable. ``The more I looked at the field, the
more confident I was that we could have an impact. I spent more
energy analyzing the other horses than training my own horse. I
didn't predict a win, but I knew, with Day up, we'd be in the
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth Belmont victory for Lukas, and the third for
Day. Lukas teamed with Day to win the 1994 Belmont with Tabasco
Cat, and also tallied with Thunder Gulch ('95), and Editor's Note
('96). Day's other triumph came with Easy Goer in 1989. The other
members of Team Commendable are owners Bob and Beverly Lewis. The
Lewises won their first Belmont, after losing Triple Crown bids
with Silver Charm in 1997, and Charismatic last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was counting on Mr. Lukas's decision to run him,'' said Day.
``You can't count him out in one of these fixtures. Mr. Lukas asked
me to have an energy-saving trip. The horse was very relaxed. He
coasted along all the way. He took me to the lead on the turn. At
that point, I hadn't asked him to run, but I wasn't sure what I had
under me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked him, he responded. We didn't get to the bottom of
this horse today. I want to commend Mr. Lukas for his courage in
bringing him up here (Commendable is based at Churchill Downs) and
taking a shot. Last year, he was watching the way this horse got
over the ground and he said this was a Belmont horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises, the sport's top ambassadors, had won the Kentucky
Derby twice, and the Preakness three times (Timber Country in '95
being the other), but had suffered only frustration at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was heartache in our previous Belmont runs with Silver
Charm (who just missed), and Charismatic (who broke down),'' said
Bob Lewis. ``A lot of that was erased today. I called Wayne on
Wednesday morning and asked, `Are we doing the right thing?' He
reassured me, and he and Pat brought us a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was gracious in victory, but he couldn't resist a little
jab at the media, the majority of which gave Commendable no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm told I can't do something, that drives our whole
organization,'' he said. ``We feed off that, and do our best work
when they don't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, who had run second in the Derby, was last early in the
11-horse field, and that's no way to win a Belmont. ``I was hoping
for more pace,'' said Alex Solis. ``He was spinning his wheels on
the first turn. He got better when we got to the mile pole. He got
in gear, and started running. At the eighth-pole, I still thought I
had a chance. But Commendable had too easy of a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The game gelding Unshaded, sent away at 5-1, tried hard even
though he was last after a mile. But he was overcome by heat
exhaustion past the wire, suffering in the 95-degree heat. It
looked bad for a moment, but he was quickly cooled off with ice and
cold water, and was able to walk off the track, even though the
horse ambulance had been called. Later, Unshaded walked briskly
around his barn, proving he was all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was patting myself on the back at the three-eighths pole,''
said Sellers. ``He really kicked in on the turn. I thought I was
home free. But, as we straightened out, he got the wobbles, and I
didn't know what was happening. It was a very gutty performance.
But every time you count Lukas out, he steps up. He's a tough
man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
