<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS GETTING SHACKLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Larry Bird has done all of this before. He knows
about adversity in the NBA Finals. He knows the quirks of the 2-3-2
format. He knows about stopping unstoppable Lakers centers.
</P>
<P>
   He knows. But this time he's powerless to do much about it. Bird
can't put on a uniform, step into the paint, and bother Shaquille
O'Neal. And he can't make Reggie Miller shoot the way Larry Bird
shot in fourth quarters against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Finals resume Sunday night at Conseco Fieldhouse and
Bird's Pacers trail the Lakers, two games to none. In the first two
games in Los Angeles, Diesel Shaq scored 83 points while Miller
shot 25 percent (8 for 32). Meanwhile, Pacers center Rik Smits was
a cigar store Indian, bottoming out with a 16-minute, 4-point,
2-rebound no-show in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think, Larry? Time to call your players ``sissies,''
as you did after the Celtics were routed at the Forum in 1984? Time
for a Kevin McHale-like takedown of an unsuspecting Laker?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I believe is that they have to play hard,'' Bird said.
``When Shaq gets the ball underneath the basket, instead of going
up and trying to block his shot, which is almost impossible, they
have to take the hard foul and put him at the line. It's not to
hurt anyone, it's to try and save the 2 points and make him make
both.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the impact of McHale's play in '84. The Celtics had
lost two of the first three games _ and been outplayed in all three
_ when McHale's clothesline tackle of Kurt Rambis changed the
series (and the NBA rulebook).
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Maxwell said it best: ``Before that play, the Lakers were
like little kids just running across the street without looking.
But after that play, they would stop, press the `walk' button, wait
for the light to turn, then look both ways before walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Game 3 is the proverbial ``must game'' for the Pacers,
and Bird knows it. His team is in danger of being swept out of the
Finals, and only a Game 3 win will put a scare into Shaq and the LA
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers may be without sparkling young guard Kobe Bryant, but
it hardly mattered Friday when Bryant rolled his ankle in the first
quarter and never returned. The estimable Ron Harper charged the
basket and Bryant was hardly missed. Bryant is not the problem for
the Pacers. Shaq is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Bird went against his pledge Friday and ordered the Hack-a-Shaq
defense. It got so bad that O'Neal was actually fouled once while
he was standing out of bounds. The Big Fella took a Finals-record
39 free throws, making 18. It made for dreadful viewing as the
fourth quarter took 48 minutes. Bird was asked how this might
affect TV ratings and responded as you knew he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't worry about ratings,'' said the man who shot
ratings to new heights when he played. ``I'm trying to win a
ballgame right now. Whatever it takes to win a ballgame, we're
going to do it. If it takes a four-hour game, that's what we have
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the effectiveness of Hack-a-Shaq, Bird conceded, ``The
more you put him at the line, the better he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Fred Hickman (a.k.a. the George King of NBA MVP voters),
Shaquille O'Neal is MVP of the roundball universe in 2000. There is
no second-, third-, or fourth-place finisher. He is Wilt
Chamberlain in a league that has no Bill Russell answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played as hard as we could,'' said Bird after Game 2, ``but
tonight I just thought Shaq was better than he was the other
night.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's coach, Phil Jackson, a man who played against Wilt and
Russell, said, ``His ability to dominate the game compares
favorably to Chamberlain, who could dominate both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq has already done something Chamberlain never did: score 40
or more points in consecutive Finals games. Only Michael Jordan,
Rick Barry, and Jerry West performed the feat.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers guard Mark Jackson, who is old enough to have seen Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar joust with Bird and the Celtics, said of Shaq, ``He is
still the best center who's ever played the game. I've seen the
best centers and he truly is a step above any other center who ever
played. He's just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the right place at the right time,'' said O'Neal.
``I've listened and things are falling into place for me. When Kobe
went out, we felt that we had to pick it up. So I took it upon
myself to get position and take the high-percentage shots.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Lakers and Trail Blazers were battling for the
right to play Indiana in the Finals. Shaq was largely invisible for
three quarters against Portland and one-time great center Bill
Walton (now a TV guy) was questioning O'Neal's status as a dominant
big man.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed in that fourth quarter against the Blazers at
Staples Center and it could not have worked out worse for Larry
Bird and the Pacers. The coach and his players have no answer for
O'Neal. If they don't do something soon, the next big event at
Staples Center will be the Democratic National Convention in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Larry knows this. He just can't do anything about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
