<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN FINALLY AT A LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It's a good thing for Phil Jackson that Michael
Jordan didn't have as much trouble closing games as he does
coaching deals.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan again has run into trouble simply trying to get a coach
for the Wizards. The reason is not that no one wants the job,
although that probably should suffice. This time, it's that
Jordan's newest best friend, Leonard Hamilton, has this little
buyout clause in the seven-year deal he signed two months ago to
stay at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving moral obligations aside _ we wonder what top recruit
Darius Rice may be thinking _ the situation again underscores the
folly of Jordan's position. Why is he scouring the college ranks
for an unproven pro coach when (a) his team already is paying off
two dismissed coaches and (b) he has a coach ready, willing, able,
and, most important, who understands that he's going to lose 50
games a year for the next two years?
</P>
<P>
   That person is, of course, Darrell Walker. He's one of Mike's
guys. He knows the drill. He knows he's got a bad team, as does
Mike. He would do it on the cheap for a couple years and give
Jordan the time to reconstruct the roster. Then, Jordan could
either keep him or bring in a coach to deal with the new roster.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of doing the smart thing, Jordan is reaching out to
the college ranks. Why? To have his ``own'' man? He already has a
few. To put a ``new face'' on the old product? Sorry, but coaches
don't sell tickets; just ask us in Boston. To placate the players?
Why? John Wooden couldn't get the Wizards into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is in a tough situation,'' Magic Johnson said.
``Nobody in this league wants to help him because he beat them most
of the time. No one is going to say, `I'll take Juwan (Howard), or
Rod (Strickland), or Ike Austin. Nobody wanted to help us (the
Lakers), either. That's the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to see him lose. They're smiling because he
has no cap room. But he'll break through. He has to remember it's a
business. That as much as everyone loves him, it's still a
business. It's like when I walked into a guy's office. He said,
`Magic, I love you. But how are you going to make me money?' It's
the same. Everyone loves him. Once he gets his coach, he'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will be fine. But his coach will get chewed up and his
team will still stink. By then, however, he will be in a position
to rebuild and that's when he should get a new coach involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were him, I would be frustrated, too,'' Johnson said.
``But Michael will survive. He's a survivor, a champion, a winner.
It's going to take time. It's just that when we were playing, it
didn't take any time. We just went out and did it.''
</P>
<P>
   How true.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exchange rate
</P>
<P>
   Another bomb was dropped on the reeling Raptors last week and,
for a change, it didn't come from coach Butch Carter. It came from
Toronto's prize free agent, Tracy McGrady, who said it would be
``real tough'' for him to re-sign. It's no secret McGrady was a
lock to sign elsewhere _ Chicago seems to be the choice du jour _
but he never put it in such clear terms. McGrady said he wants to
continue playing with the Toronto veterans, all of whom ripped
Carter recently for one of the coach's many bumbling moves. McGrady
also moved away from Vince Carter in the great debate, isolating
his more celebrated teammate as the only pro-Butch voice of
consequence on the club. This is not good news for the Raptors. But
if McGrady wants to play with those players, he won't get to do so
in Chicago, Orlando, or, probably, anywhere else. So far, the
Raptors are still (publicly) committed to Butch Carter, although a
poll in the Toronto Sun had 83 percent urging the franchise to give
him the pink slip. Something's got to give. Unless there's a
coaching change, Charles Oakley probably will be moved, Dee Brown
is definitely gone, Antonio Davis has the opportunity to leave at
the end of next season, and Doug Christie wants to go. But they
still have Michael Stewart . . . The news on Jayson Williams is not
encouraging. His agent may have been floating a trial balloon or it
could be that Williams is, indeed, finished. According to agent Sal
DiFazio, if Williams can't play this season, the Nets would get
some cap relief (8 percent above the league's average salary, or
around $4 million) and then the final three years of Williams's
six-year, $85 million deal would come off the Jersey cap after the
2000-01 season . . . The Celtics are scheduled to get an
up-close-and-personal look at one of the more intriguing players in
the June 28 draft, 6-foot-10-inch Olumide Oyedeji. He's rocketed
into lottery contention after a standout performance at the Nike
Hoop Summit in April during Final Four weekend. The consensus is
that the Mavericks have the hots for him at No. 12, which makes
sense, given that Don Nelson and son Donnie love foreign players.
The Mavericks already have worked out Oyedeji and Donnie Nelson did
a clinic in Nigeria, the 19-year-old's native land. This past
season, Oyedeji played in Germany for the same team Mavericks
forward Dirk Nowitzki played for a couple of seasons ago. He would
be the third Nigerian to play in the NBA after Hakeem Olajuwon and
Obinna Ekezie (who played at Worcester Academy and the University
of Maryland). Oyedeji won't be the only foreigner the Celtics will
check out next week. Also scheduled for a visit is Hidayet
Turkoglou, a 6-8 swingman who played for Efes Pilsen in Turkey.
Unlike Oyedeji, who is free to sign with an NBA team, Turkoglou has
a buyout clause in his long-term deal with Efes Pilsen . . . Shot
Across The Bow Dept.: AEK Athens has notified the NBA it will not
sit by idly if Iakovos ``Jake'' Tsakalidis continues to insist he
is a free agent and can immediately join an NBA team after the
draft. The big Georgian (as in former USSR) has a long-term deal
with his Greek team and there is some dispute _ as there always
seems to be in these cases _ over his contract. AEK insists it
holds Tsakalidis's rights and last week, the team's coach, Dusan
Ivkovic, said he was upset that no one contacted him about the
possibility of Tsakalidis leaving for the NBA. ``Even Drazen
Petrovic or Vlade Divac asked for my permission before looking for
an NBA career,'' Ivkovic said. ``It seems there's someone behind
the entire affair. As far as I know, he's still under contract with
AEK and the management should do what is needed to protect the
team.'' Tsakalidis's agents were in Chicago at the predraft camp
assuring prospective drafters the contract was no big deal, which
is what you would expect them to say. One interesting twist is that
if there is a buyout clause, an NBA team that is over the cap and
drafts Tsakalidis (as would be the case for just about any team)
could pay no more than $350,000 to secure the 7-2 center's release.
Tsakalidis already has worked out for Vancouver, which holds the
second pick but may be willing to move down. Both Chicago and
Orlando hold multiple lottery picks and would be willing to move up
because it (a) would give them a better player and (b) would free
up cap room . . . Speaking of Chicago, can we believe reports that
the Bulls were not pleased with Chris Mihm? GM Jerry Krause never
says a thing about such matters, so could it be that the man they
call ``The Sleuth'' (among other things) purposely leaked it so
Chicago might be able to get Mihm at No. 4? Meanwhile, Marcus Fizer
may be one of those players who could really mess things up. The
word is he's measuring in at 6-6. He is not expected to go No. 1 or
No. 2 and, if the Clippers don't take him at No. 3, he could drop.
Chicago (Nos. 4 and 7) wouldn't need him with Elton Brand around,
although it might be hard for Tim Floyd to pass up the guy he
basically discovered and brought to Iowa State. The Hawks (No. 6)
already have Alan Henderson and Lorenzen Wright at the position. If
Orlando passes at No. 5, Fizer could drop to Houston (No. 9). But
that's a reach. And, in addition, in the words of one scout at
Chicago, ``He's the only guy in the draft who can draw a
double-team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A floor plan
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, more than 40 bids had been entered for the 21
items of the famed parquet floor that are being auctioned online.
The top bid so far: $101,000 for the center-court piece, complete
with the leprechaun. The next-highest bid was $30,000 for a piece
that had autographs of retired players. That item had drawn the
most interest: eight bids. Someone is willing to pay $15,000 for
the panel on which John Havlicek stole the ball in 1965, but only
one bid of $5,000 has been offered for the panel on which Gerald
Henderson stole the ball in the 1984 Finals. Seven items had not
drawn any bids . . . There also are 95 items available via online
bidding from the estate of Wilt Chamberlain. The biggest seller so
far are the sneakers Chamberlain wore the night he scored 100
points. (We are presuming these are the real deal, unlike the
basketball from that game.) Someone has bid $40,000 for the
sneakers. Someone also bid $75 for Wilt's ice skates and $151 for
his lunchbox and thermos, $150 for Wilt's bowling ball, bowling
bag, bowling shoes, and bowling trophies, and a $400 bid for his
1964 passport. Bidding runs through Tuesday . . . If you've paid
attention, you may have noticed longtime referee Jess Kersey was
nowhere to be seen in the last few rounds of the playoffs. He
missed several weeks of the season because of an ailment. The
league felt it was unfair to give Kersey the plum playoff
assignments because he missed so much of the regular season . . .
The Hawks are still looking for that so-called ``veteran
assistant'' to help guide new coach Lon Kruger through his first
NBA season. They already hired Eric Musselman and Rick Mahorn, but
they need a guy who has been around the loop once or twice. The
names being mentioned include Don Chaney, Mike D'Antoni, and Jim
Lynam. Also, among those expected to interview with New Jersey is
former Grizzlies head coach Lionel Hollins. Meanwhile, the Clippers
brought in John Lucas for an interview, and he seems like a good
fit . . . The NBA Coaches Association may have its top two
executives out of work next season. President Lenny Wilkens (fired
by the Hawks) was kept on and Don Casey (let go by the Nets) is in
as the vice president from the East. (Bill Bertka is the veep from
the West.) The group has decided to add four members to its
executive committee, one per division, and three already have been
decided: Dave Wohl (Atlantic), Brian Winters (Pacific), and Phil
Johnson (Midwest) . . . Dikembe Mutombo will be honored Tuesday at
the White House for his work in his native country, the former
Zaire. Mutombo has given $3 million to help build a hospital in
Kinshasa and also is leading a fund-raising effort to raise another
$12 million to finish the project. He is involved in the country's
efforts to vaccinate the approximately 10 million children under
the age of 5 . . . And, finally, this miracles-never-cease item:
NBA.com asked readers to select the most dominant player in the
first game of the NBA Finals. You know, the one the Lakers won,
104-87, propelled by a 43-point, 19-rebound effort by Shaquille
O'Neal. More than 30,000 votes were registered and Shaq got
``only'' 89.8 percent. The rest were split among Austin Croshere,
Rick Fox, Ron Harper, and Mark Jackson. Fred Hickman denies doing
the voting.
</P>
