<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-EXPANSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, THAT'S ANOTHER COLD DRAFT YOU FEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The NHL expansion draft _ hopefully the final one of
the millennium _ will be held June 23 in Calgary. By late
afternoon, the Columbus Blue Jackets and Minnesota Wild officially
will be members of the Original 30.
</P>
<P>
   NHL clubs turn inside-out in preparation for this event, perhaps
best known as Castaway Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why do they worry?
</P>
<P>
   The going rate in the last phases of expansion has been $75
million-$80 million, a steep initiation fee for the right to pick
over a bunch of goalies, defensemen, and forwards who, for the most
part, are destined to remain as anonymous with their new clubs as
they were with their old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the players who remain with their clubs from the last
two expansion drafts:
</P>
<P>
   Nashville (June '98): Gs Mike Dunham and Tomas Vokoun, and Fs
Greg Johnson and Scott Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (June '99): G Norm Maracle, Ds Petr Buzek, David
Harlock, Maxim Galanov, Steve Staios, and Yannick Tremblay, and Fs
Johan Garpenlov, Matt Johnson, and Mike Stapleton.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news is that NHL commissioner Gary Bettman sounded
sincere last week when he dismissed thoughts of Houston as an
expansion franchise. Adding teams, said Bettman, ``isn't on our
radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   And if history holds, the names chosen June 23 quickly will
disappear from the screen, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anonymous GM
</P>
<P>
   The Flames surprised everybody last week by hiring 37-year-old
Craig Button as general manager. Button has front office
experience, formerly with the Dallas Stars, but the leading
candidates were Mike Murphy, Jim Nill, and Les Jackson. No one
knows whether the Flames will still be in Calgary when the puck
drops in October. The franchise could be sold, likely to Paul Allen
in Portland, Ore., if the season-ticket level (currently a little
more than 11,000) don't reach 14,000 in the next 19 days. Button
probably came at a cheaper price than Mssrs. Murphy, Nill, or
Jackson, which would make it easier for a new owner to place his
own guy in the GM's job . . . Ray Bourque's agent, Steve Freyer,
says he has had only brief conversations with Colorado GM Pierre
Lacroix about Bourque's future with the Avalanche. Bourque becomes
an unrestricted free agent July 1 and said repeatedly during the
playoffs that he: 1. would play again and 2. would like it to be in
Denver. The bet here: Look for Lacroix to wheel defenseman Sandis
Ozolinsh and re-sign Bourque to a one- or two-year deal. Ozolinsh
disappeared during the Western Conference finals (with Joe Sakic in
the sidecar) and the Avalanche won't want him back at $4
million-plus. The Avalanche have a better shot at signing Bourque
now, before Detroit, Philadelphia, and New Jersey boost the bidding
when the free agent gate opens . . . Still no word from Montreal
about the future of GM Rejean Houle. One possible scenario, if
Houle gets the gate: Guy Carbonneau (still with the Stars) will
assume the job, with the Habs adding a front office lawyer or two
to work the contracts . . . It gets nastier by the hour in Philly.
GM Bob Clarke said he would welcome back Eric Lindros, but not
unless L'Enfant Terrible dropped his two backstage wingers, agents
Carl (dad) and Bonnie (mom). Now with six concussions in 27 months,
the 27-year-old Lindros is suggesting he might take a year off to
get his head together. Meanwhile, Lindros becomes a free agent if
the Flyers don't make him an $8 million-plus qualifying offer . . .
Ex-Bruin Phil Esposito, working the Cup finals for Fox, still wears
his 1970 Cup ring every day and keeps the '72 version at home. Phil
gave the '70 ring to his father, Pat, soon after the Bruins won in
'72. ``Then, about 10 days before he passed away (in 1984), he said
to me, `Look, Phil, I want you to have the ring back . . . when I
die, I don't want to be in the casket with your ring,' '' Esposito
said. ``And I said, `Ah, c'mon . . . I don't want to talk about
that.' But he was adamant. He said, `Listen, take the ring, but
I'll keep the All-Star watch, because you've got plenty of those.'
'' Just as Phil said his farewell, he slipped the ring from his
father's finger and closed the casket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another aide for Gretzky?
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, his ownership role (managing partner in charge of
hockey operations) still ambiguous in Phoenix, has not dismissed
the chance of longtime pal Mike Barnett joining the Coyotes
operation. Barnett, head of IMG's hockey division, would have to
leave his current job _ just as Lacroix relinquished his job to
become the Nordiques/Avalanche GM. ``He has been my right arm for
20 years,'' said the Great One. ``I hope he will be my left arm for
20 years.'' Gretzky also said he had frequent conversations with
former Bruin Rick Tocchet, who is very familiar with the Phoenix
roster, before deciding to invest in the Desert Dogs . . . Look for
Glen Sather, now running the show on Broadway, to swing a deal that
would bring Doug Weight back to the Rangers. Slats stole Weight in
'93 in a swap for Esa Tikkanen. Weight will make a minimum $4.2
million in 2000-01. Sather's biggest obstacle will be finding ways
to clear the financial clutter tied up in the likes of Theo Fleury,
Stephane Quintal, Valeri Kamensky, and Sylvain Lefebvre . . . Once
again, if you're making your list and counting it twice, clubs have
two options in the expansion draft. No. 1: protect two goalies,
three defensemen, and seven forwards, or No. 2: protect one goalie,
five forwards, and nine defensemen. The Bruins, at the moment, will
go with the 2-3-7 formula, protecting Byron Dafoe and John Grahame
in net . . . Word around Nashville is the Predators could have a
keen interest in BU netminder Rick DiPietro, if he slips to No. 6.
That could make things interesting for the Bruins, who own the
seventh pick. If DiPietro is still there when Nashville picks, look
for the Bruins to make Nashville GM David Poile an offer that would
include the No. 7, at least one roster player, and perhaps another
pick or two . . . Perhaps the biggest surprise of unsigned 1998
draft picks was junior netminder Mathieu Chouinard, whom the
Senators selected No. 15 overall. Chouinard goes back into the pool
as a 20-year-old and, following two mediocre years in the juniors,
he may fall to the second round. The Senators were offering
guaranteed money of around $1.5 million on a three-year deal but
Chouinard was looking for about twice that . . . The Islanders did
not send a representative to the draft lottery. When the Islanders
were announced the winners, Atlanta GM Don Waddell, whose team had
the best odds to win, immediately said, ``Winner must be present!''
The last time the Islanders had the No. 1 pick was '73, when GM
Bill Torrey resisted offers from Montreal GM Sam Pollock and picked
Denis Potvin. To this day, Torrey won't reveal Pollock's bait.
``Boy did Sam try,'' said Torrey, recalling the draft that year in
Montreal. ``We took two slow walks around the Queen Elizabeth
Hotel, and Sam kept trying, but I wouldn't budge.'' Other notable
first-rounders in 1973: No. 5 John Davidson (St. Louis), No. 8 Bob
Gainey (Montreal), and No. 14 Rick Middleton (Rangers) . . . TV
isn't everything (didn't they say that about money in the 20th
century?), but the 2.8 average rating the NHL pulled down on ABC
for Games 3 and 4 of the Cup finals is, at best, extremely
underwhelming. Bettman kept a stiff upper lip, saying he's sure
ratings will increase over the years. Perhaps. But not until there
is a monumental cultural shift among owners and players, aimed at
the athletes being more accessible to the media during the game's
showcase event, and throughout the season. If the league and the
players don't agree to do their best to market the sport and
continue to equate media coverage with root canals, even these low
ratings will atrophy and the major news outlets _ print and
electronic _ ultimately will ignore the sport. There are just too
many other sports that thirst for the opportunity that many in the
league, players included, now view with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olympian effort
</P>
<P>
   Ex-NHL coach Harry Neale, now a CBC-TV analyst, would like to
see the 2002 Olympic hockey teams select their squads in the summer
of 2001 and bring them together for mini-training camps in
September. ``It would give the coaches a few days to get a feel for
their rosters,'' said Neale. ``And it would add some real hype
through the season and into the Olympics in 2002.'' Neale envisions
the US squad training at Lake Placid, N.Y., the Canadians in
Calgary, and the European squads in their respective countries . .
. The Oilers are likely to dump Roman Hamrlik and/or ex-BC Eagle
Bill Guerin over the summer _ perhaps as early as the draft two
weeks from now. Both are making big money ($2 million-plus) in the
Edmonton scheme of things. Guerin, who turns 30 in November, was
the fifth pick in the 1989 draft and could be worth a late
first-rounder. Guerin will be an unrestricted free agent July 1,
2002 . . . Scotty Bowman is expected to tell the Red Wings this
week whether he'll return. He said he'd be in Calgary for the
draft, a sure sign he'll be back for at least one more season . . .
Ex-Bruin Trent McCleary, who nearly died when struck in the throat
by a slap shot last season, has regained full strength and is
expected back with Montreal next season . . . Just wondering, but
what does it tell us when the Bruins' AHL affiliate in Providence
wins the Calder Cup in '99 and Boston misses the 2000 playoffs, and
the Rangers, without a playoff berth since '97, watch their
Hartford WolfPack win the Calder Cup this spring? The AHL club is
supposed to develop players for the NHL, but somehow the paradigm
got turned inside-out . . . Tampa Bay GM Rick Dudley, with 15 picks
in nine rounds, will be the busiest shopper at the draft.
Admittedly, five of those picks are in the seventh round, but
Dudley has the chance to land blue-chippers with the fifth and
eighth picks _ or deal for an impact player . . . Devils center
Bobby Holik, raised in the Czech Republic, reminded teammates to
give it their best in the finals because his father, Jaroslav, was
back home in Prague, providing color commentary for the
Devils-Stars series. The senior Holik recently coached the Czech
Republic squad in the World Junior tournament. ``He just does the
TV thing for fun,'' said Holik, the games starting at 3 a.m., Czech
time. ``He doesn't want to do anything full-time anymore, except
maybe play with his grandchildren and watch some hockey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
