<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-FSU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HOLDS OFF FLORIDA STATE AT CWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ USC shortstop Seth Davidson jumped in the air and
took a stab at the line drive. Unsure he caught it, he carefully
turned his glove upside down before checking so the ball could not
fall out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it burned a hole in my glove,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ball stayed in his mitt, however, and Davidson easily picked
a disbelieving Florida State runner off second for a game-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been a little divine intervention,'' relief
pitcher Ronald Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's just typical of the way things are going for the
streaking Trojans, who defeated Florida State 6-4 in front of
19,516 at Rosenblatt Stadium on Saturday in the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   USC has won 16 straight games, with its last loss April 28. More
importantly, the Trojans won a College World Series opener for the
first time since 1978. In USC coach Mike Gillespie's two other CWS
appearances (1995, '98), the Trojans lost their opener and had to
play out of the losers' bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Without Davidson, they might have lost another opener. The
Trojans were nursing a two-run lead with one out in the ninth
inning, and the fifth-ranked Seminoles had runners at first and
second.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's Blair McCaleb then ripped a Flores pitch toward
left field before Davidson snatched the ball out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `How are we going to get out of this game with
a 6-5 lead, runners at first and third, and only one out?''' Flores
said, after watching the ball leave McCaleb's bat.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Florida State coach Mike Martin assumed the ball
would head toward the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was over the shortstop's head,'' Martin said.
``He had a little yeast. He went up there and got that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning, fourth-ranked USC (44-18) did not waste an
impressive performance by starting pitcher Rik Currier, who allowed
four runs and six hits in 72/3 innings and improved his record to
15-3.
</P>
<P>
   Currier kept the Seminoles off the bases, with their first three
hitters going 1 for 12. And he escaped a major meltdown in the
second inning, with the bases loaded and no outs. After getting
Brett Groves to pop up, Currier walked Michael Futrell to score a
run.
</P>
<P>
   But he then struck out McCaleb and Chris Smith to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't give us anything in that situation,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a demonstration of USC's ability to keep cool under
adversity in the postseason. Florida State (51-18) led 2-0 after
three innings, the fourth team in the playoffs to open a two-run
advantage on the Trojans. USC has won all of those games.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans erased the deficit by scoring three runs in the
fourth inning and two in the fifth, as Anthony Lunetta and Beau
Craig homered and Abel Montanez, Davidson and Alberto Concepcion
added run-scoring singles for a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson picked up his second RBI with a sacrifice fly in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Currier's one nemesis was first baseman Ryan Barthelemy, who
went 4 for 4 with two home runs and three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans play Louisiana State at noon PDT Monday in a
winners' bracket game.
</P>
<P>
   USC might be the hottest team in college baseball at the moment,
but the Trojans claim they are unaffected by their winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing because everyone asks about the streak and I can
see why, but we don't think about it,'' Davidson said. ``We're not
the Lakers. We're not gods. We have to scrape for everything. We're
a feisty team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 2220EDT &QL; 
