<HEADLINE>
LUNETTA HAD JUST WHAT DOCTOR ORDERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Doctors told USC second baseman Anthony Lunetta
that he had strep throat, but the freshman looked like the
healthiest Trojan on the field during Saturday's 6-4 victory over
Florida State at Rosenblatt Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And despite playing in his first College World Series, he didn't
have a trace of nerves either.
</P>
<P>
   Lunetta singled in his first at-bat, homered in his second and
sharply lined out to shortstop. He scored two runs, drove in
another and cleanly fielded eight grounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't nervous. I don't know why. I think I should
have been,'' Lunetta said. ``Maybe the sickness had something to do
with it. I felt like I was feeling better, but I didn't know what
to expect. I guess it turned out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his offensive prowess, Lunetta was also part of the
prettiest defensive play of the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, he fielded a ground ball that forced his
momentum toward second base, and calmly tossed it over to shortstop
Seth Davidson, who spun and threw Florida State's Blair McCaleb out
at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the ball and heard (Davidson) say `Flip, flip, flip' and
we got him out,'' Lunetta said.
</P>
<P>
   The play is actually encouraged by USC coach Mike Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice that every day. We talk about that all the time,''
Davidson said. ``I think coach has been waiting for a long time for
that to happen. He actually gets mad and says `Hey, why don't you
guys flip it?' We can't believe that it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIAR FOE: Florida State coach Mike Martin had one question
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many Flores do they have at USC?''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Flores picked up his fifth save of the season in
Saturday's victory over the Seminoles, and his brother Randy, USC's
all-time wins leader, was on the Trojan team that defeated Florida
State in the 1995 College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Flores is currently pitching in Norwich, Conn., with the
Yankees' Double-A team, and he watched Saturday's victory on TV
before starting that evening's contest for his own club.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother left a message for me,'' Ronald Flores said. ``He
was jazzed.''
</P>
<P>
   STAT OF THE DAY: One troubling sign for the Trojans, despite the
victory, was going 3 for 16 with runners in scoring position. USC
stranded 14 baserunners, which tied a season high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated,'' Gillespie said. ``I think we all were with
the number of opportunities we had.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
