<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT WILL MAKE THE CALL ABOUT ANKLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The electrodes and trainer's tape attached to
Kobe Bryant's left ankle said more than anyone else could Saturday:
The Lakers' All-Star guard was in no condition to play, and might
not be this evening in Game 3 of the NBA Finals against the Indiana
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers have an opportunity to push their series lead to
a commanding 3-0 with a win at Conseco Fieldhouse, and they will do
whatever necessary. Even play Bryant with a sprained ankle, so long
as the pain is negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't give any games away in this business,'' said coach
Phil Jackson, ``and you're certainly not going to pull any punches
just to have him there. If he can play, he'll play regardless. If
he's not at least 90 percent of his capabilities, or 85 percent is
a realistic number, then he won't be capable of putting up with
what he has to do to be a competitor in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's got to make the decision,'' Jackson said. ``He hasn't
got anything wrong with his foot except for swelling and pain or
whatever, so he ultimately can make the decision, but the doctor
will have a big influence on what we say or how we go about doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was still on crutches Saturday, less than 24 hours after
suffering the injury in the first quarter of Game 2. But he said
he's noticed improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as bad as we thought it would be,'' Bryant said.
``I'm able to put pressure on it. Yesterday I couldn't put any
pressure on it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bryant takes today off, he'll have four full days of rest
before Game 4 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bryant said ``there's no need to rush'' back, he knows
his scoring, defense and playmaking are irreplaceable assets. And
he's not worried about risking further injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could rest my foot in the summertime,'' he said. ``I mean,
you have to be smart. As I said, the doctors are going to know
best. They're going to be able to judge my foot better than I can,
because I'll probably just react off of sheer emotion and sheer
competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if left up to him, ``I'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   ON DECK: Brian Shaw started the second half Friday, but Jackson
said he's still weighing whether to start Shaw or Derek Fisher if
needed today.
</P>
<P>
   Bet on Shaw. At 6-foot-6, Shaw gives the Lakers the tall
backcourt Jackson prefers, and leaves the 6-1 Fisher available to
come in when the Pacers bring 5-11 Travis Best off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   EASYGOING: The Lakers have had series leads of 2-0 and 3-0 in
these playoffs, only to run into trouble. But even with three road
games ahead _ in a building where the Pacers went 36-5 this season
_ they are feeling cautiously confident.
</P>
<P>
   One win this week sends them back to L.A. for two chances to
close out the series. Two wins here, and they are champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can definitely get one win out of three,''
Fisher said, ``but we aren't really looking past (today). I think
we're really going to come out and play (this) game as if it was a
Game 7 really. I mean, we really feel like (this) game kind of sets
the tone for the rest of the series. I mean, if they win basically
you can say it's a new series. It's 2-1 and then they have two more
games here. But if we win, it's a totally different thing. So we're
putting a lot of focus on (today's game).'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
