<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-10 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTED HOOSIER MAKES GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Lakers forward Rick Fox tells a story that blows
``Hoosiers'' out of the cornfields.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with a kindly coach from a small Christian college in
north central Indiana who travels to the Bahamas one summer and
strikes oil. He discovers a boy with raw basketball skills just
waiting to be refined.
</P>
<P>
   The man returns to the States but can't shake the image of the
tall, talented player he left behind. At length, he arranges it so
the boy can come to America's heartland _ and basketball's ground
zero _ for his final three years of high school. He places the boy
with a family that worships the triangle offense as run by the
Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The grounded boy and the God-fearing family hit it off
immediately. The boy feels right at home, even if the frigid
winters and flaxen fields take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   He blossoms as a basketball player, grows as a person and goes
on to grace one of the most glamorous college basketball programs,
marry one of the most glamorous women on the planet and play for
the most glamorous team in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Fox never tires of telling the story because, well, it is his
own.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fanciful, full circle Fox has circumnavigated, from a
star turn at Warsaw (Ind.) Community High to an NBA Finals
appearance today in his adopted home state in Game 3 of the
best-of-seven championship series between the Lakers and the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole experience (of attending high school in
Indiana) was quite miraculous when you look back on it,'' Fox says
Saturday after a short shootaround at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid comes from the sand and surf of the Bahamas to the snow
drifts and cornfields of Indiana, gets an opportunity to play
organized basketball for the first time and winds up back in
Indiana years later playing for an NBA championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Fox, who majored in Radio, Televison and Motion
Pictures at the University of North Carolina, shakes his head. He
was schooled to appreciate how hard it would be to sell the
screenplay he just described. He agrees it is way too sappy.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, sometimes the truth is sweeter than fiction.
Ironically, despite Fox's Hollywood connections, it was a high
school teammate of his who appeared in the movie ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way I can explain Rick coming into our lives is that
it is a miracle from God,'' Eugene Gossman said. He is speaking
from Warsaw, Ind., on the day before he is due to make the
two-and-a-half-hour drive here with his wife and son to watch Fox
and the rest of the Lakers try to back the Pacers into a 3-0
corner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when Fox dropped into the Gossmans' home as if sent
second-day air from Above, Gossman was teaching math at Warsaw
Community High. He and his wife had recently seen their daughter
married. Their youngest child, Doug, was starting his freshman year
at his father's alma mater, Grace College.
</P>
<P>
   The Gossmans had an extra bedroom and a vacancy in their lives.
To that point, they had led rather insular lives revolving around
their religion. But their hearts were open when the Grace College
coach approached Gossman about billeting this basketball player
from the Bahamas who needed this outlet pass to get a jump on his
oh-so-promising future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never met the young man, we didn't know anything about his
family,'' Gossman says. ``You have to know our family. We're not
socialites. We keep to ourselves. But we prayed about it and felt
like we should give this young man a chance. And then Rick came
into our home, and it was like he was one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox came for a one-week feeling-out period and stayed three
years. The Gossmans were grand surrogates for his parents, Ulrick
and Dianne. They attended all his basketball games (Fox played one
game for the junior varsity team as a sophomore before he was
promoted to the varsity, where he stayed and eventually starred).
They sat with him in their living room and entertained college
coaches who came courting him in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to commit, the Gossmans sat down with Fox, who
then got both his parents on the telephone, and together the five
of them whittled his choices down to Dean Smith's Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   The Gossmans were at the RCA Dome in 1991 when Fox's collegiate
career ended with a disappointing loss to Kansas in an NCAA
Tournament semifinal. Fox, the Tar Heel who had come so far, was
despondent. He had tried too hard and ended up doing too little.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, Fox says, he has been plotting his vindication.
It took nine years, but his V-day finally arrived last week, when
the Lakers wrested the Western Conference crown from Portland, and
with it, the right to beat up (so far) Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself at least once a week that when I got another
opportunity to play for a championship, I was going to be prepared,
calm and confident,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games, the 6-foot-7 forward (and husband of
former Miss America Vanessa Williams) has been as good as his word,
averaging 8.5 points and 19.5 minutes off the bench. Gossman, for
one, couldn't be prouder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a little deja vu in Rick (in these NBA Finals),''
Gossman said. ``I can see Rick has learned to keep his emotions in
control and not overplay.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it'll be hard to keep emotions in check. Fox and the
Gossmans, after all, have traveled far together. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
