r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-T     06-10 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PUT MONEY ON OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In his quest to reach another Super Bowl, Dallas
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones is hopeful that offense can replace the
``entertainment value'' gone with Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had to take both the present and the future into
account, and we just couldn't take the risk at this stage of
Deion's career,'' said Jones, explaining the logic beyond releasing
a perennial Pro Bowl cornerback. Sanders signed with the NFC East
rival Washington Redskins three days after his June 2 release.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big franchise decision when you're talking about
those kind of dollars,'' Jones said. ``We just couldn't make that
decision. What it would've taken to sign Deion, we put into our
receivers instead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have arguably the NFL's fastest wide-receiver tandem
in Joey Galloway and Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, acquiring Galloway
from Seattle for two first-round picks and signed him to a
seven-year, $42 million deal with a $12.5 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway's contract with the Cowboys is $14 million less than
Sanders' seven-year, $56 million contract with the Redskins,
although both deals are heavily backloaded, which means both more
than likely will be redone for salary-cap purposes after two or
three seasons. Galloway's signing bonus was $12.5 million, Sanders'
$8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jones understands the entertainment side of the NFL as well as
any owner in professional sports. He admits he will miss that part
of Prime Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion adds an entertainment value that only someone who can
play at that level can add,'' Jones said. ``He's exciting,
entertaining, controversial ... and sometimes controversial isn't
all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had a top Hollywood executive once tell him that Sanders
possessed star power that easily could transfer to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion Sanders can look into the camera and speak to you
without saying a word,'' Jones said he was told.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Jones likes entertainment value, he values
winning more. The Cowboys ranked 17th in the NFL in touchdown
passes (20) last season, finishing 8-8 and making a first-round
exit from the playoffs for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a .500 team the last three years with Deion,''
Jones said. ``Principally because of his (toe and leg) injuries,
teams went after him the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question mark for the Cowboys remains at cornerback.
Kevin Smith is coming off an injury-plagued season, and Ryan McNeil
is a 29-year-old free agent being asked to learn a new system. The
Cowboys also spent three of their top four draft picks on
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go with the idea that Deion wouldn't be back,''
coach Dave Campo said. ``But I feel very comfortable with the
players we've got there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we'll still be sound in the secondary,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   As for entertainment value, Jones now must turn to Galloway and
Ismail streaking downfield to haul in passes from Troy Aikman or
his new backup, Randall Cunningham. Pass-catching tight end Jackie
Harris also has been added to an offense that will utilize Emmitt
Smith more in the passing game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFC East is definitely a defensive division,'' new
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was time for the Cowboys to put the ``entertainment
value'' back on the offensive side of the ball.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
