r s BC-BKN-MAGIC-BIRD-TEX     06-10 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-BIRD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, MAGIC AND BIRD ON OPPOSITE SIDES IN FINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It remains their stage, though they are no longer
the leading actors.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years after they last met in the NBA Finals, Larry Bird
and Magic Johnson are together on stage again as opponents. Bird
coaches the Pacers, who trail Magic's Lakers in the best-of-seven
NBA Finals, 2-0. Game 3 is at 6:30 p.m. Sunday at Conseco
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But just because they are not playing on the court doesn't mean
Johnson and Bird are any less intense about this series than
Shaquille O'Neal or Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, I wish we could go at it again like we did in the old
days,'' said Johnson, a Lakers co-owner and vice president. ``Those
were the good old days when the Lakers and Celtics used to battle
it out like cats and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was basketball at its best during a time when the NBA was
struggling. But I think I brought out the best in Bird and he
brought out the best in me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Magic appears excited about the matchup, Bird avoids
revisiting the Bird-Magic rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy now for Magic to do all the talking,'' Bird said.
``He doesn't have to coach the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic might not be coaching the Lakers, but it was Magic who
convinced guard Kobe Bryant not to return for the second half of
Friday night's Game 2 of the NBA Finals after Bryant suffered a
sprained left ankle in the first period. Magic sits near the
Lakers' bench, and often keeps close tabs on the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they're going to be talked about a lot in their
matchups,'' Pacers forward Derrick McKey said. ``We just hope we
can have that type of battle out on the court that they had back in
their day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put on a good show for the people _ as they did.''
</P>
<P>
   They put on such a good show. In fact, a case can be made that
they saved the NBA. The two players entered the league in 1979,
after Johnson's Michigan State team beat Bird's Indiana State team
in the NCAA championship game. The NBA was awash with problems,
from drug use among players to diminished fan interest. The NBA
Finals weren't even televised live; they were broadcast on a
tape-delay basis.
</P>
<P>
   But Magic and Bird transformed the NBA with their ability and
enthusiasm, Magic with the Los Angeles Lakers and Bird with the
Boston Celtics. In a short time, their rivalry defined the surging
NBA, which has become an billion-dollar operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two of the guys responsible for the heights that the
league is at this point,'' Indiana Pacers president Donnie Walsh
said. ``That was one of the great rivalries of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though it was the Lakers and Celtics, it focused on
Bird and Magic, because they were the ones who brought that to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex English, who played briefly for the Mavericks in the early
1990s, said it's difficult to discuss this series without
mentioning Magic-Bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great thing that they're both back here in the
Finals,'' said English, who works for NBATV.com. ``These guys set
lot of records. They've set the pace for this group that's here
now, and they gave them the goals that they've set for themselves
to reach for.''
</P>
<P>
   English said when Bird and Magic broke into the NBA, no one knew
how significant that would become, and how indelible their mark
would be on this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great individuals,'' English said. ``But what made
them so great was they were great team players. They knew the game
and saw the floor so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you really didn't know how good they were going to be
until after you played them and you see how they meshed.''
</P>
<P>
   They dominated the 1980s, winning eight championships _ Magic
and the Lakers in '80, '82, '85, '87 and '88; Bird and the Celtics
in '81, '84 and '86. The Lakers beat the Celtics in two of their
three championship meetings, including the 1987 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Although Magic has more NBA titles than Bird, Bird is the first
person to coach in the NBA Finals while enshrined in the Basketball
Hall of Fame. He also has been the more successful coach, leading
the Pacers to their first NBA Finals. The Lakers went 5-11 at the
end of the 1993-94 season with Johnson as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Both were fiery competitors, but Walsh said Bird has been
unfairly perceived as a subpar bench coach because he doesn't rant
and rave on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he recognizes he's dealing with men, and he doesn't
have to scream and yell,'' Walsh said. ``He knows they're supposed
to do their job, and they know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a great player's coach, and I think more NBA
coaches will coach like Larry Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bird is right, Magic does have it easier these days, and not
just because of his team's 2-0 series lead. Bird, the coach, is
concerned with stopping Shaquille O'Neal, who has scored 43 and 40
points in the first two Finals games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about (TV) ratings,'' Bird said. ``I'm trying to
win a ballgame right now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
