<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-RAIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN WON'T GO AWAY, SO RACE IS POSTPONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rain ruled again at Texas Motor Speedway on
Saturday, forcing postponement of the Indy Racing League's Casino
Magic 500 from Saturday night to noon Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Intermittent showers played havoc with Saturday's race-day
schedule, washing out a final half-hour practice scheduled for 3:45
p.m., and ultimately prompting IRL officials to postpone a race
originally scheduled for 7 p.m. and move it to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made at 6:10 p.m., shortly after a
``window'' of dry weather opened and TMS crews began the task of
drying the 1.5-mile quadoval. Brian Barnhart, the IRL's director of
racing operations, delivered the decision to the drivers and crews
during a meeting in the track's Victory Theater but also advised
the teams to stick around. Looking to dry the track by a reasonable
hour, IRL officials were hoping to run a 30-minute final practice
Saturday night under full-tank conditions. But that idea was
scrapped at 9 p.m., when attempts to fully dry the surface proved
futile.
</P>
<P>
   The final practice has been rescheduled for 9 a.m. Sunday. Live
telecast of the race has been switched from ESPN to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said the decision to postpone the race was made in the
best interests of all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much drying that's going to be necessary on the racetrack,
I don't want to start the thing at 10:45 or 11 o'clock,'' Barnhart
said. ``The concentration level the guys need, I'm not going to
race from 11 p.m. to 1 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   This became only the second event in the IRL's five-year history
to be postponed at least one day by rain. The first was the 1997
Indianapolis 500, which was rained out on its original May 25 date,
started May 26 but halted by rain after 15 laps, and completed May
27. No one in the TMS garage area, or any of the anticipated crowd
of 70,000, wants a repeat of that marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we'll get a window (Sunday) and get the thing in,''
said Barnhart, referring to the scheduled distance of 312 miles/208
laps. ``We'd love to go full-distance, obviously. We need
half-distance for an official race, but if we can get it in
(Sunday) we will. If not, we'll probably pick a hole in our
schedule somewhere. In August and September we have some time in
there, and we'll come back and run again.''
</P>
<P>
   The down time allowed drivers to mingle with fans in the garage
area, while crews continued to work on the open-wheel cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have much to complain about,'' said Scott
Goodyear, the winner of this event last June and driver of the No.
4 Pennzoil Panther Dallara/Aurora. ``It's nothing like 1997 at the
Indianapolis 500, where we had the cars on the grid every day.
Again, I trust the IRL and TMS officials made the right call by
delaying it. The decision was smart and fully endorsed by all the
drivers and teams. When the cars run, it doesn't matter. You just
want to get the full show in, and this gives us the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart has been revising the schedule since Thursday, when
Davey Hamilton and Jimmy Kite crashed in Turn 4 in separate
incidents during practice. Citing a possible problem with right
rear pushrods in the 2000 G Force chassis and a bump in the racing
groove of Turn 4, IRL and TMS officials canceled the second
practice to allow teams to modify suspensions overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the 27-car field had made successful qualifying
attempts Friday afternoon when the rains came, prompting officials
to scrub the session and revert to 2000 entrant points to set the
starting grid.
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray, the reigning IRL champion, said he felt it was
fair to give all the teams a chance to run on full tanks before
taking the green flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of teams that have fresh motors in, maybe some
teams that haven't run on full tanks,'' said Ray, who will start a
season's-worst 17th in the No. 1 Conseco Dallara/Aurora. ``It's
only fair to give teams that opportunity, because they're expecting
it _ to do a simple leak check, make sure the gearboxes are OK, do
any last-minute changes on the race car. Just as a matter of
safety, you should afford that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lopes, team manager of Rockwall-based TeamExtreme, noted
this weekend's scenario was a repeat of the season-opening race at
Walt Disney World Speedway in Orlando, Fla., in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no qualifying, and we didn't do full-tank runs, and
we raced,'' said Lopes, whose driver lineup is Hamilton and rookie
Airton Dare. ``But there's other issues here. These cars _ low to
the ground, heavy, with that bump (in Turn 4) _ they probably want
everybody to get a feel that they've got the right springs, the
right shocks. They want a safe race. Most of the cars have been in
qualifying trim in practice, and they haven't done full tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking as unofficial ``host team'' for the race, Lopes
issued this rejoinder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't take blame for the weather,'' Lopes said. ``They
brought this weather from Indianapolis.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
