<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PITCHER ROGERS SUCCEEDS WITH `NOTHING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Kenny Rogers felt lousy warming up in the bullpen
before Friday's game. His back was killing him, and he had nothing
on his pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman tried to convince him
he had good stuff and was ready to go, but Rogers wasn't buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Come on Bozzy. I'm not a rookie,''' Rogers said.
``I knew I had nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen catcher Ken Guthrie jokingly told Rogers he'd get long
reliever Matt Perisho warmed up right away. Rogers didn't laugh,
because he thought it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd get out of the first inning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers not only got out of the first, he cruised through the
next six. In a remarkable pitching performance in the high altitude
of Coors Field, the Rangers left-handed gave up just one run on
three hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost, 3-2, when the Rockies scored two runs in the
12th inning off reliever John Wetteland, but Rogers still was
pleased with his outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really good day,'' he said. ``I wish we'd have won
it, first and foremost, but I was really happy with what I did. I
really didn't expect that. I expected to have to struggle, because
I didn't feel great. Colorado and not feeling great is not a good
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have won it if he'd spaced the three hits a little
better. Instead, two of them came in the second inning and gave the
Rockies their only run against Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the next 14 batters after the run, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to find a way to get through each inning,'' he
said. ``I didn't have any long innings or any major mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' good day even included a sacrifice bunt in the second
and a single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single was nice, but I really didn't expect to get a
hit,'' he said. ``I was really thinking about not even swinging the
bat the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because his back was hurting so much, which was the one
damper on Rogers' day. He's been taking treatment for a stiff lower
back, but so far there's no improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, though, was able to succeed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed speeds well,'' Bosman said. ``He had a good
curveball to go along with a very effective sinker and changeup.
He's creative. Over the years he's learned how to use what he's
got, and that's so key.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
