<HEADLINE>
WHO IS JOHN E. ROBINSON SR.? 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY, MARK MORRIS AND DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (into it)
 &LR; brk:Chips and checks  &LR; tx:The next decade was even more turbulent.
His wife filed for divorce in 1980 but reconsidered after
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson took a job in Liberty at Guy's Foods, a large
manufacturer of potato chips and other snacks.
</P>
<P>
   James Caldwell, now operations manager at Guy's, remembers the
period as a chaotic time. The firm recently had been sold. In the
confusion, no one ran a background check on Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Robinson) was our director of personnel,'' Caldwell said.
``Most of those are outgoing, friendly people, and that's what he
was. Then this money went missing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 17, 1980, Robinson took a $6,000 company check and put
it in a new bank account disguised to look like a legitimate Guy's
corporate account.
</P>
<P>
   He faced felony stealing charges six months later. But the full
extent of Robinson's work at Guy's was only beginning to become
clear. ``It was the tip of the iceberg,'' Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The company soon filed a civil lawsuit alleging Robinson had
submitted false vouchers and forged checks.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson ultimately paid more than $41,000 in restitution in the
civil case and faced up to seven years on the criminal charge. He
was handed five years of probation after serving 60 days of ``shock
time'' at the Clay County jail.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't seem to learn much from the experience, area records
show.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1984, a mutual friend introduced him to a Kansas City
woman who was looking for a divorce lawyer, records show. A
transcript of a later law enforcement interview with the woman
suggests Robinson assumed the role of divorce lawyer. In addition
to her marriage license and birth certificate, Robinson also took
the title to her car and promised to finish work on her case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm divorced,'' the woman complained to
investigators. ``He keeps telling me I'm divorced, go out get
married. He said I can go and do what I wanted to do and I didn't
need a copy of divorce papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by his probation officer, Robinson denied everything,
saying he promised only to help the woman find her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Court records reflect no action on the complaint. But Robinson's
conviction in the Guy's case would dog him for years into the
future.
 &LR; brk:`An answer for everything'  &LR; tx:In mid-December 1984, Steve
Haymes, Robinson's probation officer, took a phone call from Ann
Smith at Birthright, a nonprofit group that assists young women
wishing to complete their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The call came just three months after 19-year-old Paula Godfrey
was reported missing in Overland Park, but no one had yet linked
Robinson to her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told Haymes that Robinson had been paying her visits at
the office, according to notes Haymes later compiled for the
court's consideration. Robinson allegedly told Smith he was
affiliated with the First Presbyterian Church of Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stated that the church was in the process of developing a
program to help young women who had just delivered babies,'' Haymes
wrote. ``He stated that the church wished to place these young
mothers in a duplex in Olathe and pay their expenses while the
young mother got on her feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The smooth stranger spoke of big plans _ even of a ``Trans
Tech'' school in Texas that would teach young mothers skills, cover
$800-a-month living expenses and provide baby-sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith called the Stanley church, which knew nothing of the
program. She then phoned an Olathe, Kan., bank, which rebutted the
man's claim of serving on its board of directors, according to
court records.
</P>
<P>
   A few more checks led her to the Missouri Division of Probation
and Parole and Haymes.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Robinson had created Equi-II, an umbrella outfit _
ostensibly a management consulting firm _ that he invoked in a
broad variety of ventures, both commercial and philanthropic.
</P>
<P>
   Making the rounds at several places that served struggling young
mothers, Robinson allegedly produced a fact sheet on the ``Kansas
City Outreach Program...sponsored by Equi-II.'' It came with an
application form and a list of questions such as: ``What are your
goals, what would you like to be doing 2 years from now?''
</P>
<P>
   At Truman Medical Center he claimed to represent a group of
Overland Park businesspeople wishing ``to give back to the
community for the successes they had'' in life, said Karen Gaddis,
then a social worker for the hospital's obstetrics unit.
</P>
<P>
   She said Robinson told her he was working closely with Catholic
Charities. When he spoke of social-service groups in the region,
Gaddis said, ``he knew everything he needed to now. He knew names,
he knew agencies....He had an answer for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   His approach was so convincing, many agencies failed to verify
his stories with one another, she told /{The Star/} last week.
 &LR; brk:Nice `Mr. Osborne'  &LR; tx:About Christmas 1984, Gaddis grew
suspicious when Robinson showed less enthusiasm for potential black
candidates for his program than for white candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say, `You know, I don't really care about this, but can
you tell me: Is the mother white or black?,' '' Gaddis recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy white infants, social workers knew, could be worth a
small fortune in the black-market adoption trade.
</P>
<P>
   Since a disproportionate share of maternity patients at the
publicly funded Truman are black, ``he didn't take any of ours,''
said Gaddis, who had worked at the hospital several years.
</P>
<P>
   Court records, however, suggest that Robinson did locate one
white woman who had recently delivered at Truman. She was Lisa
Stasi, 19. She was staying that Christmas at the Hope House shelter
for battered women.
</P>
<P>
   By Jan. 9, 1985, she and her 5-month-old daughter, Tiffany, were
staying in Room 131 at the Overland Park Rodeway Inn, where a man
she knew only as ``Mr. Osborne'' had checked her in. She had told
relatives that she was enlisting in a program sponsored by area
businessmen who could help her get a job and high-school
equivalency degree.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi and her daughter checked out the morning of Jan. 10, never
to be seen again.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi's sister-in-law, Kathy Klinginsmith, phoned Overland Park
police the next day to report the disappearance and that a Mr.
Robinson had paid for the room with an Equi-II company credit card.
That afternoon Klinginsmith's husband, David, tracked down
Equi-II's offices at 98th Street and Metcalf Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   An Overland Park police report stated: ``Mr. Klinginsmith
advised that while there, he spoke to an unknown gentleman who
became very upset and pushed him out of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Probation officer Haymes had spent about a month interviewing
social workers about Robinson's alleged activities _ and trying to
reach Robinson, without success _ when he decided to call the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   An agent told him, records state, that ``they were aware of John
Robinson but that they were not currently investigating him (and)
they were not aware of any baby-selling ring operating.''
</P>
<P>
   The same day _ Jan. 24, 1985 _ Robinson showed up at Haymes'
office, two weeks after Haymes had requested that he appear.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes asked him about the Kansas City Outreach Program. He came
forth with details about an apartment, No. 313, at 8110 Troost
Ave., which Robinson said he and some local businessmen had rented
to house young families in need. Robinson told Haymes ``he was
simply getting the satisfaction of being a help to the community
and (to) people less fortunate than himself,'' Haymes' notes state.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes didn't buy it. And after Stasi and her baby turned up
missing, neither did the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1985 a message from Robinson reached the Overland Park
Police Department: Stasi recently had done some baby-sitting for a
local girl. Stasi had told the girl she didn't want any contact
with her family.
</P>
<P>
   Police immediately interviewed the girl and got a very different
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The girl) has stated to all three agencies that she was told
to tell this story by Robinson as she owed him $900 and he had
taken nude pictures of her,'' Haymes wrote in a report. ``(The
girl) states she does not know, nor has she ever seen, Lisa Stasi
or her daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   As suspicions heightened, Gaddis said, the FBI even considered
placing a young undercover agent, posing as an unwed mother, in
Robinson's program. But another woman _ who ultimately would
cooperate with the FBI _ soon appeared in Robinson's orbit.  &LR; brk:A
tough customer  &LR; tx:Theresa L. Williams had come to Kansas City in
1984 and worked odd jobs at a Kmart and a self-service laundry.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Robinson at a McDonald's restaurant, she agreed to
become his mistress in May 1985 and to move into the Troost
apartment, according to her testimony in Clay County Circuit Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he could take care of me, and I wouldn't have to worry
about working, about anything,'' Williams testified.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though Robinson denied it, Williams contended he
provided her with marijuana, which would have been a violation of
his Missouri probation.
</P>
<P>
   Her stay on Troost was brief, only two months, but it was framed
by two frightening incidents.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Robinson introduced her to ``a customer Mr.
Robinson had lined up for you to...provide sex for,'' as described
by an assistant Clay County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the customer would pay $1,200. She was blindfolded
in the customer's car as they drove around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a certain man who needed brutality and who paid for
it,'' Williams testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what Mr. Robinson told you, what was to happen for
the money?'' the prosecutor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would let him do things to me,'' Williams replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of things generally?'' the prosecutor followed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brutality and other unnatural sex acts,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The next incident took her completely by surprise. Early one
morning, Williams testified, she awoke to find Robinson in her
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He woke me up and started pulling my hair,'' Williams
testified. ``I started screaming. And then he took the gun out, put
it to my head and said, ``if you don't shut up, I'll blow your
brains out.''
</P>
<P>
   She then alleged he sexually assaulted her with the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Haymes and two FBI agents soon interviewed Williams and within
hours moved her out of the Troost Avenue apartment so quickly that
they inadvertently took a TV set that belonged to the landlord.
Eventually they put her in hiding out of state.
</P>
<P>
   When Haymes moved to suspend Robinson's probation based on
Williams' story of drugs and guns, his lawyer demanded the right to
interview her before the revocation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI refused to produce her for the deposition. Clay County
Circuit Court Judge John Hutcherson, concerned by Robinson's
behavior, revoked his bond based on her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Court of Appeals reversed Hutcherson's decision,
ruling that authorities violated his constitutional right to
confront his accuser.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Williams lives out of state.  &LR; brk:Limited partners
 &LR; tx:Even as Robinson parried the federal baby-selling
investigation, he was soaking up attention for his business
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1985, just days after his probation revocation hearing
concluded, he was featured in a /{Farm Journal/} cover story,
touting Equi-II as a farm management consulting firm and advising
ranchers on the tax benefits of limited partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Robinson portrayed himself as the enthusiastic expert.
The lingo sounded just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every dollar the limited partner invests, he gets $2 to $4
in tax write-offs, along with a return of 25 percent to 50 percent
on his investment over the life of the partnership,'' Robinson told
the writers.
</P>
<P>
   The writers also quoted Sam Brownback, then a Kansas State
University agricultural law professor and currently a U.S. senator,
about the advantages of the limited partnerships in beef
operations. (Brownback said Saturday he never met or spoke to
Robinson.)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson pointed to the $2.2 million partnership set up by one
of his clients as a model for others; the program was new and had
not yet shown a long-term profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more (the client) makes for the investors, the more he
takes home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't turn out that way for at least one rancher, Bob
Lowrey of Norwich, Kan. He and his partner, Bill Mills, each lost
$10,000 in Robinson's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid him and so did my partner, and we never saw anything
come out of all the talk,'' said Lowrey said. ``I questioned it at
the time, but Billy did visit with the man....He was certain he was
an honest person.''
</P>
<P>
   In that busy summer of 1985, Robinson's luck in avoiding jail
time was about to run out.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County authorities had been investigating him for months
about his relationship with a business called Back Care Systems.
Back Care Systems hired his Equi Plus to market its program of
providing backache seminars at industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   Equi Plus agreed to prepare a marketing plan, printed materials,
a video and slide presentation and other services. But Back Care
started getting invoices for work not done.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 30, 1986, a jury found him guilty, agreeing that
Robinson had submitted false invoices totaling $3,600 to Back Care.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Obermeier, the assistant district attorney who prosecuted
the case, asked Johnson County District Judge Herbert W. Walton to
apply the Habitual Criminal Act in sentencing Robinson in light of
Robinson's previous convictions. Walton did so, ordering five to 14
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Then in July, Johnson County charged Robinson with more fraud
and theft counts. This time he was accused of pocketing $50,000
while serving as a middleman in the sale of condominium property in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had talked an Overland Park man into investing $150,000
in the project in Page, Ariz., records state. He then told the
Arizona landowner spearheading the project that the Kansas investor
had put up only $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was convicted of making a false writing. Now he faced
an overall sentence of six to 19 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Haymes, the Missouri probation officer, told /{The Star/} in
1987 that he didn't expect time behind bars to change Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never gives up,'' he said. ``He's like one of those toys
that runs into a wall and goes on.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
