<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PROFILE 3TAKES-KAN &LR;    06-10 2434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS JOHN E. ROBINSON SR. 
</HEADLINE>
 3 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By By RICK MONTGOMERY, MARK MORRIS and DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Go back to 1985 to understand how John E. Robinson
Sr. became the man he is today, a career con man turned suspected
serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   That year he and his consulting company, Equi-II, seemed to be
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A three-page spread in the August 1985 /{Farm Journal/} quoted
Robinson among other experts on the benefits of limited
partnerships for ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   Always nattily dressed, Robinson also was lining up investors
for some six-figure condominium deals. And he was telling people
about Equi-II's good Samaritan side, how it helped social-service
groups find homes for young mothers in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He made a great impression that year: well-spoken, enthusiastic,
family man, polite, with just a hint of superiority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy presented himself as if he was the president of the
Jaycees,'' said Karen Gaddis, a hospital social worker who had met
Robinson about that time.
</P>
<P>
   Equi-II, however, had another side. So did its creator.
</P>
<P>
   As 1985 clicked on, the FBI and officials in Missouri grew
concerned that the company was a front for black-market baby
selling. One young mother and her daughter had disappeared in
January after meeting with Robinson. By June, another witness
alleged that Robinson had sexually assaulted her with a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly addicted to theft, Robinson would turn out to have a
scam for everyone. To one woman he posed as a divorce lawyer; to
potential investors he boasted of having a hand in making ``First
Blood,'' the Sylvester Stallone film; to employers he struck an
earnest pose while swiping company checks, even postage stamps.
</P>
<P>
   And later, after the law had finally caught up with him and put
him behind bars for a few years, he still charmed. He worked his
cons first on the prison doctors, who recommended his early
release, and perhaps tragically on a prison librarian.
</P>
<P>
   The dangerous dimension to this pudgy con man surfaced with a
vengeance last week when barrels with the remains of five women
came out of a rural Kansas field and a Missouri storage locker.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investigators sort through Robinson's past while he sits in
the Johnson County Jail on a $5 million bond: businesses mostly on
paper, a ``Slavemaster'' presence on the Internet, and a growing
count of dead or missing persons that may have reached as many as
nine.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say they plan to file murder charges. If Robinson is
indeed a serial murderer, /{The Kansas City Star/} has found that
his profile reads unlike any other's.  &LR; hd:A kiss from Judy Garland
 &LR; tx:Of all the bizarre stories that would surround Robinson in his
56 years, perhaps the most unbelievable was that, as an Eagle
Scout, he sang for the Queen of England.
</P>
<P>
   Except that one's true.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson achieved the rank of Eagle Scout on Nov. 3, 1957. He
was 13 and senior patrol leader of Boy Scout Troop 259, which was
sponsored by the Holy Name Society of Mary Queen of Heaven Roman
Catholic Church in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like the youngest Eagle Scouts ever made,'' recalled
James Krcmarik, who made Eagle with Robinson. ``He wasn't a big
guy. He was a little guy. He was kind of quiet and nondescript.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days later, Robinson flew to London to appear in the
chorus of a popular variety Boy Scout act called ``The Gang Show.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a /{Chicago Tribune/} article, Robinson _ a
freshman at Quigley Preparatory Seminary _ was selected ``because
of his scholastic ability, scouting experience and poise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He sings, too, in Holy Name Cathedral with the Quigley
choir,'' the article said. ``He also has an engaging smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``all-around Chicago school boy'' led 120 Scouts onto the
stage of the Palladium theater for a royal command performance Nov.
18, 1957.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper article described him as the first American boy
ever to appear before Queen Elizabeth at the annual royal command
variety performance.
</P>
<P>
   He met Judy Garland backstage. When he told a reporter that ``We
Americans gotta stick together,'' the actress kissed him and said,
``You're right.''
</P>
<P>
   He told British actress Gracie Fields that when he finished at
the Quigley Preparatory Seminary in Chicago he planned to study for
the priesthood and would certainly come to Rome some time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many aspects of Robinson's life, the event marked an
incredible, strange-but-true chapter cast against a childhood that
otherwise appeared rather bland.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Dec. 27, 1943, the middle child of five in a
blue-collar Cicero, Ill., family. His father, Henry Robinson, at
one time was a machinist for Western Electric. Decades later, among
the things John Robinson would tell Kansas Department of
Corrections psychiatric evaluators was that his father was a binge
drinker and that his mother, Alberta, was the disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   Cicero, the neighborhood where Robinson grew up, is an enclave
with its own city government on the western edge of Chicago. Those
living in the surrounding well-kept, lower-middle-class homes
around 4916 W. 32nd St. did not recall the Robinson family.
</P>
<P>
   He attended the cathedrallike Quigley in the heart of downtown
Chicago, a few blocks from the city's landmark Water Tower. At the
time Robinson attended, it was a popular five-year academy for
young Catholic boys wanting a good education and interested in the
priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson entered in the fall of 1957. In the 1958 edition of Le
Petit Seminaire, the Quigley yearbook, he looks like a bubbly
13-year-old choir boy with a cherubic smile. He does not appear in
yearbooks beyond the 1958 edition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shotke, former public relations director for Chicago Boy
Scouts, said Robinson was ``a good kid...an above-average student,
but not brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't talk a great deal, but when he did talk, it was to
produce an effect that he wanted,'' Shotke said. ``He was shrewd.
He was aspiring to more than he was capable of, quite frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years later a Kansas Department of Corrections
clinical evaluation noted that he graduated with average grades,
with high marks in science but not in math.
</P>
<P>
   The report goes on to say that Robinson attended Morton Junior
College in Cicero in 1961 and trained as a medical X-ray
technician. He also said he worked at a hospital in that capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is thought to have moved to the Kansas City area about
1964, the year he married. He and Nancy Jo Robinson would raise
four children and stay together long after women with ties to John
Robinson began disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson lived his first five years in Kansas City without a
blot on his record, according to area court files. But then he
started stealing, again and again.  &LR; brk:Penny-ante professional
 &LR; tx:Right from the start of Robinson's scamming days, nobody was
too prominent to bilk.
</P>
<P>
   He began in the office of Wallace H. Graham _ Harry S. Truman's
personal physician. After a stint as office manager, Robinson was
convicted of embezzling money from Graham in August 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, then 25, was put on three years probation.
</P>
<P>
   He found a new job as a systems analyst at the Kansas City
office of Mobile Oil Corp. In September 1970, police charged
Robinson with stealing 6,200 postage stamps from the company,
valued at $372.
</P>
<P>
   He paid restitution.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, having moved back to Chicago, Robinson was
charged with embezzling $5,586 from his employer, the R.B. Jones
Co. He paid full restitution and the prosecution dismissed the
case.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to Kansas City and established Professional
Services Association Inc., a medical consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   One day he asked his secretary to prepare letters dated 1973 for
prospective clients saying that the Board of Regents of the
University of Missouri-Kansas City ``had voted (Robinson) the full
rights and privileges of professor'' at the School of Dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   Not true.
</P>
<P>
   First, UMKC didn't have a ``Board of Regents.'' Second, the
signature of the dental school's dean was forged, according to
court documents.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Missouri returned a four-count
indictment against Robinson and his Professional Services
Association in 1975 for securities fraud and mail fraud. The
damning evidence was another letter distributed to potential
investors.
</P>
<P>
   It suggested that pharmaceutical maker Marion Laboratories was
negotiating with Robinson to acquire Professional Services
Association and to purchase $364,000 worth of training manuals.
</P>
<P>
   A Marion executive, John E. Hartlein, supposedly signed the
letter. One problem: his name was misspelled ``Hartlin.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mac Cahal of Prairie Village received the letter, he
contacted his good friend Ewing M. Kauffman _ founder of Marion
Labs. ``Ewing hit the ceiling,'' Cahal recalled last week.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge fined Robinson $2,500 and placed him on three
years probation.  &LR; brk:A good impression  &LR; tx:Jack Walker of Overland
Park, Kan., a retired physician, said he hired John Robinson in the
mid-1970s to serve as a business consultant for the Family Practice
Department at the University of Kansas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Walker at the time was department chairman and mayor of Overland
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was hired by a corporation formed by the department's
doctors, Walker said, so state funds were never involved in paying
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came and presented himself to me as an expert as a
physician's professional consultant,'' a service that a lot of
doctors were beginning to use, Walker told /{The Star/}.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a very good impression: well-dressed, nice-looking,
late 20s, seemed to know a lot, very glib, good speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he brought Robinson to a staff meeting and ``our
people all liked him so we hired him.''
</P>
<P>
   After only a few months, doctors in the orthopedic surgery
department, which also had hired Robinson, advised him they were
letting Robinson go, he said, because of ``doubts about his
handling of our financial affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Walker said, Robinson told him that he needed the
corporation's checkbook. The corporation's bookkeeper objected.
After hearing other troubling reports, Walker dismissed Robinson.
 &LR; brk:Money leaks away  &LR; tx:In July 1977 he moved his family into a
new home at 15500 Arapaho in a budding Stanley subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   And he had a new venture: hydroponics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If It Grows It Grows Better Hydroponically,'' pitched
Robinson's Hydro-Gro Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A booklet he published featured water-based home-gardening
products that would allow families to grow tomatoes, cucumbers and
other vegetables ``in a minimum space, in the corner of your
home.'' One page featured a photograph of Robinson's 5-year-old
twins grinning in their ``Grow Your Own'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that as you read this book,'' said the section about
the author, Robinson, ``you will form an acquaintance with John
Robinson as a sensitive and stimulating human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people viewed him that way.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Rickard, now 47, said she first met Robinson when her
father, Brooks, agreed to invest in Hydro-Gro. Her mother, Beth,
was dying of cancer and her father, who was recently retired, was
under a lot of stress to keep up with the mounting medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Nancy Rickard was a young, aspiring artist, and
Robinson allowed her to illustrate his how-to gardening booklet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very nice to me, very encouraging,'' she said last
week. ``He coached me through it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Brooks Rickard and some of his children had invested
more than $5,000 in the Hydro-Gro venture. An aunt had invested
about $20,000, another relative said.
</P>
<P>
   They lost it all.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor remembers Robinson as more gruff than sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was condescending to other people in the neighborhood. The
guy was intense. He wasn't someone you'd joke with, '' said
Margaret Adams, whose family lived next door for eight years. The
Robinson children baby-sat the Adamses' pets.
</P>
<P>
   Adams first met Robinson in 1978 at a trade show where she
watched him demonstrate his hydroponic unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we moved out here I learned that he lived next door. So
I went over and asked him about hydroponics and that unit he was
selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was nice as can be as he was explaining it to me, but when
he told me the price _ between two and three thousand dollars _ I
said that would be too expensive for me to grow tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was furious, telling me that he had wasted his time and he
shouldn't be dealing with people who were small time.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams remembers that Robinson once took a swing at a neighbor
and was verbally abusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear him yelling at the kids and her and anyone. Our
lots are 4 acres apiece, but we're down in the valley and sound
carries.''  &LR; brk:`He'll stop at nothing'  &LR; tx:Not all of Robinson's
schemes were aimed at fattening his wallet. At least one was
designed to gratify his ego.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1977 he was honored as ``Man of the Year'' at a
luncheon sponsored by a local sheltered workshop association and
attended by then state Sen. Mary Gant.
</P>
<P>
   After the luncheon, at which Robinson received a plaque that he
had ordered, details emerged that suggested Robinson had engineered
the award for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Letters to the mayor's office asking for the proclamation
purportedly were signed by Paul Reiff, then the director of a
sheltered workshop on Truman Road in Kansas City. Two weeks after
the luncheon, Reiff told /{The Star/} he never signed such letters.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Reiff remembered the profound embarrassment he felt as
Robinson rose to accept the award. Robinson had only been on the
board of the workshop for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me he was trying to fake surprise,'' Reiff said
recently. ``I thought, this guy is bad news. If he'll use an
organization that's trying to help the disabled to his personal
advantage, he'll stop at nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the luncheon, /{The Star/} also received a six-page
typewritten press release profiling Robinson, which was purportedly
prepared by Robert G. O'Bryant, former president of a sheltered
workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Again, O'Bryant told the paper he knew nothing of the profile.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks of the deception becoming known, Robinson
resigned from the board of the sheltered workshop association.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's pattern was clear to one of his defense attorneys,
Bruce Houdek.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a small-time, penny-ante con guy,'' Houdek said. ``He
worked harder getting out of trouble than getting into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
