</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000610.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0690 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PROFILE 3RDTAKE-KAN &LR;    06-10 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS JOHN E. ROBINSON SR.? 
</HEADLINE>
 3RD TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY, MARK MORRIS AND DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (goes on.'')
 &LR; brk:`Docile, nonviolent'  &LR; tx:In 1987, Catherine Clampitt, 27,
tried to escape a life of drugs and drinking in Wichita Falls,
Texas, by moving in with her brother and sister-in-law in Overland
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Soon she told them she found work at a company called Equi-II,
which apparently was still operating while Robinson was appealing
his convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson finally lost. His Kansas prison sentence began on May
16, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The following month, Clampitt was reported missing by her
brother who had not seen her for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Robinson showed exemplary behavior in the four years
Kansas had him. In fact, when he was office coordinator for the
prison maintenance operations at the Hutchinson Correctional
Facility, Robinson developed computer programs that would help the
state save up to $100,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when he leaves,'' wrote physical plant supervisor Jim
Jestes in 1989, ``this office should function well.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressed were the medical and psychiatric professionals
who examined Robinson in late 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robinson by that time had suffered a series of strokes
that left slackness in the right side of his face, ``his verbal
skills (were measured) in the high average range, performance
skills in the very superior range.''
</P>
<P>
   The clinical team concluded:
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a docile, nonviolent individual who does not pose a
threat to society....we recommend his immediate release on
parole.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas paroled Robinson in January 1991, but he was not free.
His Johnson County troubles occurred while he was still on
probation for the Guy's Foods theft 10 years earlier. He faced more
years behind Missouri bars.
</P>
<P>
   From the Moberly Correctional Center, Robinson wrote to a Clay
County Circuit Judge in May 1991, begging for an early release:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this what is considered proportionate punishment for my
crime in Missouri? I taught my children to believe in the basic
fairness of our system of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   A Missouri prison physician, Fred L. King, examined Robinson and
considered him so sick and frail from strokes he wrote that ``this
inmate should be released without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Missouri parole board made Robinson stay another two
years. Eventually he wound up at the Western Missouri Correctional
Center in Cameron, where the prison library was staffed by a
middle-aged woman named Beverly Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   The two got to know each other, Bonner's former husband said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson remained imprisoned in Cameron until the spring of
1993. At 49 he was a free man again.
</P>
<P>
   A year later librarian Bonner would seek another kind of
freedom. She divorced and moved to Kansas City. She told friends
that she had a wonderful job lined up, one that involved foreign
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later she dropped out of sight.
 &LR; brk:New beginnings  &LR; tx:While Robinson was in Hutchinson, his wife
had sold their longtime Stanley home to Gene Clark in January 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Robinson ``was living with the twins then and was forced
to sell the house because he'd gotten them so far in debt with all
his shenanigans,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   He never did meet John Robinson, but knew of his reputation and
stories of missing women from friends on the Overland Park police
force. ``They'd been watching him for some time,'' he said. ``But
they couldn't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson got out of Missouri prison, he moved back in with
his wife, who was managing the Southfork Mobile Home Community in
Belton. They lived in a unit at 464 Valeen Lane.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1993, Robinson rented a Stor-Mor unit in Raymore. His
wife had rented two before that in November 1992, one in her name
and the other in her husband's name.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1995, Robinson and his wife bought a house on Big
Pine Key in Florida. Their oldest son moved into the house, for
which his parents paid about $95,000, according to Florida
assessment records. The Florida home would be sold in early 1999,
and the couple would then buy 16.5 acres, complete with mobile home
and pond, in rural Linn County, about an hour drive south of Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Robinson's probation ended in 1996, about the time he
and Nancy moved their trailer home to 36 Monterey Lane in Olathe.
There, Nancy began managing the Santa Barbara Estates park of 484
mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   While she spent her days at the park office, residents often saw
her husband watering flowers on the boulevard or coming and going
in his white pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Pulley, 79, said Robinson was helpful on more than one
occasion. As she worked out in the yard, she said: ``He'd stop by
and say, `Don't you think you've worked a little too long in the
heat?' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Timmons, 79, who lived next to the Robinsons on Monterey
Lane, added: ``He always seemed to be in a hurry. He never had time
for long conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Timmons said Robinson put out ``marvelous decorations'' for all
the holidays and kept his yard in immaculate shape.
</P>
<P>
   But the tidiness of the Robinson marriage was a matter of
question.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, one ``John Anthony Robinson'' applied for a
marriage license to Izabela K. Lewicka, a Polish immigrant who had
moved to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   She has not been seen since last fall, prosecutors note.
 &LR; brk:Still selling  &LR; tx:In the mid-90s, John Robinson began a free
publication about mobile homes. The trade magazine, /{Manufactured
Modular Living/} resembled another magazine published by John
Woolfolk of Prairie Village.
</P>
<P>
   It was so similar that Woolfolk sent a ``cease and desist''
letter to Robinson ``but he just ignored it,'' said Woolfolk, who
stopped publishing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he just lifted everything from my magazine,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread in the mobile-home trade that Robinson's magazine
was one to avoid. ``That man was a constant black eye to us in the
industry,'' said Tom Hagar, president of Mid-America Home Center
Inc., in Lee's Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``His articles would give suggestions to home owners that ran
against all the standards in the industry. He didn't care. When
anyone confronted him on what he was saying, he'd tell them it was
a free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet still, as always, Robinson maintained a smooth charm _ some
called it arrogance _ as he visited trailer parks and retail
centers trying to sell ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely friendly, jovial even,'' said Debbie Adriano,
from Mid-America Discount Homes in Gardner. ``He always dressed
preppy, with khaki pants, loafers and a nice golf shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   To others _ such as Robinson's neighbor, Joy Friedemann, 43 _ he
seemed like ``a dirty old man.''
</P>
<P>
   She said he repeatedly tried to lure her into having sex. He'd
drop by to flirt with the married mother and ask if her husband was
at work all day. Sometimes, Robinson would just stare at her and
say, ``Today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I said, I'm going to tell your wife,'' Friedemann
told Robinson last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She don't care,'' Robinson supposedly shot back, but the
harassment stopped.  &LR; brk:Going online  &LR; tx:Just three months ago,
Robinson introduced himself to a local Web site designer, Steve
Gwartney, and asked him to develop an online version of the
modular-homes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Gwartney produced a Web site _ www.mmhl.com _ tailored to
Robinson's precise specifications. A click of the mouse could link
browsers to various modular-home trade associations and retailers.
Another click, and ``J.R.'s Comments'' would flash on the screen,
with a line sketch of a grinning Robinson in the upper corner.
</P>
<P>
   His editorial for the May 2000 edition was headlined:
``Manufactured Homes Hold Their Value.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwartney, who said he was still owed about $1,000 for his work,
said his client appeared to have little Web expertise. He had no
idea that Robinson was also using an online identity
``Slavemaster'' to seek out women interested in engaging in
sadomasochistic sex.
</P>
<P>
   Two women he encountered in cyberspace met him in separate
Johnson County hotels this spring to act as his ``sex slaves,'' as
authorities later put it.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the women talked to authorities after their encounters.
They said Robinson had brutalized them in a way that went beyond
what they had intended.
</P>
<P>
   Their reports prompted police to file sexual assault charges
against Robinson and to launch yet another investigation.
</P>
<P>
   This time they found bodies. Two were discovered in barrels in
Linn County, Kan., and three more were found in barrels in the
storage facility the Robinsons had rented years ago in Raymore. All
appeared to have suffered blows to the head.
</P>
<P>
   No murder charges have been filed.
 &LR; brk:Geraniums and mum  &LR; tx:``He was a model neighbor,'' neighbor
Timmons said. ``We were really shocked to see all these charges
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m. on June 2, Timmons stepped outside his trailer to
take a walk and saw plainclothes detectives escorting John Robinson
out of his trailer in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nine or 10 unmarked police cars were parked around the Robinson
property. Officers stayed until 3 p.m. going through the trailer's
contents. Timmons said he saw them carry out a computer, fax
machine and cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a surreal scene there amid the potted pink geraniums that
decorated the Robinsons' patio out front, and the religious statue
in the flower bed. What on earth, Timmons wondered, could that nice
man who lived in one of the prettiest trailers in the park done to
bring out all those cops?
</P>
<P>
   When the police searching was complete _ after they hauled
Robinson's pickup away the following night _ Timmons remembered how
silent and stoic Robinson seemed, staring straight ahead, as the
authorities escorted him away.
</P>
<P>
   For once, John Robinson had nothing to say.  &LR; tag1:Staff writers
Mike McGraw, Lee Kavanaugh, Tanyanika Samuels, Scott Canon, Judy
Thomas, Tony Rizzo, Malcolm Garcia and Kate Beem contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
