<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHBURN DOES IT ALL FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Jarrod Washburn smiled on the basepaths. He smiled in
the dugout. And he was smiling in the clubhouse after his
performance both on the mound and at the plate keyed the Angels'
10-3 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks Saturday afternoon in
front of 35,213 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn (2-1) gave up one run and five hits in seven innings to
earn the win, but what had everybody talking after the game was his
performance at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn drew a two-out, bases-loaded walk in the second inning
to drive in the first run of the game. It also allowed Darin Erstad
a chance to bat in the inning, and Erstad drove in two runs with a
double.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Washburn got his first major-league hit, a
blooper that landed just inside the left-field foul line that drove
in another run. And in both the fifth and seventh innings, Washburn
laid down successful sacrifice bunts.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia called for the baseball after
Washburn's hit, and Washburn broke into an ear-to-ear grin while
standing on first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was laughing because I couldn't believe I got a hit,'' said
Washburn, whose last hit was in high school. ``I was a pretty good
hitter in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys (Angels pitchers) have worked hard the last 2{
weeks offensively,'' Scioscia said. ``You couldn't have any better
day than Washburn had. The pitchers take a lot of pride in their
hitting. The first two at-bats were huge in this ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was the Angels' second this season in a National
League ballpark, meaning there is no designated hitter and the
pitchers must bat. In Friday's game, pitcher Brian Cooper got one
at-bat and struck out. Of course, he was facing Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitcher Omar Daal (2-7) had given up a two-out
double to Matt Walbeck that gave the Angels runners at second and
third in the second inning. But Daal intentionally walked No.8
hitter Adam Kennedy to load the bases and get to Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn walked on a 3-1 pitch that could have been called a
strike. Instead, it forced home Garret Anderson with the first run
of the game. Erstad followed with his two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, the Angels had already scored twice on RBI
singles by Walbeck and Kennedy when Washburn lifted a little pop-up
behind third and down the line. It fell in and gave the Angels a
6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Benji Gil homered and Tim Salmon hit a
two-run homer for a 9-0 lead. Anderson homered in the sixth to put
the Angels up 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was up to Washburn, who threw six scoreless innings
before giving up a leadoff homer to Luis Gonzalez in the seventh.
He was replaced by Lou Pote to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best pitches he made were his fastball, locating his
fastball,'' Scioscia said. ``He never got into huge trouble, but he
was able to prevent trouble by making pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After my last start (seven runs in 5 innings vs. the Dodgers)
I needed to get my command back,'' Washburn said. ``This was the
first time I didn't have any walks. I put the ball over the plate
and made 'em put the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a typical day at the plate, getting 13 hits,
including three by Kennedy and two each by Salmon, Anderson and
Walbeck. Salmon raised his batting average to .284, which doesn't
like seem much unless one considers he was hitting only .242 as
late as May 21.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting .217 in April, Salmon hit .330 in May and is
hitting .345 in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it seems I've got to get down so low, there's nowhere
else to go,'' Salmon said. ``It seems like I get down to
ground-zero and build myself up. I refine my swing and get it
going. This is pretty typical for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also enjoyed winning a game by seven runs, when so
many have come down to the final inning or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have our share of tight games and blowouts,''
Scioscia said. ``This is a club that grinds it out. We're the type
of club that knows we can get back into any game, or put a team
away. But it's good to see us win a game by getting out in front
and playing well from start to finish.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
