<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-10 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALWAYS BEEN HIP TO BE `HICK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The New York papers headlined the Eastern
Conference finals ``Knicks vs. Hicks.'' After the Indiana Pacers
advanced to the NBA Finals to face the Lakers, a fan in Los Angeles
waved a sign reading, ``Bring on the Hicks.''
</P>
<P>
   And I guess they might be right about the Pacers and their
public. But only if their definition of ``hicks'' is broad enough
to account for the coolest arena in pro basketball, the hippest
franchise history in pro basketball, and the loyalty of a citified
Hoosier named David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in a studio-audience quiz segment, Letterman cajoled a
woman into choosing a category called ``Know Your ABA Indiana
Pacers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What was Bob Netolicky's nickname?'' was one question.
(``Netto!'' the woman was allowed to read off Letterman's cue card,
as the screen showed a mugshot of the toothy forward of the 1960s
and '70s, a high-living young man who kept a pet ocelot and lioness
and styled himself as the Joe Namath of Indianapolis.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who had the ABA's best hairdo?'' was the next question.
(``Darrell Hillman!'' the woman read, before Letterman pointed out
the name was in fact Darnell, and we saw a picture of the man with
the biggest Afro in the ABA.)
</P>
<P>
   OK, Letterman seemed to be laughing (ital) at (endital) the old
Pacers, not with them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, evoking the memory of those Pacers of the bell-bottoms
era, of a hard-drinking and brawling coach named Slick Leonard and
players who followed him to the bar and beyond, of the American
Basketball Association and its trend-setting 3-point arc, slam-dunk
contests and bikinied ball girls, served as a humbling reminder to
Californians tempted to look down our sunburned noses at the ...
hicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers don't have the corner on cool in this NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers definitely don't have the corner on history.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, with six NBA championships in Los Angeles, will
never lay down roots as deep in their home region as the Pacers,
with no NBA titles, have grown in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly needs to be said that basketball in Indiana is like
celluloid in Hollywood, the substance of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back there maybe this isn't the right term _ but it seems like
it's almost a religion,'' said Bill Sharman, the former Lakers
coach and longtime club executive. ``It seems like those people (in
Indiana) go to church and basketball games, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the basketball party that begins here with tonight's Game 3
at Conseco Fieldhouse, it's not the ``hicks'' who should feel ill
at ease, it's the L.A. types.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet you've forgotten, if you're old enough to have ever
known, that this isn't the first time the Pacers have faced Los
Angeles in a championship final. The first time was in May 1970,
when the Pacers and the Los Angeles Stars played for the ABA title.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, in the shadow of the Lakers in a city with a limited
basketball appetite, typically drew 3,000 a game to the Sports
Arena. The Pacers drew 10,000 every night.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Brown dropped 53-, 39- and 45-point games on Willie Wise,
and the Pacers won that series in six to take home the first of
their three trophies in the red-white-and-blue-ball league.
</P>
<P>
   Sharman and Leonard were the respective coaches of the Stars and
Pacers. Sharman remembers Bill Cosby showing up for one of the
games in Los Angeles, but that was it for actual star power. The
next season, the Stars moved to Utah and won the ABA title after
turning back Indiana in the finals of the reconfigured Western
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Those Pacers rosters boasted not just the free-wheeling Brown
and the flamboyant Hillman and Netolicky, but two-time ABA MVP Mel
Daniels, 3-point ace Billy Keller, Indiana favorite Rick Mount and
early George McGinnis, the Karl Malone of his day.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of them could have made it in the NBA, and McGinnis
did with the Philadelphia 76ers. Unfortunately, most were ex-Pacers
by the time the ABA folded and the team joined the establishment
league in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers endured a long down cycle in which they missed the
NBA playoffs 11 times in 13 seasons. Thus the franchise and its
fans acquired something else the Lakers are missing: grit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers had the great years (but) they've never had a
struggling franchise. They've never had to go through that,'' said
Leonard, a former Minneapolis and L.A. Lakers player who, since his
Pacers coaching days, has been a Pacers radio man. ``Now, they've
had some ballclubs that weren't that good, and I know it's been a
while since they won a championship. But they really never had to
struggle the way the Pacer franchise had to struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, and all the loyalty dating back to when
the franchise started, this (first NBA Finals appearance) gives
everybody a great deal of satisfaction. Everybody feels a part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who walks into Conseco Fieldhouse in downtown
Indianapolis feels a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The first-year arena, properly described as the first ``retro''
basketball building, the sport's Camden Yards, captures Indiana
hoops history in its exhibit cases and its ambiance.
</P>
<P>
   It is the anti-Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've seen `Hoosiers,' it's like that,'' Pacers
forward-center Sam Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ```Fieldhouse' says it all,'' Pacers guard Travis Best said.
``You're not going to get all the glitz and glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, in some circles, glitz and glamour equal cool while the
celebration of home-grown history is for hicks.
</P>
<P>
   But not here. Not this week. The hicks are hip.
</P>
<P>
   I like what Sharman had in mind when he said of the Pacers, ``If
they weren't playing us, I could root for them very easily.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
