<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD GETS HIT NO. 100
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Darin Erstad's second-inning double Saturday afternoon
was his 100th hit of the season. He did it in 61 games, the fastest
to 100 since Heinie Manush got 100 in 60 games for the Washington
Senators in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's reaction when informed of his achievement: ``So? ...
People can talk all you want about what you're doing now. But at
the end of the season is when it really counts. Every day's
important, but you have to keep it in perspective. There's a lot of
baseball left.''
</P>
<P>
   If he continues his current pace, Erstad would finish the season
with 265 hits. The major-league record for one season is 257, set
by George Sisler in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, Erstad has been sensational,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``He's been as consistent as any ballplayer I've
seen over as long a stretch as I've seen. It's not like he's on a
hot streak. It's been going on for over a third of the season. He's
been as good as you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, though, said it's not as easy as he's made it look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I battle to get myself in position to get ready to
play,'' he said. ``It's not like it's easy. You try to put a good
swing on the ball. Sometimes they fall, sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad admitted he never heard of Manush. ``I know my baseball
history, but I'm not that deep. If somebody breaks it 70 years from
now, I'm sure they'll say `Who the hell was Darin Erstad?'''
</P>
<P>
   REHAB REPORT: Tim Belcher and Ken Hill both made rehab starts
Saturday night, Belcher at Triple-A Edmonton and Hill at Single-A
Lake Elsinore. For Belcher, the start was his second on the current
rehab assignment. The goal was to get him up to about 75 pitches,
then have him join the starting rotation and start Saturday's game
in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   For Hill, the start is his first since he strained a rib-cage
muscle May 9. He'll need to make at least one more rehab start
before he can rejoin the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dickson (strained hip) is scheduled to make a rehab start
for Edmonton today.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mark Petkovsek threw 38 pitches in 1 innings Friday
night for Lake Elsinore and is expected to rejoin the team Monday.
Petkovsek has been out since May 17 after coming down with a viral
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   GOING WITH FOUR: Because of off days this week, the Angels don't
need a fifth starter until Saturday. Until then, they will continue
with a four-man rotation that consists of Seth Etherton (age 23),
Scott Schoeneweis (26), Jarrod Washburn (25) and Brian Cooper (25).
</P>
<P>
   ``As a group, they're holding their own,'' Scioscia said. ``They
are young and will make mistakes that cost runs, but their poise
has been so good. We're confident they're going to continue to keep
us in ballgames, when we're looking for the offense to take control
of games. But we want to see them be aggressive and put up zeroes
early in the game, so we don't have to come back so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Etherton, Schoeneweis, Cooper and Washburn are 9-7
with a 4.74 ERA. By comparison, the American League average ERA is
4.88. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
